{"title_page": "Syndicate (series)", "text_new": "{{Short description|Video game series}}\n{{Infobox video game series\n| title                  = Syndicate\n| image                  = Syndicate.png\n| caption                = PC DOS version of ''Syndicate''.\n| platforms              = [[MS-DOS]], [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[Xbox 360]], [[Amiga]], [[Amiga CD32]], [[Apple Macintosh|Mac]], [[Sega Genesis]], [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|SNES]], [[3DO Interactive Multiplayer|3DO]], [[Atari Jaguar]], [[Acorn Archimedes]], [[FM Towns]], [[NEC PC-9801]], [[Sega-CD]], [[PlayStation Portable|PSP]]\n| developer              = [[Bullfrog Productions]], [[Ocean Software]], [[Starbreeze Studios]]\n| publisher              =[[Electronic Arts]] \n| genre                  = [[Real-time tactics]], [[First-person shooter]]\n| spinoffs               = \n| creator                = \n| artist                 = \n| writer                 = \n| composer               = \n| first release version  = ''[[Syndicate (video game)|Syndicate]]''\n| first release date     = {{Start date and age|1993}}\n| latest release version =''[[Syndicate (2012 video game)|Syndicate]]'' \n| latest release date    ={{Start date and age|2012|02|21|df=yes}} \n}}\nThe '''''Syndicate''''' series is a series of [[science fiction]] [[video game]]s created by [[Bullfrog Productions]] and published by [[Electronic Arts]]. There are two main titles in the series: ''[[Syndicate (video game)|Syndicate]]'' (1993) and ''[[Syndicate Wars]]'' (1996), both of which are [[Isometric video game graphics|isometric]] [[real-time tactics]] games. An additional [[first-person shooter]] ''[[Syndicate (2012 video game)|Syndicate]]'' title was released in 2012, and a [[spiritual successor]] to the series (returning to the real-time tactics format), entitled ''[[Satellite Reign]]'', was released in 2015.\n\n==Games==\n\n=== ''Syndicate'' (1993) ===\n{{Main|Syndicate (1993 video game)}}\n''[[Syndicate (video game)|Syndicate]]'', the first game in the series, was first released for [[PC game|PC]] and [[Amiga]] in June 1993, with later releases on other platforms including [[Sega Genesis]], [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|SNES]], and [[PlayStation Portable]]. In 2015, the game was made available for free on [[Origin (digital distribution software)|Electronic Arts' Origin platform]].  however it now costs \u00a34.25 (As of 20JUN19)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-03-04-bullfrog-classic-syndicate-free-on-ea-origin-now|title=Bullfrog classic Syndicate free on EA Origin now,|last=Purchese|first=Robert|date=2015-03-04|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}} https://www.origin.com/gbr/en-us/store/syndicate/syndicate-1993</ref>\n\nAn expansion pack, titled ''[[Syndicate: American Revolt]]'', was also released for PC and Amiga in 1993.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/GameBytes/issue18/greviews/syndicat/synd.html|title=SYNDICATE: AMERICAN REVOLT from Bullfrog/Electronic Arts|last=Webb|first=Russell|date=|website=Game Bytes Magazine|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.igdb.com/g/1e|title=Syndicate: American Revolt|website=IGDB.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Syndicate Wars'' ===\n{{Main|Syndicate Wars}}\nThe second game in the series, ''[[Syndicate Wars]]'', was released for [[PC game|PC]] in October 1996<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gamefaqs.gamespot.com/pc/198873-syndicate-wars/data|title=Syndicate Wars Release Information for PC|last=|first=|date=|website=Game FAQs|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> and [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] in July 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gamefaqs.gamespot.com/ps/198874-syndicate-wars/data|title=Syndicate Wars Release Information for PlayStation|last=|first=|date=|website=Game FAQs|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> ''Syndicate Wars'' utilized a more demanding graphics engine, including a [[Three-dimensional space|3-dimensional]] environment, compared with the [[Two-dimensional space|2-dimensional]] layout of ''Syndicate'').\n\nIn 2008, a [[digital distribution]] version of the PlayStation version was released on the [[PlayStation Network]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://brutalgamer.com/2008/11/27/european-psn-store-update-112708/|title=European PSN store update 11/27/08|date=2008-11-27|website=Brutal Gamer|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Syndicate'' (2012) ===\n{{Main|Syndicate (2012 video game)}}\nReports of a new ''Syndicate'' game, developed for EA by [[Starbreeze Studios]], first surfaced in March 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/90609-New-Syndicate-Game-Confirmed|title=New Syndicate Game Confirmed|last=Chalk|first=Andy|date=2009-03-31|website=The Escapist|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> and were officially confirmed in September 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-09-12-ea-and-starbreeze-announce-syndicate-fps|title=EA and Starbreeze reveal Syndicate FPS|last=Purchese|first=Robert|date=2011-09-12|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref> The game, also entitled ''[[Syndicate (2012 video game)|Syndicate]]'', was released on 21 February 2012; however, it used a [[first-person shooter]] format, which differed significantly from the [[Isometric video game graphics|isometric]] [[real-time tactics]] format of the series' original games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/syndicate-review/1900-6350825/|title=Syndicate Review|last=VanOrd|first=Kevin|date=2012-02-22|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Future and cancelled games ===\nAccording to a former Bullfrog Productions employee, a follow-up ''Syndicate'' title for PC began development shortly after the release of [[Dungeon Keeper 2]] in 1999; however, this development effort was never completed. This was followed by several further development efforts which did not progress.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/370930/the-syndicate-games-that-never-were|title=The Syndicate Games that Never Were|last=|first=|date=2008-03-22|website=Kotaku|archive-url=http://www.consolecity.com/forum/archive/index.php/t-90307.html|archive-date=2008-03-22|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe same employee states that a ''Syndicate'' title on [[PlayStation 2]] was under development for approximately one year; however, this title was also never released. It was intended to feature featuring a \"free-roaming multi-tiered city\" and two new factions, known as the ''Freemen'' and the ''Hybrid''.<ref name=\":22\" /> Several pieces of concept art from this project were released by another former Bullfrog employee, Mike Man.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/mike.man/concept_art.html|title=Mike Man - Concept Art|last=Man|first=Mike|date=|website=NTL World|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=dead|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2006 interview at the [[Leipzig Games Convention]] for [[GameSpot]], [[Peter Molyneux]] (co-founder of Bullfrog Productions) said that he would like to revisit some of his old efforts, but adds that it is very unlikely that will happen; however, Molyneux made one possible exception:<blockquote>\"Aside from the licensing complications, some sort of next-gen online version of ''Syndicate'' would certainly be popular with gamers.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=144507|title=Molyneux talks game design and next-gen|last=|first=|date=2006-08-15|website=Computer and Video Games (CVG)|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==== ''Creation'' ====\n{{Main|Creation (video game)}}\nA Bullfrog project named ''[[Creation (video game)|Creation]]'' was intended to take place on an alien world set in the ''Syndicate'' universe. The game's plot was to have EuroCorp as the antagonists, while the player, representing a third-party biologist, utilized semi-sentient dolphins to fight them.<ref name=\"Bullfrog96\">{{cite magazine|date=April 1996|title=Bullfrog|department=Prescreen|magazine=Edge|location=Bath|publisher=[[Future plc]]|issue=31|pages=42\u201345|ISSN=1350-1593}}</ref><ref name=\"Water\">{{cite magazine|date=1996|title=Water, Water Everywhere...|magazine=Bullfrog Bulletin|location=Guildford|publisher=Bullfrog Productions|issue=3|pages=15\u201317}}</ref>\n\nFollowing development for [[MS-DOS]],<ref>{{cite magazine|date=1997|title=What's With Windows 95?|magazine=Bullfrog Bulletin|location=Guildford|publisher=Bullfrog Productions|issue=4|page=12}}</ref> [[Amiga CD32]],<ref name=\"AComp\">{{cite magazine|date=November 1993|title=Creation|magazine=Amiga Computing|publisher=[[Europress]]|issue=66|pages=13, 14|ISSN=0959-9630}}</ref> [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]],<ref name=\"CCrazy\">{{cite magazine|date=1996|title=Console Crazy|magazine=Bullfrog Bulletin|location=Guildford|publisher=Bullfrog Productions|issue=3|pages=18, 19}}</ref> and [[Sega Saturn]],<ref name=\"CCrazy\" /> the game was cancelled in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-10-18-the-lost-worlds-of-lionhead-and-bullfrog|title=The lost worlds of Lionhead and Bullfrog|last=Donlan|first=Christian|date=2016-03-13|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref><ref name=\"PCGUS\">{{cite magazine|author=Colin Williamson|date=August 1998|title=Creation|url=http://scans.roushimsx.com/PCGamer_1998_08_pg089.jpg|magazine=[[PC Gamer US]]|page=89|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322185131/http://scans.roushimsx.com/PCGamer_1998_08_pg089.jpg|archivedate=22 March 2016|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Related games ===\n\n==== ''Satellite Reign'' ====\n{{Main|Satellite Reign}}\nOn 15 May 2013, Mike Diskett (who was the producer and lead programmer for ''[[Syndicate Wars]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobygames.com/developer/sheet/view/developerId,2253/|title=Mike Diskett Video Game Credits and Biography|website=MobyGames|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>) posted a video on [[YouTube]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9nWNAXLJEb8|title=Satellite Reign - Coming Soon|last=|first=|date=2013-05-15|website=YouTube|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> that revealed an imminent [[Kickstarter]] [[crowdfunding]] campaign for a new [[spiritual successor]] to ''Syndicate Wars'', called ''[[Satellite Reign]]'', which returned to the series' original real-time tactics format. When it closed on 28 July 2013, the campaign had raised \u00a3461,333 ($720,832), compared to its \u00a3350,000 ($546,875) goal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/5livesstudios/satellite-reign|title=Satellite Reign|website=Kickstarter|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref> ''Satellite Reign'' was subsequently released on August 28, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-07-13-syndicate-wars-inspired-satellite-reign-gets-release-date|title=Syndicate Wars-inspired Satellite Reign gets release date|last=Purchese|first=Robert|date=2015-07-13|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/satellite-reign-the-kotaku-review-1726032962|title=Satellite Reign: The Kotaku Review|last=Plunkett|first=Luke|date=2015-08-25|website=Kotaku|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\n=== ''Syndicate'' (1993) and ''Syndicate Wars'' ===\n\nThe original ''Syndicate'' is set in the year 2096. As outlined in the game's [[Video game packaging#Instruction manuals|instruction manual]], [[Multinational corporation|multinational]] [[megacorporation]]<nowiki/>s, have replaced global governments and one such corporation, named ''EuroCorp'', have established the \"CHIP\": a device inserted into a person's neck which alters their perception (\"numbing their senses to the misery and squalor around them\") and allows them to be directly manipulated. The megacorporations have subsequently been infiltrated and overtaken by corrupt crime Syndicates, fighting for global control.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|url=http://syndicate.lubiki.pl/downloads/synd_docs/synd_manual_pc_usa_release.pdf|title=Syndicate - Manual (USA PC)|last=|first=|publisher=[[Electronic Arts]]|year=1993|isbn=|location=|pages=3\u20136, 51\u201353}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://syndicate.lubiki.pl/downloads/swars_docs/swars_official_guide_part1of7.pdf|title=Bullfrog's Official Guide to Syndicate Wars (Part 1)|last=Tyler|first=Melissa|publisher=[[Prima Games|Prima Publishing]]|year=1996|isbn=0-7615-0089-8|location=United States of America|pages=|lccn=96-68003}}</ref>\n\nThe player is placed in charge one such corporation, for which they choose a name and [[logo]]. During the course of the game, as missions for the player's corporation are completed by teams of cyborg enforcers (known as \"agents\"), it gains global dominance over its competitors.\n\n''Syndicate Wars'' is set 95 years after the original game (in the year 2191), when ''EuroCorp'' holds full global control, using CHIP technology to influence the population. At this point, the release of a virus into the global communications network leads to CHIP failures, resulting in the emergence of armed insurrectionists, referred to as \"unguided citizens\". The group responsible for the viral attack is a militant religious organisation, named the ''Church of the New Epoch''.\n\nThe game's instruction manual specifically addresses the player as a newly hired ''EuroCorp'' executive;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://syndicate.lubiki.pl/downloads/swars_docs/swars_pc_manual_usa_release.pdf|title=Syndicate Wars - Manual|last=|first=|publisher=[[Electronic Arts]]|year=1996|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> however, they can choose to control agents from either ''EuroCorp'' (to suppress uprisings resulting from the virus outbreak) or the ''Church of the New Epoch'' (to seize power from ''EuroCorp'').\n\nThe game ends with a battle for control of [[ionosphere]] calibration equipment on [[Moon|the moon]], which the Church's leaders intend to use in eliminating life on Earth; however (regardless of which faction the player chooses to play as), the leaders are eliminated before this plan can be executed.\n\n=== ''Syndicate'' (2012) ===\nThe plot of the later ''Syndicate'' game renames the CHIP technology to the \"DART chip\", and introduces the concept of the \"unchipped\", a proportion of the world's population who declined the use of this technology. The game is set in the year 2069 (prior to the original games), at which point, ''EuroCorp'' is already an established global mecorporation.\n\nThe main story focuses on a specific agent, named Miles Kilo. Kilo uncovers a plot from a rival corporation, ''Aspari'', to begin a war against ''EuroCorp'', before discovering that ''EuroCorp'' killed his family, abducted him as a baby and modified his memory. The game ends with the apparent downfall of ''EuroCorp''.\n\n== Gameplay ==\nGameplay for the original ''Syndicate'' games involved ordering a team of four [[cyborg]] agents around gritty [[cyberpunk]]-themed cities, in pursuit of mission goals, such as assassinating executives of a rival syndicate, rescuing captured allies, \"persuading\" civilians and scientists to join the corporation/church, demolishing buildings, or killing enemy agents. Unlike some games, which either punish the player for civilian deaths or reward them for violent actions committed, ''Syndicate'' remains indifferent. The player must collect funds to finance the research and development of new weaponry and cyborg upgrades, such as by taxing conquered territories (in the original game) or robbing banks (in ''Syndicate Wars'').\n\nNotable features of both original games are the use of context-sensitive background music, which changes to suit the mood of the on-screen action, and a high degree of interactivity: many objects in the first game, and nearly every object in the second game, can be destroyed. The visual aesthetic of these games borrows heavily from films such as ''[[Blade Runner]]''.\n\nThe gameplay of the 2012 ''Syndicate'' game did not include the same real-time tactics and strategy elements as the previous games, instead following a typical [[first-person shooter]] format.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Cite book|title=Bullfrog's Official Guide to Syndicate Wars|last=Tyler|first=Melissa|publisher=[[Prima Games|Prima Publishing]]|year=1996|isbn=0-7615-0089-8|location=United States of America|pages=|lccn=96-68003}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.rockpapershotgun.com/?p=1020 ''Syndicate'' retrospective] by [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]\n\n{{Bullfrog Productions}}\n\n[[Category:Bullfrog Productions games]]\n[[Category:Electronic Arts franchises]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises]]\n[[Category:Cyberpunk video games]]\n[[Category:Organized crime video games]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 1993]]\n\n[[cs:Syndicate]]\n[[it:Syndicate]]\n[[ru:Syndicate]]\n[[fi:Syndicate]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Video game series}}\n{{Infobox video game series\n| title                  = Syndicate\n| image                  = Syndicate.png\n| caption                = PC DOS version of ''Syndicate''.\n| platforms              = [[MS-DOS]], [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[Xbox 360]], [[Amiga]], [[Amiga CD32]], [[Apple Macintosh|Mac]], [[Sega Genesis]], [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|SNES]], [[3DO Interactive Multiplayer|3DO]], [[Atari Jaguar]], [[Acorn Archimedes]], [[FM Towns]], [[NEC PC-9801]], [[Sega-CD]], [[PlayStation Portable|PSP]]\n| developer              = [[Bullfrog Productions]], [[Ocean Software]], [[Starbreeze Studios]]\n| publisher              =[[Electronic Arts]] \n| genre                  = [[Real-time tactics]], [[First-person shooter]]\n| spinoffs               = \n| creator                = \n| artist                 = \n| writer                 = \n| composer               = \n| first release version  = ''[[Syndicate (video game)|Syndicate]]''\n| first release date     = {{Start date and age|1993}}\n| latest release version =''[[Syndicate (2012 video game)|Syndicate]]'' \n| latest release date    ={{Start date and age|2012|02|21|df=yes}} \n}}\nThe '''''Syndicate''''' series is a series of [[science fiction]] [[video game]]s created by [[Bullfrog Productions]] and published by [[Electronic Arts]]. There are two main titles in the series: ''[[Syndicate (video game)|Syndicate]]'' (1993) and ''[[Syndicate Wars]]'' (1996), both of which are [[Isometric video game graphics|isometric]] [[real-time tactics]] games. An additional [[first-person shooter]] ''[[Syndicate (2012 video game)|Syndicate]]'' title was released in 2012, and a [[spiritual successor]] to the series (returning to the real-time tactics format), entitled ''[[Satellite Reign]]'', was released in 2015.\n\n==Games==\n\n=== ''Syndicate'' (1993) ===\n{{Main|Syndicate (1993 video game)}}\n''[[Syndicate (video game)|Syndicate]]'', the first game in the series, was first released for [[PC game|PC]] and [[Amiga]] in June 1993, with later releases on other platforms including [[Sega Genesis]], [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|SNES]], and [[PlayStation Portable]]. In 2015, the game was made available for free on [[Origin (digital distribution software)|Electronic Arts' Origin platform]].  however it now costs \u00a34.25 (As of 20JUN19)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-03-04-bullfrog-classic-syndicate-free-on-ea-origin-now|title=Bullfrog classic Syndicate free on EA Origin now,|last=Purchese|first=Robert|date=2015-03-04|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}} https://www.origin.com/gbr/en-us/store/syndicate/syndicate-1993</ref>\n\nAn expansion pack, titled ''[[Syndicate: American Revolt]]'', was also released for PC and Amiga in 1993.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ibiblio.org/GameBytes/issue18/greviews/syndicat/synd.html|title=SYNDICATE: AMERICAN REVOLT from Bullfrog/Electronic Arts|last=Webb|first=Russell|date=|website=Game Bytes Magazine|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.igdb.com/g/1e|title=Syndicate: American Revolt|website=IGDB.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Syndicate Wars'' ===\n{{Main|Syndicate Wars}}\nThe second game in the series, ''[[Syndicate Wars]]'', was released for [[PC game|PC]] in October 1996<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gamefaqs.gamespot.com/pc/198873-syndicate-wars/data|title=Syndicate Wars Release Information for PC|last=|first=|date=|website=Game FAQs|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> and [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] in July 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gamefaqs.gamespot.com/ps/198874-syndicate-wars/data|title=Syndicate Wars Release Information for PlayStation|last=|first=|date=|website=Game FAQs|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> ''Syndicate Wars'' utilized a more demanding graphics engine, including a [[Three-dimensional space|3-dimensional]] environment, compared with the [[Two-dimensional space|2-dimensional]] layout of ''Syndicate'').\n\nIn 2008, a [[digital distribution]] version of the PlayStation version was released on the [[PlayStation Network]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://brutalgamer.com/2008/11/27/european-psn-store-update-112708/|title=European PSN store update 11/27/08|date=2008-11-27|website=Brutal Gamer|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Syndicate'' (2012) ===\n{{Main|Syndicate (2012 video game)}}\nReports of a new ''Syndicate'' game, developed for EA by [[Starbreeze Studios]], first surfaced in March 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/90609-New-Syndicate-Game-Confirmed|title=New Syndicate Game Confirmed|last=Chalk|first=Andy|date=2009-03-31|website=The Escapist|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> and were officially confirmed in September 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-09-12-ea-and-starbreeze-announce-syndicate-fps|title=EA and Starbreeze reveal Syndicate FPS|last=Purchese|first=Robert|date=2011-09-12|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref> The game, also entitled ''[[Syndicate (2012 video game)|Syndicate]]'', was released on 21 February 2012; however, it used a [[first-person shooter]] format, which differed significantly from the [[Isometric video game graphics|isometric]] [[real-time tactics]] format of the series' original games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/syndicate-review/1900-6350825/|title=Syndicate Review|last=VanOrd|first=Kevin|date=2012-02-22|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Future and cancelled games ===\nAccording to a former Bullfrog Productions employee, a follow-up ''Syndicate'' title for PC began development shortly after the release of [[Dungeon Keeper 2]] in 1999; however, this development effort was never completed. This was followed by several further development efforts which did not progress.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/370930/the-syndicate-games-that-never-were|title=The Syndicate Games that Never Were|last=|first=|date=2008-03-22|website=Kotaku|archive-url=http://www.consolecity.com/forum/archive/index.php/t-90307.html|archive-date=2008-03-22|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe same employee states that a ''Syndicate'' title on [[PlayStation 2]] was under development for approximately one year; however, this title was also never released. It was intended to feature featuring a \"free-roaming multi-tiered city\" and two new factions, known as the ''Freemen'' and the ''Hybrid''.<ref name=\":22\" /> Several pieces of concept art from this project were released by another former Bullfrog employee, Mike Man.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/mike.man/concept_art.html|title=Mike Man - Concept Art|last=Man|first=Mike|date=|website=NTL World|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=dead|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2006 interview at the [[Leipzig Games Convention]] for [[GameSpot]], [[Peter Molyneux]] (co-founder of Bullfrog Productions) said that he would like to revisit some of his old efforts, but adds that it is very unlikely that will happen; however, Molyneux made one possible exception:<blockquote>\"Aside from the licensing complications, some sort of next-gen online version of ''Syndicate'' would certainly be popular with gamers.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=144507|title=Molyneux talks game design and next-gen|last=|first=|date=2006-08-15|website=Computer and Video Games (CVG)|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==== ''Creation'' ====\n{{Main|Creation (video game)}}\nA Bullfrog project named ''[[Creation (video game)|Creation]]'' was intended to take place on an alien world set in the ''Syndicate'' universe. The game's plot was to have EuroCorp as the antagonists, while the player, representing a third-party biologist, utilized semi-sentient dolphins to fight them.<ref name=\"Bullfrog96\">{{cite magazine|date=April 1996|title=Bullfrog|department=Prescreen|magazine=Edge|location=Bath|publisher=[[Future plc]]|issue=31|pages=42\u201345|ISSN=1350-1593}}</ref><ref name=\"Water\">{{cite magazine|date=1996|title=Water, Water Everywhere...|magazine=Bullfrog Bulletin|location=Guildford|publisher=Bullfrog Productions|issue=3|pages=15\u201317}}</ref>\n\nFollowing development for [[MS-DOS]],<ref>{{cite magazine|date=1997|title=What's With Windows 95?|magazine=Bullfrog Bulletin|location=Guildford|publisher=Bullfrog Productions|issue=4|page=12}}</ref> [[Amiga CD32]],<ref name=\"AComp\">{{cite magazine|date=November 1993|title=Creation|magazine=Amiga Computing|publisher=[[Europress]]|issue=66|pages=13, 14|ISSN=0959-9630}}</ref> [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]],<ref name=\"CCrazy\">{{cite magazine|date=1996|title=Console Crazy|magazine=Bullfrog Bulletin|location=Guildford|publisher=Bullfrog Productions|issue=3|pages=18, 19}}</ref> and [[Sega Saturn]],<ref name=\"CCrazy\" /> the game was cancelled in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-10-18-the-lost-worlds-of-lionhead-and-bullfrog|title=The lost worlds of Lionhead and Bullfrog|last=Donlan|first=Christian|date=2016-03-13|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref><ref name=\"PCGUS\">{{cite magazine|author=Colin Williamson|date=August 1998|title=Creation|url=http://scans.roushimsx.com/PCGamer_1998_08_pg089.jpg|magazine=[[PC Gamer US]]|page=89|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322185131/http://scans.roushimsx.com/PCGamer_1998_08_pg089.jpg|archivedate=22 March 2016|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Related games ===\n\n==== ''Satellite Reign'' ====\n{{Main|Satellite Reign}}\nOn 15 May 2013, Mike Diskett (who was the producer and lead programmer for ''[[Syndicate Wars]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobygames.com/developer/sheet/view/developerId,2253/|title=Mike Diskett Video Game Credits and Biography|website=MobyGames|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>) posted a video on [[YouTube]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9nWNAXLJEb8|title=Satellite Reign - Coming Soon|last=|first=|date=2013-05-15|website=YouTube|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-03-20}}</ref> that revealed an imminent [[Kickstarter]] [[crowdfunding]] campaign for a new [[spiritual successor]] to ''Syndicate Wars'', called ''[[Satellite Reign]]'', which returned to the series' original real-time tactics format. When it closed on 28 July 2013, the campaign had raised \u00a3461,333 ($720,832), compared to its \u00a3350,000 ($546,875) goal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/5livesstudios/satellite-reign|title=Satellite Reign|website=Kickstarter|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref> ''Satellite Reign'' was subsequently released on August 28, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-07-13-syndicate-wars-inspired-satellite-reign-gets-release-date|title=Syndicate Wars-inspired Satellite Reign gets release date|last=Purchese|first=Robert|date=2015-07-13|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/satellite-reign-the-kotaku-review-1726032962|title=Satellite Reign: The Kotaku Review|last=Plunkett|first=Luke|date=2015-08-25|website=Kotaku|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\n=== ''Syndicate'' (1993) and ''Syndicate Wars'' ===\n\nThe original ''Syndicate'' is set in the year 2096. As outlined in the game's [[Video game packaging#Instruction manuals|instruction manual]], [[Multinational corporation|multinational]] [[megacorporation]]<nowiki/>s, have replaced global governments and one such corporation, named ''EuroCorp'', have established the \"CHIP\": a device inserted into a person's neck which alters their perception (\"numbing their senses to the misery and squalor around them\") and allows them to be directly manipulated. The megacorporations have subsequently been infiltrated and overtaken by corrupt crime Syndicates, fighting for global control.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|url=http://syndicate.lubiki.pl/downloads/synd_docs/synd_manual_pc_usa_release.pdf|title=Syndicate - Manual (USA PC)|last=|first=|publisher=[[Electronic Arts]]|year=1993|isbn=|location=|pages=3\u20136, 51\u201353}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://syndicate.lubiki.pl/downloads/swars_docs/swars_official_guide_part1of7.pdf|title=Bullfrog's Official Guide to Syndicate Wars (Part 1)|last=Tyler|first=Melissa|publisher=[[Prima Games|Prima Publishing]]|year=1996|isbn=0-7615-0089-8|location=United States of America|pages=|lccn=96-68003}}</ref>\n\nThe player is placed in charge one such corporation, for which they choose a name and [[logo]]. During the course of the game, as missions for the player's corporation are completed by teams of cyborg enforcers (known as \"agents\"), it gains global dominance over its competitors.\n\n''Syndicate Wars'' is set 95 years after the original game (in the year 2191), when ''EuroCorp'' holds full global control, using CHIP technology to influence the population. At this point, the release of a virus into the global communications network leads to CHIP failures, resulting in the emergence of armed insurrectionists, referred to as \"unguided citizens\". The group responsible for the viral attack is a militant religious organisation, named the ''Church of the New Epoch''.\n\nThe game's instruction manual specifically addresses the player as a newly hired ''EuroCorp'' executive;<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://syndicate.lubiki.pl/downloads/swars_docs/swars_pc_manual_usa_release.pdf|title=Syndicate Wars - Manual|last=|first=|publisher=[[Electronic Arts]]|year=1996|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> however, they can chose to control agents from either ''EuroCorp'' (to suppress uprisings resulting from the virus outbreak) or the ''Church of the New Epoch'' (to seize power from ''EuroCorp'').\n\nThe game ends with a battle for control of [[ionosphere]] calibration equipment on [[Moon|the moon]], which the Church's leaders intend to use in eliminating life on Earth; however (regardless of which faction the player chooses to play as), the leaders are eliminated before this plan can be executed.\n\n=== ''Syndicate'' (2012) ===\nThe plot of the later ''Syndicate'' game renames the CHIP technology to the \"DART chip\", and introduces the concept of the \"unchipped\", a proportion of the world's population who declined the use of this technology. The game is set in the year 2069 (prior to the original games), at which point, ''EuroCorp'' is already an established global mecorporation.\n\nThe main story focuses on a specific agent, named Miles Kilo. Kilo uncovers a plot from a rival corporation, ''Aspari'', to begin a war against ''EuroCorp'', before discovering that ''EuroCorp'' killed his family, abducted him as a baby and modified his memory. The game ends with the apparent downfall of ''EuroCorp''.\n\n== Gameplay ==\nGameplay for the original ''Syndicate'' games involved ordering a team of four [[cyborg]] agents around gritty [[cyberpunk]]-themed cities, in pursuit of mission goals, such as assassinating executives of a rival syndicate, rescuing captured allies, \"persuading\" civilians and scientists to join the corporation/church, demolishing buildings, or killing enemy agents. Unlike some games, which either punish the player for civilian deaths or reward them for violent actions committed, ''Syndicate'' remains indifferent. The player must collect funds to finance the research and development of new weaponry and cyborg upgrades, such as by taxing conquered territories (in the original game) or robbing banks (in ''Syndicate Wars'').\n\nNotable features of both original games are the use of context-sensitive background music, which changes to suit the mood of the on-screen action, and a high degree of interactivity: many objects in the first game, and nearly every object in the second game, can be destroyed. The visual aesthetic of these games borrows heavily from films such as ''[[Blade Runner]]''.\n\nThe gameplay of the 2012 ''Syndicate'' game did not include the same real-time tactics and strategy elements as the previous games, instead following a typical [[first-person shooter]] format.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Cite book|title=Bullfrog's Official Guide to Syndicate Wars|last=Tyler|first=Melissa|publisher=[[Prima Games|Prima Publishing]]|year=1996|isbn=0-7615-0089-8|location=United States of America|pages=|lccn=96-68003}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.rockpapershotgun.com/?p=1020 ''Syndicate'' retrospective] by [[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]\n\n{{Bullfrog Productions}}\n\n[[Category:Bullfrog Productions games]]\n[[Category:Electronic Arts franchises]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises]]\n[[Category:Cyberpunk video games]]\n[[Category:Organized crime video games]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 1993]]\n\n[[cs:Syndicate]]\n[[it:Syndicate]]\n[[ru:Syndicate]]\n[[fi:Syndicate]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e''Syndicate'' (1993) and ''Syndicate Wars'':Typo fixing, replaced: can chose \u2192 can choose", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syndicate_(series)"}
{"title_page": "Delta-v (physics)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Delta-''v'' (physics)}}\n{{for|a more in depth astrodynamical definition|Delta-v}}\nDelta comes as the 4th letter in the Greek alphabets which is spelled as 'D' in the English alphabets . In general physics, '''delta-''v''''' is simply a change in [[velocity]].  The Greek uppercase letter delta is the standard mathematical symbol to represent change in some quantity.\n\nDepending on the situation, delta-''v'' can be either a [[Euclidean vector|spatial vector]] (\u0394'''v''') or [[Scalar (physics)|scalar]] (\u0394''v''). In either case it is equal to the [[acceleration]] (vector or scalar) integrated over time:\n\n:<math>\\Delta \\mathbf{v} = \\mathbf{v}_1 - \\mathbf{v}_0 = \\int^{t_1}_{t_0} \\mathbf {a} \\, dt</math> (vector version)\n:<math>\\Delta{v} = {v}_1 - {v}_0 = \\int^{t_1}_{t_0} {a} \\, dt</math> (scalar version)\n\nIf acceleration is constant, the change in velocity can thus be expressed as:\n:<math>\\Delta \\mathbf{v} = \\mathbf{v}_1 - \\mathbf{v}_0 = \\mathbf {a} * (t_1-t_0)</math>\nwhere:\n*'''v'''<sub>0</sub> or ''v''<sub>0</sub> is initial velocity (at time ''t''<sub>0</sub>),\n*'''v'''<sub>1</sub> or ''v''<sub>1</sub> is subsequent velocity (at time ''t''<sub>1</sub>).\n\nChange in velocity is useful in many cases, such as determining the change in [[momentum]] ([[Impulse_(physics)|impulse]]), where :<math>\\Delta{\\mathbf{p}} = m\\Delta{\\mathbf{v}}</math>, where <math>\\mathbf{p}</math> is momentum and m is mass. \n[[Category:Physical quantities]]\n\n\n{{physics-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Delta-''v'' (physics)}}\n{{for|a more in depth astrodynamical definition|Delta-v}}\nDelta comes as the 4th letter in the greek alphabets which is spelled as 'D' in the english alphabets . In general physics, '''delta-''v''''' is simply a change in [[velocity]].  The Greek uppercase letter delta is the standard mathematical symbol to represent change in some quantity.\n\nDepending on the situation, delta-''v'' can be either a [[Euclidean vector|spatial vector]] (\u0394'''v''') or [[Scalar (physics)|scalar]] (\u0394''v''). In either case it is equal to the [[acceleration]] (vector or scalar) integrated over time:\n\n:<math>\\Delta \\mathbf{v} = \\mathbf{v}_1 - \\mathbf{v}_0 = \\int^{t_1}_{t_0} \\mathbf {a} \\, dt</math> (vector version)\n:<math>\\Delta{v} = {v}_1 - {v}_0 = \\int^{t_1}_{t_0} {a} \\, dt</math> (scalar version)\n\nIf acceleration is constant, the change in velocity can thus be expressed as:\n:<math>\\Delta \\mathbf{v} = \\mathbf{v}_1 - \\mathbf{v}_0 = \\mathbf {a} * (t_1-t_0)</math>\nwhere:\n*'''v'''<sub>0</sub> or ''v''<sub>0</sub> is initial velocity (at time ''t''<sub>0</sub>),\n*'''v'''<sub>1</sub> or ''v''<sub>1</sub> is subsequent velocity (at time ''t''<sub>1</sub>).\n\nChange in velocity is useful in many cases, such as determining the change in [[momentum]] ([[Impulse_(physics)|impulse]]), where :<math>\\Delta{\\mathbf{p}} = m\\Delta{\\mathbf{v}}</math>, where <math>\\mathbf{p}</math> is momentum and m is mass. \n[[Category:Physical quantities]]\n\n\n{{physics-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: greek \u2192 Greek, english \u2192 English", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delta-v_(physics)"}
{"title_page": "Carl Kasell", "text_new": "{{For|the Democratic politician and Alaskan mayor|Karl Kassel}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Carl Kasell\n| image              = Carl Kasell, Peabody Awards 2008 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Kasell at the 2008 [[Peabody Award]]s\n| birth_name         = Carl Ray Kasell\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1934|04|02}}\n| birth_place        = [[Goldsboro, North Carolina|Goldsboro]], [[North Carolina]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"npr-bio\">{{cite web | title = Carl Kasell | url = https://www.npr.org/people/2100708/carl-kasell | publisher = [[NPR]] | access-date = 2011-04-11}}</ref>\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2018|04|17|1934|04|02}}\n| death_place        = [[Potomac, Maryland|Potomac]], [[Maryland]], U.S.\n| education          = \n| years_active       = 1975\u20132014\n| occupation         = Radio Newscaster\n| employer           = [[NPR]]\n| spouse             = Clara DeZorzi (m. 1959; died 1997)\nMary Ann Foster (m. 2003 - his death)\n| parents            = \n| children           = \n| nationality        = United States\n| website            = \n}}\n'''Carl Ray Kasell''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|\u00e6|s|\u0259l}}; April 2, 1934&nbsp;\u2013 April 17, 2018) was an [[Americans|American]] radio personality. He was best known as a newscaster for [[NPR|National Public Radio]], and later as the official judge and scorekeeper of the weekly news [[Game show|quiz show]] ''[[Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me!]]'' until his retirement in 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2014/03/04/285780588/after-five-decade-career-nprs-carl-kasell-will-retire|title=After 5-Decade Career, NPR's Carl Kasell Will Retire|last=Peralta|first=Eyder|date=2014-03-04|work=[[NPR]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418005507/https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2014/03/04/285780588/after-five-decade-career-nprs-carl-kasell-will-retire|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nA native of [[Goldsboro, North Carolina]], Carl Ray Kasell was a student of drama in high school, where one of his mentors was [[Andy Griffith]], then a high school drama instructor.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/carl-kasell-npr-broadcaster-who-brought-gravitas-and-goofiness-to-the-airwaves-dies-at-84/2018/04/17/173eecc2-3b49-11e8-a7d1-e4efec6389f0_story.html|title=Carl Kasell, NPR broadcaster who brought gravitas and goofiness to the airwaves, dies at 84|last=Bernstein|first=Adam|date=2018-04-17|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Although Griffith urged Kasell to pursue a career in theatre, Kasell preferred radio. Kasell began practicing his newscaster voice as a child and got his first on-air job at 16.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/04/17/528656453/npr-newscaster-carl-kasell-dies-at-84-after-a-lifelong-career-on-air|title=NPR Newscaster Carl Kasell Dies At 84, After A Lifelong Career On-Air|last=[[Neda Ulaby]]|date=2018-04-17|work=[[NPR]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418000423/https://www.npr.org/2018/04/17/528656453/npr-newscaster-carl-kasell-dies-at-84-after-a-lifelong-career-on-air|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://wunc.org/post/ive-enjoyed-every-minute-it-carl-kasell-his-60-years-radio|title='I've Enjoyed Every Minute Of It': Carl Kasell On His 60 Years In Radio|date=2014-05-14|work=[[WUNC (FM)]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418000911/http://wunc.org/post/ive-enjoyed-every-minute-it-carl-kasell-his-60-years-radio#stream/0|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=|language=en}}</ref> In an interview with [[Ren\u00e9e Montagne]] just before his final broadcast on NPR's ''[[Morning Edition]]'', Kasell revealed that he knew he would be in radio at a young age. He said that he hid behind the radio to fool passers-by into thinking they were listening to the radio when they in fact were hearing the young Kasell.<ref name=\"NPR-sleep\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=122017544|title=Carl Kasell: After 30 Years, A Chance to Sleep In|date=December 30, 2009|publisher=NPR|access-date=2017-07-11}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]], Kasell helped launch local radio station [[WUNC (FM)|WUNC]] with fellow student and future broadcaster [[Charles Kuralt]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/article209144054.html|title=Carolina native, NPR newscaster Carl Kasell of 'Wait, Wait' dies at 84|last=Bennett|first=Abbie|date=2018-04-17|work=[[The News & Observer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418004905/http://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/article209144054.html|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=|language=en}}</ref> Kasell pursued a degree in [[English studies|English]], but never graduated due to being drafted into the U.S. Army.<ref name=\":4\" /> After serving, he worked as an announcer and DJ at radio station [[WGBR]] in Goldsboro, North Carolina.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> He moved to Northern Virginia in 1965.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==Career==\nAfter leaving North Carolina, Kasell first worked as an announcer and DJ at WPIK in Alexandria, Virginia.  He would soon join the staff of all-news [[WAVA (AM)|WAVA]] in Arlington, Virginia as a weekend news announcer, and eventually would advance to the position of news director.  As news director, he hired [[Katie Couric]], then a student at the [[University of Virginia]], as an intern one summer, thus starting her career in news broadcasting.\n\nKasell joined [[NPR|National Public Radio]]'s staff as a news announcer for ''[[All Things Considered|Weekend All Things Considered]]'' in 1975.<ref name=\":1\" /> He was also the news announcer for NPR's ''[[Morning Edition]]'' from its inception in 1979 through 2009.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nOn November 23, 2009, NPR announced that Kasell would retire from newscasting at the end of 2009. Kasell's final newscast aired on December 30, 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2009/11/nprs_carl_kasell_leaving_newsc.html|title=NPR's Kasell Leaving Newscasts; Remains On 'Wait Wait'|last=Memmott|first=Mark|date=2009-11-23|work=[[NPR]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418005725/https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2009/11/nprs_carl_kasell_leaving_newsc.html|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=|language=en}}</ref> \nHe continued to work for NPR through fundraising and visits to member stations.<ref name=\"NPR-sleep\" />\nHe also continued to appear as the official scorer of ''Wait Wait&nbsp;... Don't Tell Me!''\n\n=== ''Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me!'' ===\nNPR launched its weekly news quiz ''[[Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me!]]'' in 1998, with Kasell as official judge and scorekeeper.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theringer.com/2018/1/4/16849150/wait-wait-dont-tell-me-npr-quiz-show|title='Wait Wait' ... Please Tell Me: The Story Behind NPR's Beloved Quiz Show|last=Varghese|first=Daniel|date=2018-01-04|work=[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418001825/https://www.theringer.com/2018/1/4/16849150/wait-wait-dont-tell-me-npr-quiz-show|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=}}</ref> Kasell featured in several segments including \"Who's Carl This Time?\" and the \"Listener Limerick Challenge.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/17/obituaries/carl-kasell-dies.html|title=Carl Kasell, NPR Newsman Who Discovered Laughs, Dies at 84|last=[[Robert D. McFadden]]|date=2018-04-17|work=[[The New York Times]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418001322/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/17/obituaries/carl-kasell-dies.html?mtrref=undefined&gwh=27BD4B51E642474A768978ACE89978C6&gwt=pay|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nPrior to October 21, 2017, listeners who won a game on the show could have Kasell record a greeting for their home answering machine or voice mail system. Because this prize has been such a long-standing tradition for the show, more than 2,000 people have had his voice on their answering machines, which he recorded even after he left the show.<ref name=\"NPR-sleep\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> The current prize is to have any show panelist or staff member of the contestant's choice record the greeting, including Kasell until his death.[[File:Carl Kasell Speaking in Nashville.jpg|thumb|left|Kasell speaking in Nashville, Tennessee, in 2009]]\n\nDuring the August 7, 2010, broadcast of ''Wait Wait&nbsp;... Don't Tell Me!'', host [[Peter Sagal]] announced that Kasell had been voted into the [[National Radio Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Opening Segment|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=129039403|work=Wait Wait Don't Tell Me|publisher=National Public Radio|access-date=7 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Carl Kasell Knocks Out Howard Stern in Voting |url=http://www.rbr.com/radio/26478.html |publisher=Radio Business Report |access-date=14 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100806011840/http://www.rbr.com/radio/26478.html |archivedate=6 August 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New Radio Hall of Famers: Cathy Hughes, Carl Kasell, Terri Hemmert, Ralph Emery |url=http://www.radio-info.com/news/new-radio-hall-of-famers-cathy-hughes-carl-kasell-terri-hemmert-ralph-emery# |work=Radio-Info.com |access-date=14 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100807091226/http://www.radio-info.com/news/new-radio-hall-of-famers-cathy-hughes-carl-kasell-terri-hemmert-ralph-emery |archivedate=7 August 2010 }}</ref>\n\nFor many years, Kasell was the announcer for the annual [[Kennedy Center Honors]] broadcast on [[CBS]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/carl-kasell-dead-longtime-voice-npr-morning-edition-was-84-1103571|title=Carl Kasell, Longtime Voice on NPR's 'Morning Edition, Dies at 84|last=Barnes|first=Mike|date=2018-04-17|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418005845/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/carl-kasell-dead-longtime-voice-npr-morning-edition-was-84-1103571|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, 2014, NPR announced that Kasell would be stepping down from his ''Wait Wait&nbsp;... Don't Tell Me!'' duties.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/about-npr/285327851/carl-kasell-to-retire-from-wait-wait-dont-tell-me-this-spring|title=Carl Kasell To Retire From 'Wait Wait&nbsp;... Don't Tell Me!' This Spring|date=2014-03-04|work=[[NPR]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418005953/https://www.npr.org/about-npr/285327851/carl-kasell-to-retire-from-wait-wait-dont-tell-me-this-spring|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=|language=en}}</ref> It was later announced that his last show would be May 17, 2014; subsequently he was credited on the air as \"Scorekeeper Emeritus\".<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Retirement and death ==\nKasell's final show on ''Wait Wait&nbsp;... Don't Tell Me!'' was recorded on May 15, 2014 and broadcast two days later. [[Stephen Colbert]], [[Katie Couric]], [[Tom Hanks]], and President [[Barack Obama]] called in to the show to voice their appreciation for Kasell.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn September 2014, Kasell published his memoir titled ''Wait Wait&nbsp;... I'm Not Done Yet!''<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nKasell died on April 17, 2018, from complications of [[Alzheimer's disease]] in [[Potomac, Maryland]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Awards==\n* 2004 \u2014 North Carolina Media & Journalism Hall of Fame\n*2010&nbsp;\u2014 [[National Radio Hall of Fame]]<ref name=\":4\" />\n* 2011 \u2014 Honorary Doctor of Humane Letters of the [[University of Southern Maine]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://usm.maine.edu/publicaffairs/usm-present-honorary-degrees-and-distinguished-achievement-awards-131st-commencement-m|title=USM to Present Honorary Degrees and Distinguished Achievement Awards at 131st Commencement on May 14|date=2011-05-11|website=[[University of Southern Maine]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418010143/https://usm.maine.edu/publicaffairs/usm-present-honorary-degrees-and-distinguished-achievement-awards-131st-commencement-m|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=}}</ref>\n* 2013&nbsp;\u2014 North Carolinian of the Year<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=2100708 NPR biography]\n*[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=111036549 NPR : Wait Wait -- Don't Tell Me! : Messages by Carl Kasell]\n*{{C-SPAN|Carl Kasell}}\n*[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/188912776/carl-ray-kasell  Find a Grave]\n\n{{NPR}}\n{{Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me! |state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kasell, Carl}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:American radio journalists]]\n[[Category:American game show hosts]]\n[[Category:NPR personalities]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Goldsboro, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Journalists from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Radio personalities from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me!]]\n[[Category:Deaths from Alzheimer's disease]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the Democratic politician and Alaskan mayor|Karl Kassel}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Carl Kasell\n| image              = Carl Kasell, Peabody Awards 2008 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Kasell at the 2008 [[Peabody Award]]s\n| birth_name         = Carl Ray Kasell\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1934|04|02}}\n| birth_place        = [[Goldsboro, North Carolina|Goldsboro]], [[North Carolina]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"npr-bio\">{{cite web | title = Carl Kasell | url = https://www.npr.org/people/2100708/carl-kasell | publisher = [[NPR]] | access-date = 2011-04-11}}</ref>\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2018|04|17|1934|04|02}}\n| death_place        = [[Potomac, Maryland|Potomac]], [[Maryland]], U.S.\n| education          = \n| years_active       = 1975\u20132014\n| occupation         = Radio Newscaster\n| employer           = [[NPR]]\n| spouse             = Clara DeZorzi (m. 1959; died 1997)\nMary Ann Foster (m. 2003 - his death)\n| parents            = \n| children           = \n| nationality        = United States\n| website            = \n}}\n'''Carl Ray Kasell''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|\u00e6|s|\u0259l}}; April 2, 1934&nbsp;\u2013 April 17, 2018) was an [[Americans|American]] radio personality. He was best known as a newscaster for [[NPR|National Public Radio]], and later as the official judge and scorekeeper of the weekly news [[Game show|quiz show]] ''[[Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me!]]'' until his retirement in 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2014/03/04/285780588/after-five-decade-career-nprs-carl-kasell-will-retire|title=After 5-Decade Career, NPR's Carl Kasell Will Retire|last=Peralta|first=Eyder|date=2014-03-04|work=[[NPR]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418005507/https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2014/03/04/285780588/after-five-decade-career-nprs-carl-kasell-will-retire|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nA native of [[Goldsboro, North Carolina]], Carl Ray Kasell was a student of drama in high school, where one of his mentors was [[Andy Griffith]], then a high school drama instructor.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/carl-kasell-npr-broadcaster-who-brought-gravitas-and-goofiness-to-the-airwaves-dies-at-84/2018/04/17/173eecc2-3b49-11e8-a7d1-e4efec6389f0_story.html|title=Carl Kasell, NPR broadcaster who brought gravitas and goofiness to the airwaves, dies at 84|last=Bernstein|first=Adam|date=2018-04-17|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=2018-04-18|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Although Griffith urged Kasell to pursue a career in theatre, Kasell preferred radio. Kasell began practicing his newscaster voice as a child and got his first on-air job at 16.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/04/17/528656453/npr-newscaster-carl-kasell-dies-at-84-after-a-lifelong-career-on-air|title=NPR Newscaster Carl Kasell Dies At 84, After A Lifelong Career On-Air|last=[[Neda Ulaby]]|date=2018-04-17|work=[[NPR]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418000423/https://www.npr.org/2018/04/17/528656453/npr-newscaster-carl-kasell-dies-at-84-after-a-lifelong-career-on-air|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://wunc.org/post/ive-enjoyed-every-minute-it-carl-kasell-his-60-years-radio|title='I've Enjoyed Every Minute Of It': Carl Kasell On His 60 Years In Radio|date=2014-05-14|work=[[WUNC (FM)]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418000911/http://wunc.org/post/ive-enjoyed-every-minute-it-carl-kasell-his-60-years-radio#stream/0|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=|language=en}}</ref> In an interview with [[Ren\u00e9e Montagne]] just before his final broadcast on NPR's ''[[Morning Edition]]'', Kasell revealed that he knew he would be in radio at a young age. He said that he hid behind the radio to fool passers-by into thinking they were listening to the radio when they in fact were hearing the young Kasell.<ref name=\"NPR-sleep\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=122017544|title=Carl Kasell: After 30 Years, A Chance to Sleep In|date=December 30, 2009|publisher=NPR|access-date=2017-07-11}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]], Kasell helped launch local radio station [[WUNC (FM)|WUNC]] with fellow student and future broadcaster [[Charles Kuralt]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/article209144054.html|title=Carolina native, NPR newscaster Carl Kasell of 'Wait, Wait' dies at 84|last=Bennett|first=Abbie|date=2018-04-17|work=[[The News & Observer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418004905/http://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/article209144054.html|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=|language=en}}</ref> Kassell pursued a degree in [[English studies|English]], but never graduated due to being drafted into the U.S. Army.<ref name=\":4\" /> After serving, he worked as an announcer and DJ at radio station [[WGBR]] in Goldsboro, North Carolina.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> He moved to Northern Virginia in 1965.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==Career==\nAfter leaving North Carolina, Kasell advanced to the position of news director at [[WAVA (AM)|WAVA]] in Arlington, Virginia. As news director in Virginia, he hired [[Katie Couric]], then a student at the [[University of Virginia]], as an intern one summer, thus starting her career in news broadcasting.\n\nKasell joined [[NPR|National Public Radio]]'s staff as a news announcer for ''[[All Things Considered|Weekend All Things Considered]]'' in 1975.<ref name=\":1\" /> He was also the news announcer for NPR's ''[[Morning Edition]]'' from its inception in 1979 through 2009.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nOn November 23, 2009, NPR announced that Kasell would retire from newscasting at the end of 2009. Kasell's final newscast aired on December 30, 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2009/11/nprs_carl_kasell_leaving_newsc.html|title=NPR's Kasell Leaving Newscasts; Remains On 'Wait Wait'|last=Memmott|first=Mark|date=2009-11-23|work=[[NPR]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418005725/https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2009/11/nprs_carl_kasell_leaving_newsc.html|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=|language=en}}</ref> \nHe continued to work for NPR through fundraising and visits to member stations.<ref name=\"NPR-sleep\" />\nHe also continued to appear as the official scorer of ''Wait Wait&nbsp;... Don't Tell Me!''\n\n=== ''Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me!'' ===\nNPR launched its weekly news quiz ''[[Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me!]]'' in 1998, with Kasell as official judge and scorekeeper.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theringer.com/2018/1/4/16849150/wait-wait-dont-tell-me-npr-quiz-show|title='Wait Wait' ... Please Tell Me: The Story Behind NPR's Beloved Quiz Show|last=Varghese|first=Daniel|date=2018-01-04|work=[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418001825/https://www.theringer.com/2018/1/4/16849150/wait-wait-dont-tell-me-npr-quiz-show|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=}}</ref> Kasell featured in several segments including \"Who's Carl This Time?\" and the \"Listener Limerick Challenge.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/17/obituaries/carl-kasell-dies.html|title=Carl Kasell, NPR Newsman Who Discovered Laughs, Dies at 84|last=[[Robert D. McFadden]]|date=2018-04-17|work=[[The New York Times]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418001322/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/17/obituaries/carl-kasell-dies.html?mtrref=undefined&gwh=27BD4B51E642474A768978ACE89978C6&gwt=pay|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nPrior to October 21, 2017, listeners who won a game on the show could have Kasell record a greeting for their home answering machine or voice mail system. Because this prize has been such a long-standing tradition for the show, more than 2,000 people have had his voice on their answering machines, which he recorded even after he left the show.<ref name=\"NPR-sleep\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> The current prize is to have any show panelist or staff member of the contestant's choice record the greeting, including Kasell until his death.[[File:Carl Kasell Speaking in Nashville.jpg|thumb|left|Kasell speaking in Nashville, Tennessee, in 2009]]\n\nDuring the August 7, 2010, broadcast of ''Wait Wait&nbsp;... Don't Tell Me!'', host [[Peter Sagal]] announced that Kasell had been voted into the [[National Radio Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Opening Segment|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=129039403|work=Wait Wait Don't Tell Me|publisher=National Public Radio|access-date=7 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Carl Kasell Knocks Out Howard Stern in Voting |url=http://www.rbr.com/radio/26478.html |publisher=Radio Business Report |access-date=14 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100806011840/http://www.rbr.com/radio/26478.html |archivedate=6 August 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New Radio Hall of Famers: Cathy Hughes, Carl Kasell, Terri Hemmert, Ralph Emery |url=http://www.radio-info.com/news/new-radio-hall-of-famers-cathy-hughes-carl-kasell-terri-hemmert-ralph-emery# |work=Radio-Info.com |access-date=14 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100807091226/http://www.radio-info.com/news/new-radio-hall-of-famers-cathy-hughes-carl-kasell-terri-hemmert-ralph-emery |archivedate=7 August 2010 }}</ref>\n\nFor many years, Kasell was the announcer for the annual [[Kennedy Center Honors]] broadcast on [[CBS]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/carl-kasell-dead-longtime-voice-npr-morning-edition-was-84-1103571|title=Carl Kasell, Longtime Voice on NPR's 'Morning Edition, Dies at 84|last=Barnes|first=Mike|date=2018-04-17|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418005845/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/carl-kasell-dead-longtime-voice-npr-morning-edition-was-84-1103571|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, 2014, NPR announced that Kasell would be stepping down from his ''Wait Wait&nbsp;... Don't Tell Me!'' duties.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/about-npr/285327851/carl-kasell-to-retire-from-wait-wait-dont-tell-me-this-spring|title=Carl Kasell To Retire From 'Wait Wait&nbsp;... Don't Tell Me!' This Spring|date=2014-03-04|work=[[NPR]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418005953/https://www.npr.org/about-npr/285327851/carl-kasell-to-retire-from-wait-wait-dont-tell-me-this-spring|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=|language=en}}</ref> It was later announced that his last show would be May 17, 2014; subsequently he was credited on the air as \"Scorekeeper Emeritus\".<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Retirement and death ==\nKasell's final show on ''Wait Wait&nbsp;... Don't Tell Me!'' was recorded on May 15, 2014 and broadcast two days later. [[Stephen Colbert]], [[Katie Couric]], [[Tom Hanks]], and President [[Barack Obama]] called in to the show to voice their appreciation for Kasell.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn September 2014, Kasell published his memoir titled ''Wait Wait&nbsp;... I'm Not Done Yet!''<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nKasell died on April 17, 2018, from complications of [[Alzheimer's disease]] in [[Potomac, Maryland]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Awards==\n* 2004 \u2014 North Carolina Media & Journalism Hall of Fame\n*2010&nbsp;\u2014 [[National Radio Hall of Fame]]<ref name=\":4\" />\n* 2011 \u2014 Honorary Doctor of Humane Letters of the [[University of Southern Maine]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://usm.maine.edu/publicaffairs/usm-present-honorary-degrees-and-distinguished-achievement-awards-131st-commencement-m|title=USM to Present Honorary Degrees and Distinguished Achievement Awards at 131st Commencement on May 14|date=2011-05-11|website=[[University of Southern Maine]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418010143/https://usm.maine.edu/publicaffairs/usm-present-honorary-degrees-and-distinguished-achievement-awards-131st-commencement-m|archive-date=2018-04-18|url-status=}}</ref>\n* 2013&nbsp;\u2014 North Carolinian of the Year<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=2100708 NPR biography]\n*[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=111036549 NPR : Wait Wait -- Don't Tell Me! : Messages by Carl Kasell]\n*{{C-SPAN|Carl Kasell}}\n*[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/188912776/carl-ray-kasell  Find a Grave]\n\n{{NPR}}\n{{Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me! |state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kasell, Carl}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:American radio journalists]]\n[[Category:American game show hosts]]\n[[Category:NPR personalities]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Goldsboro, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Journalists from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Radio personalities from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me!]]\n[[Category:Deaths from Alzheimer's disease]]\n", "name_user": "RSkyWave", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Add details of work after locating to Northern Virginia", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Kasell"}
{"title_page": "Rule of product", "text_new": "[[File:Multiplication-principle.svg|thumb|upright|The elements of the set {A, B} can combine with the elements of the set {1, 2, 3} in six different ways.]]\nIn [[combinatorics]], the '''rule of product''' or '''multiplication principle''' is a basic [[combinatorial principles|counting principle]] (a.k.a. the '''fundamental principle of counting''').  Stated simply, it is the idea that if there are '''a''' ways of doing something and '''b''' ways of doing another thing, then there are '''a'''&nbsp;\u00b7&nbsp;'''b''' ways of performing both actions.<ref name=transition>Johnston, William, and Alex McAllister. ''A transition to advanced mathematics''. Oxford Univ. Press, 2009. Section 5.1</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtamu.edu/academic/anns/mps/math/mathlab/col_algebra/col_alg_tut55_count.htm|title=College Algebra Tutorial 55: Fundamental Counting Principle|accessdate= December 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Examples==\n:<math>\n\\begin{matrix}\n& \\underbrace{ \\left\\{A,B,C\\right\\} }\n& & \\underbrace{ \\left\\{ X,Y\\right\\} } \\\\\n\\mathrm{To}\\ \\mathrm{choose}\\ \\mathrm{one}\\ \\mathrm{of} & \\mathrm{these} &\n\\mathrm{AND}\\ \\mathrm{one}\\ \\mathrm{of} & \\mathrm{these}\n\\end{matrix}\n</math>\n\n:<math>\n\\begin{matrix}\n\\mathrm{is}\\ \\mathrm{to}\\ \\mathrm{choose}\\ \\mathrm{one}\\ \\mathrm{of} & \\mathrm{these}. \\\\\n& \\overbrace{ \\left\\{ AX, AY, BX, BY, CX, CY \\right\\} }\n\\end{matrix}</math>\n\nIn this example, the rule says: multiply 3 by 2, getting 6.\n\nThe sets {''A'', ''B'', ''C''} and {''X'', ''Y''} in this example are [[disjoint sets]], but that is not necessary.  The number of ways to choose a member of {''A'', ''B'', ''C''}, and then to do so again, in effect choosing an [[ordered pair]] each of whose components are in {''A'', ''B'', ''C''}, is 3&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;3&nbsp;=&nbsp;9.\n\nAs another example, when you decide to order pizza, you must first choose the type of crust: thin or deep dish (2 choices). Next, you choose one topping: cheese, pepperoni, or sausage (3&nbsp;choices).\n\nUsing the rule of product, you know that there are 2&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;3&nbsp;=&nbsp;6 possible combinations of ordering a pizza.\n\nOther typical example is using it with the [[rule of sum]], in this case we have two groups, the group '''A''' with '''3''' elements and the group '''B''' with '''10''' elements. We want to pick one element ( we don't care if it is from group A or B) and a second element that must be from the group B. The way that we can choose the elements are:\n\n:<math>\n\\mathrm{Total}\\ \\mathrm{ways} = (3*10) + (10*9)\n</math>\n\nFirst, we use the rule of product to get the number of ways if we pick an element from group '''A''' and then from group '''B'''. After this, we repeat the process but now choosing the first element from group \u2018\u2019\u2019B\u2019\u2019\u2019 and the second element, different from the one we now chose, also from group \u2018\u2019\u2019B\u2019\u2019\u2019 (as required) so we get \u2018\u2019\u2019B\u2019\u2019\u2019 times \u2018\u2019\u2019B-1\u2019\u2019\u2019 for the second product in the addition.\n\n==Applications==\nIn [[set theory]], this multiplication principle is often taken to be the definition of the product of [[cardinal number]]s.<ref name=transition />  We have\n\n:<math>|S_{1}|\\cdot|S_{2}|\\cdots|S_{n}| = |S_{1} \\times S_{2} \\times \\cdots \\times S_{n}| </math>\n\nwhere <math> \\times </math> is the [[Cartesian product]] operator.  These sets need not be finite, nor is it necessary to have only finitely many factors in the product; see [[cardinal number]].\n\n==Related concepts==\nThe [[rule of sum]] is another basic [[combinatorial principles|counting principle]].  Stated simply, it is the idea that if we have ''a'' ways of doing something and ''b'' ways of doing another thing and we can not do both at the same time, then there are ''a''&nbsp;+&nbsp;''b'' ways to choose one of the actions.<ref>Rosen, Kenneth H., ed. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=yJIMx9nXB6kC&pg=PA90&dq=%22Rule+of+product%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiTy-aJjq_fAhVKXKwKHc_3ASwQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=%22Rule%20of%20product%22&f=false Handbook of discrete and combinatorial mathematics].'' CRC pres, 1999.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Combinatorial principles]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Combinatorics]]\n[[Category:Mathematical principles]]\n\n[[fi:Todenn\u00e4k\u00f6isyysteoria#Tuloperiaate ja summaperiaate]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Multiplication-principle.svg|thumb|upright|The elements of the set {A, B} can combine with the elements of the set {1, 2, 3} in six different ways.]]\nIn [[combinatorics]], the '''rule of product''' or '''multiplication principle''' is a basic [[combinatorial principles|counting principle]] (a.k.a. the '''fundamental principle of counting''').  Stated simply, it is the idea that if there are '''a''' ways of doing something and '''b''' ways of doing another thing, then there are '''a'''&nbsp;\u00b7&nbsp;'''b''' ways of performing both actions.<ref name=transition>Johnston, William, and Alex McAllister. ''A transition to advanced mathematics''. Oxford Univ. Press, 2009. Section 5.1</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtamu.edu/academic/anns/mps/math/mathlab/col_algebra/col_alg_tut55_count.htm|title=College Algebra Tutorial 55: Fundamental Counting Principle|accessdate= December 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Examples==\n:<math>\n\\begin{matrix}\n& \\underbrace{ \\left\\{A,B,C\\right\\} }\n& & \\underbrace{ \\left\\{ X,Y\\right\\} } \\\\\n\\mathrm{To}\\ \\mathrm{choose}\\ \\mathrm{one}\\ \\mathrm{of} & \\mathrm{these} &\n\\mathrm{AND}\\ \\mathrm{one}\\ \\mathrm{of} & \\mathrm{these}\n\\end{matrix}\n</math>\n\n:<math>\n\\begin{matrix}\n\\mathrm{is}\\ \\mathrm{to}\\ \\mathrm{choose}\\ \\mathrm{one}\\ \\mathrm{of} & \\mathrm{these}. \\\\\n& \\overbrace{ \\left\\{ AX, AY, BX, BY, CX, CY \\right\\} }\n\\end{matrix}</math>\n\nIn this example, the rule says: multiply 3 by 2, getting 6.\n\nThe sets {''A'', ''B'', ''C''} and {''X'', ''Y''} in this example are [[disjoint sets]], but that is not necessary.  The number of ways to choose a member of {''A'', ''B'', ''C''}, and then to do so again, in effect choosing an [[ordered pair]] each of whose components are in {''A'', ''B'', ''C''}, is 3&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;3&nbsp;=&nbsp;9.\n\nAs another example, when you decide to order pizza, you must first choose the type of crust: thin or deep dish (2 choices). Next, you choose one topping: cheese, pepperoni, or sausage (3&nbsp;choices).\n\nUsing the rule of product, you know that there are 2&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;3&nbsp;=&nbsp;6 possible combinations of ordering a pizza.\n\nOther typical example is using it with the [[rule of sum]], in this case we have two groups, the group '''A''' with '''3''' elements and the group '''B''' with '''10''' elements. We want to pick one element ( we don't care if it is from group A or B) and a second element that must be from the group B. The way that we can chose the elements are:\n\n:<math>\n\\mathrm{Total}\\ \\mathrm{ways} = (3*10) + (10*9)\n</math>\n\nFirst, we use the rule of product to get the number of ways if we pick an element from group '''A''' and then from group '''B'''. After this, we repeat the process but now choosing the first element from group \u2018\u2019\u2019B\u2019\u2019\u2019 and the second element, different from the one we now chose, also from group \u2018\u2019\u2019B\u2019\u2019\u2019 (as required) so we get \u2018\u2019\u2019B\u2019\u2019\u2019 times \u2018\u2019\u2019B-1\u2019\u2019\u2019 for the second product in the addition.\n\n==Applications==\nIn [[set theory]], this multiplication principle is often taken to be the definition of the product of [[cardinal number]]s.<ref name=transition />  We have\n\n:<math>|S_{1}|\\cdot|S_{2}|\\cdots|S_{n}| = |S_{1} \\times S_{2} \\times \\cdots \\times S_{n}| </math>\n\nwhere <math> \\times </math> is the [[Cartesian product]] operator.  These sets need not be finite, nor is it necessary to have only finitely many factors in the product; see [[cardinal number]].\n\n==Related concepts==\nThe [[rule of sum]] is another basic [[combinatorial principles|counting principle]].  Stated simply, it is the idea that if we have ''a'' ways of doing something and ''b'' ways of doing another thing and we can not do both at the same time, then there are ''a''&nbsp;+&nbsp;''b'' ways to choose one of the actions.<ref>Rosen, Kenneth H., ed. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=yJIMx9nXB6kC&pg=PA90&dq=%22Rule+of+product%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiTy-aJjq_fAhVKXKwKHc_3ASwQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=%22Rule%20of%20product%22&f=false Handbook of discrete and combinatorial mathematics].'' CRC pres, 1999.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Combinatorial principles]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Combinatorics]]\n[[Category:Mathematical principles]]\n\n[[fi:Todenn\u00e4k\u00f6isyysteoria#Tuloperiaate ja summaperiaate]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExamples:Typo fixing, replaced: can chose \u2192 can choose", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rule_of_product"}
{"title_page": "Goff Richards", "text_new": "'''Goff Richards''' (18 August 1944 \u2013 25 June 2011),<ref>{{cite web |title=Goff Richards - New Songs, Playlists & Latest News - BBC Music |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/6020365a-828a-4359-93b2-64ca32b2ca69 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref> sometimes credited as '''Godfrey Richards''',<ref name=\"Dead\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cornwall-13927540 Cornish musician, composer & teacher Goff Richards dies], ''BBC News'', 28 June 2011</ref> was a prominent [[Cornish people|Cornish]] [[brass band]] arranger and composer.<ref name=\"MBB book\">{{cite book|last=Newsome|first=Roy|title=The modern brass band: from the 1930s to the new millennium|publisher=Ashgate Publishing Limited|location=Aldershot, Hants, England and Burlington, VT|year=2006|pages=128, 241, and passim|isbn=0-7546-0716-X|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O6-iHNQwga8C&pg=PA366 }}</ref><ref name=\"NBBC profile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalbrassbandchampionships.com/index.php?id=3&newsID=125|title=News - About Goff Richards|last=Anon|date=June 1, 2009|work=National Brass Band Championships website|publisher=Kapitol Promotions|accessdate=15 March 2010}}</ref> He was born in [[Cornwall]],<ref name=\"Dead\"/> studying at the [[Royal College of Music]] and [[Reading University]]. Between 1976 and 1989, he lectured in arranging and at [[Salford College of Technology]].<ref name=\"NBBC profile\"/>  He was the musical director of the [[Chetham's School of Music#Ensembles|Chetham's Big Band]] for many years. In 1976, he was made a Bard of the [[Cornish Gorsedd]]. He received a Doctorate from [[Salford University]] in 1990, after a career that had seen him lead the University Jazz Orchestra to the BBC Big Band of the Year title in 1989.\n\nHe was well known for his original brass compositions such as \"Trailblaze\", \"Doyen\", \"Exploding Brass!\" and the marches \"The Jaguar\" and \"Barnard Castle\", and won a [[European Broadcasting Union]] Award in 1984 for his \"Continental Caprice\".<ref name=\"Publisher\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reift.ch/fichiers/pdfcomposers/32.pdf|title=Profile|last=Anon|date=June 1, 2009|work=Marc Reift Editions website|publisher=Marc Reift Editions|accessdate=1 July 2010}}</ref> He was also a prolific arranger for brass bands, and his works included \"Hymns of Praise\", \"Shepherd's Song\", \"Over the Rainbow\", \"[[Mack the Knife]]\", \"New York, New York\", \"Chanson d'Amour\", \"I'll Walk with God\", and \"[[That's a Plenty]]\". He also arranged and composed [[light music|light]] orchestral and choral works, and his works have been performed by the [[King's Singers]], [[Huddersfield Choral Society]], [[London Brass]], [[Evelyn Glennie]] and various BBC orchestras.<ref name=\"Dead\"/><ref name=\"NBBC profile\"/>\n\nHe died on 25 June 2011 in [[Cheshire]], following an illness, at the age of 66.<ref name=\"Dead\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n*[http://www.reift.ch/fichiers/pdfcomposers/32.pdf Publisher's profile] Editions Marc Reift\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101120150905/http://www.haydockmvc.com/goff.htm Biography]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richards, Goff}}\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:Cornish composers]]\n[[Category:British music arrangers]]\n[[Category:Brass band composers]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Bards of Gorsedh Kernow]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Music]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Reading]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:English male classical composers]]\n[[Category:English classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "'''Goff Richards''' (18 August 1944 \u2013 25 June 2011),<ref>{{cite web |title=Goff Richards - New Songs, Playlists & Latest News - BBC Music |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/6020365a-828a-4359-93b2-64ca32b2ca69 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref> sometimes credited as '''Godfrey Richards''',<ref name=\"Dead\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cornwall-13927540 Cornish musician, composer & teacher Goff Richards dies], ''BBC News'', 28 June 2011</ref> was a prominent [[Cornish people|Cornish]] [[brass band]] arranger and composer.<ref name=\"MBB book\">{{cite book|last=Newsome|first=Roy|title=The modern brass band: from the 1930s to the new millennium|publisher=Ashgate Publishing Limited|location=Aldershot, Hants, England and Burlington, VT|year=2006|pages=128, 241, and passim|isbn=0-7546-0716-X|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O6-iHNQwga8C&pg=PA366 }}</ref><ref name=\"NBBC profile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalbrassbandchampionships.com/index.php?id=3&newsID=125|title=News - About Goff Richards|last=Anon|date=June 1, 2009|work=National Brass Band Championships website|publisher=Kapitol Promotions|accessdate=15 March 2010}}</ref> He was born in [[Cornwall]],<ref name=\"Dead\"/> studying at the [[Royal College of Music]] and [[Reading University]]. Between 1976 and 1989, he lectured in arranging and at [[Salford College of Technology]].<ref name=\"NBBC profile\"/>  He was the musical director of the [[Chetham's School of Music#Ensembles|Chetham's Big Band]] for many years. In 1976, he was made a Bard of the [[Cornish Gorsedd]]. He received a Doctorate from [[Salford University]] in 1990, after a career that had seen him lead the University Jazz Orchestra to the BBC Big Band of the Year title in 1989.\n\nHe was well known for his original brass compositions such as \"Trailblaze\", \"Doyen\", \"Exploding Brass!\" and the marches \"The Jaguar\" and \"Barnard Castle\", and won a [[European Broadcasting Union]] Award in 1984 for his \"Continental Caprice\".<ref name=\"Publisher\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reift.ch/fichiers/pdfcomposers/32.pdf|title=Profile|last=Anon|date=June 1, 2009|work=Marc Reift Editions website|publisher=Marc Reift Editions|accessdate=1 July 2010}}</ref> He was also a prolific arranger for brass bands, and his works included \"Hymns of Praise\", \"Shepherd's Song\", \"Over the Rainbow\", \"[[Mack the Knife]]\", \"New York, New York\", \"Chanson d'Amour\", \"I'll Walk with God\", and \"[[That's a Plenty]]\". He also arranged and composed [[light music|light]] orchestral and choral works, and his works have been performed by the [[King's Singers]], [[Huddersfield Choral Society]], [[London Brass]], [[Evelyn Glennie]] and various BBC orchestras.<ref name=\"Dead\"/><ref name=\"NBBC profile\"/>\n\nHe died on 25 June 2011 in [[Cheshire]], following an illness, at the age of 66.<ref name=\"Dead\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.reift.ch/fichiers/pdfcomposers/32.pdf Publisher's profile] Editions Marc Reift\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101120150905/http://www.haydockmvc.com/goff.htm Biography]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richards, Goff}}\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:Cornish composers]]\n[[Category:British music arrangers]]\n[[Category:Brass band composers]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Bards of Gorsedh Kernow]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Music]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Reading]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:English male classical composers]]\n[[Category:English classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goff_Richards"}
{"title_page": "SVOX", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Xbox}}\n{{notability|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox company |\n| name = SVOX\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| predecessor = SVOX GmbH\n| foundation = 2000 ([[Gesellschaft mit beschr\u00e4nkter Haftung|GmbH]]), 2001 ([[Aktiengesellschaft|AG]])\n| founder = Volker Jantzen<br />Christof Traber (GmbH)<ref>{{cite web|title=Internet-Auszug|last=Handelsregister des Kantons Z\u00fcrich|url=http://zh.powernet.ch/webservices/inet/HRG/HRG.asmx/getHRGHTML?chnr=0204021547a&amt=020&toBeModified=0&validOnly=0&lang=1&sort=0}}</ref> <br />Bettina Hein <br />Thomas Benz (AG) <ref>{{cite web|title=Internet-Auszug|last=Handelsregister des Kantons Z\u00fcrich|url=http://search.powernet.ch/webservices/net/HRG/HRG.asmx/getHRGHTML?chnr=CH-020.4.021.547-1&amt=020&toBeModified=0&validOnly=0&lang=1&sort=}}</ref>\n| location = [[Zurich]], [[Switzerland]]\n| area_served = Global\n| key_people = Martin Reber, <small>([[chief executive officer|CEO]])</small>\n| industry = [[Speech Processing]], [[Natural Language Processing]]\n| products = [[Speech Recognition]] (ASR), [[Speech Synthesis|Speech Output]] (TTS), Speech Dialog\n| num_employees = 90 <small>(2009)</small>\n}}\n:''For the Canadian media company, see [[S-VOX]].''\n'''SVOX''' is an embedded [[speech processing|speech technology]]  [[company]] founded in 2000 and headquartered in [[Zurich]], [[Switzerland]]. SVOX was acquired by [[Nuance Communications]] in 2011. The company's products included [[Speech Recognition|Automated Speech Recognition]] (ASR), [[Speech Synthesis|Text-to-Speech]] (TTS) and Speech Dialog systems, with customers mostly being manufacturers and system integrators in automotive and mobile device industries.\n\n==History==\nSVOX was started in 2000 by researchers at [[ETH Zurich|Federal Institute of Technology Zurich]] ([[ETH Zurich]]) and first focused exclusively on [[Speech Synthesis|Speech Output]] (TTS) solutions for [[automotive industry]].\n\nIn 2002 Siemens Mobile Acceleration (today's smac|partners GmbH) invested into SVOX.<ref>{{cite web|title=Erste Investition in der Schweiz Siemens Mobile Acceleration investiert in den Schweizer Text-to-Speech-Spezialisten SVOX AG|url=http://www.presseportal.ch/de/pm/100002664/100021140/erste-investition-in-der-schweiz-siemens-mobile-acceleration-investiert-in-den-schweizer-text-to|publisher=na presseportal}}</ref>\n\nLater, as the market for [[Personal navigation assistant|Personal Navigation Devices]] and [[smartphones]] developed, the company started to supply those markets as well. In 2008 SVOX released Pico, a small-footprint TTS system optimized for mobile phones.<ref>{{cite web|title=SVOX releases Pico: highest-quality sub-1 MB Text-to-Speech system available|url=http://www.pressebox.de/pressemitteilung/svox-ag/SVOX-releases-Pico-highest-quality-sub-1-MB-Text-to-Speech-system-available/boxid/217338|publisher=PresseBox}}</ref>\n\nIn parallel, SVOX has branched into [[Speech Recognition]] and Speech Dialog. As part of that process the company acquired Professional Speech Processing Group of [[Siemens|Siemens AG]] in early 2009.<ref>{{cite web|first=Adam|last=Boretz|title=SVOX Acquires Siemens' Speech Unit|url=http://www.speechtechmag.com/Articles/News/News-Feature/SVOX-Acquires-Siemens-Speech-Unit-52388.aspx|publisher=Speech Technology Magazine}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 SVOX made headlines with news that [[Google]] had chosen to include company's Pico TTS solution into the 1.6 release of [[Android (operating system)|Android platform]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Conneally|first=Tim|title=Android 'Donut' SDK released: What's new inside|url=http://betanews.com/2009/09/15/android-donut-sdk-released-what-s-new-inside/}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2011, [[Nuance Communications]] acquired SVOX.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nuance Press Release|title=Nuance acquires SVOX|url=http://www.nuance.com/company/news-room/press-releases/reutliweb.doc}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\nSVOX products include [[Speech Recognition|Automated Speech Recognition]] (ASR), [[Speech Synthesis|Text-to-Speech]] (TTS) and Speech Dialog systems. Typical uses include:\n* destination entry and voice directions in [[turn-by-turn navigation]] systems;\n* voice dialing and caller ID announcement in mobile phones and in-car telematics systems;\n* Point of Interest (POI) output and traffic information in navigation systems (PND and in-car).\nCompany's speech products are especially popular with German car makers such as [[Audi]], [[Porsche]], [[BMW]], [[Daimler AG|Daimler]] and [[VW]] and are often found in premium cars.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Comparison of speech synthesizers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.svox.com Official Company Website (now redirected to Nuance)]\n* [http://www.smacpartners.com/?p=598&lang=de smac|partners GmbH]\n\n{{Open Handset Alliance Members}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Svox}}\n[[Category:Software companies of Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Private equity firms]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Xbox}}\n{{notability|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox company |\n| name = SVOX\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| predecessor = SVOX GmbH\n| foundation = 2000 ([[Gesellschaft mit beschr\u00e4nkter Haftung|GmbH]]), 2001 ([[Aktiengesellschaft|AG]])\n| founder = Volker Jantzen<br />Christof Traber (GmbH)<ref>{{cite web|title=Internet-Auszug|last=Handelsregister des Kantons Z\u00fcrich|url=http://zh.powernet.ch/webservices/inet/HRG/HRG.asmx/getHRGHTML?chnr=0204021547a&amt=020&toBeModified=0&validOnly=0&lang=1&sort=0}}</ref> <br />Bettina Hein <br />Thomas Benz (AG) <ref>{{cite web|title=Internet-Auszug|last=Handelsregister des Kantons Z\u00fcrich|url=http://search.powernet.ch/webservices/net/HRG/HRG.asmx/getHRGHTML?chnr=CH-020.4.021.547-1&amt=020&toBeModified=0&validOnly=0&lang=1&sort=}}</ref>\n| location = [[Zurich]], [[Switzerland]]\n| area_served = Global\n| key_people = Martin Reber, <small>([[chief executive officer|CEO]])</small>\n| industry = [[Speech Processing]], [[Natural Language Processing]]\n| products = [[Speech Recognition]] (ASR), [[Speech Synthesis|Speech Output]] (TTS), Speech Dialog\n| num_employees = 90 <small>(2009)</small>\n}}\n:''For the Canadian media company, see [[S-VOX]].''\n'''SVOX''' is an embedded [[speech processing|speech technology]]  [[company]] founded in 2000 and headquartered in [[Zurich]], [[Switzerland]]. SVOX was acquired by [[Nuance Communications]] in 2011. The company\u2019s products included [[Speech Recognition|Automated Speech Recognition]] (ASR), [[Speech Synthesis|Text-to-Speech]] (TTS) and Speech Dialog systems, with customers mostly being manufacturers and system integrators in automotive and mobile device industries.\n\n==History==\nSVOX was started in 2000 by researchers at [[ETH Zurich|Federal Institute of Technology Zurich]] ([[ETH Zurich]]) and first focused exclusively on [[Speech Synthesis|Speech Output]] (TTS) solutions for [[automotive industry]].\n\nIn 2002 Siemens Mobile Acceleration (today's smac|partners GmbH) invested into SVOX.<ref>{{cite web|title=Erste Investition in der Schweiz Siemens Mobile Acceleration investiert in den Schweizer Text-to-Speech-Spezialisten SVOX AG|url=http://www.presseportal.ch/de/pm/100002664/100021140/erste-investition-in-der-schweiz-siemens-mobile-acceleration-investiert-in-den-schweizer-text-to|publisher=na presseportal}}</ref>\n\nLater, as the market for [[Personal navigation assistant|Personal Navigation Devices]] and [[smartphones]] developed, the company started to supply those markets as well. In 2008 SVOX released Pico, a small-footprint TTS system optimized for mobile phones.<ref>{{cite web|title=SVOX releases Pico: highest-quality sub-1 MB Text-to-Speech system available|url=http://www.pressebox.de/pressemitteilung/svox-ag/SVOX-releases-Pico-highest-quality-sub-1-MB-Text-to-Speech-system-available/boxid/217338|publisher=PresseBox}}</ref>\n\nIn parallel, SVOX has branched into [[Speech Recognition]] and Speech Dialog. As part of that process the company acquired Professional Speech Processing Group of [[Siemens|Siemens AG]] in early 2009.<ref>{{cite web|first=Adam|last=Boretz|title=SVOX Acquires Siemens' Speech Unit|url=http://www.speechtechmag.com/Articles/News/News-Feature/SVOX-Acquires-Siemens-Speech-Unit-52388.aspx|publisher=Speech Technology Magazine}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 SVOX made headlines with news that [[Google]] had chosen to include company\u2019s Pico TTS solution into the 1.6 release of [[Android (operating system)|Android platform]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Conneally|first=Tim|title=Android 'Donut' SDK released: What's new inside|url=http://betanews.com/2009/09/15/android-donut-sdk-released-what-s-new-inside/}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2011, [[Nuance Communications]] acquired SVOX.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nuance Press Release|title=Nuance acquires SVOX|url=http://www.nuance.com/company/news-room/press-releases/reutliweb.doc}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\nSVOX products include [[Speech Recognition|Automated Speech Recognition]] (ASR), [[Speech Synthesis|Text-to-Speech]] (TTS) and Speech Dialog systems. Typical uses include:\n* destination entry and voice directions in [[turn-by-turn navigation]] systems;\n* voice dialing and caller ID announcement in mobile phones and in-car telematics systems;\n* Point of Interest (POI) output and traffic information in navigation systems (PND and in-car).\nCompany\u2019s speech products are especially popular with German car makers such as [[Audi]], [[Porsche]], [[BMW]], [[Daimler AG|Daimler]] and [[VW]] and are often found in premium cars.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Comparison of speech synthesizers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.svox.com Official Company Website (now redirected to Nuance)]\n* [http://www.smacpartners.com/?p=598&lang=de smac|partners GmbH]\n\n{{Open Handset Alliance Members}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Svox}}\n[[Category:Software companies of Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Private equity firms]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SVOX"}
{"title_page": "BMW 5 Series (E28)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = BMW 5 Series (E28)\n| image = 1983 BMW 528i (E28) sedan (21539857803).jpg\n| production = 1981&ndash;1988\n| assembly = {{unbulleted list\n| Germany: [[BMW Group Plant Dingolfing|Dingolfing]]\n| South Africa: [[Rosslyn, Gauteng|Rosslyn]]}}\n| class = [[Executive car]] ([[E-segment|E]])\n| body_style = 4-door [[sedan (automobile)|sedan]]\n| layout = [[Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|FR layout]]\n| related = [[BMW 6 Series (E24)]]\n| engine = {{ubl || '''[[Petrol engine|Petrol:]]''' || 1.8&nbsp;L ''[[BMW M10|M10]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] || 2.0-3.5&nbsp;L ''[[BMW M20|M20]]''/''[[BMW M30|M30]]''/''[[BMW M88|M88]]''/''[[BMW S38|S38]]'' [[Straight-six engine|I6]] || '''[[Diesel engine|Diesel:]]''' || 2.4&nbsp;L ''[[BMW M21|M21]]'' I6 }}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2625|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|4620|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1700|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1415|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| predecessor = [[BMW 5 Series (E12)]]\n| successor = [[BMW 5 Series (E34)]]\n}}\n\nThe '''BMW E28''' is the second generation of [[BMW 5 Series]] executive cars,<ref>{{cite web|title=1982 BMW 528e specifications|url=http://www.automobile-catalog.com/car/1982/263675/bmw_528e.html|website=www.automobile-catalog.com}}</ref> which was produced from 1981 to 1988 and replaced the [[BMW 5 Series (E12)|E12 5 Series]].\n\nThe E28 was initially produced with straight-four and straight-six petrol engines until 1983, when the 524td model became the first BMW car to be powered by a diesel engine. It was also the first 5 Series with the centre console angled towards the driver and to be available with [[anti-lock brakes]] (ABS).<ref>{{cite web|title=The BMW 5 Series History. The 2nd Generation (E28)|url=https://youtube.com/XgCtQVQ26VM?t=18s|website=www.youtube.com/BMW|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe first [[BMW M5#E28|BMW M5]] was produced during the E28 generation. It was powered by the [[BMW M88|M88/3]] and [[BMW S38|S38]] straight-six engines. The [[BMW 6 Series (E24)|E24 6 Series]] coup\u00e9s were built on the E28 platform from 1982\u20131989. \n\nThe E28 was replaced by the [[BMW 5 Series (E34)|E34 5 Series]] in 1988.\n\n== Body and interior ==\nThe E28 has a self-supporting body that is welded to the body platform. The passenger cell is a safety passenger cell with deformation elements both in the front and rear of the vehicle. Unlike its E12 predecessor and E34 successor, the E28 has a rear-hinged bonnet. The boot has a volume of {{convert|460|litre|gal|0|abbr=on}}. Most models have a fuel tank capacity of {{convert|70|litre|gal|0|abbr=on}},<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" /> with some models having a smaller tank of {{convert|63|litre|gal|0|}}. The kerb weight is {{convert|1140|\u2013|1410|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW E28 5 Series 518i Specs|url=https://www.ultimatespecs.com/car-specs/BMW/1360/BMW--518i.html|website=www.ultimatespecs.com|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nCruise control, an 'on-board computer' (to display trip information) and a \"check control\" panel (to alert the driver about fluid levels and lighting faults) were introduced to the 5 Series on the E28. The glazing is made of single-pane safety glass, the windscreen has laminated glass.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" /> As part of developing the air-conditioning system for the E28, several of the BMW engineers in charge of this program drove a previous generation E12 5 Series during the middle of summer in Texas. The E12 528i was painted black with a black interior, and driven {{convert|500|mi|km|0|abbr=on}} in one day.<ref name=OBC86>{{citation | ref = RT86 | title = Road & Track On BMW Cars 1979-1983 | date = 1986 | publisher = CBS Publications | location = Greenwich, CT | page = 56 }}</ref>\n\nThe styling was developed under BMW's chief designer [[Claus Luthe]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Caspers |first1=Markus |title=Designing Motion: Automotive Designers 1890 to 1990 |date=2017 |publisher=Birkh\u00e4user |isbn=9783035607840 |page=134 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B9UXDQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA1&pg=PA134#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=18 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref> with development of the E28 beginning in 1975.<ref>{{cite web |title=BMW Classic - Recherche-Client |url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3824021 |website=bmw-grouparchiv.de |accessdate=22 November 2019 |language=German}}</ref> At the time that BMW was designing the E28, the company had only one computer, which was used for payroll management and spare parts logistics. Wolfgang Matschinsky and his team borrowed that computer to perform the calculations necessary to develop the new drivetrain and chassis. This was due to the fact that the addition of an ABS system necessitated a redesign from the previous model due to excessive vibrations under heavy braking.<ref>{{Citation|title=The BMW 5 Series History. The 2nd Generation (E28)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XgCtQVQ26VM|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> \n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"150px\" style=\"text-align:left\">\nFile:1983 BMW 528i (E28) sedan (24955078763).jpg |Rear view\nFile:525i innen.jpg |Interior\n</gallery>\n\n== Engines ==\nThe E28 was the first 5 Series produced with diesel engines (the 524d and 524td models) and with a petrol engined model specifically aimed at increased fuel economy (525e/528e model).\n\nThe four models available at the launch of the E28 were the 518, 520i, 525i and 528i,<ref>BMW: [https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/media/cdd55d90-1cc5-4456-a984-4ef3b84ad22e/web 518 520i 525i 528i]. February 1982</ref> with the 518 using a straight-four petrol engine and the other three models using a straight-six petrol engine. Over the course of the E28 model, the following models were added: the 524d and 524td using diesel engines, the 518i (a fuel-injected version of the 518), the 525e/528e as fuel-economy models, and the upper-specification 533i, 535i, M535i, and M5 models.\n\nA liquid petroleum gas (LPG) option was introduced for some petrol engines in 1984.<ref>{{cite web |title=5er BMW mit Autogasanlage |url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=6628055 |website=bmw-grouparchiv.de |accessdate=22 November 2019 |language=German}}</ref>\n\n=== Petrol ===\n{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| width = 220px\n| image1 = BMW M20 Engine.JPG\n| caption1 = [[BMW M20]] straight-six engine\n| image2 = BMW M5 E28 Minervablau Motorraum.jpg\n| caption2 = [[BMW M88|BMW M88/3]] straight-six engine\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! Model !! Engine !! Power !! Torque !! Fuel supply !! Years\n|-\n|518 || rowspan=2|[[BMW M10#M10B18|M10B18]] <br/> 4-cyl|| {{convert|66|kW|PS|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 5500 rpm|| {{convert|140|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4000 rpm || Pierburg 2BE <br/> [[carburettor]] || 1981-1984\n|-\n|518i || {{convert|77|kW|PS|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 5800 rpm || {{convert|145|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4500 rpm || [[Jetronic#L|L-Jetronic]] || 1981\u20131987\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 520i || rowspan=\"4\" |[[BMW M20#M20B20|M20B20]] <br/> 6-cyl || rowspan=\"2\" | {{convert|92|kW|PS|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 5800 rpm || {{convert|165|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4500 rpm || [[Jetronic#K|K-Jetronic]] || 1981\u20131982\n|-\n| {{convert|170|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4000 rpm || [[Jetronic#L|L-Jetronic]] || 1982-1987\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | {{convert|95|kW|PS|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 6000 rpm || {{convert|174|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 4000 rpm || [[Jetronic#LE|LE-Jetronic]] || 1985-1988\n|-\n| {{convert|164|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 4300 rpm || [[Motronic]] || 1986-1988\n|-\n|525i || [[BMW M30#M30B25|M30B25]] <br/> 6-cyl || {{convert|110|kW|PS|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 5500 rpm || {{convert|215|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 4000 rpm || [[Jetronic#L|L-Jetronic]] || 1981\u20131987\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |&nbsp; 525e / <br />528e|| rowspan=\"4\" | [[BMW M20#M20B27|M20B27]] <br/> 6-cyl || {{convert|92|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 4250 rpm || {{convert|240|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 3250 rpm || [[Motronic]] || 1982\u20131987 \n|-\n|{{convert|90|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 4250 rpm || {{convert|230|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 3250 rpm || [[Jetronic#L|L-Jetronic]], <br/> [[Motronic]] || 1982\u20131987\n|-\n|{{convert|95|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 4250 rpm || {{convert|240|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 3250 rpm || [[Motronic]] || 1984\u20131988\n|-\n|525e || {{convert|88|kW|PS|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4250 rpm || {{convert|240|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 3250 rpm || [[Motronic]] || 1985\u20131987\n|-\n|528i || [[BMW M30#M30B28|M30B28]] <br/> 6-cyl || {{convert|135|kW|PS|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 5800 rpm || {{convert|240|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4200 rpm || [[Jetronic#L|L-Jetronic]] || 1981\u20131987\n|-\n| &nbsp; 533i<ref>BMW: [https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/media/abdc109b-ddc2-441b-9701-9438b65de2ac/web BMW 528e, 533i]</ref> || [[BMW M30#M30B32|M30B32]] <br/> 6-cyl || {{convert|135|kW|PS|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 6000 rpm || {{convert|265|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4000 rpm || [[Motronic]] || 1982\u20131984\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |535i, <br /> M535i || rowspan=\"2\" | [[BMW M30#M30B34|M30B34]] <br/> 6-cyl || {{convert|160|kW|PS|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 5500 || {{convert|310|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4000 rpm || [[Motronic]] || 1985\u20131988\n|-\n|{{convert|182|hp|kW|disp=flip|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 5400 rpm || {{convert|290|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4000 rpm || [[Motronic]] || 1985\u20131988 (US)\n|-\n| M5 || [[BMW M88|M88/3]] <br/> 6-cyl || {{convert|210|kW|PS|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at  6500 rpm<ref>[https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3943080 BMW M88/3 Automobilmotor]</ref>|| {{convert|340|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4500 rpm|| [[Motronic]] || 1985\u20131988\n|-\n| M5 || [[BMW S38|S38B35]] <br/> 6-cyl || {{convert|256|hp|kW|disp=flip|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 6500 rpm<ref>BMW: [https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3944267 S38B35 Automobilmotor]</ref> || {{convert|330|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4500 rpm || [[Motronic]] || 1986\u20131988 (US)\n|}\n\n'''518:''' Sold only in some European markets where it suited local tax categories, the 518 was the lowest specification model which used a four-cylinder engine with a [[carburettor|carburetor]]. Factory performance figures for the manual transmission cars are a top speed of {{convert|164|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 14.0 seconds.<ref name=\"E28_518\">[https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/media/dd27a20d-f46a-4795-a968-dda29aa39fbd/web 518, 520i, 525i, 528i]. Pages 6 and 50</ref>\n\n'''518i:''' The base model in Japan and some European countries, the 518i used a fuel-injected four-cylinder engine. Factory performance figures for the manual transmission cars are a top speed of {{convert|175|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 12.6 seconds.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />  This version was not sold in Germany until the 1984 facelift, when it replaced the carburetted 518.\n\n'''520i:''' A mid-range model with the smallest of the available six-cylinder engines. Factory performance figures for the manual transmission cars are a top speed of {{convert|190|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 11.4 seconds.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n'''525e / 528e:''' The 525e (called 528e in North America and Japan) uses a 2.7-litre 6-cylinder [[BMW M20|M20]] petrol engine which is optimised for fuel economy and torque at low engine speed, rather than the traditional high revving characteristics of BMW straight-six engines.<ref>{{cite web|title=Curbside Classic: 1984 BMW 528e \u2013 The Low Rev Modest Driving Machine|url=http://www.curbsideclassic.com/curbside-classics-european/curbside-classic-1986-bmw-528e-the-low-rev-modest-driving-machine/|website=www.curbsideclassic.com|accessdate=15 May 2017}}</ref> The \"e\" stands for the Greek letter ''eta'', for economy. According to BMW, the 525e is more fuel efficient than the 520i, which has the same rated power of 92&nbsp;kW.<ref>BMW: ''[https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/media/14f2b16b-55f6-4221-95a2-94dab1671eda/web 525e 525e Katalysator]''. 1985</ref> Since many markets tax cars based on engine displacement, the eta's larger engine meant that it was not suitable everywhere. The model was expressly developed with the American market in mind. BMW's [[corporate average fuel economy]] was at risk of not meeting requirements by 1984, primarily due to higher sales of their bigger, more expensive cars in the early 1980s.<ref name=AG941>{{cite magazine | ref = AG94 | magazine = De AutoGids | number = 94 | volume = 4 | page = 130 | title = BMW: Met de ETA op de zuinige tor | trans-title = BMW: With Eta on an economy run | first = Vic | last = Heylen | language = Dutch | date = 1983-04-28 | publisher = Uitgeverij Auto-Magazine | location = Brussels, Belgium }}</ref> In Austria, the 525e was detuned to {{convert|88|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nFactory performance figures for the manual transmission cars without a catalytic converter are a top speed of {{convert|190|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 10.7 seconds. With a catalytic converter, the figures are a top speed of {{convert|188|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 11.3 seconds<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n'''525i:''' This mid-range model is powered by a 2.5-litre 6-cylinder engine. The 525i was only sold in Europe. Factory performance figures for the manual transmission cars are a top speed of {{convert|201|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 9.8 seconds.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n'''528i:''' Initially the highest specification available, the 6-cylinder 528i became a mid-range model following the release of the 533i and 535i models. Factory performance figures for the manual transmission cars are a top speed of {{convert|215|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 8.4 seconds.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n'''533i:'''\nOnly sold in Japan and North America,<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW E28 5 Series 533i (US) Specs|url=https://www.ultimatespecs.com/car-specs/BMW/1408/BMW-E28-5-Series-533i-(US).html|website=www.ultimatespecs.com|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1984 BMW 533i E28 specifications|url=http://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=227689|website=www.carfolio.com|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> the 6-cylinder 533i was the highest specification model during its production years of 1983\u20131984. It was replaced by the 535i.\n\n'''535i:''' Released in 1984, the 535i replaced the 533i and uses the same 6-cylinder drivetrain as the M535i. Factory performance figures for the manual transmission cars without a catalytic converter are a top speed of {{convert|225|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 7.2 seconds. With a catalytic converter, the figures are a top speed of {{convert|212|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 7.9 seconds<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n[[File:1986 BMW M535i (E28) sedan (2015-06-04) 01.jpg|thumb|right|M535i]]\n'''M535i:''' The top of the regular production model range, the M535i uses the drivetrain from the 535i plus M-Technic suspension, and wheels and body panels not found on any other E28. The M535i was assembled on the standard E28 assembly lines in Dingolfing and Rosslyn. Factory performance figures for the manual transmission cars without a catalytic converter are a top speed of {{convert|230|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 7.2 seconds. With a catalytic converter, the figures are a top speed of {{convert|217|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 7.9 seconds<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n{{clear right}}\n\n=== Diesel ===\n[[File:BMW_E28_engine_2_16.09_JM.jpg|thumb|right|[[BMW M21]] straight-six engine]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! Model !! Engine !! Power !! Torque !! Aspiration !! Years\n|-\n|524d || rowspan=2|[[BMW M21|M21D24]] <br/> 6-cyl || {{convert|63|kW|hp|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4600 rpm || {{convert|152|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 2500 rpm || [[Naturally aspirated engine|naturally <br/> aspirated]] || 1985\u20131987\n|-\n|524td || {{convert|85|kW|hp|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4800 rpm || {{convert|210|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 2400 rpm || [[turbocharger|turbo]] || 1983\u20131988\n|}\n\n'''524d:''' At the 1986 [[Geneva Motor Show]], four years after the introduction of the more powerful 524td model, the naturally-aspirated 524d model was introduced.<ref name=\"AR87\">{{cite book | title = Automobil Revue 1987 | editor-last = B\u00fcschi | editor-first = Hans-Ulrich | publisher = Hallwag AG | location = Berne, Switzerland | language = German, French | volume = 82 | date = March 5, 1987 | isbn = 3-444-00458-3 }}</ref>{{rp|188,190}} It was only sold in some markets.<ref name=\"AR87\" />{{rp|191}}\n\n'''524td:''' This [[turbodiesel]] model was the first diesel car produced by BMW. It entered production in late 1982, when 100 pre-series cars were built.<ref name=\"AK84\">{{cite book | title = Auto Katalog 1984 | editor-last = Heitz | editor-first = Rudolf | publisher = [[:de:Motor Presse Stuttgart|Vereinigte Motor-Verlage GmbH & Co. KG]] | location = Stuttgart | page = 242 | volume = 27 | language = German | year = 1983 }}</ref> Factory performance figures for the manual transmission cars are a top speed of {{convert|180|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 12.9 seconds.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n== Drivetrain ==\nBMW offered the E28 with both manual and automatic gearboxes. The torque is transmitted from the engine with a single-disc dry clutch with a torsional damper in the models with a manual gearbox, the automatic models have a torque converter with built in lockup-clutch.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n;Manual transmissions\nThe 4-speed manual transmissions are:<ref>{{cite web|title=5' E28 model selection|url=http://www.realoem.com/bmw/en/select?product=P&archive=1&series=E28&body=Lim|website=www.realoem.com}}</ref>\n* [[Getrag]] 242 (for M10 and M20 engine models)\n* Getrag 262 (M30 engines)\n\nThe 5-speed manual transmissions are:\n* Getrag 240 (M10 and M21 engines)\n* Getrag 245 (M10 engines)\n* [[Getrag 260 transmission|Getrag 260]] (M20, M21 and M30 engines)\n* Getrag 265 (M30 engines and 525e/528e)\n* Getrag 280 (M88/3 and S38 engines)\n* [[List of ZF transmissions|ZF]] S5-16 (M20 engines)\n\n;Automatic transmissions\nThe 3-speed automatic transmissions are:\n* [[ZF 3HP22 transmission|ZF 3HP22]] (M20 and M30 engines, US market only)\n\nThe 4-speed automatic transmissions are:\n* [[ZF 4HP22 transmission|ZF 4HP22]] (M10, M20, M21)\n* [[ZF 4HP22 transmission|ZF 4HP22]] EH (M20, M30)\n\n== Suspension ==\nIndependent front and rear suspension is used, with [[Macpherson strut]]s at the front and a [[trailing arm#Semi-trailing arm|semi-trailing arm]] design for the rear.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\">{{citation|publisher=BMW AG |title=Betriebsanleitung, Serviceheft 518, 520i, 525e, 525i, 528i, 535i, M535i, 524td |date=1985 |language=German |url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3058985 |access-date=20 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe front suspension was upgraded to use dual links at the bottom of the strut, as first seen on the [[BMW 7 Series (E23)|E23 7 Series]]. This increases steering offset while cornering, to improve steering feel.<ref name=\"noakes\">{{cite book|last1=Noakes|first1=Andrew|title=The Ultimate History of BMW|date=2008}}</ref>{{refpage|page=106}} Double-acting shock absorbers, coil springs and a front [[anti-roll bar]] are used.\n\nThe rear suspension is mounted on a delta beam that is connected to the body with three screws in rubber bearings, that have longitudinal play.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} Some models have a rear anti-roll bar.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\nThe steering on most models is a speed-dependent [[recirculating ball]] power steering system made by ZF Friedrichshafen. The 518i has a Gemmer steering system with a double enveloping worm gear, also made by ZF.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\nWheel sizes are 14-inch (16-inch for the M5 model) or 390&nbsp;mm [[Michelin TRX]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Taylor|first1=James|title=BMW M5- The Complete Story|date=2015}}</ref>{{refpage|page=44}}<ref>{{cite web|title=1981  BMW E28 5 Series 525i Specs|url=http://www.ultimatespecs.com/car-specs/BMW/230/BMW-E28-5-Series-525i.html|website=www.ultimatespecs.com|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1984 BMW E28 5 Series 535i Specs|url=http://www.ultimatespecs.com/car-specs/BMW/1409/BMW-E28-5-Series-535i.html|website=www.ultimatespecs.com|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref> All rims have 22&nbsp;mm positive rim offset.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n== Brakes ==\nThe brakes use a hydraulic dual-circuit brake system with power assistance. The front wheels have disc brakes, that are \u2013 except for the 518i<!--518 and 524d as well?--> \u2013 internally ventilated. All models with 2.5&nbsp;l or more displacement have rear disc brakes (non-vented), while the lesser powered models have rear drum brakes. To prevent the wheels from locking, BMW equipped the E28 after 1984 with an [[anti-lock braking system]], although it was an option in some markets.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n== M5 model ==\n[[File:BMW M5 E28 Minervablau.jpg|thumb|right|M5 model]]\n{{main|BMW M5#E28 M5 (1985\u20131987)}}\nThe E28 was the first M5 model produced, and is powered by the [[BMW M88|M88/3]] and [[BMW S38|S38]] straight-six engines.\n{{clear right}}\n\n== North American market models ==\n[[File:BMW-535is.jpg|thumb|right|BMW 535is (North America)]]\n[[File:M5sig (E28).jpg|thumb|North American M5 fitted with European market headlights]]\nThe North American line-up consisted of the '''528e''' (1982-1988, known as the 525e in Europe), '''533i''' (1983-1984), '''535i''' (1985-1988), '''524td''' (1985-1986), '''M5''' (1986-1987) and '''535is''' (1987-1988).\n\nThe launch model was the 528e in 1982, followed by the 533i.<ref>{{cite web|title=1984 BMW 533i E28 Specifications|url=http://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=227689|website=www.carfolio.com|accessdate=22 November 2017}}</ref> The optional automatic transmission was initially a 3-speed (a 4-speed automatic was available in Europe at the time), with a 4-speed automatic transmission becoming optional in 1983. From 1985, all North American models had ABS Brakes as standard.\n\nThe North American E28 models had larger bumpers (designed to withstand a {{convert|5|mph|abbr=on}} collision without body damage), which increased the overall length by {{convert|180|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nThe 528i, 533i and 535i were sold with a [[catalytic converter]] in the United States.\n\nInstead of importing the M535i, BMW of North America created the 535is.<ref>{{cite web|title=1985 BMW E28 5 Series 535is (US) Specs|url=http://www.ultimatespecs.com/car-specs/BMW/1413/BMW-E28-5-Series-535is-(US).html|website=www.ultimatespecs.com|accessdate=22 November 2017}}</ref> This model is based on a 535i, plus front and rear spoilers, sport suspension and sport seats.\n\nProduction of North American market M5 models began in late 1986 (two years after M5 production began for European markets), and it was only produced for twelve months as 1988 [[model year]] car.<ref>{{cite web|title=1988 BMW M5 values|url=https://www.hagerty.com/apps/ValuationTools/1988-BMW-M5|website=www.hagerty.com|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref> North American M5 models use the S38 engine instead of the M88/3.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Taylor|first1=James|title=BMW M5 - The Complete Story|date=2015|isbn=978 1 78500 045 4}}</ref>{{refpage|page=37}} All North American M5 cars were painted Jet Black and most interiors were tan (\"Natur\") coloured leather.<ref>{{cite web|title=FAQ E28 M5|url=https://www.bmwmregistry.com/model_faq.php?id=7|website=www.bmwmregistry.com|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\nE28 production started in July 1981 and ended in December 1987.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Taylor|first1=James|title=BMW M5: The Complete Story|date=February 2016|publisher=The Crowood Press UK|location=Ramsbury, Marlborough Wiltshire|isbn=1785000462|url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1785000462|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref> A total of 722,328 cars were built.<ref name=DeAutos45bis90Oswald>{{cite book |last=Oswald |first=Werner |authorlink= |coauthors= |title= Deutsche Autos 1945\u20131990, Band 4, 1. Auflage|year=2001 |publisher=Motorbuch Verlag |location=Stuttgart |isbn=3-613-02131-5}}</ref>\n\nThe E28 was still sold in North America as a 1988 Model Year car after its E34 successor had been released in Europe in early 1988. A limited edition model was also sold in South Africa from mid-1987 to the end of 1988.<ref>{{cite web|title=M5 E28|url=http://www.africanmusclecars.com/index.php/bmw/m5-e28|website=www.africanmusclecars.com|accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{BMW cars: 1980s to 2000s}}\n[[Category:BMW vehicles|5 Series (E28)]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1981]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = BMW 5 Series (E28)\n| image = 1983 BMW 528i (E28) sedan (21539857803).jpg\n| production = 1981&ndash;1988\n| assembly = {{unbulleted list\n| Germany: [[BMW Group Plant Dingolfing|Dingolfing]]\n| South Africa: [[Rosslyn, Gauteng|Rosslyn]]}}\n| class = [[Executive car]] ([[E-segment|E]])\n| body_style = 4-door [[sedan (automobile)|sedan]]\n| layout = [[Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|FR layout]]\n| related = [[BMW 6 Series (E24)]]\n| engine = {{ubl || '''[[Petrol engine|Petrol:]]''' || 1.8&nbsp;L ''[[BMW M10|M10]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] || 2.0-3.5&nbsp;L ''[[BMW M20|M20]]''/''[[BMW M30|M30]]''/''[[BMW M88|M88]]''/''[[BMW S38|S38]]'' [[Straight-six engine|I6]] || '''[[Diesel engine|Diesel:]]''' || 2.4&nbsp;L ''[[BMW M21|M21]]'' I6 }}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2625|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|4620|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1700|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1415|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| predecessor = [[BMW 5 Series (E12)]]\n| successor = [[BMW 5 Series (E34)]]\n}}\n\nThe '''BMW E28''' is the second generation of [[BMW 5 Series]] executive cars,<ref>{{cite web|title=1982 BMW 528e specifications|url=http://www.automobile-catalog.com/car/1982/263675/bmw_528e.html|website=www.automobile-catalog.com}}</ref> which was produced from 1981 to 1988 and replaced the [[BMW 5 Series (E12)|E12 5 Series]].\n\nThe E28 was initially produced with straight-four and straight-six petrol engines until 1983, when the 524td model became the first BMW car to be powered by a diesel engine. It was also the first 5 Series with the centre console angled towards the driver and to be available with [[anti-lock brakes]] (ABS).<ref>{{cite web|title=The BMW 5 Series History. The 2nd Generation (E28)|url=https://youtube.com/XgCtQVQ26VM?t=18s|website=www.youtube.com/BMW|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe first [[BMW M5#E28|BMW M5]] was produced during the E28 generation. It was powered by the [[BMW M88|M88/3]] and [[BMW S38|S38]] straight-six engines. The [[BMW 6 Series (E24)|E24 6 Series]] coup\u00e9s were built on the E28 platform from 1982-1989. \n\nThe E28 was replaced by the [[BMW 5 Series (E34)|E34 5 Series]] in 1988.\n\n== Body and interior ==\nThe E28 has a self-supporting body that is welded to the body platform. The passenger cell is a safety passenger cell with deformation elements both in the front and rear of the vehicle. Unlike its E12 predecessor and E34 successor, the E28 has a rear-hinged bonnet. The boot has a volume of {{convert|460|litre|gal|0|abbr=on}}. Most models have a fuel tank capacity of {{convert|70|litre|gal|0|abbr=on}},<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" /> with some models having a smaller tank of {{convert|63|litre|gal|0|}}. The kerb weight is {{convert|1140|\u2013|1410|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW E28 5 Series 518i Specs|url=https://www.ultimatespecs.com/car-specs/BMW/1360/BMW--518i.html|website=www.ultimatespecs.com|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nCruise control, an 'on-board computer' (to display trip information) and a \"check control\" panel (to alert the driver about fluid levels and lighting faults) were introduced to the 5 Series on the E28. The glazing is made of single-pane safety glass, the windscreen has laminated glass.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" /> As part of developing the air-conditioning system for the E28, several of the BMW engineers in charge of this program drove a previous generation E12 5 Series during the middle of summer in Texas. The E12 528i was painted black with a black interior, and driven {{convert|500|mi|km|0|abbr=on}} in one day.<ref name=OBC86>{{citation | ref = RT86 | title = Road & Track On BMW Cars 1979-1983 | date = 1986 | publisher = CBS Publications | location = Greenwich, CT | page = 56 }}</ref>\n\nThe styling was developed under BMW's chief designer [[Claus Luthe]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Caspers |first1=Markus |title=Designing Motion: Automotive Designers 1890 to 1990 |date=2017 |publisher=Birkh\u00e4user |isbn=9783035607840 |page=134 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B9UXDQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA1&pg=PA134#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=18 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref> with development of the E28 beginning in 1975.<ref>{{cite web |title=BMW Classic - Recherche-Client |url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3824021 |website=bmw-grouparchiv.de |accessdate=22 November 2019 |language=German}}</ref> At the time that BMW was designing the E28, the company had only one computer, which was used for payroll management and spare parts logistics. Wolfgang Matschinsky and his team borrowed that computer to perform the calculations necessary to develop the new drivetrain and chassis. This was due to the fact that the addition of an ABS system necessitated a redesign from the previous model due to excessive vibrations under heavy braking.<ref>{{Citation|title=The BMW 5 Series History. The 2nd Generation (E28)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XgCtQVQ26VM|language=en|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> \n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"150px\" style=\"text-align:left\">\nFile:1983 BMW 528i (E28) sedan (24955078763).jpg |Rear view\nFile:525i innen.jpg |Interior\n</gallery>\n\n== Engines ==\nThe E28 was the first 5 Series produced with diesel engines (the 524d and 524td models) and with a petrol engined model specifically aimed at increased fuel economy (525e/528e model).\n\nThe four models available at the launch of the E28 were the 518, 520i, 525i and 528i,<ref>BMW: [https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/media/cdd55d90-1cc5-4456-a984-4ef3b84ad22e/web 518 520i 525i 528i]. February 1982</ref> with the 518 using a straight-four petrol engine and the other three models using a straight-six petrol engine. Over the course of the E28 model, the following models were added: the 524d and 524td using diesel engines, the 518i (a fuel-injected version of the 518), the 525e/528e as fuel-economy models, and the upper-specification 533i, 535i, M535i, and M5 models.\n\nA liquid petroleum gas (LPG) option was introduced for some petrol engines in 1984.<ref>{{cite web |title=5er BMW mit Autogasanlage |url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=6628055 |website=bmw-grouparchiv.de |accessdate=22 November 2019 |language=German}}</ref>\n\n=== Petrol ===\n{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| width = 220px\n| image1 = BMW M20 Engine.JPG\n| caption1 = [[BMW M20]] straight-six engine\n| image2 = BMW M5 E28 Minervablau Motorraum.jpg\n| caption2 = [[BMW M88|BMW M88/3]] straight-six engine\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! Model !! Engine !! Power !! Torque !! Fuel supply !! Years\n|-\n|518 || rowspan=2|[[BMW M10#M10B18|M10B18]] <br/> 4-cyl|| {{convert|66|kW|PS|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 5500 rpm|| {{convert|140|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4000 rpm || Pierburg 2BE <br/> [[carburettor]] || 1981-1984\n|-\n|518i || {{convert|77|kW|PS|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 5800 rpm || {{convert|145|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4500 rpm || [[Jetronic#L|L-Jetronic]] || 1981\u20131987\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 520i || rowspan=\"4\" |[[BMW M20#M20B20|M20B20]] <br/> 6-cyl || rowspan=\"2\" | {{convert|92|kW|PS|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 5800 rpm || {{convert|165|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4500 rpm || [[Jetronic#K|K-Jetronic]] || 1981\u20131982\n|-\n| {{convert|170|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4000 rpm || [[Jetronic#L|L-Jetronic]] || 1982-1987\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | {{convert|95|kW|PS|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 6000 rpm || {{convert|174|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 4000 rpm || [[Jetronic#LE|LE-Jetronic]] || 1985-1988\n|-\n| {{convert|164|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 4300 rpm || [[Motronic]] || 1986-1988\n|-\n|525i || [[BMW M30#M30B25|M30B25]] <br/> 6-cyl || {{convert|110|kW|PS|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 5500 rpm || {{convert|215|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 4000 rpm || [[Jetronic#L|L-Jetronic]] || 1981\u20131987\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |&nbsp; 525e / <br />528e|| rowspan=\"4\" | [[BMW M20#M20B27|M20B27]] <br/> 6-cyl || {{convert|92|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 4250 rpm || {{convert|240|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 3250 rpm || [[Motronic]] || 1982\u20131987 \n|-\n|{{convert|90|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 4250 rpm || {{convert|230|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 3250 rpm || [[Jetronic#L|L-Jetronic]], <br/> [[Motronic]] || 1982\u20131987\n|-\n|{{convert|95|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 4250 rpm || {{convert|240|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br/> at 3250 rpm || [[Motronic]] || 1984\u20131988\n|-\n|525e || {{convert|88|kW|PS|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4250 rpm || {{convert|240|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 3250 rpm || [[Motronic]] || 1985\u20131987\n|-\n|528i || [[BMW M30#M30B28|M30B28]] <br/> 6-cyl || {{convert|135|kW|PS|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 5800 rpm || {{convert|240|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4200 rpm || [[Jetronic#L|L-Jetronic]] || 1981\u20131987\n|-\n| &nbsp; 533i<ref>BMW: [https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/media/abdc109b-ddc2-441b-9701-9438b65de2ac/web BMW 528e, 533i]</ref> || [[BMW M30#M30B32|M30B32]] <br/> 6-cyl || {{convert|135|kW|PS|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 6000 rpm || {{convert|265|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4000 rpm || [[Motronic]] || 1982\u20131984\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |535i, <br /> M535i || rowspan=\"2\" | [[BMW M30#M30B34|M30B34]] <br/> 6-cyl || {{convert|160|kW|PS|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 5500 || {{convert|310|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4000 rpm || [[Motronic]] || 1985\u20131988\n|-\n|{{convert|182|hp|kW|disp=flip|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 5400 rpm || {{convert|290|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4000 rpm || [[Motronic]] || 1985\u20131988 (US)\n|-\n| M5 || [[BMW M88|M88/3]] <br/> 6-cyl || {{convert|210|kW|PS|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at  6500 rpm<ref>[https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3943080 BMW M88/3 Automobilmotor]</ref>|| {{convert|340|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4500 rpm|| [[Motronic]] || 1985\u20131988\n|-\n| M5 || [[BMW S38|S38B35]] <br/> 6-cyl || {{convert|256|hp|kW|disp=flip|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 6500 rpm<ref>BMW: [https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3944267 S38B35 Automobilmotor]</ref> || {{convert|330|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4500 rpm || [[Motronic]] || 1986\u20131988 (US)\n|}\n\n'''518:''' Sold only in some European markets where it suited local tax categories, the 518 was the lowest specification model which used a four-cylinder engine with a [[carburettor|carburetor]]. Factory performance figures for the manual transmission cars are a top speed of {{convert|164|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 14.0 seconds.<ref name=\"E28_518\">[https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/media/dd27a20d-f46a-4795-a968-dda29aa39fbd/web 518, 520i, 525i, 528i]. Pages 6 and 50</ref>\n\n'''518i:''' The base model in Japan and some European countries, the 518i used a fuel-injected four-cylinder engine. Factory performance figures for the manual transmission cars are a top speed of {{convert|175|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 12.6 seconds.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />  This version was not sold in Germany until the 1984 facelift, when it replaced the carburetted 518.\n\n'''520i:''' A mid-range model with the smallest of the available six-cylinder engines. Factory performance figures for the manual transmission cars are a top speed of {{convert|190|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 11.4 seconds.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n'''525e / 528e:''' The 525e (called 528e in North America and Japan) uses a 2.7-litre 6-cylinder [[BMW M20|M20]] petrol engine which is optimised for fuel economy and torque at low engine speed, rather than the traditional high revving characteristics of BMW straight-six engines.<ref>{{cite web|title=Curbside Classic: 1984 BMW 528e \u2013 The Low Rev Modest Driving Machine|url=http://www.curbsideclassic.com/curbside-classics-european/curbside-classic-1986-bmw-528e-the-low-rev-modest-driving-machine/|website=www.curbsideclassic.com|accessdate=15 May 2017}}</ref> The \"e\" stands for the greek letter ''eta'', for economy. According to BMW, the 525e is more fuel efficient than the 520i, which has the same rated power of 92&nbsp;kW.<ref>BMW: ''[https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/media/14f2b16b-55f6-4221-95a2-94dab1671eda/web 525e 525e Katalysator]''. 1985</ref> Since many markets tax cars based on engine displacement, the eta's larger engine meant that it was not suitable everywhere. The model was expressly developed with the American market in mind. BMW's [[corporate average fuel economy]] was at risk of not meeting requirements by 1984, primarily due to higher sales of their bigger, more expensive cars in the early 1980s.<ref name=AG941>{{cite magazine | ref = AG94 | magazine = De AutoGids | number = 94 | volume = 4 | page = 130 | title = BMW: Met de ETA op de zuinige tor | trans-title = BMW: With Eta on an economy run | first = Vic | last = Heylen | language = Dutch | date = 1983-04-28 | publisher = Uitgeverij Auto-Magazine | location = Brussels, Belgium }}</ref> In Austria, the 525e was detuned to {{convert|88|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nFactory performance figures for the manual transmission cars without a catalytic converter are a top speed of {{convert|190|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 10.7 seconds. With a catalytic converter, the figures are a top speed of {{convert|188|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 11.3 seconds<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n'''525i:''' This mid-range model is powered by a 2.5-litre 6-cylinder engine. The 525i was only sold in Europe. Factory performance figures for the manual transmission cars are a top speed of {{convert|201|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 9.8 seconds.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n'''528i:''' Initially the highest specification available, the 6-cylinder 528i became a mid-range model following the release of the 533i and 535i models. Factory performance figures for the manual transmission cars are a top speed of {{convert|215|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 8.4 seconds.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n'''533i:'''\nOnly sold in Japan and North America,<ref>{{cite web|title=BMW E28 5 Series 533i (US) Specs|url=https://www.ultimatespecs.com/car-specs/BMW/1408/BMW-E28-5-Series-533i-(US).html|website=www.ultimatespecs.com|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1984 BMW 533i E28 specifications|url=http://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=227689|website=www.carfolio.com|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> the 6-cylinder 533i was the highest specification model during its production years of 1983-1984. It was replaced by the 535i.\n\n'''535i:''' Released in 1984, the 535i replaced the 533i and uses the same 6-cylinder drivetrain as the M535i. Factory performance figures for the manual transmission cars without a catalytic converter are a top speed of {{convert|225|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 7.2 seconds. With a catalytic converter, the figures are a top speed of {{convert|212|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 7.9 seconds<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n[[File:1986 BMW M535i (E28) sedan (2015-06-04) 01.jpg|thumb|right|M535i]]\n'''M535i:''' The top of the regular production model range, the M535i uses the drivetrain from the 535i plus M-Technic suspension, and wheels and body panels not found on any other E28. The M535i was assembled on the standard E28 assembly lines in Dingolfing and Rosslyn. Factory performance figures for the manual transmission cars without a catalytic converter are a top speed of {{convert|230|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 7.2 seconds. With a catalytic converter, the figures are a top speed of {{convert|217|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 7.9 seconds<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n{{clear right}}\n\n=== Diesel ===\n[[File:BMW_E28_engine_2_16.09_JM.jpg|thumb|right|[[BMW M21]] straight-six engine]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! Model !! Engine !! Power !! Torque !! Aspiration !! Years\n|-\n|524d || rowspan=2|[[BMW M21|M21D24]] <br/> 6-cyl || {{convert|63|kW|hp|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4600 rpm || {{convert|152|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 2500 rpm || [[Naturally aspirated engine|naturally <br/> aspirated]] || 1985\u20131987\n|-\n|524td || {{convert|85|kW|hp|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 4800 rpm || {{convert|210|Nm|lbft|abbr=on|0}} <br/> at 2400 rpm || [[turbocharger|turbo]] || 1983\u20131988\n|}\n\n'''524d:''' At the 1986 [[Geneva Motor Show]], four years after the introduction of the more powerful 524td model, the naturally-aspirated 524d model was introduced.<ref name=\"AR87\">{{cite book | title = Automobil Revue 1987 | editor-last = B\u00fcschi | editor-first = Hans-Ulrich | publisher = Hallwag AG | location = Berne, Switzerland | language = German, French | volume = 82 | date = March 5, 1987 | isbn = 3-444-00458-3 }}</ref>{{rp|188,190}} It was only sold in some markets.<ref name=\"AR87\" />{{rp|191}}\n\n'''524td:''' This [[turbodiesel]] model was the first diesel car produced by BMW. It entered production in late 1982, when 100 pre-series cars were built.<ref name=\"AK84\">{{cite book | title = Auto Katalog 1984 | editor-last = Heitz | editor-first = Rudolf | publisher = [[:de:Motor Presse Stuttgart|Vereinigte Motor-Verlage GmbH & Co. KG]] | location = Stuttgart | page = 242 | volume = 27 | language = German | year = 1983 }}</ref> Factory performance figures for the manual transmission cars are a top speed of {{convert|180|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}} and 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h acceleration in 12.9 seconds.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n== Drivetrain ==\nBMW offered the E28 with both manual and automatic gearboxes. The torque is transmitted from the engine with a single-disc dry clutch with a torsional damper in the models with a manual gearbox, the automatic models have a torque converter with built in lockup-clutch.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n;Manual transmissions\nThe 4-speed manual transmissions are:<ref>{{cite web|title=5' E28 model selection|url=http://www.realoem.com/bmw/en/select?product=P&archive=1&series=E28&body=Lim|website=www.realoem.com}}</ref>\n* [[Getrag]] 242 (for M10 and M20 engine models)\n* Getrag 262 (M30 engines)\n\nThe 5-speed manual transmissions are:\n* Getrag 240 (M10 and M21 engines)\n* Getrag 245 (M10 engines)\n* [[Getrag 260 transmission|Getrag 260]] (M20, M21 and M30 engines)\n* Getrag 265 (M30 engines and 525e/528e)\n* Getrag 280 (M88/3 and S38 engines)\n* [[List of ZF transmissions|ZF]] S5-16 (M20 engines)\n\n;Automatic transmissions\nThe 3-speed automatic transmissions are:\n* [[ZF 3HP22 transmission|ZF 3HP22]] (M20 and M30 engines, US market only)\n\nThe 4-speed automatic transmissions are:\n* [[ZF 4HP22 transmission|ZF 4HP22]] (M10, M20, M21)\n* [[ZF 4HP22 transmission|ZF 4HP22]] EH (M20, M30)\n\n== Suspension ==\nIndependent front and rear suspension is used, with [[Macpherson strut]]s at the front and a [[trailing arm#Semi-trailing arm|semi-trailing arm]] design for the rear.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\">{{citation|publisher=BMW AG |title=Betriebsanleitung, Serviceheft 518, 520i, 525e, 525i, 528i, 535i, M535i, 524td |date=1985 |language=German |url=https://bmw-grouparchiv.de/research/detail/index.xhtml?id=3058985 |access-date=20 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe front suspension was upgraded to use dual links at the bottom of the strut, as first seen on the [[BMW 7 Series (E23)|E23 7 Series]]. This increases steering offset while cornering, to improve steering feel.<ref name=\"noakes\">{{cite book|last1=Noakes|first1=Andrew|title=The Ultimate History of BMW|date=2008}}</ref>{{refpage|page=106}} Double-acting shock absorbers, coil springs and a front [[anti-roll bar]] are used.\n\nThe rear suspension is mounted on a delta beam that is connected to the body with three screws in rubber bearings, that have longitudinal play.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} Some models have a rear anti-roll bar.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\nThe steering on most models is a speed-dependent [[recirculating ball]] power steering system made by ZF Friedrichshafen. The 518i has a Gemmer steering system with a double enveloping worm gear, also made by ZF.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\nWheel sizes are 14-inch (16-inch for the M5 model) or 390&nbsp;mm [[Michelin TRX]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Taylor|first1=James|title=BMW M5- The Complete Story|date=2015}}</ref>{{refpage|page=44}}<ref>{{cite web|title=1981  BMW E28 5 Series 525i Specs|url=http://www.ultimatespecs.com/car-specs/BMW/230/BMW-E28-5-Series-525i.html|website=www.ultimatespecs.com|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1984 BMW E28 5 Series 535i Specs|url=http://www.ultimatespecs.com/car-specs/BMW/1409/BMW-E28-5-Series-535i.html|website=www.ultimatespecs.com|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref> All rims have 22&nbsp;mm positive rim offset.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n== Brakes ==\nThe brakes use a hydraulic dual-circuit brake system with power assistance. The front wheels have disc brakes, that are \u2013 except for the 518i<!--518 and 524d as well?--> \u2013 internally ventilated. All models with 2.5&nbsp;l or more displacement have rear disc brakes (non-vented), while the lesser powered models have rear drum brakes. To prevent the wheels from locking, BMW equipped the E28 after 1984 with an [[anti-lock braking system]], although it was an option in some markets.<ref name=\"BMW-E28-Betriebsanleitung\" />\n\n== M5 model ==\n[[File:BMW M5 E28 Minervablau.jpg|thumb|right|M5 model]]\n{{main|BMW M5#E28 M5 (1985\u20131987)}}\nThe E28 was the first M5 model produced, and is powered by the [[BMW M88|M88/3]] and [[BMW S38|S38]] straight-six engines.\n{{clear right}}\n\n== North American market models ==\n[[File:BMW-535is.jpg|thumb|right|BMW 535is (North America)]]\n[[File:M5sig (E28).jpg|thumb|North American M5 fitted with European market headlights]]\nThe North American line-up consisted of the '''528e''' (1982-1988, known as the 525e in Europe), '''533i''' (1983-1984), '''535i''' (1985-1988), '''524td''' (1985-1986), '''M5''' (1986-1987) and '''535is''' (1987-1988).\n\nThe launch model was the 528e in 1982, followed by the 533i.<ref>{{cite web|title=1984 BMW 533i E28 Specifications|url=http://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=227689|website=www.carfolio.com|accessdate=22 November 2017}}</ref> The optional automatic transmission was initially a 3-speed (a 4-speed automatic was available in Europe at the time), with a 4-speed automatic transmission becoming optional in 1983. From 1985, all North American models had ABS Brakes as standard.\n\nThe North American E28 models had larger bumpers (designed to withstand a {{convert|5|mph|abbr=on}} collision without body damage), which increased the overall length by {{convert|180|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nThe 528i, 533i and 535i were sold with a [[catalytic converter]] in the United States.\n\nInstead of importing the M535i, BMW of North America created the 535is.<ref>{{cite web|title=1985 BMW E28 5 Series 535is (US) Specs|url=http://www.ultimatespecs.com/car-specs/BMW/1413/BMW-E28-5-Series-535is-(US).html|website=www.ultimatespecs.com|accessdate=22 November 2017}}</ref> This model is based on a 535i, plus front and rear spoilers, sport suspension and sport seats.\n\nProduction of North American market M5 models began in late 1986 (two years after M5 production began for European markets), and it was only produced for twelve months as 1988 [[model year]] car.<ref>{{cite web|title=1988 BMW M5 values|url=https://www.hagerty.com/apps/ValuationTools/1988-BMW-M5|website=www.hagerty.com|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref> North American M5 models use the S38 engine instead of the M88/3.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Taylor|first1=James|title=BMW M5 - The Complete Story|date=2015|isbn=978 1 78500 045 4}}</ref>{{refpage|page=37}} All North American M5 cars were painted Jet Black and most interiors were tan (\"Natur\") coloured leather.<ref>{{cite web|title=FAQ E28 M5|url=https://www.bmwmregistry.com/model_faq.php?id=7|website=www.bmwmregistry.com|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\nE28 production started in July 1981 and ended in December 1987.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Taylor|first1=James|title=BMW M5: The Complete Story|date=February 2016|publisher=The Crowood Press UK|location=Ramsbury, Marlborough Wiltshire|isbn=1785000462|url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1785000462|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref> A total of 722,328 cars were built.<ref name=DeAutos45bis90Oswald>{{cite book |last=Oswald |first=Werner |authorlink= |coauthors= |title= Deutsche Autos 1945\u20131990, Band 4, 1. Auflage|year=2001 |publisher=Motorbuch Verlag |location=Stuttgart |isbn=3-613-02131-5}}</ref>\n\nThe E28 was still sold in North America as a 1988 Model Year car after its E34 successor had been released in Europe in early 1988. A limited edition model was also sold in South Africa from mid-1987 to the end of 1988.<ref>{{cite web|title=M5 E28|url=http://www.africanmusclecars.com/index.php/bmw/m5-e28|website=www.africanmusclecars.com|accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{BMW cars: 1980s to 2000s}}\n[[Category:BMW vehicles|5 Series (E28)]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1981]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: greek \u2192 Greek, 1982-1989 \u2192 1982\u20131989 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BMW_5_Series_(E28)"}
{"title_page": "Race and ethnicity in censuses", "text_new": "[[File:Ethnicity and race in censuses.png|thumb|500px|Map showing countries where the ethnicity or race of people was enumerated in at least one census since 1991.]]\n\nMany [[countries]] and national [[census]]es currently enumerate or have previously enumerated their [[populations]] by [[Race (human classification)|race]], [[ethnicity]], [[nationality]], or a combination of these characteristics.<ref name = \"pbs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/race/000_About/002_03-godeeper.htm |title=RACE&nbsp;\u2014 The Power of an Illusion . Go Deeper |publisher=PBS |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ND1__tXqfDYC&pg=PT11&lpg=PT11&dq=%22ann+morning%22+soviet+union |title=Ethnicity&nbsp;\u2014 Steve Fenton&nbsp;\u2014 Google Books |date= 2013-05-02|accessdate=2013-06-20|isbn=9780745658438 |last1=Fenton |first1=Steve }}</ref> Different countries have different classifications and census options for race and ethnicity/nationality which are not comparable with data from other countries.<ref name = \"pbs\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/sconcerns/popchar/Morning.pdf |title=Approaches To Racial And Ethnic Classification |date= |accessdate=2013-03-16}}</ref> In addition, many of the race and ethnicity concepts that appear on national censuses worldwide have their origins in [[Europe]] or in the views of [[Europeans]], rather than in the views of the locals of these countries.<ref name=\"catdir\">{{cite web|title=Census and identity: The Politics of Race, Ethnicity and Language in National Censuses|url=http://catdir.loc.gov/catdir/samples/cam031/2001037352.pdf|publisher=Cambridge University|accessdate=2 December 2012|author1=David I. Kertzer |author2=Dominique Arel }}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n==Africa==\n\n===Angola===\n[[File:Angola Ethnic map 1970.svg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Angola in 1970]]\n\nThe [[Portugal|Portuguese]] asked about race in colonial censuses when they controlled Angola, and they provided three options: White, Mestizo, or African/Black. Africans had to then pick either \"Assimilado\" (assimilated) or \"Indigenato\" (indigenous).<ref name = \"angola\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/angola/ |title=Angola |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> Angola has not used any racial categories since its independence in 1975.<ref name = \"angola\"/> Tribe and language for Africans were recorded only in 1950 and 1960.<ref name = \"angola\"/>\n\n===Benin===\nThe people in [[Benin]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1979, 1992, and 2013 but not in 2002.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Botswana===\n[[Botswana]] enumerated people by race in all censuses between 1904 and 1946, and again in the 1964 census (though not in 1956), but in no censuses after 1964.<ref name = \"botswana\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/botswana/ |title=Botswana |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> People were enumerated by language use in 1946 and 1956 and again in 2001 and 2011.<ref name = \"botswana\"/>\n\n===Cape Verde===\n[[Cape Verde]] enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1950.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Central African Republic===\nThe [[Central African Republic]] enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1959/1960.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Chad===\n[[Chad]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1993 and 2009.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Democratic Republic of Congo===\nThe people in the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]] were enumerated by ethnicity from 1955\u20131958.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Republic of Congo===\nThe people in the [[Republic of Congo]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1960, 1974, and 1984.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Equatorial Guinea===\nThe population of [[Equatorial Guinea]] was enumerated by ethnicity in 1950.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Ethiopia===\n[[Ethiopia]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1994 and in 2007.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Gabon===\nThe population of [[Gabon]] was enumerated by ethnicity in 1960\u20131961 and 1993.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Ghana===\nThe population of [[Ghana]] was enumerated by ethnicity in 1960, 2000,<ref name=autogenerated6 /> and 2010.<ref>{{cite web|author=Major Trading Currencies |url=http://www.ghanabusinessnews.com/2012/06/05/group-not-satisfied-with-2010-ghana-census-report/ |title=Group not satisfied with 2010 Ghana census report |publisher=Ghana Business News |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Guinea===\nThe population of [[Guinea]] was enumerated by ethnicity in 1955.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Guinea-Bissau===\nThe population of [[Guinea-Bissau]] was enumerated by ethnicity in 1950 and in 2009.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Ivory Coast===\n[[File:IvoryCoastEthno.jpg|right|thumb|100px|Ethnic composition of the Ivory Coast (note: the map is in French).]]\nThe people of [[Ivory Coast]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1948, 1957\u20131958, and 1988.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> The ethnicity data from 1957\u20131958 was only for the [[rural]] areas of the country, though.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Kenya===\nSince 1945, [[Kenya]] enumerated people by ethnicity from 1948 all the way up to its most recent census in 2009 (however, the 1999 census ethnicity figures were not made public).<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minorityrights.org/download.php?id=147|title=Kenya: Minorities, Indigenous Peoples and Ethnic Diversity|author=Maurice Odhiambo Makoloo|type=Report|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080614023538/http://www.minorityrights.org/download.php?id=147|archivedate=June 14, 2008|publisher=Minority Rights Group International}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kenya.rcbowen.com/people/population.html |title=Kenya - Population Distribution |publisher=Kenya.rcbowen.com |date= |accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/08/25/kenya-holds-first-census_n_268076.html |title=Kenya Holds First Census In A Decade, Causes Outcry Over Ethnic Identity |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= 2009-08-25|accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.knbs.or.ke/censusethnic.php |title=Welcome to Kenya National Bureau of Statistics |publisher=Knbs.or.ke |accessdate=2012-12-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424174848/http://knbs.or.ke/censusethnic.php |archivedate=2013-04-24 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://marsgroupkenya.org/census/?data=ethaf |title=Kenya 2009 Census Data &#124; Population by Ethnic Affiliation |publisher=Mars Group Kenya |date= |accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref> There were some concerns about asking an ethnicity equation in the 2009 census since it came just a year after the disputed Kenyan presidential election of 2007 and the riots that followed it, but Kenya went through with asking about ethnicity in 2009 anyway.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nyambura |first=Helen |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2009/08/25/ozatp-kenya-census-idAFJOE57O0GP20090825 |title=Ethnic question in Kenya census stokes suspicions |work=Reuters |date= 2009-08-25|accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref>\n\n===Lesotho===\nPeople in [[Lesotho]] were enumerated by race between 1904 and 1976, but not after 1976.<ref name = \"lesotho\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/lesotho/ |title=Lesotho |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> Language was only recorded in 1946 and 1956, tribe and language for Africans were recorded only in 1950 and 1960.<ref name = \"lesotho\"/>\n\n===Malawi===\nPeople in [[Malawi]] were enumerated by race between 1911 and 1987, and again in 2018.<ref name = \"malawi\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/malawi/ |title=Malawi |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> They were enumerated by language only in 1966, 1998, and 2008.<ref name = \"malawi\"/> They were enumerated by tribal affiliation only in 1926, 1945, and 2008.<ref name = \"malawi\"/>\n\n===Mali===\n[[Mali]] enumerated people in some parts of the country by ethnicity in 1950.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Mauritius===\n[[Mauritius]] enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1952, 1962, and 1972.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Morocco===\n[[File:Volkeren in Marokko.jpg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnolinguistic composition of Morocco.]]\n[[Morocco]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1950 and 1971.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> The 2014 census enumerated people by nationality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hcp.ma/Note-sur-les-premiers-resultats-du-Recensement-General-de-la-Population-et-de-l-Habitat-2014_a1516.html |title=Note sur les premiers r\u00e9sultats du Recensement G\u00e9n\u00e9ral de la Population et de l'Habitat 2014  |accessdate=24 July 2015 |format=docx |work=[[Haut Commissariat au Plan]]}}{{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\n===Mozambique===\nPeople in [[Mozambique]] were counted by race only in 1894, 1970, 1997, 2007, and 2017.<ref name = \"mozambique\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/mozambique/ |title=Mozambique |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> The race categories in Mozambique were the same ones as in Angola, due to both being controlled by Portugal before acquiring their independence.<ref name = \"mozambique\"/> People were counted by language in all censuses since 1940.<ref name = \"mozambique\"/>\n\n===Namibia===\nPeople in [[Namibia]] were enumerated by race in all 20th century censuses but not in the 2001 census. They were enumerated by language in all censuses since 1951.<ref name = \"namibia\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/namibia/ |title=Namibia |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref>\n\n===Niger===\n[[Niger]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1959/1960 and 2001.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Nigeria===\n[[File:Afro asiatic peoples nigeria.png|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Nigeria.]]\n[[Nigeria]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1963.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> In addition, Nigeria has announced plans to enumerate its population by ethnicity in its 2016 census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbulletin.net/?aType=haber&ArticleID=115785 |title=Nigeria to include religion, ethnicity in 2016 census &#124; Africa |publisher=World Bulletin |date=2013-08-22 |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref>\n\n===Rwanda===\n[[Rwanda]] enumerated people by ethnicity from 1933/34 until 1991.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite book|first=David E.|last=Kiwuwa|title=Ethnic Politics and Democratic Transition in Rwanda|publisher=Routledge|location=Abingdon|page=71|year=2012|isbn=978-0415616089|url=https://books.google.com/?id=uGclH0p46ogC&lpg=PA71&dq=rwanda%20ethnicity%20census&pg=PA71#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> Due to the [[1994 Rwandan Genocide]] and the ethnic hatred and tensions that caused it, the Rwandan census of 2002 did not enumerate people by ethnicity.<ref>{{cite web|author=Agence France-Presse |url=http://reliefweb.int/report/rwanda/ethnic-origins-ignored-rwandas-first-census-genocide |title=Ethnic origins ignored in Rwanda's first census since genocide &#124; ReliefWeb |publisher=Reliefweb.int |date=2002-08-16 |accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref>\n\n===Sao Tome and Principe===\nThe [[Sao Tome and Principe]] enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1950 and 1960.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Senegal===\nThe people of [[Senegal]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1960\u20131961, 1988, and 2002.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Seychelles===\nThe people of the [[Seychelles]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1947, 1987, and 1994.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Somalia===\nIn the pre-independence period in [[Somalia]], the colonial administrations in [[British Somaliland]] and [[Italian Somaliland]] officially classified the [[Somali people|ethnic Somali]] majority within the two territories as \"[[Hamitic]]\".<ref name=\"Gbco\">{{cite book|title=An Economic Survey of the Colonial Territories, Volumes 1-4|date=1952|publisher=Great Britain, Colonial Office|page=122|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=Gr8vAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Esoa\">{{cite book|title=Ethnographic Survey of Africa, Volume 5, Issue 1|date=1969|publisher=International African Institute|pages=45 & 50|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=szhNAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> The Italian Somaliland census of 1935 reported that the remaining 6.2% of the area's population consisted of \"[[Negroid]] groups\", including the [[Somali Bantu|Bantu]] ethnic minorities inhabiting the southern riverine region.<ref name=\"Kmbeiis\">{{cite journal|last1=Menkhaus|first1=Ken|title=Bantu ethnic identities in Somalia|journal=Annales d'\u00c9thiopie|date=2003|volume=XIX|page=323|url=http://www.persee.fr/articleAsPDF/ethio_0066-2127_2003_num_19_1_1051/article_ethio_0066-2127_2003_num_19_1_1051.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024155331/http://www.persee.fr/articleAsPDF/ethio_0066-2127_2003_num_19_1_1051/article_ethio_0066-2127_2003_num_19_1_1051.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-10-24|accessdate=22 November 2014|doi=10.3406/ethio.2003.1051}}</ref> These census designations were at the time pre-assigned rather than based on self-reporting. Following independence in 1960, no official census was taken until 1975. This first post-independence national census only collected information on district of birth.<ref name=\"Tmonps\">{{cite book|last1=Ministry of National Planning|title=The 1982 labour force survey: analytical report|date=1985|publisher=Ministry of National Planning of Somalia, Central Statistical Department|page=126|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=C5IoAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> However, the general government literature maintained that the country's ethnic Somali majority was of Hamitic stock, or alternately of [[Arabs|Arab]] heritage.<ref name=\"Tmoiang\">{{cite book|last1=Ministry of Information and National Guidance|title=Somalia and the Arab League|date=1974|publisher=Ministry of Information and National Guidance|page=7|url=https://www.google.com/books?lr=&id=4FkMAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> Similarly, Article 3 of the [[Constitution of Somalia|Provision Constitution]] adopted in 2012 indicates that Somalia is an Arab nation.<ref name=\"Fgspc\">{{cite web|title=Provisional Constitution|url=http://unpos.unmissions.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=RkJTOSpoMME=|publisher=Federal Government of Somalia|accessdate=22 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402122013/http://unpos.unmissions.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=RkJTOSpoMME%3D|archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref> In 2014, the Ministry of Planning and International Cooperation also announced that it would release a new national population census before 2016.<ref name=\"Sgtlpcaote\">{{cite news|title=SOMALIA: Gov't to launch population census ahead of 2016 elections|url=http://koonfurta.com/somalia-govt-to-launch-population-census-ahead-of-2016-elections/|accessdate=22 November 2014|agency=Koonfurta|date=10 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030155132/http://koonfurta.com/somalia-govt-to-launch-population-census-ahead-of-2016-elections/|archive-date=30 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===South Africa===\n{{See also|Population Registration Act, 1950}}\n[[File:South Africa 2011 White population proportion map.svg|right|100px|thumb|Whites as a percentage of the total South African population in 2011.]]\n[[South Africa]] has enumerated people by race in all of its censuses since 1904.<ref name=\"southafrica\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/south-africa/ |title=South Africa |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date=1986-07-23 |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> Five population group options are provided in response to the question \"How would ''(name)'' describe him/herself in terms of population group?\": \"Black African\", \"Coloured\", \"Indian or Asian\", \"White\" and \"Other\".<ref>[http://www.statssa.gov.za/census2011/documents/CensusQuestionnaires/Census%202011_q_A.pdf Census 2011 Household Questionnaire A]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> South Africa has also asked about language use since 1921 for [[white South African]]s and since 1936 for all races.<ref name = \"southafrica\"/>\n\n===Sudan===\n[[Sudan]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1956.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Swaziland===\nThe [[Swaziland|Swazi]] census counted people by race in all censuses between 1904 and 1976.<ref name = \"swazi\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/swaziland/ |title=Swaziland |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> People were counted by ethnic group and tribe only in 1966 and 1976.<ref name = \"swazi\"/>\n\n===Tanzania===\nThe [[Tanzania]]n census enumerated people by race from colonial times until 1967, by ethnicity and tribe from colonial times until 1973. It enumerated people by language only in 1952 and 1958.<ref name = \"tanzania\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/tanzania |title=Tanzania |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref>\n\n===Togo===\nThe people in [[Togo]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1948, 1958\u20131960, and 1970.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Tunisia===\n[[Tunisia]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1956.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Uganda===\nThe people of [[Uganda]] were enumerated by ethnicity from 1948 all the way up to Uganda's most recent census in 2012,<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ubos.org/UgCensus2012/docs/2012_CENSUS_BULLETIN_Vol1.pdf|title=The 2012 Uganda Population and Housing Census|magazine=The 2012 Uganda Population & Housing Census Bulletin|volume=1|date=March 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113175759/http://www.ubos.org/UgCensus2012/docs/2012_CENSUS_BULLETIN_Vol1.pdf|archivedate=November 13, 2014}}</ref> with the exception of 1980 and possibly 1969.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mongabay.com/reference/country_studies/uganda/SOCIETY.html |title=Uganda - SOCIETY |publisher=Mongabay.com |date= |accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref>\n\n===Zambia===\nPeople in [[Zambia]] were not continuously counted by race before independence, and when they were counted by race it were primarily the non-Africans/non-blacks who were counted.<ref name = \"zambia\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/zambia/ |title=Zambia |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> People were counted by language only in 1931, while they were counted for ethnicity at various points since 1969.<ref name = \"zambia\"/> The 1969 census asked about language but not ethnic group, and the 1974 census asked about ethnic group, but not language. The 1980 census asked about ethnic group, mother tongue, and language of most frequent use, while the 1990 census asked about ethnic group and mother tongue. The 2000 census asked about ethnic group, language of most frequent use, and second language.<ref name = \"zambia\"/>\n\n===Zimbabwe===\nPeople in [[Zimbabwe]] were enumerated by race between 1901 and 2012, but many censuses were done separately for Whites/Europeans and Blacks/Africans before the 1970s.<ref name = \"zimbabwe\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/zimbabwe/ |title=Zimbabwe |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> People were enumerated by language only in 1982 (when they were enumerated by \"[their] father's dialect\").<ref name = \"zimbabwe\"/>\n\n==Asia==\n\n===Abkhazia===\nPeople in [[Abkhazia]] (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by [[native tongue]] [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12>{{cite web|url=http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/rus_lan_97_uezd_eng.php |title=Demoscope Weekly - Annex. Statistical indicators reference |publisher=Demoscope.ru |date=2012-09-16 |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated11>{{cite web|url=http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/rus_rel_97.php?reg=0 |title=\u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f Weekly - \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435. \u0421\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439 |publisher=Demoscope.ru |date= |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite web|url=http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/census_types.php?ct=6 |title=\u041f\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0430 Weekly |publisher=Demoscope.ru |date=2013-01-15 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> the [[International recognition of Abkhazia|partially recognized state]] of [[Abkhazia]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses of 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/abkhazia-ethnic2003.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Abkhazia 2003 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/abkhazia-ethnic2011.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Abkhazia 2011 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Afghanistan===\nPrior to 2010, [[Afghanistan]] had not held a census since 1979 due to the wars and conflicts that have occurred there over those three decades (since the [[Soviet invasion of Afghanistan]] in 1979).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cso.gov.af/Content/files/Population.pdf|title=Afghanistan Statistical Yearbook 2009-10}}</ref>\n\n===Armenia===\nPeople in Armenia (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Armenia]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses of 2001<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/armenia-ethnic2001.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Armenia 2001 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armstat.am/file/doc/99465273.pdf|title=CENSUS PROGRAMME (CONTENT OF QUESTIONNAIRE) 2011 CENSUS OF THE REPUBLIC OF ARMENIA }}</ref>\n\n===Azerbaijan===\n[[File:Azerbaijan ethnic 2003.png|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Azerbaijan in 2003.]]\nPeople in Azerbaijan (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Azerbaijan]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses of 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/azerbaijan-ethnic1999.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Azerbaijan 1999 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/azerbaijan-ethnic2009.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Azerbaijan 2009 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date=1971-04-07 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Bahrain===\n[[Bahrain]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1965<ref name=autogenerated6 /> and 2010.<ref name=autogenerated10>{{cite web |url=http://www.census2010.gov.bh/results_en.php |title=Bahraini Census 2010 - \u062a\u0639\u062f\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0643\u0640\u0640\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0645 \u0644\u0644\u0628\u062d\u0631\u064a\u0640\u0640\u0646 2010 |publisher=Census2010.gov.bh |accessdate=2013-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320104234/http://www.census2010.gov.bh/results_en.php |archive-date=2012-03-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The 2010 Bahrain census also enumerated people by their religious beliefs.<ref name=autogenerated10 />\n\n===Bangladesh===\n[[British India]] (which Bangladesh was a part of) enumerated its population by race between 1872 and 1941.<ref name=\"censusindia1\">{{cite web|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/Data_Products/Library/Indian_perceptive_link/Census_Terms_link/censusterms.html |title=Census of India - Census Terms |publisher=Censusindia.gov.in |date= |accessdate=2013-06-10}}</ref>\n\n===Brunei===\nSince 1945, [[Brunei]] enumerated people by ethnicity in all censuses since 1947.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/dyb2.htm#2001 |title=United Nations Statistics Division - Demographic and Social Statistics |publisher=Unstats.un.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Burma===\nThe people in [[Burma]] (also known as Myanmar) were enumerated by ethnicity in 1931,<ref name=autogenerated27>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvb.no/analysis/burma%E2%80%99s-troublesome-census/21931 |title=Burma's troublesome census &#124; Democratic Voice of Burma |publisher=Dvb.no |date=2009-08-17 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 1953.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> A new census which plans to enumerate the people of Burma by ethnicity and race is planned to be held in 2014.<ref name=autogenerated27 /><ref name=autogenerated26>{{cite news|author=Sonu Trivedi |url=http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/myanmars-census-a-crucial-democracy-test/article4137474.ece |title=Opinion / Op-Ed : Myanmar's census a crucial democracy test |newspaper=The Hindu |date=2012-11-27 |accessdate=2013-03-21 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> The 1931 Burmese census generated a lot of anger from non-Burmese ethnic groups who were marked as Burmese on the census.<ref name=autogenerated27 /> There is hope that the scheduled [[2014 Burma Census]] will help empower the various ethnic groups in Burma.<ref name=autogenerated26 />\n\n===China===\n[[File:Ethnolinguistic map of China 1983.jpg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnolinguistic groups in China in 1983]]\n\n[[The People's Republic of China]] [[Demographics of China|counted people by ethnicity]] since at least [[First National Population Census of the People's Republic of China|1952]] but does not count people by mother tongue.<ref>{{cite news|author=Mark Mackinnon |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/asia-pacific/chinas-disappearing-languages-deemed-not-that-important/article1792549/ |title=China's disappearing languages deemed 'not that important' |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date= 2012-08-23|accessdate=2012-09-21 |location=Toronto}}</ref>\n\n===Cyprus===\nThe people of [[Cyprus]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1960.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===East Timor===\n[[East Timor]] enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1950.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Georgia===\nPeople in Georgia (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in both post-Soviet censuses in 2002 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/georgia-ethnic2002.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Georgia 2002 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===India===\nWhen it was a [[British India|British colony]], India enumerated its population by race between 1872 and 1941.<ref name=\"censusindia1\"/>\n\n===Indonesia===\n[[File:Indonesia Ethnic Groups Map English.svg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Indonesia]]\n[[Indonesia]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1930, 2000, and 2010 but not in any other censuses.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=UFNKQcvGNSAC&pg=PA20&dq=census+ethnic#v=onepage&q=census%20ethnic&f=false |title=Ethnic Chinese in Contemporary Indonesia - Leo Heng Chew Suryadinata - Google Books |accessdate=2013-03-21|isbn=9789812308351 |last1=Suryadinata |first1=Leo |year=2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\n[[File:Arab population israel 2000 en.png|thumb|100px|Map of Arab population, 2000]]\n\nThe census in [[Israel]] directly asked people about their ethnicity only in 1983.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> However, Israel has used the religion question on its census to determine the ethnic composition of its population from 1948 to the present day.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |url=http://www1.cbs.gov.il/reader/shnatonenew_site.htm |title=Statistical Abstract of Israel 2011 |publisher=cbs.gov.il |date=2011-09-26 |accessdate=2012-09-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120914092802/http://www1.cbs.gov.il/reader/shnatonenew_site.htm |archivedate=2012-09-14 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs.gov.il/shnaton63/st_eng02.pdf|title= Statistical Abstract of Israel 2012 National Population Estimates |publisher=CBS }}</ref> Israel has enumerated [[Israeli Jews|its Jewish population]] by their '''continent''' of birth since 1948.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.cbs.gov.il/reader/shnaton/templ_shnaton_e.html?num_tab=st02_25&CYear=2012 |title=Statistical Abstract of Israel 2012 - No. 63 Subject 2 - Table No. 25 |publisher=.cbs.gov.il |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Kazakhstan===\n[[File:Kazakhstan European Rus.png|thumb|right|100px|[[Europeans|European ethnicities]] as a percentage of the total population in Kazakhstan in 2016 (note: map is in Russian).]]\n\nPeople in Kazakhstan (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Kazakhstan]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses of 1999<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ide.go.jp/English/Publish/Download/Mes/pdf/51_02.pdf|title=Ethnodemographic situation in Kazakhstan|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120133116/http://www.ide.go.jp/English/Publish/Download/Mes/pdf/51_02.pdf|archivedate=2013-01-20}}</ref> and 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/kazakhstan-ethnic2009reg-census.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Kazakhstan 2009 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |accessdate=2013-03-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130622201346/http://pop-stat.mashke.org/kazakhstan-ethnic2009reg-census.htm |archivedate=2013-06-22 }}</ref>\n\n===Kyrgyzstan===\nPeople in Kyrgyzstan (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Kyrgyzstan]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses of 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stat.kg/stat.files/din.files/census/5010003.pdf|title=5.01.00.03 \u041d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206105009/http://www.stat.kg/stat.files/din.files/census/5010003.pdf|archivedate=February 6, 2009}}</ref> and 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/kyrgyzstan-ethnic2009v1.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Kyrgyzstan 2009 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/kyrgyzstan-ethnic2009v2.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Kyrgyzstan 2009 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Malaysia===\nPeople in [[Malaysia]] were enumerated by ethnicity/race from 1871 to the present day.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://faculty.washington.edu/charles/pubs/1987-MeaningandMeasurementofEthnicityinMalaysia.pdf|title=The Meaning and Measurement of Ethnicity in Malaysia: An Analysis of Census Classifications|author=Charles Hirschman|journal=The Journal of Asian Studies|volume=46|issue=3|pages = 555\u2013582|date=August 1987|publisher=Association for Asian Studies|doi= 10.2307/2056899|jstor=2056899|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021071854/http://faculty.washington.edu/charles/pubs/1987-MeaningandMeasurementofEthnicityinMalaysia.pdf|archivedate=October 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Mongolia===\n[[Mongolia]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1963 and 2000.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Nagorno-Karabakh===\n[[File:Nagorno Karabakh Ethnic Map 1989.png|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Nagorno Karabakh in 1989]]\n\nPeople in Nagorno-Karabakh (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> the de facto independent state of [[Nagorno-Karabakh]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its only post-Soviet census of 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/nkr-ethnic2005.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Nagorno-Karabakh Republic (self-proclaimed) 2005 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Nepal===\n[[File:Nepal ethnic groups.png|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Nepal. (note that <span style=\"color:#ff6600;\">Kulu Rodu (Kulung) territories</span> are mistakenly marked as <span style=\"color:green;\">Tamu/Gurung territories</span> in this map)]]\n[[Nepal]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1991 and 2001.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Pakistan===\n[[British India]] (which Pakistan was a part of) enumerated its population by race between 1872 and 1941.<ref name=\"censusindia1\"/>\n\n===Palestine===\nThe population in the [[Palestinian territories]] was enumerated by ethnicity in 1997.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Philippines===\n[[File:Peoples of the Philippines en.svg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of the Philippines in 2000.]]\n\nThe [[Philippines]] enumerated their population by ethnicity in 1948, 1970<ref name=autogenerated6 />, 2000, and 2010.\n\n===Russia/Soviet Union===\n[[File:Ethnic map of Russia 2010.png|100px|thumb|Dominant ethnicity in each [[Russian oblast]] in 2010]]\n\nThe [[Russian Empire]] began counting people by native tongue with [[1897 census|its first modern census in 1897]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /> In 1920, the [[Soviet Union]] replaced this question with a question about ethnicity.<ref>[https://www.un.org/esa/socdev/unpfii/.../workshop_data_stepanov.doc] {{dead link|date=December 2016}}</ref> The Soviet government organized lists of ethnicities and wanted to shape these various ethnic groups in the mold of [[Communism]].<ref name=autogenerated13>\"{{lang|ru|\u041d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441 \u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043a\u0443\u043b\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0430 \u0432 \u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u041a\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0435 (\u0418\u0442\u043e\u0433\u0438 \u0438 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u044b): \u041a \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u0449\u0435\u043c\u0443 \u0441\u044a\u0435\u0437\u0434\u0443 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432}}\" (''Natsionalny vopros i natsionalnaya kultura v Severo-Kavkazskom kraye (Itogi i perspektivy): K predstoyashchemu syezdu gorskikh narodov''), [[Rostov-on-Don]], 1926.</ref> In the words of Soviet politician [[Anastas Mikoyan]], the Soviet Union was \"creating and organising new nations\"<ref name=autogenerated13 /> The government of the U.S.S.R. was eager to get ethnic data for many ethnic groups in order to create republics and autonomous regions for many of these ethnic groups and nationalities, and later on (under [[Joseph Stalin]]) in order to deport some of them.<ref name=slezkine>\n{{cite journal|author=Slezkine, Yuri|year=1994|jstor=2501300|title=The USSR as a Communal Apartment, or How a Socialist State Promoted Ethnic Particularism|journal=[[Slavic Review]]|volume=53|issue=2|pages=414\u2013452|doi=10.2307/2501300}}</ref><ref name=\"martin1998\">{{cite journal|author=Martin, Terry|year=1998|title=The Origins of Soviet Ethnic Cleansing|journal=[[The Journal of Modern History]]|volume=70|issue=4|pages=813\u2013861|doi=10.1086/235168|jstor=10.1086/235168|url=https://dash.harvard.edu/bitstream/handle/1/3229636/Martin%201998.pdf?sequence=2}}</ref> The [[Bolsheviks]] also wanted to get more support from ethnic minority groups within the Soviet Union, many of whom were previously oppressed under [[Russian Tsars|Tsarist]] rule.<ref name=\"martin1998\"/> The Soviet Union continued to ask about ethnicity for the rest of its existence, and [[Russia]] also asked about ethnicity in its two post-Soviet censuses of 2002 and 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/census_types.php?ct=6 |title=\u041f\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0430 Weekly |publisher=Demoscope.ru |date=2011-12-26 |accessdate=2012-09-08}}</ref> Unlike in 1989, the 2002 census did not require respondents to prove their ethnicity/nationality when they responded to this question.<ref>{{cite web|author=F. Joseph Dresen |url=http://www.wilsoncenter.org/publication/russia-counts-the-2002-russian-census |title=Russia Counts: The 2002 Russian Census |publisher=Wilson Center |date=2002-11-18 |accessdate=2013-12-09}}</ref> The number of ethnicity/nationality options available on Soviet censuses was enormous\u2014the Soviet Union offered 194 different choices for ethnicity/nationality in its 1926 census.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=http://www.demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/rus_nation.php |title=\u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f Weekly - \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435. \u0421\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439 |publisher=Demoscope.ru |date=2007-05-27 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> There were 97 options in 1939, 126 options in 1959, 122 options in 1970, 123 options in 1979, and 128 options for the Soviet Union in 1989.<ref name=autogenerated4/> There were 192 ethnicity/nationality options for Russia in 2002.<ref name=autogenerated4/>\n\n===Singapore===\nThe people in [[Singapore]] were numerated by ethnicity from at least 1947 up to the most recent Singaporean census in 2010.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.singstat.gov.sg/pubn/popn/c2010acr.pdf |accessdate=July 2, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327064912/http://www.singstat.gov.sg/pubn/popn/c2010acr.pdf |archivedate=March 27, 2012 |title=Census of Population 2010 Advance Census Release |isbn= 978-981-08-6819-2|publisher=Department of Statistics, Ministry of Trade & Industry, Republic of Singapore }}</ref>\n\n===Sri Lanka===\n{{Disputed|date=November 2019}}\n{{Update|section|date=November 2019}}\n[[Sri Lanka]] enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1971, 1981, and 2012.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Tajikistan===\n[[File:Tajikistan ethnic 92.jpg|right|thumb|100px|Ethnic composition of Tajikistan in 1992]]\nPeople in Tajikistan (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Tajikistan]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses in 2000 and 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.edu/programs/ccs/Docs/Central_Asia/Tajikistan_July09.pdf |title=Table_of_Contents_Central_Asia Series |date= |accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref>\n\n===Thailand===\n[[File:Thailand ethnic map.svg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Thailand in 1974]]\n\n[[Thailand]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1947.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Turkey===\nBetween 1881 and 1893 the [[Ottoman Empire]] implemented its first census, which enumerated the people in the empire by ethnicity.<ref name=autogenerated20>{{harv|Karpat|1978|pp.237-274}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated19>{{harv|Shaw|1978|p.323-338}}</ref> Some other censuses and studies were conducted in the Ottoman Empire for enumerating the population by ethnicity after the first Ottoman census.<ref name=autogenerated20 /><ref name=autogenerated19 />\n\n===Turkmenistan===\nPeople in Turkmenistan (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Turkmenistan]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its only post-Soviet census in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/documents/organization/171762.pdf|title=TURKMENISTAN|publisher=state.gov}}</ref>\n\n===Uzbekistan===\nPeople in [[Uzbekistan]] (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> The Soviet Union (to which Uzbekistan also belonged) enumerated people by ethnicity for its entire existence.<ref name=autogenerated5 /> Uzbekistan has not conducted any censuses at all since 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.edu/programs/ccs/Docs/Central_Asia/Uzbekistan_Overview_June09.pdf|title=Central Asia Executive Summary Series: Uzbekistan Country Profile |publisher=Naval Postgraduate School|date= June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605012218/http://www.nps.edu/Programs/CCS/Docs/Central_Asia/Uzbekistan_Overview_June09.pdf|archivedate=June 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Vietnam===\n[[Communist]] [[North Vietnam]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1960, when Vietnam was still divided into two countries.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/sconcerns/popchar/Ethnicitypaper.pdf |title=Microsoft Word - Ethnicitypaper.doc |date= |accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref> After [[Vietnamese reunification]], Vietnam enumerated its population by ethnicity from 1979 up to the most recent census in 2019.<ref name=autogenerated3 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gso.gov.vn/default.aspx?tabid=503&ItemID=1841 |title=Tong Cuc Thong Ke |publisher=Gso.gov.vn |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>[unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/.../Session8.0_VietNam.ppt]</ref>\n\n===Yemen===\n[[File:Yemen ethno 2002.jpg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnoreligious composition of Yemen in 2002.]]\n\nYemen enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1994.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> The [[British Empire|British]] [[Colony of Aden]] (which is within Yemen's current borders) enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1946 and 1955.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n==Europe==\n\n===Albania===\n[[Albania]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1955,<ref name=autogenerated6>{{cite web|title=Ethnicity: A Review of Data Collection and Dissemination|url=http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/sconcerns/popchar/Ethnicitypaper.pdf|publisher=United Nations Statistics Division|accessdate=30 November 2012|date=August 2003}}</ref> 1989,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/albania-ethnic1989.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Albania 1989 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 2011.<ref name=autogenerated16>{{cite web|author=Gezim Krasniqi |url=http://www.citsee.eu/blog/politics-numbers-and-identity-albania |title=Natitonality and census in Albania |publisher=Citsee.Eu |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated15>{{cite web|url=http://census.al/Resources/Data/Census2011/PES%20Questionnaire%20ENG.pdf|title=Albania Post Enumeration Survey|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711042241/http://census.al/Resources/Data/Census2011/PES%20Questionnaire%20ENG.pdf|archivedate=July 11, 2012|date=2011}}</ref>  The 2011 Albanian census also enumerated people by language used and by their religious beliefs.<ref name=autogenerated16 /><ref name=autogenerated15 />\n\n===Belarus===\n[[File:Belarusians in Belarus 2009.png|thumb|right|100px|[[Belarusians]] as a percentage of the total population in Belarus in 2009 (note: map is in Ukrainian).]]\n\nPeople in Belarus (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Belarus]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses of 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/belarus-ethnic1999.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Belarus 1999 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/belarus-ethnic2009.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Belarus 2009 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Bosnia and Herzegovina===\n[[File:Ethnic Composition of BiH in 1991.gif|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Bosnia and Herzegovina in 1991.]]\n\nThe population of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] has been enumerated by ethnicity since at least 1885, including the recent censuses in 1991 and 2013.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=V9DtlRfO6JMC&pg=PA16&lpg=PA16&dq=yugoslavia+census+1948+1961+serbs#v=onepage&q=yugoslavia%20census%201948%201961%20serbs&f=false |title=Territorial Proposals for the Settlement of the War in Bosnia-Hercegovina ... - Mladen Klemen\u010di\u0107 - Google Books |accessdate=2013-03-21|isbn=9781897643150 |last1=Klemen\u010di\u0107 |first1=Mladen |year=1994 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/bosnia-ethnic1991.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Bosnia & Herzegovina 1991 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Bulgaria===\n[[File:Ethnic composition of Bulgaria, 2011.PNG|thumb|100px|Dominant ethnicities in Bulgaria in 2011]]\n\n[[Bulgaria]] enumerated people by mother tongue in 1880 and 1887 and used this info to determine their ethnicities.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DdEPbQzOjFQC&pg=PA425&lpg=PA425&dq=bulgaria+census+ethnicity+1880+1887+mother+tongue#v=onepage&q=bulgaria%20census%20ethnicity%201880%201887%20mother%20tongue&f=false |title=Bulgaria |author=R.J. Crampton|via=Google Books |publisher=OUP Oxford |date= 2007|accessdate=2012-12-02|isbn=9780191513312}}</ref> Bulgaria directly enumerated people by ethnicity from 1900 all the way up to its most recent census in 2011, with the exception of the 1985 census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsi.bg/census2011/PDOCS2/Census2011final_en.pdf|title=2011 POPULATION CENSUS \u2013 Main Results}}</ref>\n\n===Croatia===\n[[File:Croatia-Ethnic-2011.png|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Croatia in 2011]]\n\nThe people of Croatia have been enumerated by ethnicity/nationality from at least 1953, including the censuses of 2001 and 2011.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/croatia-ethnic2001.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Croatia 2001 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dzs.hr/Eng/censuses/census2011/forms/langs/Englezi%20OP.pdf |title=Og |date= |accessdate=2013-03-16}}</ref>\n\n===Czech Republic===\n[[Czechoslovakia]] (of which the territory of the Czech Republic was a part) enumerated people by ethnicity in 1921 and 1930, and the Czech Republic did the same thing from 1991 to the present day.<ref name=autogenerated23>{{cite web|url=http://praguemonitor.com/2010/11/30/second-czechoslovak-census-held-80-years-ago |title=Second Czechoslovak census held 80 years ago |publisher=Prague Monitor |date=2010-11-30 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Estonia===\nPeople in [[Estonia]] were enumerated by ethnicity/nationality from 1922 to the present day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.ohchr.org/english/bodies/hrc/docs/ngos/LIC_Estonia99.pdf|title=Minority Rights in Estonia|type=Report|publisher= Legal Information Centre for Human Rights}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/estonia-ethnic2000.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Estonia 2000 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stat.ee/34278 |title=Population by ethnic nationality, 1 January, years - Statistics Estonia |publisher=Stat.ee |date=2012-03-30 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> People in Estonia were also enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> During this time period Estonia was under the control of the [[Russian Empire]], then independent, then (excluding [[World War II]]) under the control of the [[Soviet Union]], and then independent again since 1991.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://estonia.eu/about-estonia/country/population-by-nationality.html |title=Population by Nationality |publisher=Estonia.eu |accessdate=2013-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304225022/http://estonia.eu/about-estonia/country/population-by-nationality.html |archive-date=2012-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> There were 192 different ethnicity/nationality options in the 2011 Estonian census.<ref>{{cite web|author=<nowiki>Juhan Tere, BC, Tallinn</nowiki> |url=http://www.baltic-course.com/eng/analytics/?doc=62935 |title=Census 2011: people of 192 ethnic nationalities live in Estonia :: The Baltic Course &#124; Baltic States news & analytics |publisher=The Baltic Course |date=2012-09-17 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Finland===\nFinland has enumerated its population by language of most frequent use from at least 1990 to the present day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pxweb2.stat.fi/Dialog/varval.asp?ma=030_vaerak_tau_102_en&ti=Language+according+to+age+and+gender+by+region+1990+-+2010&path=../Database/StatFin/vrm/vaerak/&lang=1&multilang=en |title=Table: Language according to age and sex by region 1990 - 2011 |publisher=Pxweb2.stat.fi |accessdate=2013-03-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130106153419/http://pxweb2.stat.fi/Dialog/varval.asp?ma=030_vaerak_tau_102_en&ti=Language+according+to+age+and+gender+by+region+1990+-+2010&path=../Database/StatFin/vrm/vaerak/&lang=1&multilang=en |archivedate=2013-01-06 }}</ref>\n\n===France===\n[[France]] has not counted individuals by race or ethnicity since at least 1978, when a law was passed that prevented individuals from being enumerated by these categories without their consent or a state committee waiver.<ref name = \"francerace\">{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:vLz6pnq_4oAJ:www.brookings.edu/fp/cusf/analysis/laurence.pdf+france+census+race+ethnicity+1872+law&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESiJ1dyvouY6Ibx8dja6tnv8e0sqVHvda_pLjbRRf94-Opttxtn4eBTEDpPHnM5A8uyb_RcxB4IVVPWJTc2M_cKtnshQHFZFpIqG53wsjVbhXtoCwZiQaEGMKL3olzpyzvf33sLa&sig=AHIEtbTLE-kOeESgjIHxqg6u_5kmCZk6yQ |title=Powered by Google Docs |date= |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated24>{{cite web|last=Bleich |first=Erik |url=http://www.brookings.edu/research/articles/2001/05/france-bleich |title=Race Policy in France &#124; Brookings Institution |publisher=Brookings.edu |date=2001-05-01 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> The reasons for this are that many French people consider asking people about race and ethnicity to be a contradiction of their principle of [[Social equality|equality]] and equal treatment for all French people.<ref name=autogenerated5 /> Also, there is a desire to avoid repeating what [[Vichy France]] [[The Holocaust in occupied France|did in regards to its Jewish population]] and to prevent the [[National Front (France)|National Front]] from getting more popularity.<ref name=autogenerated5 /><ref name = \"francerace\"/> Former [[French President]] [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] and his administration supported and proposed counting French people by race and ethnicity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.civilrights.org/archives/2009/04/255-french-census.html |title=Next Census in France May Track Race, Ethnicity and Religion - The Leadership Conference on Civil and Human Rights |publisher=Civilrights.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> Due to criticism, however, this proposal was never implemented, and as of 2013 former French President [[Francois Hollande]] opposes enumerating people by race and ethnicity.<ref>{{cite web|last=Admin |first=The |url=http://blackpoliticsontheweb.com/2012/04/16/despite-ethnic-tensions-counting-voters-by-race-remains-taboo-in-french-presidential-campaign/ |title=Despite ethnic tensions, counting voters by race remains taboo in French presidential campaign |publisher=Black Politics on the Web |date=2012-04-16 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Germany===\nGermany enumerated its citizens of Jewish descent in 1939 based on the [[Mischlinge|percent of Jewish ancestry that they had]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wernercohn.com/Paulus.html#5 |title=Bearers of a Common Fate ? The half Jews in Nazi Germany |publisher=Wernercohn.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Hungary===\n[[File:Greater austria ethnic.svg|100px|right|thumb|Ethnic composition of the regions of [[Austria-Hungary]] in 1910]]\n\n[[Hungary]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1880, between 1900 and 1941,<ref>A n\u00e9pess\u00e9g v\u00e1ltoz\u00f3 etnikai arculata Magyarorsz\u00e1g mai ter\u00fclet\u00e9n (map+data+essay) (Kocsis K\u00e1roly, Bottlik Zsolt, [[Hungarian Academy of Sciences]] - F\u00f6ldrajztudom\u00e1nyi Kutat\u00f3int\u00e9zet, [[Budapest]], 2009, {{ISBN|978-963-9545-19-9}})</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-zZ_NVM9mNEC&pg=PA116&lpg=PA116&dq=hungary+census+1941#v=onepage&q=hungary%20census%201941&f=false |title=Ethnic Geography of the Hungarian Minority on the Carpathian Basin - Kocsis, K\u00e1roly, Eszter Kocsisn\u00e9 Hodosi - Google Books |date=1938-11-02 |accessdate=2013-03-21|isbn=9781931313759 |last1=Kocsis |first1=Karoly |last2=Kocsis-Hodosi |first2=Eszter }}</ref> and again from 1980 to the present day<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Ireland===\nThe 2002 Irish census enumerated people by their place of birth and their country of citizenship.<ref name=\"autogenerated9\">[http://www.irishtimes.com/timeseye/whoweare/p3top.htm ireland.com / In Time's Eye / Who we are] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304074405/http://www.irishtimes.com/timeseye/whoweare/p3top.htm |date=March 4, 2011 }}</ref> Ireland introduced an ethnicity question to its census in 2006. The 2011 Irish census enumerated people by ethnicity as well, and offered the options White Irish, White Irish Traveller, Other White, Black or Black Irish (with options for African and Other Black), Asian or Asian Irish (with options for Chinese and Other Asian), Other, and Not Stated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cso.ie/px/pxeirestat/Statire/SelectVarVal/Define.asp?maintable=CD701&PLanguage=0 |title=Population Usually Resident and Present in the State by Age Group, Sex, Ethnic or Cultural Background and CensusYear - StatBank - data and statistics |publisher=Cso.ie |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Italy===\nCensuses in Italy do not inquire about race or ethnicity. Only information disposable are those of civil registers, where only the country of birth is noted down.\n\n===Kosovo===\n[[File:Kosovo ethnic 2005.png|thumb|right|100px|Dominant ethnicities in Kosovo in 2005]]\n\nThe population of Kosovo was enumerated by ethnicity from at least 1948 all the way up to the present day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.icty.org/x/file/About/OTP/War_Demographics/en/milosevic_kosovo_020814.pdf|title=Report on the size and ethnic composition of the population of Kosovo|last=|first=|date=14 August 2002|website=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/kosovo-ethnic2011.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Kosovo 2011 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Latvia===\n[[File:Russians in Baltic States (2011).svg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic Russians as a percentage of the total population in the [[Baltic States]] 2011]]\n\nPeople in Latvia (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> [[Latvia]] enumerated people by ethnicity between 1920 and 1935.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roots-saknes.lv/Ethnicities/ethnicities_statistics.htm |title=Ethnicities in Latvia. Statistics |publisher=Roots-saknes.lv |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> The Soviet Union [[Occupation of the Baltic states|occupied Latvia]] in 1940, and it enumerated people there by ethnicity from 1959 to 1989.<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Latvia]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses of 2000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/latvia-ethnic2000.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Latvia 2000 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://data.csb.gov.lv/Dialog/varval.asp?ma=TSG11-06a&ti=TSG11-06%2E+RESIDENT+POPULATION+ON+MARCH+1%2C+2011+BY+ETHNICITY%2C+SEX+AND+AGE+GROUP&path=../DATABASEEN/tautassk_11/Final%20results%20of%20the%20Population%20and%20Housing%20Census%202011/&lang=1 |title=Table: TSG11-06. RESIDENT POPULATION ON MARCH 1, 2011 BY ETHNICITY, SEX AND AGE GROUP |publisher=Data.csb.gov.lv |date=2011-03-01 |accessdate=2013-03-21 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Lithuania===\nPeople in Lithuania (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> [[Lithuania]] enumerated people by ethnicity in its 1923 census and in its 1925 census of its [[Klaipeda]] region.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kasatkina|first=Natalija|last2=Marcinkevicius|first2=Andrius|title=Russians in Lithuania According to the 1897 and 1923 Censuses: Comparative Analysis|url=http://www.ces.lt/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/EtSt_Kasatkina_Marcinkevicius_2008.pdf|journal=Ethnicity Studies|volume=|issn=1822-1041}}</ref> The Soviet Union [[Occupation of the Baltic states|occupied Lithuania]] in 1940, and it enumerated people there by ethnicity from 1959 to 1989.<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Lithuania]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses of 2001<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/lithuania-ethnic2001.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Lithuania 2001 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.15min.lt/en/article/in-lithuania/lithuania-s-population-stands-at-3-043-million-525-259643 |title=Lithuania's population stands below three million |publisher=15min.lt |date=2013-02-04 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Luxembourg===\nIt is illegal to collect statistics about the race, ethnicity, religion or ancestry of Luxembourg citizens.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\n===Moldova===\n[[File:Major ethnics groups in Moldova 1989.jpg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Moldova in 1989]]\n\nPeople in Moldova (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Moldova]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in both its post-Soviet censuses: in [[2004 Moldovan Census|2004]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/moldova-ethnic2004.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Moldova 2004 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and [[2014 Moldovan Census|2014]].<ref>[http://www.statistica.md/pageview.php?l=en&idc=479 Results of Population and Housing Census in the Republic of Moldova in 2014]</ref>\n\n===Monaco===\n[[Monaco]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1982.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Montenegro===\n[[File:Ethnic map of Montenegro by municipality.svg|thumb|100px|Dominant ethnicities in Montenegro in 2011]]\n\nThe population of [[Montenegro]] was enumerated by ethnicity from 1909 up to its most recent census in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njegos.org/census/index.htm |title=Montenegrin Census' from 1909 to 2003 - Aleksandar Rakovic |publisher=Njegos.org |date=2004-09-23 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/montenegro-ethnic2003.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Montenegro 2003 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transconflict.com/2011/07/montenegro-a-census-like-no-other-147/ |title=Montenegro - a census like no other? |publisher=TransConflict |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===North Macedonia===\n[[File:Map of the majority ethnic groups of Macedonia by municipality.svg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of North Macedonia in 2002.]]\n\nPeople in [[North Macedonia]] were enumerated by ethnicity/nationality from at least 1921 all the way up to the present day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://epc2008.princeton.edu/papers/80013|title=Changes in ethnic structure in Macedonia after emigration of Turkish minority|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> In the most recent census in 2002, 64.2% of the population declared themselves to be [[ethnic Macedonian]]s. The second-largest ethnic group in the country was the ethnic [[Albanians]] with 25.2%. Other major ethnic groups were [[Turkish people|Turks]] (3.9%), [[Romani people|Romani]] (2.7%), and [[Serbs]] (1.8%).<ref name=\"Statistical Office\">[http://www.stat.gov.mk/Publikacii/knigaX.pdf Macedonian census, language and religion]</ref>\n\n===Norway===\nNorway enumerated the population in the northern part of the country by ethnicity between 1845 and 1930.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mbMs68rD9doC&pg=PA173&dq=norway+census+ethnicity#v=onepage&q=norway%20census%20ethnicity&f=false |title=Indigenous Peoples and Demography: The Complex Relation Between Identity and ... - Google Books |date=2011-08-15 |accessdate=2013-09-01|isbn=9780857450036 |last1=Axelsson |first1=Per |last2=Sk\u00f6ld |first2=Peter }}</ref> In the census of 1970, in limited areas in Northern Norway, people were identified by ethnicity and language.  Such information has not been included in any census since then.<ref>{{cite web| title = Norwegian National Archives | url = http://www.ssb.no/befolkning/artikler-og-publikasjoner/paa-vei-mot-eu-medlemskap | date = 2013\n| accessdate = 29 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Poland===\nPeople in Poland (when [[Partitions of Poland|the country was still occupied]] by the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated allegedly by their native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> Sovereign [[Poland]] enumerated people by ethnicity/nationality in 1921.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kresy.co.uk/census_demographic.html |title=Polish 1921 Census and Demographic Data |publisher=Kresy.co.uk |accessdate=2013-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130305005728/http://www.kresy.co.uk/census_demographic.html |archive-date=2013-03-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It enumerated people by mother tongue in 1931, and used this data to determine ethnicity/nationality.<ref name=autogenerated14>{{cite web |url=http://www6.gencat.net/llengcat/noves/hm04primavera-estiu/docs/moskal.pdf |title=Language minorities in Poland at the moment of accession to the EU, by Marta Moskal |accessdate=2013-03-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512204841/http://www6.gencat.net/llengcat/noves/hm04primavera-estiu/docs/moskal.pdf |archivedate=2013-05-12 }}</ref> After [[World War II]], the [[Polish People's Republic|Communist Polish government]] did not enumerate people by nationality/ethnicity.<ref name=autogenerated14 /> The post-Communist 2002 Polish census did enumerate people by nationality/ethnicity and language used at home.<ref name=autogenerated14 />\n\n===Romania===\n[[File:Romania harta etnica 2011.PNG|100px|thumb|Ethnic map of Romania in 2011]]\n\n[[Romania]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1859\u20131860,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.recensamantromania.ro/en/history/censuses-1859-1990/ |title=Censuses of 1859-1990 &#124; Recensamant 2011 |publisher=Recensamantromania.ro |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> 1887,<ref>{{cite book | page=407 | title = The Statesman's Year-Book | year = 1889| publisher = St. Martin's Press | url = }}</ref> 1899,<ref>{{cite book | page=612 | title = New International Yearbook | year = 1915| publisher = Dodd, Mead and Company | url = }}</ref> and in every census since 1930, with the exception of the 1948 census, which enumerated people only by mother tongue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hungarianhistory.com/lib/humis/humis07.htm |title=The Hungarian Minority's Situation in Ceausescu's Romania |publisher=Hungarianhistory.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/#romania|title=Population Statistics of Eastern Europe \u00a7 Romania|publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.insse.ro/cms/files%5Cstatistici%5Ccomunicate%5Calte%5C2012%5CComunicat%20DATE%20PROVIZORII%20RPL%202011e.pdf |title=Comunicat DATE PROVIZORII RPL 2011_transmis |accessdate=2012-12-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114205218/http://www.insse.ro/cms/files/statistici/comunicate/alte/2012/Comunicat%20DATE%20PROVIZORII%20RPL%202011e.pdf |archivedate=2012-11-14 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.recensamantromania.ro/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/Comunicat_DATE_PROVIZORII_RPL_2011.pdf|title=COMUNICAT DE PRES\u0102 2 februarie 2012 privind rezultatele provizorii ale Recens\u0103m\u00e2ntului Popula\u0163iei \u015fi Locuin\u0163elor \u2013 2011 |date=February 2, 2012}}</ref> The [[World Jewish Congress]] also carried out a census of [[Romanian Jews|Romania's Jewish population]] in 1947.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/vjw/romaniatoc.html|title=Romania|work=Virtual Jewish Library}}</ref>\n\n===Serbia===\n[[File:Census 2002 Serbia, ethnic map (by municipalities).png|thumb|100px|right|Ethnic composition of Serbia in 2002]]\n\nIn addition to [[Yugoslavia]] enumerating people by ethnicity/nationality, [[Serbia]] enumerated people by ethnicity/nationality in its 2002 and 2011 censuses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.osce.org/serbia/30908|title=Ethnic Minorities in Serbia - An overview|date=February 27, 2008|publisher=Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/society.php?yyyy=2011&mm=11&dd=16&nav_id=77354 |title=Serbia has fewer citizens, census results show |publisher=B92 |date=2011-11-16 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Slovakia===\nThe population of [[Slovakia]] was enumerated by ethnicity/nationality since 1910 all the way up to the present day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hhrf.org/kisebbsegkutatas/mr_04/cikk.php?id=1188 |title=L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Gyurgyik:Hungarians in Czechoslovakia: Changes in Their Population And Settlement System from 1918 to the Present Day |publisher=Hhrf.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sodb.infostat.sk/sodb/eng/1848-2001/tab.III.2-2B_en.htm |title=Demografick\u0439 \u044adaje zo s\u0438\u043dtania \u040audu 1921 |publisher=Sodb.infostat.sk |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://portal.statistics.sk/files/Sekcie/sek_600/Demografia/SODB/Tabulky/Tabulky_AJ_SODB/tab11.pdf|title=Table 11. Resident population by nationality - 2001, 1991|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715152521/http://portal.statistics.sk/files/Sekcie/sek_600/Demografia/SODB/Tabulky/Tabulky_AJ_SODB/tab11.pdf|archivedate=July 15, 2007|publisher=Statistical Office of the SR|year=2005}}</ref>\n\n===Slovenia===\nThe population of [[Slovenia]] was enumerated by ethnicity since 1953 all the way up to the present day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stat.si/popis2002/en/rezultati/rezultati_red.asp?ter=SLO&st=7 |title=Statisti\u010dni urad RS - Popis 2002 |publisher=Stat.si |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Transnistria===\nPeople in [[Transnistria]] (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> the de facto independent country of Transnistria also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses in 2004 and 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.olvia.idknet.com/ol37-09-05.htm |title=Ol37-09-05 |publisher=Olvia.idknet.com |accessdate=2013-03-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105231746/http://www.olvia.idknet.com/ol37-09-05.htm |archivedate=2012-11-05 }}</ref> [[Romania]] also enumerated people in Transnistria by ethnicity in its 1941 census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Holocaust/romanianjewry.html|title=The Plan for the Extermination of Romanian Jewry|work=Jewish Virtual Library}}</ref>\n\n===Ukraine===\n[[File:Ethnolingusitic map of ukraine.png|right|thumb|100px|Ethnolinguistic composition of Ukraine.]]\n\nPeople in Ukraine (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Ukraine]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its only post-Soviet census in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/ukraine-ethnic2001.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Ukraine 2001 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\nThe [[United Kingdom]] began [[Classification of ethnicity in the United Kingdom|counting people by ethnicity]] in [[United Kingdom Census 1991|1991]].<ref>{{cite journal | author1 = K. Sillitoe | author2 = P. H. White | title = Ethnic Group and the British Census: the Search for a Question | journal = Journal of the Royal Statistical Society, Series A | volume = 155 | issue = 1 | pages = 141\u2013163 | year = 1992 | doi=10.2307/2982673| pmid = 12159122 | jstor = 2982673 }}</ref> There eventually became more of an interest in enumerating ethnic minorities after large-scale racial minority immigration to the United Kingdom began in the post-[[World War II]] era.<ref>{{cite book|chapterurl=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/~uctpb21/Cpapers/Ethn_2gen_revision_C1.pdf|chapter=Ethnicity and Second Generation Immigrants |author1=Christian Dustmann|author2=Tommaso Frattini|author3= Nikolaos Theodoropoulos|doi=10.1093/acprof:osobl/9780199587377.003.0016|title=The Labour Market in Winter: The State of Working Britain|isbn=9780199587377|year=2011}}</ref> The United Kingdom previously planned to enumerate people by ethnicity in 1981, but changed its mind after the large non-response rate to this question in the 1979 Test Census. In 1979, many ethnic minorities refused to answer this question due to the fear of deportation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iser.essex.ac.uk/files/iser_working_papers/2008-26.pdf|title=Who are the UK's minority ethnic groups? Issues of identification and measurement in a longitudinal study|date=September 2008|author1=Jonathan Burton|author2=Alita Nandi |author3=Lucinda Platt |type=Working paper}}</ref> In the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 census]], the ethnic group options for England and Wales were White, Mixed, [[Asian British]], [[Black British]], [[Chinese people|Chinese]] or other ethnic group, and Not stated, with ethnic origin sub-group choices for most of these.<ref name=\"TIAUKcodes\">{{cite web|title=New Ethnicity Code List|url=http://www.theia.org.uk/NR/rdonlyres/9568290B-80AA-4030-AED3-046A8E5C3F92/0/L12V_1_2_NewEthnicityCodes.doc|publisher=The Information Authority|accessdate=24 August 2012}}</ref> The census in the United Kingdom also included a question on country of citizenship between 1851 and 1961.<ref name=\"catdir\"/>\n\n===Vatican City===\n[[Vatican City]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1948.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n==North America==\n\n===Bahamas===\nThe population of the [[Bahamas]] was enumerated by ethnicity in 1953 and again in 2010.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Barbados===\nThe population of [[Barbados]] was enumerated by ethnicity in 1946, 1960, 1970, and 1980.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Belize===\nBack when [[Belize]] was [[British Honduras]], it enumerated people by ethnicity in 1946. Since gaining independence, Belize has enumerated people by ethnicity from 1980 all the way up to its most recent census in 2010.\n\n===Bermuda===\nThe people of [[Bermuda]] were enumerated by ethnicity since at least 1950 all the way up to the present day.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|author=Keith Archibald Forbes |url=http://www.bermuda-online.org/population.htm |title=Bermuda's Population and local Expatriate Organizations |publisher=Bermuda-online.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Canada===\n[[File:Censusdivisions-ethnic.png|100px|thumb|right|A map of the largest ethnic ancestry in different regions of Canada]]\n\n[[Canada]] [[Demographics of Canada|counted people by ethnic origin]] in 1765 and again from at least 1871 to 2006, with the exception of 1891.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/ref/about-apropos/history-histoire-eng.cfm |title=2011 Census - About the census: History of the Census of Canada |publisher=2.statcan.gc.ca |date=2013-01-10 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated17>{{cite web|url=http://www23.statcan.gc.ca/imdb-bmdi/pub/instrument/3901_Q2_V3-eng.pdf |title=ARCHIVED - PDF Document |publisher=3.statcan.gc.ca |date=2010-05-17 |accessdate=2013-01-14}}</ref><ref name=\"statcan2006\">{{cite web|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2006/ref/rp-guides/ethnic-ethnique-eng.cfm |title=2006 Census : Ethnic Origin Reference Guide |publisher=2.statcan.gc.ca |date=2011-05-04 |accessdate=2013-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=tRzXJAFODuwC&pg=PA4&dq=canada+census+1891+ethnic+origin#v=onepage&q=canada%20census%201891%20ethnic%20origin&f=false |title=Race and Research - Google Books |accessdate=2013-03-21|isbn=9780875530307 |last1=Beech |first1=Bettina M. |last2=Goodman |first2=Maurine |year=2004 }}</ref> The options for ethnicity in the 2006 Canadian census were various kinds of [[European Canadian]], [[Aboriginal Canadian]], and various [[non-white]] or non-European groups known officially as \"[[visible minorities]]\".<ref name=autogenerated17 /> The 2011 Canadian census did not ask about race and ethnicity,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p1/2010/2010-08-21/html/order-decret-eng.html |title=ARCHIVED \u2014 Canada Gazette \u2013 ORDERS IN COUNCIL |publisher=Gazette.gc.ca |date=2012-11-09 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> but the new voluntary National Household Survey (NHS) for that year did ask about race and ethnicity (as well as many other questions that were previously asked on the Canadian census).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/NHS-ENM/ref/Questionnaires/2011NHS-ENM-eng.cfm#Q17 |title=2011 National Household Survey Questions |publisher=2.statcan.gc.ca |accessdate=2013-03-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809041130/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/NHS-ENM/ref/Questionnaires/2011NHS-ENM-eng.cfm#Q17 |archivedate=2011-08-09 }}</ref> Prior to the 1981 Canadian census, respondents could only mark one ethnicity/ethnic ancestry, but the 1981 census and all future ones allowed multiple ethnicity responses.<ref name=\"statcan2006\"/> Canada also enumerated its population by place of birth from 1871 to the present day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/11-516-x/sectiona/4147436-eng.htm |title=Historical statistics of Canada: Section A: Population and Migration |publisher=Statcan.gc.ca |date=2008-10-22 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2006/as-sa/97-557/pdf/97-557-XIE2006001.pdf |title=Microsoft Word - 97-557-XIE_immigration_26-11-07.doc |date= |accessdate=2013-03-16}}</ref>\n\n===Costa Rica===\n[[Costa Rica]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1950.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Cuba===\n[[Cuba]] enumerated people by race since 1774 to the most recent official census in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://digital.tcl.sc.edu/cdm4/document.php?CISOROOT=/CCC&CISOPTR=1683&REC=5&CISOBOX=foreign|title=Report on the Census of Cuba, 1899 :: Census of Cuba 1899|website=Digital.tcl.sc.edu|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onei.gob.cu/sites/default/files/informe_nacional_censo_0.pdf|title=Censo de poblacion y viviendas Cuba|date=January 2014|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Dominica===\nThe people in [[Dominica]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1960 and 1981.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Dominican Republic===\nThe people in the [[Dominican Republic]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1950.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Grenada===\nThe people of [[Grenada]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1960 and 1981.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Guatemala===\n[[Guatemala]] has enumerated people by ethnicity in 1950, 1964, 2002, and 2018.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Jamaica===\nThe population of Jamaica was enumerated by ethnicity in 1960 and again from 1982 all the way up to the present day.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caricomstats.org/Files/Publications/NCR%20Reports/Jamaica.pdf |title=2000 Round of Population and Housing Census Data Analysis Sub-Project|date= |accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://statinja.gov.jm/PublicationReleases.aspx |accessdate=July 19, 2019 |title=Census 2011 General Report}}</ref>\n\n===Mexico===\n[[Mexico]] enumerates people on whether or not they speak [[Spanish language|Spanish]] or indigenous languages.<ref name=\"autogenerated2001\">{{Cite web|url=http://sociology.as.nyu.edu/docs/IO/1043/Pop.Comp.IESBS.2001.pdf|title=Population Composition by Race and Ethnicity: North America|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Mexico does not enumerate its population by race and ethnicity directly.<ref name=\"autogenerated2001\"/>\n\n===Panama===\n[[Panama]] has enumerated people by ethnicity from the 1970 census all the way up to its most recent census in 2010.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|author=Don Winner |url=http://www.panama-guide.com/article.php/20100511134852268 |title=National Census in Panama This Sunday, 16 May 2010 |publisher=Panama Guide |date= |accessdate=2013-03-16}}</ref> People in the then-United States-controlled [[Panama Canal Zone]] were numerated by ethnicity in 1950 and 1960.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Puerto Rico===\n[[Puerto Rico]] enumerated people by race in its census [[Demographics of Puerto Rico|since at least 1877]] with the exception of the period from 1960 to 1990.\n\n===United States===\n{{details|Race and ethnicity in the United States Census}}\n\n[[File:Census-2000-Data-Top-US-Ancestries-by-County.svg|400px|thumb|right|The [[wikt:plurality|plurality]] (not [[majority]]) ethnic ancestry in each [[county (United States)|county in the United States of America]]]]\n\nBefore the [[American Revolutionary War|U.S. acquired independence from Great Britain]], many of the [[Thirteen Colonies]] conducted [[censuses]] of their own where they enumerated their populations by [[Race (human classification)|race]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/22/opinion/fix-the-census-archaic-racial-categories.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 | work=The New York Times | first=Kenneth | last=Prewitt | title=Fix the Census' Archaic Racial Categories | date=2013-08-21}}</ref><ref name=\"census5\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.census.gov/prod2/statcomp/documents/CT1970p2-13.pdf |title=2-11-Z-COLONIAL & PRE-FEDERAL.pdf |date= |accessdate=2013-06-20}}</ref> The [[United States]] as a whole [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|enumerated people by race]] in every [[United States Census|census]] since [[U.S. Census, 1790|its first census]] in 1790.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/twps0056.html |title=Historical Census Statistics on Population Totals By Race, 1790 to 1990, and By Hispanic Origin, 1970 to 1990, For The United States, Regions, Divisions, and States |publisher=Census.gov |accessdate=2013-05-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224151538/http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/twps0056.html |archivedate=2014-12-24 }}</ref>  Part of the reason why the United States began counting people by race much sooner than many other countries was due to the [[Three Fifths Compromise]], which determined the amount of representation that Southern states had based on how many slaves they had (slaves were counted as three-fifths of a person for representation purposes, and a new census every ten years was needed to enumerate the current slave population).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csa.com/discoveryguides/census/review3.php |title=Multiracial Identity and the U.S. Census, ProQuest Discovery Guides |publisher=Csa.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> Initially, the [[United States Census]] only counted Americans as either [[White American|white]] or [[African American|black]], with blacks classified as either [[Free people of color|free]] or [[slaves]] until 1860 ([[slavery in the United States]] was [[Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|abolished]] in 1865).<ref name=\"usrace2002\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/twps0056.html |title=Historical Census Statistics on Population Totals By Race, 1790 to 1990, and By Hispanic Origin, 1970 to 1990, For The United States, Regions, Divisions, and States |publisher=Census.gov |accessdate=2012-09-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224151538/http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/twps0056.html |archivedate=2014-12-24 }}</ref> Over time, the United States has also added some other racial categories as well.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> [[Asian-American|Asian]] and [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] categories were added in 1860.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> However, the first census to enumerate all Native Americans occurred in 1890.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> Before that point Native Americans living on [[Indian reservation|reservations]] were not counted, and thus most Native Americans in the U.S. were not counted in census data before 1890.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> Between 1850 and 1870, and in 1890, 1910, and 1920, the [[U.S. Census Bureau]] also enumerated [[Mulattoes]] and sometimes other partially black groups ([[Quadroons]] and [[Octoroons]]) separately.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/>\n\nThe [[U.S. Census Bureau]] counted [[Mexicans]] as a separate race in 1930<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://chnm.gmu.edu/staff/sharon/readings/ngai.html |author=Mae M. Ngai |title= The Architecture of Race in American Immigration Law: A Reexamination of the Immigration Act of 1924|journal= The Journal of American History|volume=86|issue=1|publisher=The History Cooperative |via=Chnm.gmu.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-06-22|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141127115837/http://chnm.gmu.edu/staff/sharon/readings/ngai.html|archivedate=November 27, 2014}}</ref> and tried to retroactively determine the number of Mexicans in the U.S. in 1910 and 1920 as well.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/>\n\nPresident [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] promoted a [[Good Neighbor policy|\"good neighbor\" policy]] that sought better relations with Mexico.  In 1935, a [[federal judge]] ruled that three Mexican immigrants were ineligible for citizenship because they were not white, as required by federal law<!-- citation need -->.  Mexico protested, and Roosevelt decided to circumvent the decision and make sure the federal government treated Hispanics as white.  The [[U.S. State Department|State Department]], the Census Bureau, the [[U.S. Labor Department|Labor Department]], and other [[government agencies]] therefore made sure to uniformly classify people of Mexican descent as white.  This policy encouraged the [[League of United Latin American Citizens]] in its quest to minimize discrimination by asserting their whiteness.<ref>Patrick D. Lukens, ''A Quiet Victory for Latino Rights: FDR and the Controversy over Whiteness'' (University of Arizona Press, 2012)</ref>\n\nHispanics were counted as whites in 1940, but for the first time ever, the U.S. made an attempt to measure the size of the Hispanic population that year.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> The U.S. resumed enumerating its [[Hispanic]]/Latino population in 1970, with Hispanics being enumerated in every U.S. census since then.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> The U.S. Census Bureau also began offering Hispanics several sub-group options from which they could identify themselves, such as Mexican, Puerto Rican, Cuban, et cetera (these Hispanic sub-group options have changed over time).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/tabD-04.pdf |title=Table D-4. Hispanic Origin (of Any Race), for the United States, Regions, Divisions, and States: 1940 and 1970 (Sample Data) (See text for sources, definitions, and explanations) |accessdate=2017-12-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120101537/http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/tabD-04.pdf |archivedate=2013-01-20 }} </ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/tabD-02.pdf |title=Table D-2. Hispanic Origin (of Any Race), for the United States, Regions, Divisions, and States: 1990 (Sample Data) (See text for sources, definitions, and explanations) |accessdate=2017-12-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120101352/http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/tabD-02.pdf |archivedate=2013-01-20 }} </ref> The Other race category was added in 1950, and in 2000 multi-race responses were tabulated for the first time  (instructions now explicitly inform respondents that they can choose multiple race boxes).<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> Because multiracial respondents are now allowed, U.S. Census data since 2000 is not directly comparable with that of previous censuses.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> While people nowadays are enumerated by race based on self-identification, until 1950 their race on the census was mainly determined by their census enumerator.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> During this time multiracial people who were White and of another race were usually marked down as belonging to the other race due to the [[One drop rule]].<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> The instructions provided to enumerators endorsed this practice.\n\nIt is worth noting that some of the definitions of race in the United States changed over time. For instance, [[Indian Americans]] were previously marked as Hindu in 1920\u20131940, Other race in 1950\u20131960, and White in 1970 before being marked as Asian (Indian) since 1980.<ref name = \"usrace2002\"/> The [[U.S. census]] counted certain [[Asian people|Asian]] ethnic groups separately since 1870, initially counting only [[Chinese Americans|Chinese]] and [[Japanese Americans|Japanese]], but having other categories as well since 1910.<ref name = \"usrace2002\"/> It only began counting all people by ethnic ancestry since [[U.S. Census, 1980|the 1980 census]], though.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usa.ipums.org/usa/voliii/items1980.shtml |title=IPUMS USA: 1980 Census Questions and Instructions |publisher=Usa.ipums.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> In addition to a Hispanic/Latino ''ethnicity'' question that has appeared on the census short form since 1980 (based on the US [[Office of Management and Budget]]'s official categories specified in 1977). In addition, at various times the Census Bureau has also used an ''ancestry'' question. Before 1970, [[Alaska]] and [[Hawaii]] had different choices for race on their censuses in contrast to the [[continental United States]].<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/>\n\nThe United States has also used language as a way to classify people by race or ethnicity.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Leeman|first=Jennifer|date=2004|title=Racializing language: A history of linguistic ideologies in the US Census|url=https://www.academia.edu/335479|journal=Journal of Language and Politics|language=en|volume=3|issue=3|pages=507\u2013534|issn=1569-2159|via=|doi=10.1075/jlp.3.3.08lee}}</ref> From 1910 to 1940, the Census recorded the mother tongue of the foreign-born population and their children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0029/tab06.html |title=Tech Paper 29: Table 6. Mother Tongue of the Foreign-Born Population: 1910 to 1940, 1960, and 1970 |publisher=Census.gov |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> In 1960 and 1970 the Census Bureau also used mother tongue to classify respondents by ethnicity, but the definition of mother tongue was not consistent. Since 1980, the Census Bureau has tabulated [[Language Spoken at Home|language spoken at home]] for people aged five or older.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/hhes/socdemo/language/data/acs/Table2.xls |title=Table 2 (download) |publisher=Census.gov }}</ref> \n\nThe [[2020 United States Census]] might allow [[Middle Easterners]] and [[North African American|North Africans]] to write in their ethnicity/race instead of merely marking them as White.<ref name=autogenerated8>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/08/09/census-bureau-changes-race-hispanics-negro_n_1760467.html |title=Census Bureau Proposes Changes: Hispanics As Distinct Category And End Use Of Term 'Negro' |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= 2012-08-09|accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Turnbull |first=Lornet |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2019032486_censuschange31m.html |title=Latinos may get own race category on census form &#124; Local News |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> Right now, and in the past, [[Arab Americans|Arabs]] have been marked in the U.S. Census as White.<ref name=autogenerated8 /> This began in the early twentieth century when [[Arabs]] [[Immigration to the United States|coming to the United States]] successfully petitioned to be marked as White in order to avoid entry quotas and have a greater chance of achieving success and avoiding discrimination.<ref\nname=autogenerated8/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aaiusa.org/pages/not-quite-white-race-classification-and-the-arab-american-experience |title=Not Quite White: Race Classification and the Arab American Experience &#124; The Arab American Institute |publisher=Aaiusa.org |accessdate=2013-06-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826035428/http://www.aaiusa.org/pages/not-quite-white-race-classification-and-the-arab-american-experience |archivedate=2014-08-26 }}</ref>\n\nThe United States is one of the countries that uses racial and ethnic census data in order to create [[minority-majority districts]], as is required by the 1965 [[Voting Rights Act]].<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://www.personal.psu.edu/ljk20/MAJ-MINOR.pdf|title=African American Turnout in Majority-Minority Districts|author=Luke Keele|author2=Ismail White|date= December 13, 2011}}</ref> These districts were created in order to increase minority representation in the [[United States Congress]] following the end of legal [[Racial segregation|segregation]] and racial discrimination in the [[Southern United States]].<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nSince 1850, the United States enumerated its population by their country of birth of its population.<ref name=autogenerated21>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0081/twps0081.html |title=Historical Census Statistics on the Foreign-Born Population of the United States: 1850-2000 |publisher=Census.gov |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> The whole U.S. population was enumerated by country of birth between 1850 and 1930 and again from 1960 to the present day.<ref name=autogenerated21 /> Meanwhile, only the [[White Americans|White population of the United States]] was enumerated by their country of birth in 1940 and 1950.<ref name=autogenerated21 />\n\n==Oceania==\n\n===Australia===\nAustralia enumerated its population by ''race'' between 1911 and 1966, by ''racial origin'' in 1971 and 1976, by ''ethnic'' origin in 1981, and by ''ancestry'' since 1986.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/Lookup/2071.0Feature+Article2July+2011 |title=2071.0 - Reflecting a Nation: Stories from the 2011 Census, July 2011 |publisher=Abs.gov.au |date=2012-06-20 |accessdate=2013-04-06}}</ref>\n\n===Fiji===\nThe population of [[Fiji]] was enumerated by ethnicity from 1881 all the way up to Fiji's most recent census in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.int/prism/country/fj/stats/Key%20Stats/Population/1.1%20census%20of%20population.pdf|title=1.1 CENSUS OF POPULATION NY ETHNICITY 1881 - 2007|publisher=Fiji Bureau of Statistics |date=June 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114214328/http://www.spc.int/prism/country/fj/stats/Key%20Stats/Population/1.1%20census%20of%20population.pdf|archivedate=November 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Nauru===\nThe population of [[Nauru]] was enumerated by ethnicity between 1947 and 1977.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===New Zealand===\n[[File:MaoriPopulationPercentage.png|thumb|right|100px|Maoris as a percentage of the total population of New Zealand in 2006.]]\n\n[[New Zealand]] enumerated people by ethnicity from 1858 to the present day.<ref name=autogenerated7>{{cite web|url=http://www.stats.govt.nz/Census/about-2006-census/introduction-to-the-census/history-of-the-census-in-nz.aspx |title=Introduction to the Census - Statistics New Zealand |publisher=Stats.govt.nz |date=2006-11-24 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> People were enumerated by tribal affiliation in 1901 and again from 1991 to the present day.<ref name=autogenerated7 />\n\n===Palau===\n[[Palau]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1995.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Papua New Guinea===\n[[Papua New Guinea]] only enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1971.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n==South America==\n\n===Argentina===\nArgentina enumerated its population by their country of birth from 1869 to the present day.<ref name=autogenerated22>{{cite web|url=http://www.indec.gov.ar/webcenso/aquisecuenta/Aqui12.pdf|title=Tendencias recientes de la Inmigraci\u00f3n internacional |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070824231326/http://www.indec.gov.ar/webcenso/aquisecuenta/aqui12.pdf|archivedate=August 24, 2007|date=February 2004 |issn= 0329-7586|publisher=Indec}}</ref>\n\n===Bolivia===\n[[File:Pueblos originarios de Bolivia.png|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Bolivia.]]\n\n[[Bolivia]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1950,<ref name=autogenerated6 /> 2001,<ref>{{cite web|author=CEPAL - Naciones Unidas |url=http://www.eclac.org/cgi-bin/getProd.asp?xml=/publicaciones/xml/3/23263/P23263.xml&xsl=/celade/tpl/p9f.xsl&base=/celade/tpl/top-bottom.xsl |title=CEPAL - Los pueblos ind\u00edgenas de Bolivia: diagn\u00f3stico sociodemogr\u00e1fico a partir del censo del 2001 |publisher=Eclac.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 2012.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref name=autogenerated25>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/bolivias-census-omits-mestizo-category-17779349#.ULm6AJtQAak |title=Bolivia's Census Omits 'Mestizo' as Category - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> The 2012 census included 40 ethnic group options.<ref name=autogenerated25 /> However, it did not include [[Mestizo]] as an option, which critics of current [[Bolivian President]] [[Evo Morales]] say was because he wants more Bolivians to identify as one of the indigenous groups in order to lend more legitimacy to his indigenous-friendly policies.<ref name=autogenerated25 />\n\n<div class=\"mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\">\n<div style=\"font-weight:bold; font-size:100%; padding:5px;\">'''Data from the census in 2012'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Census in Bolivia|url=http://www.ine.gob.bo:8081/censo2012/PDF/resultadosCPV2012.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209134921/http://www.ine.gob.bo:8081/censo2012/PDF/resultadosCPV2012.pdf|archivedate=2014-02-09}}</ref></div>\n<div class=\"mw-collapsible-content\" style=\"background-color:#faf6ed;\">\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ethnic group !! Total people !! Male !!Female\n|-\n| Afroboliviano ||align=\"right\"|16.329 || align=\"right\"|8.785 || align=\"right\"|7.544\n|-\n| Araona || align=\"right\"|910 || align=\"right\"|452 || align=\"right\"|458\n|-\n| Aymara || align=\"right\"|1.191.352 || align=\"right\"|592.817 || align=\"right\"|598.535\n|-\n| Ayoreo || align=\"right\"|1.862 || align=\"right\"|954 || align=\"right\"|908\n|-\n| Baure || align=\"right\"|2.319 || align=\"right\"|1.219 || align=\"right\"|1.100\n|-\n| Canichana || align=\"right\"|617 || align=\"right\"|360 || align=\"right\"|257\n|-\n| Cavine\u00f1o || align=\"right\"|2.005 || align=\"right\"|1.118 || align=\"right\"|887\n|-\n| Cayubaba || align=\"right\"|1.424 || align=\"right\"|738 || align=\"right\"|686\n|-\n| Chacobo || align=\"right\"|826 || align=\"right\"|418 || align=\"right\"|408\n|-\n| Chipaya || align=\"right\"|786 || align=\"right\"|400 || align=\"right\"|386\n|-\n| Chiquitano || align=\"right\"|87.885 || align=\"right\"|45.497 || align=\"right\"|42.388\n|-\n| Esse Ejja || align=\"right\"|695 || align=\"right\"|379 || align=\"right\"|316\n|-\n| Guaran\u00ed || align=\"right\"|58.990 || align=\"right\"|29.918 || align=\"right\"|29.072\n|-\n| Guarasugwe || align=\"right\"|42 || align=\"right\"|25 || align=\"right\"|17\n|-\n| Guarayo || a