\"right\"|292 || align=\"right\"|171 || align=\"right\"|121\n|-\n|  other || align=\"right\"|42.188 || align=\"right\"|19.861 || align=\"right\"|22.327\n|-\n|  Other not specified || align=\"right\"|4.419 || align=\"right\"|2.333 || align=\"right\"|2.086\n|-\n| Not belong || align=\"right\"|4.032.014 || align=\"right\"|1.975.811 || align=\"right\"|2.056.203\n|}\n</div></div>\n\n===Brazil===\n[[File:Brancos no Brasil.png|thumb|right|100px|Brazilian states according to the percentage of [[Whites]] in 2009.]]\nThe [[Brazil]]ian census [[Race and ethnicity in Brazil|enumerated people by race]] in all censuses since 1872 with the exception of 1900, 1920, and 1970.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/soc/faculty/telles/Paper_AffirmationandAmbiguity.pdf |title=Mapping the ethno-racial composition of the Brazilian population has long been viewed as problematic due principally to the am |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> The Brazilian census classifies people by race as either white, black, pardo (brown), yellow (Asian), or indigenous.\n\n===Chile===\n[[Chile]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1992.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Guyana===\n[[Guyana]] enumerated people by ethnicity from at least 1946 to until at least 2002.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statisticsguyana.gov.gy/census.html |title=Bureau of Statistics - Guyana |publisher=Statisticsguyana.gov.gy |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Peru===\nPeru collected data in the 1940 census. In the [[2017 Peru Census|2017 census]], questions about culture and ancestors were asked in more detail for the first time for the population of 12 years old and above.<ref name=\"census2017\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.inei.gob.pe/media/MenuRecursivo/publicaciones_digitales/Est/Lib1539/libro.pdf |title=Per\u00fa: Perfil Sociodemogr\u00e1fico |page = 214 |publisher= [[Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica e Inform\u00e1tica]]|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> Results were  [[Mestizo]] 60.2%,  [[Quechua people|Quechua]] 22.3%, [[White Peruvians|White]] 5.9%, [[Afro-Peruvians|Afro-descendant]] 3.6%, [[Aymara people|Aymara]] 2.4%, [[Indigenous peoples in Peru|Native or indigenous]] to the [[Amazon basin|Amazon]] 0.3%, [[Ash\u00e1ninka]] 0.2%, Part of another Indigenous 0.2%, [[Aguaruna people|Aguaruna/Awaj\u00fan]] 0.2%, [[Shipibo-Conibo people|Shipibo-Conibo/Konibo]] 0.1%, [[Japanese Peruvians|Japanese]] ([[Japanese diaspora|Nikkei]]) 0.1%, [[Chinese Peruvians|Chinese]] (Tusan) 0.1%, Other 1.1%.<ref name=\"census2017\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.inei.gob.pe/media/MenuRecursivo/publicaciones_digitales/Est/Lib1539/libro.pdf |title=Per\u00fa: Perfil Sociodemogr\u00e1fico |page = 214 |publisher= [[Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica e Inform\u00e1tica]]|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ancestry]]\n*[[Census]]\n*[[Demography]]\n*[[Historical racial and ethnic demographics of the United States]]\n*[[IBM and the Holocaust]]\n*[[Majority minority]]\n*[[Population and housing censuses by country]]\n*[[Race and ethnicity in Brazil]]\n*[[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census]]\n*[[Visible minorities]]\n*[[Languages in censuses]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.understandingrace.org/lived/global_census.html Census racial/ethnic/national origin questions from various countries] [Link Broken]\n\n===Historical data===\n*[http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/DYBcensus/V2_Table4.pdf Ethnicity and Race Data for every country in the world which had this census category between 1985 and 2003]\n*[http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/dybcensus/V2_table5.pdf Language Data for every country in the world which had this census category between 1985 and 2003]\n*[http://censusresults.nsi.bg/Census/Reports/1/2/R7.aspx Bulgaria Ethnicity Data for 1900-2011 for the whole country and for urban and rural areas]\n*[http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/11-516-x/pdf/5500092-eng.pdf Canada Ethnic Origin Data for 1871-1971 (on page 17)]\n*[http://pop-stat.mashke.org/ Eastern Europe, Kazakhstan, and Kyrgyzstan Ethnicity/Nationality Data for the late 20th century and early 21st century]\n*[http://www.spc.int/prism/country/fj/stats/Key%20Stats/Population/1.1%20census%20of%20population.pdf Fiji Ethnicity Data for 1881-2007]\n*[http://www.cso.ie/px/pxeirestat/Statire/SelectVarVal/Define.asp?maintable=CDD27&PLanguage=0 Ireland Ethnicity Data for 2011]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121113200941/http://www1.cbs.gov.il/reader/shnaton/templ_shnaton_e.html?num_tab=st02_07x&CYear=2012 Israel Ethnicity Data for 1948-2011 for Israeli Districts and Sub-Districts]\n*[http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/census_types.php?ct=6 Russia, Russian Empire, and USSR Ethnicity/Nationality Data for 1897-2010 by Guberniyas/Oblasts/SSRs]\n*[http://www.ethnicity.ac.uk/census/HowHasEthnicDiversityGrown_Figure1_2.xls United Kingdom Ethnicity Data for 1991-2011]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20141224151538/http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/twps0056.html United States Race and Ethnicity Data for 1790-1990 for U.S. Regions and States]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080912052919/http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0076/twps0076.html United States Race and Ethnicity Data for 1790-1990 for Large Cities and Other Urban Places]\n*[http://www.socialexplorer.com/pub/maps/map3.aspx?g=0&mapi=SE0012 United States Race and Ethnicity Data for 1790-2010 for U.S. States and Counties (the 2010 data is only for subscribers)]\n*[http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/index.html United States Race and Ethnicity Data for 2000 and 2010 for U.S. States and Counties]\n\n===Future population projections, including by race and/or ethnicity===\n*[http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/91-551-x/91-551-x2010001-eng.pdf Canada Population Projections for 2006-2031]\n*[http://www1.cbs.gov.il/www/publications/tec27.pdf Israel Population Projections for 2009-2059]\n*[http://www1.cbs.gov.il/reader/newhodaot/tables_template_eng.html?hodaa=201301170 Israel Population Projections for 2015-2035]\n*[http://www.stats.govt.nz/browse_for_stats/population/estimates_and_projections/NationalEthnicPopulationProjections_HOTP2006-26/Technical%20Notes.aspx New Zealand Population Projections for 2006-2026]\n*[https://www.census.gov/population/projections/data/national/2012.html United States Population Projections for 2015-2060]\n{{Ethnicity}}\n\n[[Category:Censuses]]\n[[Category:Race (human categorization)]]\n[[Category:Ethnicity]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Ethnicity and race in censuses.png|thumb|500px|Map showing countries where the ethnicity or race of people was enumerated in at least one census since 1991.]]\n\nMany [[countries]] and national [[census]]es currently enumerate or have previously enumerated their [[populations]] by [[Race (human classification)|race]], [[ethnicity]], [[nationality]], or a combination of these characteristics.<ref name = \"pbs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/race/000_About/002_03-godeeper.htm |title=RACE&nbsp;\u2014 The Power of an Illusion . Go Deeper |publisher=PBS |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ND1__tXqfDYC&pg=PT11&lpg=PT11&dq=%22ann+morning%22+soviet+union |title=Ethnicity&nbsp;\u2014 Steve Fenton&nbsp;\u2014 Google Books |date= 2013-05-02|accessdate=2013-06-20|isbn=9780745658438 |last1=Fenton |first1=Steve }}</ref> Different countries have different classifications and census options for race and ethnicity/nationality which are not comparable with data from other countries.<ref name = \"pbs\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/sconcerns/popchar/Morning.pdf |title=Approaches To Racial And Ethnic Classification |date= |accessdate=2013-03-16}}</ref> In addition, many of the race and ethnicity concepts that appear on national censuses worldwide have their origins in [[Europe]] or in the views of [[Europeans]], rather than in the views of the locals of these countries.<ref name=\"catdir\">{{cite web|title=Census and identity: The Politics of Race, Ethnicity and Language in National Censuses|url=http://catdir.loc.gov/catdir/samples/cam031/2001037352.pdf|publisher=Cambridge University|accessdate=2 December 2012|author1=David I. Kertzer |author2=Dominique Arel }}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n==Africa==\n\n===Angola===\n[[File:Angola Ethnic map 1970.svg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Angola in 1970]]\n\nThe [[Portugal|Portuguese]] asked about race in colonial censuses when they controlled Angola, and they provided three options: White, Mestizo, or African/Black. Africans had to then pick either \"Assimilado\" (assimilated) or \"Indigenato\" (indigenous).<ref name = \"angola\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/angola/ |title=Angola |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> Angola has not used any racial categories since its independence in 1975.<ref name = \"angola\"/> Tribe and language for Africans were recorded only in 1950 and 1960.<ref name = \"angola\"/>\n\n===Benin===\nThe people in [[Benin]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1979, 1992, and 2013 but not in 2002.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Botswana===\n[[Botswana]] enumerated people by race in all censuses between 1904 and 1946, and again in the 1964 census (though not in 1956), but in no censuses after 1964.<ref name = \"botswana\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/botswana/ |title=Botswana |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> People were enumerated by language use in 1946 and 1956 and again in 2001 and 2011.<ref name = \"botswana\"/>\n\n===Cape Verde===\n[[Cape Verde]] enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1950.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Central African Republic===\nThe [[Central African Republic]] enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1959/1960.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Chad===\n[[Chad]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1993 and 2009.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Democratic Republic of Congo===\nThe people in the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]] were enumerated by ethnicity from 1955\u20131958.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Republic of Congo===\nThe people in the [[Republic of Congo]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1960, 1974, and 1984.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Equatorial Guinea===\nThe population of [[Equatorial Guinea]] was enumerated by ethnicity in 1950.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Ethiopia===\n[[Ethiopia]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1994 and in 2007.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Gabon===\nThe population of [[Gabon]] was enumerated by ethnicity in 1960\u20131961 and 1993.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Ghana===\nThe population of [[Ghana]] was enumerated by ethnicity in 1960, 2000,<ref name=autogenerated6 /> and 2010.<ref>{{cite web|author=Major Trading Currencies |url=http://www.ghanabusinessnews.com/2012/06/05/group-not-satisfied-with-2010-ghana-census-report/ |title=Group not satisfied with 2010 Ghana census report |publisher=Ghana Business News |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Guinea===\nThe population of [[Guinea]] was enumerated by ethnicity in 1955.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Guinea-Bissau===\nThe population of [[Guinea-Bissau]] was enumerated by ethnicity in 1950 and in 2009.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Ivory Coast===\n[[File:IvoryCoastEthno.jpg|right|thumb|100px|Ethnic composition of the Ivory Coast (note: the map is in French).]]\nThe people of [[Ivory Coast]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1948, 1957\u20131958, and 1988.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> The ethnicity data from 1957\u20131958 was only for the [[rural]] areas of the country, though.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Kenya===\nSince 1945, [[Kenya]] enumerated people by ethnicity from 1948 all the way up to its most recent census in 2009 (however, the 1999 census ethnicity figures were not made public).<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minorityrights.org/download.php?id=147|title=Kenya: Minorities, Indigenous Peoples and Ethnic Diversity|author=Maurice Odhiambo Makoloo|type=Report|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080614023538/http://www.minorityrights.org/download.php?id=147|archivedate=June 14, 2008|publisher=Minority Rights Group International}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kenya.rcbowen.com/people/population.html |title=Kenya - Population Distribution |publisher=Kenya.rcbowen.com |date= |accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/08/25/kenya-holds-first-census_n_268076.html |title=Kenya Holds First Census In A Decade, Causes Outcry Over Ethnic Identity |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= 2009-08-25|accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.knbs.or.ke/censusethnic.php |title=Welcome to Kenya National Bureau of Statistics |publisher=Knbs.or.ke |accessdate=2012-12-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424174848/http://knbs.or.ke/censusethnic.php |archivedate=2013-04-24 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://marsgroupkenya.org/census/?data=ethaf |title=Kenya 2009 Census Data &#124; Population by Ethnic Affiliation |publisher=Mars Group Kenya |date= |accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref> There were some concerns about asking an ethnicity equation in the 2009 census since it came just a year after the disputed Kenyan presidential election of 2007 and the riots that followed it, but Kenya went through with asking about ethnicity in 2009 anyway.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nyambura |first=Helen |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2009/08/25/ozatp-kenya-census-idAFJOE57O0GP20090825 |title=Ethnic question in Kenya census stokes suspicions |work=Reuters |date= 2009-08-25|accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref>\n\n===Lesotho===\nPeople in [[Lesotho]] were enumerated by race between 1904 and 1976, but not after 1976.<ref name = \"lesotho\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/lesotho/ |title=Lesotho |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> Language was only recorded in 1946 and 1956, tribe and language for Africans were recorded only in 1950 and 1960.<ref name = \"lesotho\"/>\n\n===Malawi===\nPeople in [[Malawi]] were enumerated by race between 1911 and 1987, and again in 2018.<ref name = \"malawi\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/malawi/ |title=Malawi |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> They were enumerated by language only in 1966, 1998, and 2008.<ref name = \"malawi\"/> They were enumerated by tribal affiliation only in 1926, 1945, and 2008.<ref name = \"malawi\"/>\n\n===Mali===\n[[Mali]] enumerated people in some parts of the country by ethnicity in 1950.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Mauritius===\n[[Mauritius]] enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1952, 1962, and 1972.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Morocco===\n[[File:Volkeren in Marokko.jpg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnolinguistic composition of Morocco.]]\n[[Morocco]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1950 and 1971.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> The 2014 census enumerated people by nationality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hcp.ma/Note-sur-les-premiers-resultats-du-Recensement-General-de-la-Population-et-de-l-Habitat-2014_a1516.html |title=Note sur les premiers r\u00e9sultats du Recensement G\u00e9n\u00e9ral de la Population et de l'Habitat 2014  |accessdate=24 July 2015 |format=docx |work=[[Haut Commissariat au Plan]]}}{{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\n===Mozambique===\nPeople in [[Mozambique]] were counted by race only in 1894, 1970, 1997, 2007, and 2017.<ref name = \"mozambique\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/mozambique/ |title=Mozambique |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> The race categories in Mozambique were the same ones as in Angola, due to both being controlled by Portugal before acquiring their independence.<ref name = \"mozambique\"/> People were counted by language in all censuses since 1940.<ref name = \"mozambique\"/>\n\n===Namibia===\nPeople in [[Namibia]] were enumerated by race in all 20th century censuses but not in the 2001 census. They were enumerated by language in all censuses since 1951.<ref name = \"namibia\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/namibia/ |title=Namibia |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref>\n\n===Niger===\n[[Niger]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1959/1960 and 2001.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Nigeria===\n[[File:Afro asiatic peoples nigeria.png|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Nigeria.]]\n[[Nigeria]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1963.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> In addition, Nigeria has announced plans to enumerate its population by ethnicity in its 2016 census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbulletin.net/?aType=haber&ArticleID=115785 |title=Nigeria to include religion, ethnicity in 2016 census &#124; Africa |publisher=World Bulletin |date=2013-08-22 |accessdate=2013-09-01}}</ref>\n\n===Rwanda===\n[[Rwanda]] enumerated people by ethnicity from 1933/34 until 1991.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite book|first=David E.|last=Kiwuwa|title=Ethnic Politics and Democratic Transition in Rwanda|publisher=Routledge|location=Abingdon|page=71|year=2012|isbn=978-0415616089|url=https://books.google.com/?id=uGclH0p46ogC&lpg=PA71&dq=rwanda%20ethnicity%20census&pg=PA71#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> Due to the [[1994 Rwandan Genocide]] and the ethnic hatred and tensions that caused it, the Rwandan census of 2002 did not enumerate people by ethnicity.<ref>{{cite web|author=Agence France-Presse |url=http://reliefweb.int/report/rwanda/ethnic-origins-ignored-rwandas-first-census-genocide |title=Ethnic origins ignored in Rwanda's first census since genocide &#124; ReliefWeb |publisher=Reliefweb.int |date=2002-08-16 |accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref>\n\n===Sao Tome and Principe===\nThe [[Sao Tome and Principe]] enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1950 and 1960.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Senegal===\nThe people of [[Senegal]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1960\u20131961, 1988, and 2002.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Seychelles===\nThe people of the [[Seychelles]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1947, 1987, and 1994.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Somalia===\nIn the pre-independence period in [[Somalia]], the colonial administrations in [[British Somaliland]] and [[Italian Somaliland]] officially classified the [[Somali people|ethnic Somali]] majority within the two territories as \"[[Hamitic]]\".<ref name=\"Gbco\">{{cite book|title=An Economic Survey of the Colonial Territories, Volumes 1-4|date=1952|publisher=Great Britain, Colonial Office|page=122|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=Gr8vAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Esoa\">{{cite book|title=Ethnographic Survey of Africa, Volume 5, Issue 1|date=1969|publisher=International African Institute|pages=45 & 50|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=szhNAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> The Italian Somaliland census of 1935 reported that the remaining 6.2% of the area's population consisted of \"[[Negroid]] groups\", including the [[Somali Bantu|Bantu]] ethnic minorities inhabiting the southern riverine region.<ref name=\"Kmbeiis\">{{cite journal|last1=Menkhaus|first1=Ken|title=Bantu ethnic identities in Somalia|journal=Annales d'\u00c9thiopie|date=2003|volume=XIX|page=323|url=http://www.persee.fr/articleAsPDF/ethio_0066-2127_2003_num_19_1_1051/article_ethio_0066-2127_2003_num_19_1_1051.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024155331/http://www.persee.fr/articleAsPDF/ethio_0066-2127_2003_num_19_1_1051/article_ethio_0066-2127_2003_num_19_1_1051.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-10-24|accessdate=22 November 2014|doi=10.3406/ethio.2003.1051}}</ref> These census designations were at the time pre-assigned rather than based on self-reporting. Following independence in 1960, no official census was taken until 1975. This first post-independence national census only collected information on district of birth.<ref name=\"Tmonps\">{{cite book|last1=Ministry of National Planning|title=The 1982 labour force survey: analytical report|date=1985|publisher=Ministry of National Planning of Somalia, Central Statistical Department|page=126|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=C5IoAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> However, the general government literature maintained that the country's ethnic Somali majority was of Hamitic stock, or alternately of [[Arabs|Arab]] heritage.<ref name=\"Tmoiang\">{{cite book|last1=Ministry of Information and National Guidance|title=Somalia and the Arab League|date=1974|publisher=Ministry of Information and National Guidance|page=7|url=https://www.google.com/books?lr=&id=4FkMAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> Similarly, Article 3 of the [[Constitution of Somalia|Provision Constitution]] adopted in 2012 indicates that Somalia is an Arab nation.<ref name=\"Fgspc\">{{cite web|title=Provisional Constitution|url=http://unpos.unmissions.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=RkJTOSpoMME=|publisher=Federal Government of Somalia|accessdate=22 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402122013/http://unpos.unmissions.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=RkJTOSpoMME%3D|archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref> In 2014, the Ministry of Planning and International Cooperation also announced that it would release a new national population census before 2016.<ref name=\"Sgtlpcaote\">{{cite news|title=SOMALIA: Gov't to launch population census ahead of 2016 elections|url=http://koonfurta.com/somalia-govt-to-launch-population-census-ahead-of-2016-elections/|accessdate=22 November 2014|agency=Koonfurta|date=10 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030155132/http://koonfurta.com/somalia-govt-to-launch-population-census-ahead-of-2016-elections/|archive-date=30 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===South Africa===\n{{See also|Population Registration Act, 1950}}\n[[File:South Africa 2011 White population proportion map.svg|right|100px|thumb|Whites as a percentage of the total South African population in 2011.]]\n[[South Africa]] has enumerated people by race in all of its censuses since 1904.<ref name=\"southafrica\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/south-africa/ |title=South Africa |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date=1986-07-23 |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> Five population group options are provided in response to the question \"How would ''(name)'' describe him/herself in terms of population group?\": \"Black African\", \"Coloured\", \"Indian or Asian\", \"White\" and \"Other\".<ref>[http://www.statssa.gov.za/census2011/documents/CensusQuestionnaires/Census%202011_q_A.pdf Census 2011 Household Questionnaire A]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> South Africa has also asked about language use since 1921 for [[white South African]]s and since 1936 for all races.<ref name = \"southafrica\"/>\n\n===Sudan===\n[[Sudan]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1956.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Swaziland===\nThe [[Swaziland|Swazi]] census counted people by race in all censuses between 1904 and 1976.<ref name = \"swazi\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/swaziland/ |title=Swaziland |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> People were counted by ethnic group and tribe only in 1966 and 1976.<ref name = \"swazi\"/>\n\n===Tanzania===\nThe [[Tanzania]]n census enumerated people by race from colonial times until 1967, by ethnicity and tribe from colonial times until 1973. It enumerated people by language only in 1952 and 1958.<ref name = \"tanzania\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/tanzania |title=Tanzania |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref>\n\n===Togo===\nThe people in [[Togo]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1948, 1958\u20131960, and 1970.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Tunisia===\n[[Tunisia]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1956.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Uganda===\nThe people of [[Uganda]] were enumerated by ethnicity from 1948 all the way up to Uganda's most recent census in 2012,<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ubos.org/UgCensus2012/docs/2012_CENSUS_BULLETIN_Vol1.pdf|title=The 2012 Uganda Population and Housing Census|magazine=The 2012 Uganda Population & Housing Census Bulletin|volume=1|date=March 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113175759/http://www.ubos.org/UgCensus2012/docs/2012_CENSUS_BULLETIN_Vol1.pdf|archivedate=November 13, 2014}}</ref> with the exception of 1980 and possibly 1969.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mongabay.com/reference/country_studies/uganda/SOCIETY.html |title=Uganda - SOCIETY |publisher=Mongabay.com |date= |accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref>\n\n===Zambia===\nPeople in [[Zambia]] were not continuously counted by race before independence, and when they were counted by race it were primarily the non-Africans/non-blacks who were counted.<ref name = \"zambia\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/zambia/ |title=Zambia |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> People were counted by language only in 1931, while they were counted for ethnicity at various points since 1969.<ref name = \"zambia\"/> The 1969 census asked about language but not ethnic group, and the 1974 census asked about ethnic group, but not language. The 1980 census asked about ethnic group, mother tongue, and language of most frequent use, while the 1990 census asked about ethnic group and mother tongue. The 2000 census asked about ethnic group, language of most frequent use, and second language.<ref name = \"zambia\"/>\n\n===Zimbabwe===\nPeople in [[Zimbabwe]] were enumerated by race between 1901 and 2012, but many censuses were done separately for Whites/Europeans and Blacks/Africans before the 1970s.<ref name = \"zimbabwe\">{{cite web|url=http://institutionalizedethnicity.net/country-narratives/zimbabwe/ |title=Zimbabwe |publisher=Institutionalized Ethnicity |date= |accessdate=2012-09-22}}</ref> People were enumerated by language only in 1982 (when they were enumerated by \"[their] father's dialect\").<ref name = \"zimbabwe\"/>\n\n==Asia==\n\n===Abkhazia===\nPeople in [[Abkhazia]] (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by [[native tongue]] [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12>{{cite web|url=http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/rus_lan_97_uezd_eng.php |title=Demoscope Weekly - Annex. Statistical indicators reference |publisher=Demoscope.ru |date=2012-09-16 |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated11>{{cite web|url=http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/rus_rel_97.php?reg=0 |title=\u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f Weekly - \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435. \u0421\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439 |publisher=Demoscope.ru |date= |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite web|url=http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/census_types.php?ct=6 |title=\u041f\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0430 Weekly |publisher=Demoscope.ru |date=2013-01-15 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> the [[International recognition of Abkhazia|partially recognized state]] of [[Abkhazia]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses of 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/abkhazia-ethnic2003.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Abkhazia 2003 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/abkhazia-ethnic2011.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Abkhazia 2011 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Afghanistan===\nPrior to 2010, [[Afghanistan]] had not held a census since 1979 due to the wars and conflicts that have occurred there over those three decades (since the [[Soviet invasion of Afghanistan]] in 1979).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cso.gov.af/Content/files/Population.pdf|title=Afghanistan Statistical Yearbook 2009-10}}</ref>\n\n===Armenia===\nPeople in Armenia (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Armenia]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses of 2001<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/armenia-ethnic2001.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Armenia 2001 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armstat.am/file/doc/99465273.pdf|title=CENSUS PROGRAMME (CONTENT OF QUESTIONNAIRE) 2011 CENSUS OF THE REPUBLIC OF ARMENIA }}</ref>\n\n===Azerbaijan===\n[[File:Azerbaijan ethnic 2003.png|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Azerbaijan in 2003.]]\nPeople in Azerbaijan (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Azerbaijan]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses of 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/azerbaijan-ethnic1999.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Azerbaijan 1999 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/azerbaijan-ethnic2009.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Azerbaijan 2009 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date=1971-04-07 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Bahrain===\n[[Bahrain]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1965<ref name=autogenerated6 /> and 2010.<ref name=autogenerated10>{{cite web |url=http://www.census2010.gov.bh/results_en.php |title=Bahraini Census 2010 - \u062a\u0639\u062f\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0643\u0640\u0640\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0645 \u0644\u0644\u0628\u062d\u0631\u064a\u0640\u0640\u0646 2010 |publisher=Census2010.gov.bh |accessdate=2013-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320104234/http://www.census2010.gov.bh/results_en.php |archive-date=2012-03-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The 2010 Bahrain census also enumerated people by their religious beliefs.<ref name=autogenerated10 />\n\n===Bangladesh===\n[[British India]] (which Bangladesh was a part of) enumerated its population by race between 1872 and 1941.<ref name=\"censusindia1\">{{cite web|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/Data_Products/Library/Indian_perceptive_link/Census_Terms_link/censusterms.html |title=Census of India - Census Terms |publisher=Censusindia.gov.in |date= |accessdate=2013-06-10}}</ref>\n\n===Brunei===\nSince 1945, [[Brunei]] enumerated people by ethnicity in all censuses since 1947.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/dyb2.htm#2001 |title=United Nations Statistics Division - Demographic and Social Statistics |publisher=Unstats.un.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Burma===\nThe people in [[Burma]] (also known as Myanmar) were enumerated by ethnicity in 1931,<ref name=autogenerated27>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvb.no/analysis/burma%E2%80%99s-troublesome-census/21931 |title=Burma's troublesome census &#124; Democratic Voice of Burma |publisher=Dvb.no |date=2009-08-17 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 1953.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> A new census which plans to enumerate the people of Burma by ethnicity and race is planned to be held in 2014.<ref name=autogenerated27 /><ref name=autogenerated26>{{cite news|author=Sonu Trivedi |url=http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/myanmars-census-a-crucial-democracy-test/article4137474.ece |title=Opinion / Op-Ed : Myanmar's census a crucial democracy test |newspaper=The Hindu |date=2012-11-27 |accessdate=2013-03-21 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> The 1931 Burmese census generated a lot of anger from non-Burmese ethnic groups who were marked as Burmese on the census.<ref name=autogenerated27 /> There is hope that the scheduled [[2014 Burma Census]] will help empower the various ethnic groups in Burma.<ref name=autogenerated26 />\n\n===China===\n[[File:Ethnolinguistic map of China 1983.jpg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnolinguistic groups in China in 1983]]\n\n[[The People's Republic of China]] [[Demographics of China|counted people by ethnicity]] since at least [[First National Population Census of the People's Republic of China|1952]] but does not count people by mother tongue.<ref>{{cite news|author=Mark Mackinnon |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/asia-pacific/chinas-disappearing-languages-deemed-not-that-important/article1792549/ |title=China's disappearing languages deemed 'not that important' |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date= 2012-08-23|accessdate=2012-09-21 |location=Toronto}}</ref>\n\n===Cyprus===\nThe people of [[Cyprus]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1960.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===East Timor===\n[[East Timor]] enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1950.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Georgia===\nPeople in Georgia (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in both post-Soviet censuses in 2002 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/georgia-ethnic2002.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Georgia 2002 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===India===\nWhen it was a [[British India|British colony]], India enumerated its population by race between 1872 and 1941.<ref name=\"censusindia1\"/>\n\n===Indonesia===\n[[File:Indonesia Ethnic Groups Map English.svg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Indonesia]]\n[[Indonesia]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1930, 2000, and 2010 but not in any other censuses.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=UFNKQcvGNSAC&pg=PA20&dq=census+ethnic#v=onepage&q=census%20ethnic&f=false |title=Ethnic Chinese in Contemporary Indonesia - Leo Heng Chew Suryadinata - Google Books |accessdate=2013-03-21|isbn=9789812308351 |last1=Suryadinata |first1=Leo |year=2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\n[[File:Arab population israel 2000 en.png|thumb|100px|Map of Arab population, 2000]]\n\nThe census in [[Israel]] directly asked people about their ethnicity only in 1983.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> However, Israel has used the religion question on its census to determine the ethnic composition of its population from 1948 to the present day.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |url=http://www1.cbs.gov.il/reader/shnatonenew_site.htm |title=Statistical Abstract of Israel 2011 |publisher=cbs.gov.il |date=2011-09-26 |accessdate=2012-09-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120914092802/http://www1.cbs.gov.il/reader/shnatonenew_site.htm |archivedate=2012-09-14 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs.gov.il/shnaton63/st_eng02.pdf|title= Statistical Abstract of Israel 2012 National Population Estimates |publisher=CBS }}</ref> Israel has enumerated [[Israeli Jews|its Jewish population]] by their '''continent''' of birth since 1948.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.cbs.gov.il/reader/shnaton/templ_shnaton_e.html?num_tab=st02_25&CYear=2012 |title=Statistical Abstract of Israel 2012 - No. 63 Subject 2 - Table No. 25 |publisher=.cbs.gov.il |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Kazakhstan===\n[[File:Kazakhstan European Rus.png|thumb|right|100px|[[Europeans|European ethnicities]] as a percentage of the total population in Kazakhstan in 2016 (note: map is in Russian).]]\n\nPeople in Kazakhstan (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Kazakhstan]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses of 1999<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ide.go.jp/English/Publish/Download/Mes/pdf/51_02.pdf|title=Ethnodemographic situation in Kazakhstan|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120133116/http://www.ide.go.jp/English/Publish/Download/Mes/pdf/51_02.pdf|archivedate=2013-01-20}}</ref> and 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/kazakhstan-ethnic2009reg-census.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Kazakhstan 2009 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |accessdate=2013-03-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130622201346/http://pop-stat.mashke.org/kazakhstan-ethnic2009reg-census.htm |archivedate=2013-06-22 }}</ref>\n\n===Kyrgyzstan===\nPeople in Kyrgyzstan (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Kyrgyzstan]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses of 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stat.kg/stat.files/din.files/census/5010003.pdf|title=5.01.00.03 \u041d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206105009/http://www.stat.kg/stat.files/din.files/census/5010003.pdf|archivedate=February 6, 2009}}</ref> and 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/kyrgyzstan-ethnic2009v1.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Kyrgyzstan 2009 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/kyrgyzstan-ethnic2009v2.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Kyrgyzstan 2009 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Malaysia===\nPeople in [[Malaysia]] were enumerated by ethnicity/race from 1871 to the present day.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://faculty.washington.edu/charles/pubs/1987-MeaningandMeasurementofEthnicityinMalaysia.pdf|title=The Meaning and Measurement of Ethnicity in Malaysia: An Analysis of Census Classifications|author=Charles Hirschman|journal=The Journal of Asian Studies|volume=46|issue=3|pages = 555\u2013582|date=August 1987|publisher=Association for Asian Studies|doi= 10.2307/2056899|jstor=2056899|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021071854/http://faculty.washington.edu/charles/pubs/1987-MeaningandMeasurementofEthnicityinMalaysia.pdf|archivedate=October 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Mongolia===\n[[Mongolia]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1963 and 2000.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Nagorno-Karabakh===\n[[File:Nagorno Karabakh Ethnic Map 1989.png|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Nagorno Karabakh in 1989]]\n\nPeople in Nagorno-Karabakh (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> the de facto independent state of [[Nagorno-Karabakh]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its only post-Soviet census of 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/nkr-ethnic2005.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Nagorno-Karabakh Republic (self-proclaimed) 2005 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Nepal===\n[[File:Nepal ethnic groups.png|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Nepal. (note that <span style=\"color:#ff6600;\">Kulu Rodu (Kulung) territories</span> are mistakenly marked as <span style=\"color:green;\">Tamu/Gurung territories</span> in this map)]]\n[[Nepal]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1991 and 2001.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Pakistan===\n[[British India]] (which Pakistan was a part of) enumerated its population by race between 1872 and 1941.<ref name=\"censusindia1\"/>\n\n===Palestine===\nThe population in the [[Palestinian territories]] was enumerated by ethnicity in 1997.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Philippines===\n[[File:Peoples of the Philippines en.svg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of the Philippines in 2000.]]\n\nThe [[Philippines]] enumerated their population by ethnicity in 1948, 1970<ref name=autogenerated6 />, 2000, and 2010.\n\n===Russia/Soviet Union===\n[[File:Ethnic map of Russia 2010.png|100px|thumb|Dominant ethnicity in each [[Russian oblast]] in 2010]]\n\nThe [[Russian Empire]] began counting people by native tongue with [[1897 census|its first modern census in 1897]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /> In 1920, the [[Soviet Union]] replaced this question with a question about ethnicity.<ref>[https://www.un.org/esa/socdev/unpfii/.../workshop_data_stepanov.doc] {{dead link|date=December 2016}}</ref> The Soviet government organized lists of ethnicities and wanted to shape these various ethnic groups in the mold of [[Communism]].<ref name=autogenerated13>\"{{lang|ru|\u041d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441 \u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043a\u0443\u043b\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0430 \u0432 \u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e-\u041a\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0435 (\u0418\u0442\u043e\u0433\u0438 \u0438 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u044b): \u041a \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u0449\u0435\u043c\u0443 \u0441\u044a\u0435\u0437\u0434\u0443 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432}}\" (''Natsionalny vopros i natsionalnaya kultura v Severo-Kavkazskom kraye (Itogi i perspektivy): K predstoyashchemu syezdu gorskikh narodov''), [[Rostov-on-Don]], 1926.</ref> In the words of Soviet politician [[Anastas Mikoyan]], the Soviet Union was \"creating and organising new nations\"<ref name=autogenerated13 /> The government of the U.S.S.R. was eager to get ethnic data for many ethnic groups in order to create republics and autonomous regions for many of these ethnic groups and nationalities, and later on (under [[Joseph Stalin]]) in order to deport some of them.<ref name=slezkine>\n{{cite journal|author=Slezkine, Yuri|year=1994|jstor=2501300|title=The USSR as a Communal Apartment, or How a Socialist State Promoted Ethnic Particularism|journal=[[Slavic Review]]|volume=53|issue=2|pages=414\u2013452|doi=10.2307/2501300}}</ref><ref name=\"martin1998\">{{cite journal|author=Martin, Terry|year=1998|title=The Origins of Soviet Ethnic Cleansing|journal=[[The Journal of Modern History]]|volume=70|issue=4|pages=813\u2013861|doi=10.1086/235168|jstor=10.1086/235168|url=https://dash.harvard.edu/bitstream/handle/1/3229636/Martin%201998.pdf?sequence=2}}</ref> The [[Bolsheviks]] also wanted to get more support from ethnic minority groups within the Soviet Union, many of whom were previously oppressed under [[Russian Tsars|Tsarist]] rule.<ref name=\"martin1998\"/> The Soviet Union continued to ask about ethnicity for the rest of its existence, and [[Russia]] also asked about ethnicity in its two post-Soviet censuses of 2002 and 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/census_types.php?ct=6 |title=\u041f\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0430 Weekly |publisher=Demoscope.ru |date=2011-12-26 |accessdate=2012-09-08}}</ref> Unlike in 1989, the 2002 census did not require respondents to prove their ethnicity/nationality when they responded to this question.<ref>{{cite web|author=F. Joseph Dresen |url=http://www.wilsoncenter.org/publication/russia-counts-the-2002-russian-census |title=Russia Counts: The 2002 Russian Census |publisher=Wilson Center |date=2002-11-18 |accessdate=2013-12-09}}</ref> The number of ethnicity/nationality options available on Soviet censuses was enormous\u2014the Soviet Union offered 194 different choices for ethnicity/nationality in its 1926 census.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=http://www.demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/rus_nation.php |title=\u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f Weekly - \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435. \u0421\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439 |publisher=Demoscope.ru |date=2007-05-27 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> There were 97 options in 1939, 126 options in 1959, 122 options in 1970, 123 options in 1979, and 128 options for the Soviet Union in 1989.<ref name=autogenerated4/> There were 192 ethnicity/nationality options for Russia in 2002.<ref name=autogenerated4/>\n\n===Singapore===\nThe people in [[Singapore]] were numerated by ethnicity from at least 1947 up to the most recent Singaporean census in 2010.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.singstat.gov.sg/pubn/popn/c2010acr.pdf |accessdate=July 2, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327064912/http://www.singstat.gov.sg/pubn/popn/c2010acr.pdf |archivedate=March 27, 2012 |title=Census of Population 2010 Advance Census Release |isbn= 978-981-08-6819-2|publisher=Department of Statistics, Ministry of Trade & Industry, Republic of Singapore }}</ref>\n\n===Sri Lanka===\n{{Disputed|date=November 2019}}\n{{Update|section|date=November 2019}}\n[[Sri Lanka]] enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1971, 1981, and 2012.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Tajikistan===\n[[File:Tajikistan ethnic 92.jpg|right|thumb|100px|Ethnic composition of Tajikistan in 1992]]\nPeople in Tajikistan (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Tajikistan]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses in 2000 and 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.edu/programs/ccs/Docs/Central_Asia/Tajikistan_July09.pdf |title=Table_of_Contents_Central_Asia Series |date= |accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref>\n\n===Thailand===\n[[File:Thailand ethnic map.svg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Thailand in 1974]]\n\n[[Thailand]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1947.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Turkey===\nBetween 1881 and 1893 the [[Ottoman Empire]] implemented its first census, which enumerated the people in the empire by ethnicity.<ref name=autogenerated20>{{harv|Karpat|1978|pp.237-274}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated19>{{harv|Shaw|1978|p.323-338}}</ref> Some other censuses and studies were conducted in the Ottoman Empire for enumerating the population by ethnicity after the first Ottoman census.<ref name=autogenerated20 /><ref name=autogenerated19 />\n\n===Turkmenistan===\nPeople in Turkmenistan (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Turkmenistan]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its only post-Soviet census in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/documents/organization/171762.pdf|title=TURKMENISTAN|publisher=state.gov}}</ref>\n\n===Uzbekistan===\nPeople in [[Uzbekistan]] (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> The Soviet Union (to which Uzbekistan also belonged) enumerated people by ethnicity for its entire existence.<ref name=autogenerated5 /> Uzbekistan has not conducted any censuses at all since 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.edu/programs/ccs/Docs/Central_Asia/Uzbekistan_Overview_June09.pdf|title=Central Asia Executive Summary Series: Uzbekistan Country Profile |publisher=Naval Postgraduate School|date= June 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605012218/http://www.nps.edu/Programs/CCS/Docs/Central_Asia/Uzbekistan_Overview_June09.pdf|archivedate=June 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Vietnam===\n[[Communist]] [[North Vietnam]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1960, when Vietnam was still divided into two countries.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/sconcerns/popchar/Ethnicitypaper.pdf |title=Microsoft Word - Ethnicitypaper.doc |date= |accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref> After [[Vietnamese reunification]], Vietnam enumerated its population by ethnicity from 1979 up to the most recent census in 2019.<ref name=autogenerated3 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gso.gov.vn/default.aspx?tabid=503&ItemID=1841 |title=Tong Cuc Thong Ke |publisher=Gso.gov.vn |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>[unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/.../Session8.0_VietNam.ppt]</ref>\n\n===Yemen===\n[[File:Yemen ethno 2002.jpg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnoreligious composition of Yemen in 2002.]]\n\nYemen enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1994.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> The [[British Empire|British]] [[Colony of Aden]] (which is within Yemen's current borders) enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1946 and 1955.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n==Europe==\n\n===Albania===\n[[Albania]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1955,<ref name=autogenerated6>{{cite web|title=Ethnicity: A Review of Data Collection and Dissemination|url=http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/sconcerns/popchar/Ethnicitypaper.pdf|publisher=United Nations Statistics Division|accessdate=30 November 2012|date=August 2003}}</ref> 1989,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/albania-ethnic1989.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Albania 1989 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 2011.<ref name=autogenerated16>{{cite web|author=Gezim Krasniqi |url=http://www.citsee.eu/blog/politics-numbers-and-identity-albania |title=Natitonality and census in Albania |publisher=Citsee.Eu |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated15>{{cite web|url=http://census.al/Resources/Data/Census2011/PES%20Questionnaire%20ENG.pdf|title=Albania Post Enumeration Survey|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711042241/http://census.al/Resources/Data/Census2011/PES%20Questionnaire%20ENG.pdf|archivedate=July 11, 2012|date=2011}}</ref>  The 2011 Albanian census also enumerated people by language used and by their religious beliefs.<ref name=autogenerated16 /><ref name=autogenerated15 />\n\n===Belarus===\n[[File:Belarusians in Belarus 2009.png|thumb|right|100px|[[Belarusians]] as a percentage of the total population in Belarus in 2009 (note: map is in Ukrainian).]]\n\nPeople in Belarus (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Belarus]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses of 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/belarus-ethnic1999.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Belarus 1999 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/belarus-ethnic2009.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Belarus 2009 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Bosnia and Herzegovina===\n[[File:Ethnic Composition of BiH in 1991.gif|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Bosnia and Herzegovina in 1991.]]\n\nThe population of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] has been enumerated by ethnicity since at least 1885, including the recent censuses in 1991 and 2013.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=V9DtlRfO6JMC&pg=PA16&lpg=PA16&dq=yugoslavia+census+1948+1961+serbs#v=onepage&q=yugoslavia%20census%201948%201961%20serbs&f=false |title=Territorial Proposals for the Settlement of the War in Bosnia-Hercegovina ... - Mladen Klemen\u010di\u0107 - Google Books |accessdate=2013-03-21|isbn=9781897643150 |last1=Klemen\u010di\u0107 |first1=Mladen |year=1994 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/bosnia-ethnic1991.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Bosnia & Herzegovina 1991 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Bulgaria===\n[[File:Ethnic composition of Bulgaria, 2011.PNG|thumb|100px|Dominant ethnicities in Bulgaria in 2011]]\n\n[[Bulgaria]] enumerated people by mother tongue in 1880 and 1887 and used this info to determine their ethnicities.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DdEPbQzOjFQC&pg=PA425&lpg=PA425&dq=bulgaria+census+ethnicity+1880+1887+mother+tongue#v=onepage&q=bulgaria%20census%20ethnicity%201880%201887%20mother%20tongue&f=false |title=Bulgaria |author=R.J. Crampton|via=Google Books |publisher=OUP Oxford |date= 2007|accessdate=2012-12-02|isbn=9780191513312}}</ref> Bulgaria directly enumerated people by ethnicity from 1900 all the way up to its most recent census in 2011, with the exception of the 1985 census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsi.bg/census2011/PDOCS2/Census2011final_en.pdf|title=2011 POPULATION CENSUS \u2013 Main Results}}</ref>\n\n===Croatia===\n[[File:Croatia-Ethnic-2011.png|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Croatia in 2011]]\n\nThe people of Croatia have been enumerated by ethnicity/nationality from at least 1953, including the censuses of 2001 and 2011.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/croatia-ethnic2001.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Croatia 2001 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dzs.hr/Eng/censuses/census2011/forms/langs/Englezi%20OP.pdf |title=Og |date= |accessdate=2013-03-16}}</ref>\n\n===Czech Republic===\n[[Czechoslovakia]] (of which the territory of the Czech Republic was a part) enumerated people by ethnicity in 1921 and 1930, and the Czech Republic did the same thing from 1991 to the present day.<ref name=autogenerated23>{{cite web|url=http://praguemonitor.com/2010/11/30/second-czechoslovak-census-held-80-years-ago |title=Second Czechoslovak census held 80 years ago |publisher=Prague Monitor |date=2010-11-30 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Estonia===\nPeople in [[Estonia]] were enumerated by ethnicity/nationality from 1922 to the present day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.ohchr.org/english/bodies/hrc/docs/ngos/LIC_Estonia99.pdf|title=Minority Rights in Estonia|type=Report|publisher= Legal Information Centre for Human Rights}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/estonia-ethnic2000.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Estonia 2000 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stat.ee/34278 |title=Population by ethnic nationality, 1 January, years - Statistics Estonia |publisher=Stat.ee |date=2012-03-30 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> People in Estonia were also enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> During this time period Estonia was under the control of the [[Russian Empire]], then independent, then (excluding [[World War II]]) under the control of the [[Soviet Union]], and then independent again since 1991.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://estonia.eu/about-estonia/country/population-by-nationality.html |title=Population by Nationality |publisher=Estonia.eu |accessdate=2013-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304225022/http://estonia.eu/about-estonia/country/population-by-nationality.html |archive-date=2012-03-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> There were 192 different ethnicity/nationality options in the 2011 Estonian census.<ref>{{cite web|author=<nowiki>Juhan Tere, BC, Tallinn</nowiki> |url=http://www.baltic-course.com/eng/analytics/?doc=62935 |title=Census 2011: people of 192 ethnic nationalities live in Estonia :: The Baltic Course &#124; Baltic States news & analytics |publisher=The Baltic Course |date=2012-09-17 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Finland===\nFinland has enumerated its population by language of most frequent use from at least 1990 to the present day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pxweb2.stat.fi/Dialog/varval.asp?ma=030_vaerak_tau_102_en&ti=Language+according+to+age+and+gender+by+region+1990+-+2010&path=../Database/StatFin/vrm/vaerak/&lang=1&multilang=en |title=Table: Language according to age and sex by region 1990 - 2011 |publisher=Pxweb2.stat.fi |accessdate=2013-03-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130106153419/http://pxweb2.stat.fi/Dialog/varval.asp?ma=030_vaerak_tau_102_en&ti=Language+according+to+age+and+gender+by+region+1990+-+2010&path=../Database/StatFin/vrm/vaerak/&lang=1&multilang=en |archivedate=2013-01-06 }}</ref>\n\n===France===\n[[France]] has not counted individuals by race or ethnicity since at least 1978, when a law was passed that prevented individuals from being enumerated by these categories without their consent or a state committee waiver.<ref name = \"francerace\">{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:vLz6pnq_4oAJ:www.brookings.edu/fp/cusf/analysis/laurence.pdf+france+census+race+ethnicity+1872+law&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESiJ1dyvouY6Ibx8dja6tnv8e0sqVHvda_pLjbRRf94-Opttxtn4eBTEDpPHnM5A8uyb_RcxB4IVVPWJTc2M_cKtnshQHFZFpIqG53wsjVbhXtoCwZiQaEGMKL3olzpyzvf33sLa&sig=AHIEtbTLE-kOeESgjIHxqg6u_5kmCZk6yQ |title=Powered by Google Docs |date= |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated24>{{cite web|last=Bleich |first=Erik |url=http://www.brookings.edu/research/articles/2001/05/france-bleich |title=Race Policy in France &#124; Brookings Institution |publisher=Brookings.edu |date=2001-05-01 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> The reasons for this are that many French people consider asking people about race and ethnicity to be a contradiction of their principle of [[Social equality|equality]] and equal treatment for all French people.<ref name=autogenerated5 /> Also, there is a desire to avoid repeating what [[Vichy France]] [[The Holocaust in occupied France|did in regards to its Jewish population]] and to prevent the [[National Front (France)|National Front]] from getting more popularity.<ref name=autogenerated5 /><ref name = \"francerace\"/> Former [[French President]] [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] and his administration supported and proposed counting French people by race and ethnicity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.civilrights.org/archives/2009/04/255-french-census.html |title=Next Census in France May Track Race, Ethnicity and Religion - The Leadership Conference on Civil and Human Rights |publisher=Civilrights.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> Due to criticism, however, this proposal was never implemented, and as of 2013 former French President [[Francois Hollande]] opposes enumerating people by race and ethnicity.<ref>{{cite web|last=Admin |first=The |url=http://blackpoliticsontheweb.com/2012/04/16/despite-ethnic-tensions-counting-voters-by-race-remains-taboo-in-french-presidential-campaign/ |title=Despite ethnic tensions, counting voters by race remains taboo in French presidential campaign |publisher=Black Politics on the Web |date=2012-04-16 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Germany===\nGermany enumerated its citizens of Jewish descent in 1939 based on the [[Mischlinge|percent of Jewish ancestry that they had]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wernercohn.com/Paulus.html#5 |title=Bearers of a Common Fate ? The half Jews in Nazi Germany |publisher=Wernercohn.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Hungary===\n[[File:Greater austria ethnic.svg|100px|right|thumb|Ethnic composition of the regions of [[Austria-Hungary]] in 1910]]\n\n[[Hungary]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1880, between 1900 and 1941,<ref>A n\u00e9pess\u00e9g v\u00e1ltoz\u00f3 etnikai arculata Magyarorsz\u00e1g mai ter\u00fclet\u00e9n (map+data+essay) (Kocsis K\u00e1roly, Bottlik Zsolt, [[Hungarian Academy of Sciences]] - F\u00f6ldrajztudom\u00e1nyi Kutat\u00f3int\u00e9zet, [[Budapest]], 2009, {{ISBN|978-963-9545-19-9}})</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-zZ_NVM9mNEC&pg=PA116&lpg=PA116&dq=hungary+census+1941#v=onepage&q=hungary%20census%201941&f=false |title=Ethnic Geography of the Hungarian Minority on the Carpathian Basin - Kocsis, K\u00e1roly, Eszter Kocsisn\u00e9 Hodosi - Google Books |date=1938-11-02 |accessdate=2013-03-21|isbn=9781931313759 |last1=Kocsis |first1=Karoly |last2=Kocsis-Hodosi |first2=Eszter }}</ref> and again from 1980 to the present day<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Ireland===\nThe 2002 Irish census enumerated people by their place of birth and their country of citizenship.<ref name=\"autogenerated9\">[http://www.irishtimes.com/timeseye/whoweare/p3top.htm ireland.com / In Time's Eye / Who we are] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304074405/http://www.irishtimes.com/timeseye/whoweare/p3top.htm |date=March 4, 2011 }}</ref> Ireland introduced an ethnicity question to its census in 2006. The 2011 Irish census enumerated people by ethnicity as well, and offered the options White Irish, White Irish Traveller, Other White, Black or Black Irish (with options for African and Other Black), Asian or Asian Irish (with options for Chinese and Other Asian), Other, and Not Stated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cso.ie/px/pxeirestat/Statire/SelectVarVal/Define.asp?maintable=CD701&PLanguage=0 |title=Population Usually Resident and Present in the State by Age Group, Sex, Ethnic or Cultural Background and CensusYear - StatBank - data and statistics |publisher=Cso.ie |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Italy===\nCensuses in Italy do not inquire about race or ethnicity. Only information disposable are those of civil registers, where only the country of birth is noted down.\n\n===Kosovo===\n[[File:Kosovo ethnic 2005.png|thumb|right|100px|Dominant ethnicities in Kosovo in 2005]]\n\nThe population of Kosovo was enumerated by ethnicity from at least 1948 all the way up to the present day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.icty.org/x/file/About/OTP/War_Demographics/en/milosevic_kosovo_020814.pdf|title=Report on the size and ethnic composition of the population of Kosovo|last=|first=|date=14 August 2002|website=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/kosovo-ethnic2011.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Kosovo 2011 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Latvia===\n[[File:Russians in Baltic States (2011).svg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic Russians as a percentage of the total population in the [[Baltic States]] 2011]]\n\nPeople in Latvia (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> [[Latvia]] enumerated people by ethnicity between 1920 and 1935.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roots-saknes.lv/Ethnicities/ethnicities_statistics.htm |title=Ethnicities in Latvia. Statistics |publisher=Roots-saknes.lv |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> The Soviet Union [[Occupation of the Baltic states|occupied Latvia]] in 1940, and it enumerated people there by ethnicity from 1959 to 1989.<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Latvia]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses of 2000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/latvia-ethnic2000.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Latvia 2000 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://data.csb.gov.lv/Dialog/varval.asp?ma=TSG11-06a&ti=TSG11-06%2E+RESIDENT+POPULATION+ON+MARCH+1%2C+2011+BY+ETHNICITY%2C+SEX+AND+AGE+GROUP&path=../DATABASEEN/tautassk_11/Final%20results%20of%20the%20Population%20and%20Housing%20Census%202011/&lang=1 |title=Table: TSG11-06. RESIDENT POPULATION ON MARCH 1, 2011 BY ETHNICITY, SEX AND AGE GROUP |publisher=Data.csb.gov.lv |date=2011-03-01 |accessdate=2013-03-21 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Lithuania===\nPeople in Lithuania (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> [[Lithuania]] enumerated people by ethnicity in its 1923 census and in its 1925 census of its [[Klaipeda]] region.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kasatkina|first=Natalija|last2=Marcinkevicius|first2=Andrius|title=Russians in Lithuania According to the 1897 and 1923 Censuses: Comparative Analysis|url=http://www.ces.lt/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/EtSt_Kasatkina_Marcinkevicius_2008.pdf|journal=Ethnicity Studies|volume=|issn=1822-1041}}</ref> The Soviet Union [[Occupation of the Baltic states|occupied Lithuania]] in 1940, and it enumerated people there by ethnicity from 1959 to 1989.<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Lithuania]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses of 2001<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/lithuania-ethnic2001.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Lithuania 2001 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.15min.lt/en/article/in-lithuania/lithuania-s-population-stands-at-3-043-million-525-259643 |title=Lithuania's population stands below three million |publisher=15min.lt |date=2013-02-04 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Luxembourg===\nIt is illegal to collect statistics about the race, ethnicity, religion or ancestry of Luxembourg citizens.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\n===Moldova===\n[[File:Major ethnics groups in Moldova 1989.jpg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Moldova in 1989]]\n\nPeople in Moldova (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Moldova]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in both its post-Soviet censuses: in [[2004 Moldovan Census|2004]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/moldova-ethnic2004.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Moldova 2004 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and [[2014 Moldovan Census|2014]].<ref>[http://www.statistica.md/pageview.php?l=en&idc=479 Results of Population and Housing Census in the Republic of Moldova in 2014]</ref>\n\n===Monaco===\n[[Monaco]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1982.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Montenegro===\n[[File:Ethnic map of Montenegro by municipality.svg|thumb|100px|Dominant ethnicities in Montenegro in 2011]]\n\nThe population of [[Montenegro]] was enumerated by ethnicity from 1909 up to its most recent census in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njegos.org/census/index.htm |title=Montenegrin Census' from 1909 to 2003 - Aleksandar Rakovic |publisher=Njegos.org |date=2004-09-23 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/montenegro-ethnic2003.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Montenegro 2003 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transconflict.com/2011/07/montenegro-a-census-like-no-other-147/ |title=Montenegro - a census like no other? |publisher=TransConflict |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===North Macedonia===\n[[File:Map of the majority ethnic groups of Macedonia by municipality.svg|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of North Macedonia in 2002.]]\n\nPeople in [[North Macedonia]] were enumerated by ethnicity/nationality from at least 1921 all the way up to the present day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://epc2008.princeton.edu/papers/80013|title=Changes in ethnic structure in Macedonia after emigration of Turkish minority|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> In the most recent census in 2002, 64.2% of the population declared themselves to be [[ethnic Macedonian]]s. The second-largest ethnic group in the country was the ethnic [[Albanians]] with 25.2%. Other major ethnic groups were [[Turkish people|Turks]] (3.9%), [[Romani people|Romani]] (2.7%), and [[Serbs]] (1.8%).<ref name=\"Statistical Office\">[http://www.stat.gov.mk/Publikacii/knigaX.pdf Macedonian census, language and religion]</ref>\n\n===Norway===\nNorway enumerated the population in the northern part of the country by ethnicity between 1845 and 1930.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mbMs68rD9doC&pg=PA173&dq=norway+census+ethnicity#v=onepage&q=norway%20census%20ethnicity&f=false |title=Indigenous Peoples and Demography: The Complex Relation Between Identity and ... - Google Books |date=2011-08-15 |accessdate=2013-09-01|isbn=9780857450036 |last1=Axelsson |first1=Per |last2=Sk\u00f6ld |first2=Peter }}</ref> In the census of 1970, in limited areas in Northern Norway, people were identified by ethnicity and language.  Such information has not been included in any census since then.<ref>{{cite web| title = Norwegian National Archives | url = http://www.ssb.no/befolkning/artikler-og-publikasjoner/paa-vei-mot-eu-medlemskap | date = 2013\n| accessdate = 29 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Poland===\nPeople in Poland (when [[Partitions of Poland|the country was still occupied]] by the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated allegedly by their native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> Sovereign [[Poland]] enumerated people by ethnicity/nationality in 1921.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kresy.co.uk/census_demographic.html |title=Polish 1921 Census and Demographic Data |publisher=Kresy.co.uk |accessdate=2013-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130305005728/http://www.kresy.co.uk/census_demographic.html |archive-date=2013-03-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It enumerated people by mother tongue in 1931, and used this data to determine ethnicity/nationality.<ref name=autogenerated14>{{cite web |url=http://www6.gencat.net/llengcat/noves/hm04primavera-estiu/docs/moskal.pdf |title=Language minorities in Poland at the moment of accession to the EU, by Marta Moskal |accessdate=2013-03-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512204841/http://www6.gencat.net/llengcat/noves/hm04primavera-estiu/docs/moskal.pdf |archivedate=2013-05-12 }}</ref> After [[World War II]], the [[Polish People's Republic|Communist Polish government]] did not enumerate people by nationality/ethnicity.<ref name=autogenerated14 /> The post-Communist 2002 Polish census did enumerate people by nationality/ethnicity and language used at home.<ref name=autogenerated14 />\n\n===Romania===\n[[File:Romania harta etnica 2011.PNG|100px|thumb|Ethnic map of Romania in 2011]]\n\n[[Romania]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1859\u20131860,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.recensamantromania.ro/en/history/censuses-1859-1990/ |title=Censuses of 1859-1990 &#124; Recensamant 2011 |publisher=Recensamantromania.ro |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> 1887,<ref>{{cite book | page=407 | title = The Statesman's Year-Book | year = 1889| publisher = St. Martin's Press | url = }}</ref> 1899,<ref>{{cite book | page=612 | title = New International Yearbook | year = 1915| publisher = Dodd, Mead and Company | url = }}</ref> and in every census since 1930, with the exception of the 1948 census, which enumerated people only by mother tongue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hungarianhistory.com/lib/humis/humis07.htm |title=The Hungarian Minority's Situation in Ceausescu's Romania |publisher=Hungarianhistory.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/#romania|title=Population Statistics of Eastern Europe \u00a7 Romania|publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.insse.ro/cms/files%5Cstatistici%5Ccomunicate%5Calte%5C2012%5CComunicat%20DATE%20PROVIZORII%20RPL%202011e.pdf |title=Comunicat DATE PROVIZORII RPL 2011_transmis |accessdate=2012-12-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114205218/http://www.insse.ro/cms/files/statistici/comunicate/alte/2012/Comunicat%20DATE%20PROVIZORII%20RPL%202011e.pdf |archivedate=2012-11-14 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.recensamantromania.ro/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/Comunicat_DATE_PROVIZORII_RPL_2011.pdf|title=COMUNICAT DE PRES\u0102 2 februarie 2012 privind rezultatele provizorii ale Recens\u0103m\u00e2ntului Popula\u0163iei \u015fi Locuin\u0163elor \u2013 2011 |date=February 2, 2012}}</ref> The [[World Jewish Congress]] also carried out a census of [[Romanian Jews|Romania's Jewish population]] in 1947.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/vjw/romaniatoc.html|title=Romania|work=Virtual Jewish Library}}</ref>\n\n===Serbia===\n[[File:Census 2002 Serbia, ethnic map (by municipalities).png|thumb|100px|right|Ethnic composition of Serbia in 2002]]\n\nIn addition to [[Yugoslavia]] enumerating people by ethnicity/nationality, [[Serbia]] enumerated people by ethnicity/nationality in its 2002 and 2011 censuses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.osce.org/serbia/30908|title=Ethnic Minorities in Serbia - An overview|date=February 27, 2008|publisher=Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/society.php?yyyy=2011&mm=11&dd=16&nav_id=77354 |title=Serbia has fewer citizens, census results show |publisher=B92 |date=2011-11-16 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Slovakia===\nThe population of [[Slovakia]] was enumerated by ethnicity/nationality since 1910 all the way up to the present day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hhrf.org/kisebbsegkutatas/mr_04/cikk.php?id=1188 |title=L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Gyurgyik:Hungarians in Czechoslovakia: Changes in Their Population And Settlement System from 1918 to the Present Day |publisher=Hhrf.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sodb.infostat.sk/sodb/eng/1848-2001/tab.III.2-2B_en.htm |title=Demografick\u0439 \u044adaje zo s\u0438\u043dtania \u040audu 1921 |publisher=Sodb.infostat.sk |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://portal.statistics.sk/files/Sekcie/sek_600/Demografia/SODB/Tabulky/Tabulky_AJ_SODB/tab11.pdf|title=Table 11. Resident population by nationality - 2001, 1991|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715152521/http://portal.statistics.sk/files/Sekcie/sek_600/Demografia/SODB/Tabulky/Tabulky_AJ_SODB/tab11.pdf|archivedate=July 15, 2007|publisher=Statistical Office of the SR|year=2005}}</ref>\n\n===Slovenia===\nThe population of [[Slovenia]] was enumerated by ethnicity since 1953 all the way up to the present day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stat.si/popis2002/en/rezultati/rezultati_red.asp?ter=SLO&st=7 |title=Statisti\u010dni urad RS - Popis 2002 |publisher=Stat.si |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Transnistria===\nPeople in [[Transnistria]] (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> the de facto independent country of Transnistria also enumerated people by ethnicity in its post-Soviet censuses in 2004 and 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.olvia.idknet.com/ol37-09-05.htm |title=Ol37-09-05 |publisher=Olvia.idknet.com |accessdate=2013-03-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105231746/http://www.olvia.idknet.com/ol37-09-05.htm |archivedate=2012-11-05 }}</ref> [[Romania]] also enumerated people in Transnistria by ethnicity in its 1941 census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Holocaust/romanianjewry.html|title=The Plan for the Extermination of Romanian Jewry|work=Jewish Virtual Library}}</ref>\n\n===Ukraine===\n[[File:Ethnolingusitic map of ukraine.png|right|thumb|100px|Ethnolinguistic composition of Ukraine.]]\n\nPeople in Ukraine (when it was still a part of the [[Russian Empire]]) were enumerated by native tongue [[1897 census|in the 1897 Russian Empire Census]].<ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated11 /> In addition to the Soviet Union enumerating people by ethnicity for its entire existence,<ref name=autogenerated5 /> [[Ukraine]] also enumerated people by ethnicity in its only post-Soviet census in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/ukraine-ethnic2001.htm |title=Ethnic composition of Ukraine 2001 |publisher=Pop-stat.mashke.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\nThe [[United Kingdom]] began [[Classification of ethnicity in the United Kingdom|counting people by ethnicity]] in [[United Kingdom Census 1991|1991]].<ref>{{cite journal | author1 = K. Sillitoe | author2 = P. H. White | title = Ethnic Group and the British Census: the Search for a Question | journal = Journal of the Royal Statistical Society, Series A | volume = 155 | issue = 1 | pages = 141\u2013163 | year = 1992 | doi=10.2307/2982673| pmid = 12159122 | jstor = 2982673 }}</ref> There eventually became more of an interest in enumerating ethnic minorities after large-scale racial minority immigration to the United Kingdom began in the post-[[World War II]] era.<ref>{{cite book|chapterurl=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/~uctpb21/Cpapers/Ethn_2gen_revision_C1.pdf|chapter=Ethnicity and Second Generation Immigrants |author1=Christian Dustmann|author2=Tommaso Frattini|author3= Nikolaos Theodoropoulos|doi=10.1093/acprof:osobl/9780199587377.003.0016|title=The Labour Market in Winter: The State of Working Britain|isbn=9780199587377|year=2011}}</ref> The United Kingdom previously planned to enumerate people by ethnicity in 1981, but changed its mind after the large non-response rate to this question in the 1979 Test Census. In 1979, many ethnic minorities refused to answer this question due to the fear of deportation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iser.essex.ac.uk/files/iser_working_papers/2008-26.pdf|title=Who are the UK's minority ethnic groups? Issues of identification and measurement in a longitudinal study|date=September 2008|author1=Jonathan Burton|author2=Alita Nandi |author3=Lucinda Platt |type=Working paper}}</ref> In the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 census]], the ethnic group options for England and Wales were White, Mixed, [[Asian British]], [[Black British]], [[Chinese people|Chinese]] or other ethnic group, and Not stated, with ethnic origin sub-group choices for most of these.<ref name=\"TIAUKcodes\">{{cite web|title=New Ethnicity Code List|url=http://www.theia.org.uk/NR/rdonlyres/9568290B-80AA-4030-AED3-046A8E5C3F92/0/L12V_1_2_NewEthnicityCodes.doc|publisher=The Information Authority|accessdate=24 August 2012}}</ref> The census in the United Kingdom also included a question on country of citizenship between 1851 and 1961.<ref name=\"catdir\"/>\n\n===Vatican City===\n[[Vatican City]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1948.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n==North America==\n\n===Bahamas===\nThe population of the [[Bahamas]] was enumerated by ethnicity in 1953 and again in 2010.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Barbados===\nThe population of [[Barbados]] was enumerated by ethnicity in 1946, 1960, 1970, and 1980.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Belize===\nBack when [[Belize]] was [[British Honduras]], it enumerated people by ethnicity in 1946. Since gaining independence, Belize has enumerated people by ethnicity from 1980 all the way up to its most recent census in 2010.\n\n===Bermuda===\nThe people of [[Bermuda]] were enumerated by ethnicity since at least 1950 all the way up to the present day.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|author=Keith Archibald Forbes |url=http://www.bermuda-online.org/population.htm |title=Bermuda's Population and local Expatriate Organizations |publisher=Bermuda-online.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Canada===\n[[File:Censusdivisions-ethnic.png|100px|thumb|right|A map of the largest ethnic ancestry in different regions of Canada]]\n\n[[Canada]] [[Demographics of Canada|counted people by ethnic origin]] in 1765 and again from at least 1871 to 2006, with the exception of 1891.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/ref/about-apropos/history-histoire-eng.cfm |title=2011 Census - About the census: History of the Census of Canada |publisher=2.statcan.gc.ca |date=2013-01-10 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated17>{{cite web|url=http://www23.statcan.gc.ca/imdb-bmdi/pub/instrument/3901_Q2_V3-eng.pdf |title=ARCHIVED - PDF Document |publisher=3.statcan.gc.ca |date=2010-05-17 |accessdate=2013-01-14}}</ref><ref name=\"statcan2006\">{{cite web|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2006/ref/rp-guides/ethnic-ethnique-eng.cfm |title=2006 Census : Ethnic Origin Reference Guide |publisher=2.statcan.gc.ca |date=2011-05-04 |accessdate=2013-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=tRzXJAFODuwC&pg=PA4&dq=canada+census+1891+ethnic+origin#v=onepage&q=canada%20census%201891%20ethnic%20origin&f=false |title=Race and Research - Google Books |accessdate=2013-03-21|isbn=9780875530307 |last1=Beech |first1=Bettina M. |last2=Goodman |first2=Maurine |year=2004 }}</ref> The options for ethnicity in the 2006 Canadian census were various kinds of [[European Canadian]], [[Aboriginal Canadian]], and various [[non-white]] or non-European groups known officially as \"[[visible minorities]]\".<ref name=autogenerated17 /> The 2011 Canadian census did not ask about race and ethnicity,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p1/2010/2010-08-21/html/order-decret-eng.html |title=ARCHIVED \u2014 Canada Gazette \u2013 ORDERS IN COUNCIL |publisher=Gazette.gc.ca |date=2012-11-09 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> but the new voluntary National Household Survey (NHS) for that year did ask about race and ethnicity (as well as many other questions that were previously asked on the Canadian census).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/NHS-ENM/ref/Questionnaires/2011NHS-ENM-eng.cfm#Q17 |title=2011 National Household Survey Questions |publisher=2.statcan.gc.ca |accessdate=2013-03-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809041130/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/NHS-ENM/ref/Questionnaires/2011NHS-ENM-eng.cfm#Q17 |archivedate=2011-08-09 }}</ref> Prior to the 1981 Canadian census, respondents could only mark one ethnicity/ethnic ancestry, but the 1981 census and all future ones allowed multiple ethnicity responses.<ref name=\"statcan2006\"/> Canada also enumerated its population by place of birth from 1871 to the present day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/11-516-x/sectiona/4147436-eng.htm |title=Historical statistics of Canada: Section A: Population and Migration |publisher=Statcan.gc.ca |date=2008-10-22 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2006/as-sa/97-557/pdf/97-557-XIE2006001.pdf |title=Microsoft Word - 97-557-XIE_immigration_26-11-07.doc |date= |accessdate=2013-03-16}}</ref>\n\n===Costa Rica===\n[[Costa Rica]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1950.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Cuba===\n[[Cuba]] enumerated people by race since 1774 to the most recent official census in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://digital.tcl.sc.edu/cdm4/document.php?CISOROOT=/CCC&CISOPTR=1683&REC=5&CISOBOX=foreign|title=Report on the Census of Cuba, 1899 :: Census of Cuba 1899|website=Digital.tcl.sc.edu|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onei.gob.cu/sites/default/files/informe_nacional_censo_0.pdf|title=Censo de poblacion y viviendas Cuba|date=January 2014|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Dominica===\nThe people in [[Dominica]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1960 and 1981.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Dominican Republic===\nThe people in the [[Dominican Republic]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1950.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Grenada===\nThe people of [[Grenada]] were enumerated by ethnicity in 1960 and 1981.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Guatemala===\n[[Guatemala]] has enumerated people by ethnicity in 1950, 1964, 2002, and 2018.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Jamaica===\nThe population of Jamaica was enumerated by ethnicity in 1960 and again from 1982 all the way up to the present day.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caricomstats.org/Files/Publications/NCR%20Reports/Jamaica.pdf |title=2000 Round of Population and Housing Census Data Analysis Sub-Project|date= |accessdate=2012-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://statinja.gov.jm/PublicationReleases.aspx |accessdate=July 19, 2019 |title=Census 2011 General Report}}</ref>\n\n===Mexico===\n[[Mexico]] enumerates people on whether or not they speak [[Spanish language|Spanish]] or indigenous languages.<ref name=\"autogenerated2001\">{{Cite web|url=http://sociology.as.nyu.edu/docs/IO/1043/Pop.Comp.IESBS.2001.pdf|title=Population Composition by Race and Ethnicity: North America|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Mexico does not enumerate its population by race and ethnicity directly.<ref name=\"autogenerated2001\"/>\n\n===Panama===\n[[Panama]] has enumerated people by ethnicity from the 1970 census all the way up to its most recent census in 2010.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|author=Don Winner |url=http://www.panama-guide.com/article.php/20100511134852268 |title=National Census in Panama This Sunday, 16 May 2010 |publisher=Panama Guide |date= |accessdate=2013-03-16}}</ref> People in the then-United States-controlled [[Panama Canal Zone]] were numerated by ethnicity in 1950 and 1960.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Puerto Rico===\n[[Puerto Rico]] enumerated people by race in its census [[Demographics of Puerto Rico|since at least 1877]] with the exception of the period from 1960 to 1990.\n\n===United States===\n{{details|Race and ethnicity in the United States Census}}\n\n[[File:Census-2000-Data-Top-US-Ancestries-by-County.svg|400px|thumb|right|The [[wikt:plurality|plurality]] (not [[majority]]) ethnic ancestry in each [[county (United States)|county in the United States of America]]]]\n\nBefore the [[American Revolutionary War|U.S. acquired independence from Great Britain]], many of the [[Thirteen Colonies]] conducted [[censuses]] of their own where they enumerated their populations by [[Race (human classification)|race]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/22/opinion/fix-the-census-archaic-racial-categories.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 | work=The New York Times | first=Kenneth | last=Prewitt | title=Fix the Census' Archaic Racial Categories | date=2013-08-21}}</ref><ref name=\"census5\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.census.gov/prod2/statcomp/documents/CT1970p2-13.pdf |title=2-11-Z-COLONIAL & PRE-FEDERAL.pdf |date= |accessdate=2013-06-20}}</ref> The [[United States]] as a whole [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|enumerated people by race]] in every [[United States Census|census]] since [[U.S. Census, 1790|its first census]] in 1790.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/twps0056.html |title=Historical Census Statistics on Population Totals By Race, 1790 to 1990, and By Hispanic Origin, 1970 to 1990, For The United States, Regions, Divisions, and States |publisher=Census.gov |accessdate=2013-05-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224151538/http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/twps0056.html |archivedate=2014-12-24 }}</ref>  Part of the reason why the United States began counting people by race much sooner than many other countries was due to the [[Three Fifths Compromise]], which determined the amount of representation that Southern states had based on how many slaves they had (slaves were counted as three-fifths of a person for representation purposes, and a new census every ten years was needed to enumerate the current slave population).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csa.com/discoveryguides/census/review3.php |title=Multiracial Identity and the U.S. Census, ProQuest Discovery Guides |publisher=Csa.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> Initially, the [[United States Census]] only counted Americans as either [[White American|white]] or [[African American|black]], with blacks classified as either [[Free people of color|free]] or [[slaves]] until 1860 ([[slavery in the United States]] was [[Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|abolished]] in 1865).<ref name=\"usrace2002\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/twps0056.html |title=Historical Census Statistics on Population Totals By Race, 1790 to 1990, and By Hispanic Origin, 1970 to 1990, For The United States, Regions, Divisions, and States |publisher=Census.gov |accessdate=2012-09-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224151538/http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/twps0056.html |archivedate=2014-12-24 }}</ref> Over time, the United States has also added some other racial categories as well.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> [[Asian-American|Asian]] and [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] categories were added in 1860.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> However, the first census to enumerate all Native Americans occurred in 1890.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> Before that point Native Americans living on [[Indian reservation|reservations]] were not counted, and thus most Native Americans in the U.S. were not counted in census data before 1890.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> Between 1850 and 1870, and in 1890, 1910, and 1920, the [[U.S. Census Bureau]] also enumerated [[Mulattoes]] and sometimes other partially black groups ([[Quadroons]] and [[Octoroons]]) separately.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/>\n\nThe [[U.S. Census Bureau]] counted [[Mexicans]] as a separate race in 1930<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://chnm.gmu.edu/staff/sharon/readings/ngai.html |author=Mae M. Ngai |title= The Architecture of Race in American Immigration Law: A Reexamination of the Immigration Act of 1924|journal= The Journal of American History|volume=86|issue=1|publisher=The History Cooperative |via=Chnm.gmu.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-06-22|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141127115837/http://chnm.gmu.edu/staff/sharon/readings/ngai.html|archivedate=November 27, 2014}}</ref> and tried to retroactively determine the number of Mexicans in the U.S. in 1910 and 1920 as well.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/>\n\nPresident [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] promoted a [[Good Neighbor policy|\"good neighbor\" policy]] that sought better relations with Mexico.  In 1935, a [[federal judge]] ruled that three Mexican immigrants were ineligible for citizenship because they were not white, as required by federal law<!-- citation need -->.  Mexico protested, and Roosevelt decided to circumvent the decision and make sure the federal government treated Hispanics as white.  The [[U.S. State Department|State Department]], the Census Bureau, the [[U.S. Labor Department|Labor Department]], and other [[government agencies]] therefore made sure to uniformly classify people of Mexican descent as white.  This policy encouraged the [[League of United Latin American Citizens]] in its quest to minimize discrimination by asserting their whiteness.<ref>Patrick D. Lukens, ''A Quiet Victory for Latino Rights: FDR and the Controversy over Whiteness'' (University of Arizona Press, 2012)</ref>\n\nHispanics were counted as whites in 1940, but for the first time ever, the U.S. made an attempt to measure the size of the Hispanic population that year.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> The U.S. resumed enumerating its [[Hispanic]]/Latino population in 1970, with Hispanics being enumerated in every U.S. census since then.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> The U.S. Census Bureau also began offering Hispanics several sub-group options from which they could identify themselves, such as Mexican, Puerto Rican, Cuban, et cetera (these Hispanic sub-group options have changed over time).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/tabD-04.pdf |title=Table D-4. Hispanic Origin (of Any Race), for the United States, Regions, Divisions, and States: 1940 and 1970 (Sample Data) (See text for sources, definitions, and explanations) |accessdate=2017-12-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120101537/http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/tabD-04.pdf |archivedate=2013-01-20 }} </ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/tabD-02.pdf |title=Table D-2. Hispanic Origin (of Any Race), for the United States, Regions, Divisions, and States: 1990 (Sample Data) (See text for sources, definitions, and explanations) |accessdate=2017-12-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120101352/http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/tabD-02.pdf |archivedate=2013-01-20 }} </ref> The Other race category was added in 1950, and in 2000 multi-race responses were tabulated for the first time  (instructions now explicitly inform respondents that they can chose multiple race boxes).<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> Because multiracial respondents are now allowed, U.S. Census data since 2000 is not directly comparable with that of previous censuses.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> While people nowadays are enumerated by race based on self-identification, until 1950 their race on the census was mainly determined by their census enumerator.<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> During this time multiracial people who were White and of another race were usually marked down as belonging to the other race due to the [[One drop rule]].<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/> The instructions provided to enumerators endorsed this practice.\n\nIt is worth noting that some of the definitions of race in the United States changed over time. For instance, [[Indian Americans]] were previously marked as Hindu in 1920\u20131940, Other race in 1950\u20131960, and White in 1970 before being marked as Asian (Indian) since 1980.<ref name = \"usrace2002\"/> The [[U.S. census]] counted certain [[Asian people|Asian]] ethnic groups separately since 1870, initially counting only [[Chinese Americans|Chinese]] and [[Japanese Americans|Japanese]], but having other categories as well since 1910.<ref name = \"usrace2002\"/> It only began counting all people by ethnic ancestry since [[U.S. Census, 1980|the 1980 census]], though.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usa.ipums.org/usa/voliii/items1980.shtml |title=IPUMS USA: 1980 Census Questions and Instructions |publisher=Usa.ipums.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> In addition to a Hispanic/Latino ''ethnicity'' question that has appeared on the census short form since 1980 (based on the US [[Office of Management and Budget]]'s official categories specified in 1977). In addition, at various times the Census Bureau has also used an ''ancestry'' question. Before 1970, [[Alaska]] and [[Hawaii]] had different choices for race on their censuses in contrast to the [[continental United States]].<ref name=\"usrace2002\"/>\n\nThe United States has also used language as a way to classify people by race or ethnicity.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Leeman|first=Jennifer|date=2004|title=Racializing language: A history of linguistic ideologies in the US Census|url=https://www.academia.edu/335479|journal=Journal of Language and Politics|language=en|volume=3|issue=3|pages=507\u2013534|issn=1569-2159|via=|doi=10.1075/jlp.3.3.08lee}}</ref> From 1910 to 1940, the Census recorded the mother tongue of the foreign-born population and their children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0029/tab06.html |title=Tech Paper 29: Table 6. Mother Tongue of the Foreign-Born Population: 1910 to 1940, 1960, and 1970 |publisher=Census.gov |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> In 1960 and 1970 the Census Bureau also used mother tongue to classify respondents by ethnicity, but the definition of mother tongue was not consistent. Since 1980, the Census Bureau has tabulated [[Language Spoken at Home|language spoken at home]] for people aged five or older.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/hhes/socdemo/language/data/acs/Table2.xls |title=Table 2 (download) |publisher=Census.gov }}</ref> \n\nThe [[2020 United States Census]] might allow [[Middle Easterners]] and [[North African American|North Africans]] to write in their ethnicity/race instead of merely marking them as White.<ref name=autogenerated8>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/08/09/census-bureau-changes-race-hispanics-negro_n_1760467.html |title=Census Bureau Proposes Changes: Hispanics As Distinct Category And End Use Of Term 'Negro' |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= 2012-08-09|accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Turnbull |first=Lornet |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2019032486_censuschange31m.html |title=Latinos may get own race category on census form &#124; Local News |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> Right now, and in the past, [[Arab Americans|Arabs]] have been marked in the U.S. Census as White.<ref name=autogenerated8 /> This began in the early twentieth century when [[Arabs]] [[Immigration to the United States|coming to the United States]] successfully petitioned to be marked as White in order to avoid entry quotas and have a greater chance of achieving success and avoiding discrimination.<ref\nname=autogenerated8/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aaiusa.org/pages/not-quite-white-race-classification-and-the-arab-american-experience |title=Not Quite White: Race Classification and the Arab American Experience &#124; The Arab American Institute |publisher=Aaiusa.org |accessdate=2013-06-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826035428/http://www.aaiusa.org/pages/not-quite-white-race-classification-and-the-arab-american-experience |archivedate=2014-08-26 }}</ref>\n\nThe United States is one of the countries that uses racial and ethnic census data in order to create [[minority-majority districts]], as is required by the 1965 [[Voting Rights Act]].<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://www.personal.psu.edu/ljk20/MAJ-MINOR.pdf|title=African American Turnout in Majority-Minority Districts|author=Luke Keele|author2=Ismail White|date= December 13, 2011}}</ref> These districts were created in order to increase minority representation in the [[United States Congress]] following the end of legal [[Racial segregation|segregation]] and racial discrimination in the [[Southern United States]].<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nSince 1850, the United States enumerated its population by their country of birth of its population.<ref name=autogenerated21>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0081/twps0081.html |title=Historical Census Statistics on the Foreign-Born Population of the United States: 1850-2000 |publisher=Census.gov |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> The whole U.S. population was enumerated by country of birth between 1850 and 1930 and again from 1960 to the present day.<ref name=autogenerated21 /> Meanwhile, only the [[White Americans|White population of the United States]] was enumerated by their country of birth in 1940 and 1950.<ref name=autogenerated21 />\n\n==Oceania==\n\n===Australia===\nAustralia enumerated its population by ''race'' between 1911 and 1966, by ''racial origin'' in 1971 and 1976, by ''ethnic'' origin in 1981, and by ''ancestry'' since 1986.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/Lookup/2071.0Feature+Article2July+2011 |title=2071.0 - Reflecting a Nation: Stories from the 2011 Census, July 2011 |publisher=Abs.gov.au |date=2012-06-20 |accessdate=2013-04-06}}</ref>\n\n===Fiji===\nThe population of [[Fiji]] was enumerated by ethnicity from 1881 all the way up to Fiji's most recent census in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spc.int/prism/country/fj/stats/Key%20Stats/Population/1.1%20census%20of%20population.pdf|title=1.1 CENSUS OF POPULATION NY ETHNICITY 1881 - 2007|publisher=Fiji Bureau of Statistics |date=June 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114214328/http://www.spc.int/prism/country/fj/stats/Key%20Stats/Population/1.1%20census%20of%20population.pdf|archivedate=November 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Nauru===\nThe population of [[Nauru]] was enumerated by ethnicity between 1947 and 1977.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===New Zealand===\n[[File:MaoriPopulationPercentage.png|thumb|right|100px|Maoris as a percentage of the total population of New Zealand in 2006.]]\n\n[[New Zealand]] enumerated people by ethnicity from 1858 to the present day.<ref name=autogenerated7>{{cite web|url=http://www.stats.govt.nz/Census/about-2006-census/introduction-to-the-census/history-of-the-census-in-nz.aspx |title=Introduction to the Census - Statistics New Zealand |publisher=Stats.govt.nz |date=2006-11-24 |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> People were enumerated by tribal affiliation in 1901 and again from 1991 to the present day.<ref name=autogenerated7 />\n\n===Palau===\n[[Palau]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1995.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Papua New Guinea===\n[[Papua New Guinea]] only enumerated its population by ethnicity in 1971.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n==South America==\n\n===Argentina===\nArgentina enumerated its population by their country of birth from 1869 to the present day.<ref name=autogenerated22>{{cite web|url=http://www.indec.gov.ar/webcenso/aquisecuenta/Aqui12.pdf|title=Tendencias recientes de la Inmigraci\u00f3n internacional |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070824231326/http://www.indec.gov.ar/webcenso/aquisecuenta/aqui12.pdf|archivedate=August 24, 2007|date=February 2004 |issn= 0329-7586|publisher=Indec}}</ref>\n\n===Bolivia===\n[[File:Pueblos originarios de Bolivia.png|thumb|right|100px|Ethnic composition of Bolivia.]]\n\n[[Bolivia]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1950,<ref name=autogenerated6 /> 2001,<ref>{{cite web|author=CEPAL - Naciones Unidas |url=http://www.eclac.org/cgi-bin/getProd.asp?xml=/publicaciones/xml/3/23263/P23263.xml&xsl=/celade/tpl/p9f.xsl&base=/celade/tpl/top-bottom.xsl |title=CEPAL - Los pueblos ind\u00edgenas de Bolivia: diagn\u00f3stico sociodemogr\u00e1fico a partir del censo del 2001 |publisher=Eclac.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> and 2012.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref name=autogenerated25>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/bolivias-census-omits-mestizo-category-17779349#.ULm6AJtQAak |title=Bolivia's Census Omits 'Mestizo' as Category - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> The 2012 census included 40 ethnic group options.<ref name=autogenerated25 /> However, it did not include [[Mestizo]] as an option, which critics of current [[Bolivian President]] [[Evo Morales]] say was because he wants more Bolivians to identify as one of the indigenous groups in order to lend more legitimacy to his indigenous-friendly policies.<ref name=autogenerated25 />\n\n<div class=\"mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\">\n<div style=\"font-weight:bold; font-size:100%; padding:5px;\">'''Data from the census in 2012'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Census in Bolivia|url=http://www.ine.gob.bo:8081/censo2012/PDF/resultadosCPV2012.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209134921/http://www.ine.gob.bo:8081/censo2012/PDF/resultadosCPV2012.pdf|archivedate=2014-02-09}}</ref></div>\n<div class=\"mw-collapsible-content\" style=\"background-color:#faf6ed;\">\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Ethnic group !! Total people !! Male !!Female\n|-\n| Afroboliviano ||align=\"right\"|16.329 || align=\"right\"|8.785 || align=\"right\"|7.544\n|-\n| Araona || align=\"right\"|910 || align=\"right\"|452 || align=\"right\"|458\n|-\n| Aymara || align=\"right\"|1.191.352 || align=\"right\"|592.817 || align=\"right\"|598.535\n|-\n| Ayoreo || align=\"right\"|1.862 || align=\"right\"|954 || align=\"right\"|908\n|-\n| Baure || align=\"right\"|2.319 || align=\"right\"|1.219 || align=\"right\"|1.100\n|-\n| Canichana || align=\"right\"|617 || align=\"right\"|360 || align=\"right\"|257\n|-\n| Cavine\u00f1o || align=\"right\"|2.005 || align=\"right\"|1.118 || align=\"right\"|887\n|-\n| Cayubaba || align=\"right\"|1.424 || align=\"right\"|738 || align=\"right\"|686\n|-\n| Chacobo || align=\"right\"|826 || align=\"right\"|418 || align=\"right\"|408\n|-\n| Chipaya || align=\"right\"|786 || align=\"right\"|400 || align=\"right\"|386\n|-\n| Chiquitano || align=\"right\"|87.885 || align=\"right\"|45.497 || align=\"right\"|42.388\n|-\n| Esse Ejja || align=\"right\"|695 || align=\"right\"|379 || align=\"right\"|316\n|-\n| Guaran\u00ed || align=\"right\"|58.990 || align=\"right\"|29.918 || align=\"right\"|29.072\n|-\n| Guarasugwe || align=\"right\"|42 || align=\"right\"|25 || align=\"right\"|17\n|-\n| Guarayo || align=\"right\"|13.621 || align=\"right\"|6.846 || align=\"right\"|6.775\n|-\n| Itonama || align=\"right\"|10.275 || align=\"right\"|5.356 || align=\"right\"|4.919\n|-\n| Joaquiniano || align=\"right\"|2.797 || align=\"right\"|1.510 || align=\"right\"|1.287\n|-\n| Kallawaya || align=\"right\"|7.389 || align=\"right\"|3.824 || align=\"right\"|3.565\n|-\n| Leco || align=\"right\"|9.006 || align=\"right\"|4.820 || align=\"right\"|4.186\n|-\n| Machiner\u00ed || align=\"right\"|38 || align=\"right\"|25 || align=\"right\"|13\n|-\n| Maropa || align=\"right\"|2.857 || align=\"right\"|1.550 || align=\"right\"|1.307\n|-\n| Moje\u00f1o || align=\"right\"|31.078 || align=\"right\"|16.564 || align=\"right\"|14.514\n|-\n| Mor\u00e9 || align=\"right\"|155 || align=\"right\"|78 || align=\"right\"|77\n|-\n| Moset\u00e9n || align=\"right\"|1.989 || align=\"right\"|1.095 || align=\"right\"|894\n|-\n| Movima || align=\"right\"|12.213 || align=\"right\"|6.349 || align=\"right\"|5.864\n|-\n| Murato || align=\"right\"|143 || align=\"right\"|78 || align=\"right\"|65\n|-\n| Pacahuara || align=\"right\"|161 || align=\"right\"|85 || align=\"right\"|76\n|-\n| Quechua || align=\"right\"|1.281.116 || align=\"right\"|626.307 || align=\"right\"|654.809\n|-\n| Sirion\u00f3 || align=\"right\"|446 || align=\"right\"|245 || align=\"right\"|201\n|-\n| Tacana || align=\"right\"|11.173 || align=\"right\"|6.060 || align=\"right\"|5.113\n|-\n| Tapiete || align=\"right\"|99 || align=\"right\"|59 || align=\"right\"|40\n|-\n| Tsimane (Chim\u00e1n) || align=\"right\"|6.464 || align=\"right\"|3.399 || align=\"right\"|3.065\n|-\n| Weenayek || align=\"right\"|3.322 || align=\"right\"|1.686 || align=\"right\"|1.636\n|-\n| Yaminahua || align=\"right\"|132 || align=\"right\"|54 || align=\"right\"|78\n|-\n| Yuki || align=\"right\"|202 || align=\"right\"|102 || align=\"right\"|100\n|-\n| Yuracar\u00e9 || align=\"right\"|3.394 || align=\"right\"|1.709 || align=\"right\"|1.685\n|-\n| Yuracar\u00e9 - Moje\u00f1o || align=\"right\"|292 || align=\"right\"|171 || align=\"right\"|121\n|-\n|  other || align=\"right\"|42.188 || align=\"right\"|19.861 || align=\"right\"|22.327\n|-\n|  Other not specified || align=\"right\"|4.419 || align=\"right\"|2.333 || align=\"right\"|2.086\n|-\n| Not belong || align=\"right\"|4.032.014 || align=\"right\"|1.975.811 || align=\"right\"|2.056.203\n|}\n</div></div>\n\n===Brazil===\n[[File:Brancos no Brasil.png|thumb|right|100px|Brazilian states according to the percentage of [[Whites]] in 2009.]]\nThe [[Brazil]]ian census [[Race and ethnicity in Brazil|enumerated people by race]] in all censuses since 1872 with the exception of 1900, 1920, and 1970.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/soc/faculty/telles/Paper_AffirmationandAmbiguity.pdf |title=Mapping the ethno-racial composition of the Brazilian population has long been viewed as problematic due principally to the am |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref> The Brazilian census classifies people by race as either white, black, pardo (brown), yellow (Asian), or indigenous.\n\n===Chile===\n[[Chile]] enumerated people by ethnicity in 1992.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\n===Guyana===\n[[Guyana]] enumerated people by ethnicity from at least 1946 to until at least 2002.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statisticsguyana.gov.gy/census.html |title=Bureau of Statistics - Guyana |publisher=Statisticsguyana.gov.gy |date= |accessdate=2013-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Peru===\nPeru collected data in the 1940 census. In the [[2017 Peru Census|2017 census]], questions about culture and ancestors were asked in more detail for the first time for the population of 12 years old and above.<ref name=\"census2017\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.inei.gob.pe/media/MenuRecursivo/publicaciones_digitales/Est/Lib1539/libro.pdf |title=Per\u00fa: Perfil Sociodemogr\u00e1fico |page = 214 |publisher= [[Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica e Inform\u00e1tica]]|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> Results were  [[Mestizo]] 60.2%,  [[Quechua people|Quechua]] 22.3%, [[White Peruvians|White]] 5.9%, [[Afro-Peruvians|Afro-descendant]] 3.6%, [[Aymara people|Aymara]] 2.4%, [[Indigenous peoples in Peru|Native or indigenous]] to the [[Amazon basin|Amazon]] 0.3%, [[Ash\u00e1ninka]] 0.2%, Part of another Indigenous 0.2%, [[Aguaruna people|Aguaruna/Awaj\u00fan]] 0.2%, [[Shipibo-Conibo people|Shipibo-Conibo/Konibo]] 0.1%, [[Japanese Peruvians|Japanese]] ([[Japanese diaspora|Nikkei]]) 0.1%, [[Chinese Peruvians|Chinese]] (Tusan) 0.1%, Other 1.1%.<ref name=\"census2017\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.inei.gob.pe/media/MenuRecursivo/publicaciones_digitales/Est/Lib1539/libro.pdf |title=Per\u00fa: Perfil Sociodemogr\u00e1fico |page = 214 |publisher= [[Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica e Inform\u00e1tica]]|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ancestry]]\n*[[Census]]\n*[[Demography]]\n*[[Historical racial and ethnic demographics of the United States]]\n*[[IBM and the Holocaust]]\n*[[Majority minority]]\n*[[Population and housing censuses by country]]\n*[[Race and ethnicity in Brazil]]\n*[[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census]]\n*[[Visible minorities]]\n*[[Languages in censuses]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.understandingrace.org/lived/global_census.html Census racial/ethnic/national origin questions from various countries] [Link Broken]\n\n===Historical data===\n*[http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/DYBcensus/V2_Table4.pdf Ethnicity and Race Data for every country in the world which had this census category between 1985 and 2003]\n*[http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/dybcensus/V2_table5.pdf Language Data for every country in the world which had this census category between 1985 and 2003]\n*[http://censusresults.nsi.bg/Census/Reports/1/2/R7.aspx Bulgaria Ethnicity Data for 1900-2011 for the whole country and for urban and rural areas]\n*[http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/11-516-x/pdf/5500092-eng.pdf Canada Ethnic Origin Data for 1871-1971 (on page 17)]\n*[http://pop-stat.mashke.org/ Eastern Europe, Kazakhstan, and Kyrgyzstan Ethnicity/Nationality Data for the late 20th century and early 21st century]\n*[http://www.spc.int/prism/country/fj/stats/Key%20Stats/Population/1.1%20census%20of%20population.pdf Fiji Ethnicity Data for 1881-2007]\n*[http://www.cso.ie/px/pxeirestat/Statire/SelectVarVal/Define.asp?maintable=CDD27&PLanguage=0 Ireland Ethnicity Data for 2011]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121113200941/http://www1.cbs.gov.il/reader/shnaton/templ_shnaton_e.html?num_tab=st02_07x&CYear=2012 Israel Ethnicity Data for 1948-2011 for Israeli Districts and Sub-Districts]\n*[http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/census_types.php?ct=6 Russia, Russian Empire, and USSR Ethnicity/Nationality Data for 1897-2010 by Guberniyas/Oblasts/SSRs]\n*[http://www.ethnicity.ac.uk/census/HowHasEthnicDiversityGrown_Figure1_2.xls United Kingdom Ethnicity Data for 1991-2011]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20141224151538/http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/twps0056.html United States Race and Ethnicity Data for 1790-1990 for U.S. Regions and States]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080912052919/http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0076/twps0076.html United States Race and Ethnicity Data for 1790-1990 for Large Cities and Other Urban Places]\n*[http://www.socialexplorer.com/pub/maps/map3.aspx?g=0&mapi=SE0012 United States Race and Ethnicity Data for 1790-2010 for U.S. States and Counties (the 2010 data is only for subscribers)]\n*[http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/index.html United States Race and Ethnicity Data for 2000 and 2010 for U.S. States and Counties]\n\n===Future population projections, including by race and/or ethnicity===\n*[http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/91-551-x/91-551-x2010001-eng.pdf Canada Population Projections for 2006-2031]\n*[http://www1.cbs.gov.il/www/publications/tec27.pdf Israel Population Projections for 2009-2059]\n*[http://www1.cbs.gov.il/reader/newhodaot/tables_template_eng.html?hodaa=201301170 Israel Population Projections for 2015-2035]\n*[http://www.stats.govt.nz/browse_for_stats/population/estimates_and_projections/NationalEthnicPopulationProjections_HOTP2006-26/Technical%20Notes.aspx New Zealand Population Projections for 2006-2026]\n*[https://www.census.gov/population/projections/data/national/2012.html United States Population Projections for 2015-2060]\n{{Ethnicity}}\n\n[[Category:Censuses]]\n[[Category:Race (human categorization)]]\n[[Category:Ethnicity]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUnited States:Typo fixing, replaced: can chose \u2192 can choose", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Race_and_ethnicity_in_censuses"}
{"title_page": "Route of the Oregon Trail", "text_new": "[[Image:Oregontrail 1907.jpg|thumb|right|400px|Map from ''The Vikings team, or the Old Oregon Trail 1852\u20131906'', by [[Ezra Meeker]]]]\n[[Image:South pass marker2.jpg|thumb|right|Oregon Trail pioneer [[Ezra Meeker]] erected this boulder near [[Pacific Creek (Sweetwater County, Wyoming)|Pacific Springs]] on Wyoming's [[South Pass (Wyoming)|South Pass]] in 1906.<ref>''Ventures and Adventures of Ezra Meeker: Or, Sixty Years of Frontier Life'' by Ezra Meeker. Rainer Printing Company 1908. ASIN: B000861WA8</ref>]]\n\nThe historic {{convert|2170|mi|adj=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blm.gov/or/oregontrail/history-basics.php|title=Basic Facts About the Oregon Trail|work=U.S. DEPARTMENT OF THE INTERIOR - BUREAU OF LAND MANAGEMENT|date=n.d.|accessdate=May 12, 2016}}</ref> '''[[Oregon Trail]]''' connected various towns along the [[Missouri River]] to Oregon's [[Willamette Valley]]. It was used during the 19th century by [[Great Plains]] pioneers who were seeking fertile land in the West and North.\n\nAs the trail developed it became marked by numerous cutoffs and shortcuts from Missouri to Oregon. The basic route follows river valleys as grass and water were absolutely necessary.\n\nWhile the first few parties organized and departed from Elm Grove, the Oregon Trail's primary starting point was [[Independence, Missouri]], or [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]] (Missouri), on the Missouri River. Later, several feeder trails led across [[Kansas]], and some towns became starting points, including [[Weston, Missouri]], [[Fort Leavenworth, Kansas]], [[Atchison, Kansas]], [[St. Joseph, Missouri]], and [[Omaha, Nebraska]].\n\nThe Oregon Trail's nominal termination point was [[Oregon City, Oregon|Oregon City]], at the time the proposed capital of the [[Oregon Territory]]. However, many settlers branched off or stopped short of this goal and settled at convenient or promising locations along the trail. Commerce with pioneers going further west helped establish these early settlements and launched local economies critical to their prosperity.\n\nAt dangerous or difficult river crossings, ferries or toll bridges were set up and bad places on the trail were either repaired or bypassed. Several toll roads were constructed. Gradually the trail became easier with the average trip (as recorded in numerous diaries) dropping from about 160 days in 1849 to 140 days 10 years later.\n\nNumerous other trails followed the Oregon Trail for much of its length, including the [[Mormon Trail]] from [[Illinois]] to [[Utah]]; the [[California Trail]] to the gold fields of [[California]]; and the [[Bozeman Trail]] to [[Montana]]. Because it was more a network of trails than a single trail there were numerous variations, with other trails eventually established on both sides of the [[Platte River|Platte]], [[North Platte River|North Platte]], [[Snake River|Snake]], and [[Columbia River|Columbia]] rivers. With literally thousands of people and thousands of livestock traveling in a fairly small time slot the travelers had to spread out to find clean water, wood, good campsites, and grass. The dust kicked up by the many travelers was a constant complaint, and where the terrain would allow it there may be between 20 and 50 wagons traveling abreast.\n\nRemnants of the trail in Kansas, Nebraska, Wyoming, Idaho, and Oregon have been listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]], and the entire trail is a designated [[National Historic Trail]] (listed as the Oregon National Historic Trail).\n\n==Missouri==\nInitially, the main \"jumping off point\" was the common head of the [[Santa Fe Trail]] and Oregon Trail\u2014[[Independence, Missouri]]/[[Kansas City, Kansas]]. Travelers starting in Independence had to ferry across the Missouri River. After following the Santa Fe trail to near present-day [[Topeka, Kansas]], they ferried across the [[Kansas River]] to start the trek across [[Kansas]] and points west. Another busy \"jumping off point\" was [[St. Joseph, Missouri]]\u2014established in 1843.<ref name=\"travel\">{{cite web|url=http://north-america.traveltoworld.com/north-america-travel-guide/5317/saint-peters-missouri/|title=Saint Peters: Missouri|accessdate=August 30, 2007|publisher=North America Travel Guide|author=North America Travel Guide|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071006123625/http://north-america.traveltoworld.com/north-america-travel-guide/5317/saint-peters-missouri/|archive-date=October 6, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In its early days, St. Joseph was a bustling outpost and rough frontier town, serving as one of the last supply points before heading over the Missouri River to the frontier. St. Joseph had good steamboat connections to [[St. Louis, Missouri]], and other ports on the combined [[Ohio River|Ohio]], [[Missouri River|Missouri]] and [[Mississippi River]] systems. During the busy season there were several ferry boats and steamboats available to transport travelers to the Kansas shore where they started their travels westward. Before the [[Union Pacific Railroad]] was started in 1865, St. Joseph was the westernmost point in the United States accessible by rail. Other towns used as supply points in Missouri included Old Franklin,<ref>Old Franklin Missouri [http://www.santafetrailresearch.com/spacepix/franklin-mo.html] accessed 13 January 2010</ref> [[Arrow Rock, Missouri|Arrow Rock]], and [[Fort Osage]].\n\n==Iowa==\nIn 1803 President [[Thomas Jefferson]] purchased from [[France]] the [[Louisiana Purchase]] for fifteen million dollars (equivalent to about $230 million today) which included all the land drained by the Missouri River and roughly doubled the size of U.S. territory. The future states of [[Iowa]] and [[Missouri]], located west of the [[Mississippi River]] and east of the Missouri River, were part of this purchase. The [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]] stopped several times in the future state of Iowa on their 1805-1806 expedition to the west coast. A disputed 1804 treaty between [[Quashquame]] and [[William Henry Harrison]] (future ninth President of the U.S.) that surrendered much of the future state of [[Illinois]] to the U.S. enraged many [[Sauk people|Sauk]] (Sac) Indians and led to the 1832 [[Black Hawk War]]. As punishment for the uprising, and as part of a larger settlement strategy, treaties were subsequently designed to remove all Indians from Iowa Territory. Some settlers started drifting into Iowa in 1833. President [[Martin Van Buren]] on July 4, 1838, signed laws establishing the Territory of Iowa. Iowa was located opposite the junction of the [[Platte River|Platte]] and Missouri rivers and was used by some of the [[Rocky Mountain Rendezvous|Fur trapper rendezvous]] traders as a starting point for their supply expeditions. In 1846 the [[Mormons]], expelled from [[Nauvoo, Illinois]], traversed Iowa (on part of the [[Mormon Trail]]) and settled temporarily in significant numbers on the Missouri River in Iowa and the future state of [[Nebraska]] at their [[Winter Quarters (North Omaha, Nebraska)|Winter Quarters]] near the future city of [[Omaha, Nebraska]]. (See: Missouri River settlements (1846\u20131854)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://winterquarters.byu.edu/pages/settlements.htm |title=Winter Quarters Project |publisher=Winterquarters.byu.edu |accessdate=2011-03-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719155702/http://winterquarters.byu.edu/pages/settlements.htm |archivedate=2011-07-19 }}</ref>) The Mormons established about 50 temporary towns, including the town of Kanesville (renamed [[Council Bluffs, Iowa]] in 1852) on the east bank of the Missouri River opposite the mouth of the Platte. For those travelers to Oregon, California, and Utah who were bringing their teams to the Platte River junction, Kanesville and other towns become major \"jumping off places\" and supply points. In 1847 the Mormons established three ferries across the Missouri River, and others established even more ferries for the spring start on the trail. In the 1850 census there were about 8,000 mostly Mormons tabulated in the large [[Pottawattamie County, Iowa]] District 21. (The original Pottawattamie County was subsequently made into five counties and parts of several more.)  By 1854 most of the Mormon towns, farms and villages were largely taken over by non-Mormons as they abandoned them or sold them for not much and continued their migration to Utah. After 1846 the towns of Council Bluffs, Iowa, [[Omaha, Nebraska]] (est. 1852) and other Missouri River towns became major supply points and \"jumping off places\" for travelers on the [[Mormon Trail|Mormon]], [[California Trail|California]], Oregon and other trails west.\n\n==Kansas==\n[[Image:Ks rivers.png|thumb|Map of principal rivers in Kansas]]\n\nStarting initially in [[Independence, Missouri|Independence]] or [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]] in Missouri, the initial trail followed the [[Santa Fe Trail]] into Kansas south of the [[Wakarusa River]]. After crossing [[Mount Oread]] at [[Lawrence, Kansas|Lawrence]], the trail crossed the [[Kansas River]] by ferry or boats near [[Topeka, Kansas|Topeka]], and crossed the Wakarusa and Vermillion rivers by ferries. After the Vermillion River the trail angles northwest to [[Nebraska]] paralleling the [[Little Blue River (Kansas/Nebraska)|Little Blue River]] until reaching the south side of the [[Platte River]]. Travel by wagon over the gently rolling Kansas countryside was usually unimpeded except where streams had cut steep banks. There a passage could be made with a lot of shovel work to cut down the banks or the travelers could find an already established crossing.\n\n==Nebraska==\n[[File:Chimney Rock NE.jpg|thumb|left|[[Chimney Rock National Historic Site|Chimney Rock, Nebraska]]]]\nThose emigrants on the eastern side of the Missouri River in [[Missouri]] or [[Iowa]] used ferries and steamboats (fitted out for ferry duty) to cross into towns in [[Nebraska]]. Several towns in Nebraska were used as \"jumping off places\" with [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]] eventually becoming a favorite after about 1855. [[Fort Kearny]] (est. 1848) is about {{convert|200|mi|km}} from the Missouri River, and the trail and its many offshoots nearly all converged close to Fort Kearny as they followed the [[Platte River]] west. The army-maintained fort was the first chance on the trail to buy emergency supplies, do repairs, get medical aid, or mail a letter. Those on the north side of the Platte could usually wade the shallow river if they needed to visit the fort.\n\n[[Image:Platterivermap.png|275px|right|thumbnail|Map showing the Platte River watershed, including the North Platte and South Platte tributaries]]\n\nThe Platte River and the [[North Platte River]] in the future states of Nebraska and Wyoming typically had many channels and islands and were too shallow, crooked, muddy and unpredictable for travel even by canoe. The Platte as it pursued its braided paths to the Missouri River was \"too thin to plow and too thick to drink\". While unusable for transport, the Platte River and North Platte River valleys provided an easily passable wagon corridor going almost due west with access to water, grass, buffalo, and [[cow dung|buffalo chip]]s for fuel.<ref>Mattes, Merrill J. ''The Great Platte River Road''. Bison Books, 1987. {{ISBN|978-0-8032-8153-0}}</ref> The trails gradually got rougher as it progressed up the North Platte. There were trails on both sides of the muddy rivers. The Platte was about {{convert|1|mi|km}} wide and {{convert|2|to|60|in|cm}} deep. The water was silty and bad tasting but it could be used if no other water was available. Letting it sit in a bucket for an hour or so or stirring in a 1/4 cup of cornmeal allowed most of the silt to settle out. Those traveling south of the Platte crossed the [[South Platte River]] with its muddy and treacherous crossings using one of about three ferries (in dry years it could sometimes be forded without a ferry) before continuing up the North Platte River valley to [[Fort Laramie]] in present-day [[Wyoming]]. After crossing over the South Platte the travelers encountered [[Ash Hollow State Historical Park|Ash Hollow]] with its steep descent down [[Windlass Hill]].\n\nIn the spring in Nebraska and Wyoming the travelers often encountered fierce wind, rain and lightning storms. Until about 1870 travelers encountered hundreds of thousands of [[bison]] migrating through Nebraska on both sides of the Platte River, and most travelers killed several for fresh meat and to build up their supplies of dried [[Jerky (food)|jerky]] for the rest of the journey. The prairie grass in many places was several feet high with only the hat of a traveler on horseback showing as they passed through the prairie grass. In many years the Indians fired much of the dry grass on the prairie every fall so the only trees or bushes available for firewood were on islands in the Platte river. Travelers gathered and ignited dried [[cow dung|buffalo chips]] to cook their meals. These burned fast in a breeze, and it could take two or more bushels of chips to get one meal prepared. Those traveling south of the Platte crossed the [[South Platte]] fork at one of about three ferries (in dry years it could be forded without a ferry) before continuing up the [[North Platte River]] valley into present-day [[Wyoming]] heading to [[Fort Laramie]]. Before 1852 those on the north side of the Platte crossed the North Platte to the south side at Fort Laramie. After 1852 they used Child's Cutoff to stay on the north side to about the present day town of [[Casper, Wyoming|Casper]], Wyoming, where they crossed over to the south side.<ref>Pictures of Oregon Trail in Nebraska [http://www.globalclassroom.org/nebraska.html] Accessed 22 February 2009</ref>\n\nNotable landmarks in Nebraska include [[Courthouse and Jail Rocks]], [[Chimney Rock National Historic Site|Chimney Rock]], [[Scotts Bluff National Monument|Scotts Bluff]], and [[Ash Hollow State Historical Park]].<ref>[http://incolor.inetnebr.com/gnelson/neocta.html Nebraska's branch of Oregon-California trail Association] Accessed 22 February 2009</ref>\n\nToday much of the Oregon Trail follows roughly along [[Interstate 80]] from Wyoming to [[Grand Island, Nebraska|Grand Island]], Nebraska. From there [[U.S. Highway 30]] which follows the Platte River is a better approximate path for those traveling the north side of the Platte. The National Park Service (NPS) gives traveling advice for those who want to follow other branches of the trail.<ref>NPS road guide Oregon Trail Nebraska eastern Wyoming [http://www.nps.gov/oreg/planyourvisit/upload/NE_ATRIG_Web.pdf] accessed 8 February 2010</ref>\n\n===Cholera on the Platte River===\nBecause of the Platte's brackish water, the preferred camping spots were along one of the many fresh water streams draining into the Platte or the occasional fresh water spring found along the way. These preferred camping spots became sources of [[cholera]] in the epidemic years (1849\u20131855) as many thousands of people used the same camping spots with essentially no sewage facilities or adequate sewage treatment. There are many cases cited where a person would be alive and apparently healthy in the morning and dead by nightfall.\n\nFort Laramie marked the end of most [[cholera]] outbreaks. Spread by cholera bacteria in fecal contaminated water, cholera caused massive diarrhea, leading to dehydration and death. In those days its cause and treatment were unknown, and it was often fatal\u2014up to 30% of infected people died. It is believed that the swifter flowing rivers in Wyoming helped prevent the germs from spreading.<ref>\"Treading the Elephant's Tail: Medical Problems on the Overland Trails\". Overland Journal, Volume 6, Number 1, 1988; Peter D. Olch; Pp. 25\u201331; {{ISBN|978-0-674-00881-6}}</ref>\n\nThe cause of cholera, ingesting the ''[[Vibrio cholerae]]'' bacterium from contaminated water,<ref>[http://www.mayoclinic.com/health/cholera/DS00579/DSECTION=causes Causes of Cholera]</ref> and the best treatment for cholera infections were unknown in this era. Literally hundreds of travelers on the combined [[California Trail|California]], Oregon, and [[Mormon Trail]]s succumbed to cholera in the 1849-1855 time period. Most were buried in unmarked graves in Kansas, Nebraska, and Wyoming.\n\n==Colorado==\nA branch of the Oregon Trail crossed the very northeast corner of [[Colorado]] if they followed the [[South Platte River]] to one of its last crossings. This branch of the trail passed through present-day [[Julesburg, Colorado]] before entering Wyoming. Later settlers to much of what became the state of Colorado followed the Platte and South Platte rivers into their settlements there.\n\n==Wyoming==\n{{Main|Emigrant Trail in Wyoming}}\n\nAfter crossing the [[South Platte River]] the Oregon Trail follows the [[North Platte River]] out of Nebraska into Wyoming. [[Fort Laramie National Historic Site|Fort Laramie]], at the junction of the [[Laramie River]] and the North Platte River, was a major stopping point. Fort Laramie was a former fur trading outpost originally named Fort John that was purchased in 1848 by the U.S. Army to protect travelers on the trails.<ref>[http://www.nps.gov/archive/fola/chrono.htm Chronological List of Fort Laramie History]</ref> It was the last army outposts till travelers reached the coast.\n\n[[File:IndependenceRock2.jpg|thumb|right|Independence Rock]]After crossing the South Platte the trail continues up the [[North Platte River]], crossing many small swift flowing creeks. As the North Platte veers to the south the trail crosses the North Platte to the [[Sweetwater River (Wyoming)|Sweetwater River]] valley which heads almost due west. [[Independence Rock (Wyoming)|Independence Rock]] is located on the Sweetwater River. The Sweetwater would have to be crossed up to nine times before the trail crosses over the [[Continental Divide]] at [[South Pass (Wyoming)|South Pass]], Wyoming. From South Pass the trail continues southwest crossing [[Big Sandy River (Wyoming)|Big Sandy Creek]] (about {{convert|10|ft|m}} wide and {{convert|1|ft}} deep) before hitting the [[Green River (Colorado River)|Green River]]. Three to five ferries were in use on the Green during peak travel periods. The swift and treacherous Green River, which eventually empties into the [[Colorado River]], was usually at high water in July and August, and it was a dangerous crossing. After crossing the Green the main trail continues on in an approximate southwest direction until it encounters the [[Blacks Fork]] of the Green River and [[Fort Bridger]], Wyoming. From Fort Bridger the [[Mormon Trail]] continued southwest following the upgraded [[Hastings Cutoff]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scienceviews.com/historical/hastingscutoff.html|title=Hastings Cutoff |publisher=Scienceviews.com |date= |accessdate=2011-03-19}}</ref> through the [[Wasatch Mountains]]. From Fort Bridger, the main trail, comprising several variants, veered northwest over the Bear River Divide and descended to the [[Bear River (Great Salt Lake)|Bear River]] Valley.<ref>http://www.blm.gov/heritage/adventures/research/StatePages/PDFs/Wyoming/wyoming_5.pdf{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The trail turned north following the Bear River past the terminus of the Sublette-Greenwood Cutoff at Smiths Fork<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wyomingtalesandtrails.com/cokeville.html |title=Lincoln County Photos II-Wyoming Tales and Trails |publisher=Wyomingtalesandtrails.com |date=1952-06-30 |accessdate=2011-03-19}}</ref> and on to the Thomas Fork Valley at the present Wyoming-Idaho border.\n\nOver time, two major heavily used cutoffs were established in Wyoming. The '''Sublette-Greenwood Cutoff''' was established in 1844 and cut about {{convert|70|mi|km}} off the main route. It leaves the main trail about {{convert|10|mi|km}} west of South Pass and heads almost due west crossing Big Sandy Creek and then about {{convert|45|mi|km}} of waterless, very dusty desert before reaching the Green River near the present town of [[La Barge, Wyoming|La Barge]]. Ferries here transferred them across the Green River. From there the Sublette-Greenwood Cutoff trail had to cross a mountain range to connect with the main trail near [[Cokeville, Wyoming]] in the Bear River valley.<ref>[http://wyoshpo.state.wy.us/trailsdemo/sublettegreenwood.htm Sublette-Greenwood Cutoff Map]</ref>\n\nThe '''Lander Road''', formally the Fort Kearney, South Pass, and Honey Lake Wagon Road, was established and built by U.S. government contractors in 1858-59.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/additionalestima00unitrich |title=Additional estimate for Fort Kearney, South Pass, and Honey Lake wagon road : letter from the acting Secretary of the Interior, transmitting a communication from Colonel Lander in regard to the Fort Kearney, South Pass and Honey Lake wagon road : United States. Dept. of the Interior : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |publisher=Archive.org |date= |accessdate=2011-03-19}}</ref> It was about {{convert|80|mi|km}} shorter than the main trail through Fort Bridger with good grass, water, firewood and fishing but it was a much steeper and rougher route, crossing three mountain ranges. In 1859, 13,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://history.idaho.gov/Reference%20Series/0631.pdf|title=0631.doc|format=PDF|accessdate=2011-03-19|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204020129/http://www.history.idaho.gov/Reference%20Series/0631.pdf|archivedate=2011-02-04}}</ref> of the 19,000<ref>[[#Unruh|Unruh]]: page 119\u2013120</ref> emigrants traveling to California and Oregon utilized the Lander Road. The traffic in later years is undocumented.\n\nThe Lander Road departs the main trail at Burnt Ranch near South Pass, crosses the Continental Divide north of South Pass and reaches the Green River near the present town of [[Big Piney, Wyoming]]. From there the trail followed Big Piney Creek west before passing over the {{convert|8800|ft|m}} Thompson Pass in the [[Wyoming Range]]. It then crosses over the Smith Fork of the Bear River before ascending and crossing another {{convert|8200|ft|m}} pass on the [[Salt River Range]] of mountains and then descending into [[Star Valley]] Wyoming. It exited the mountains near the present Smith Fork road about {{convert|6|mi|km}} south of the town of [[Smoot, Wyoming]]. The road continued almost due north along the present day Wyoming-Idaho western border through Star Valley. To avoid crossing the [[Salt River (Wyoming)|Salt River]] (which drains into the [[Snake River]]) which runs down Star Valley the Lander Road crossed the river when it was small and stayed west of the Salt River. After traveling down the Salt River valley (Star Valley) about {{convert|20|mi|km}} north the road turned almost due west near the present town of [[Auburn, Wyoming]], and entered into the present state of Idaho along Stump Creek. In Idaho it followed the Stump Creek valley northwest till it crossed the [[Caribou Mountains (Idaho)|Caribou Mountains]] and proceeded past the south end of Grays Lake.<ref>Grays Lake [http://www.seidaho.org/grays_lake.html] accessed 8 February 2010</ref>  The trail then proceeded almost due west to meet the main trail at Fort Hall; alternately, a branch trail headed almost due south to meet the main trail near the present town of [[Soda Springs, Idaho|Soda Springs]], Idaho.<ref>[http://wyoshpo.state.wy.us/trailsdemo/landerroad.htm Lander Road Cutoff Map]</ref><ref>\"Emigrant Trails of Southern Idaho\"; Bureau of Land Management & Idaho State Historical Society;1993; pp 117\u2013125 ASIN: B000KE2KTU</ref>\n\nNumerous landmarks are located along the trail in Wyoming including [[Independence Rock (Wyoming)|Independence Rock]], [[Ayres Natural Bridge]] and [[Register Cliff]].\n\n==Utah==\nIn 1847, Brigham Young and the [[Mormon Trail|Mormon]] pioneers departed from the Oregon Trail at [[Fort Bridger]] in Wyoming and followed (and much improved) the rough trail originally recommended by [[Lansford Hastings]] to the [[Donner Party]] in 1846 through the [[Wasatch Mountains]] into [[Utah]].<ref>Salt Lake Cutoff [http://www.americanwest.com/trails/pages/mormtrl.htm] accessdate=17 September 2009</ref> After getting into Utah they immediately started setting up irrigated farms and cities\u2014including [[Salt Lake City, Utah]]. In 1848, the [[Salt Lake Cutoff]] was established by Sam Hensley,<ref name=\"hensley\">{{cite news|url=http://historytogo.utah.gov/salt_lake_tribune/in_another_time/060594.html|title=It's Sam Hensley-Not Hansel-Who Discovered Cutoff|last=Schindler|first=Hal|date=June 5, 1994|newspaper=The Salt Lake Tribune|pages=D1|accessdate=2009-09-17}}</ref>  and returning members of the [[Mormon Battalion]] providing a path north of the [[Great Salt Lake]] from Salt Lake City back to the [[California Trail|California]] and Oregon Trails. This cutoff rejoined the Oregon and California Trails near the [[City of Rocks National Reserve|City of Rocks]] near the Utah-Idaho border and could be used by both California and Oregon bound travelers. Located about half way on both the [[California Trail|California]] and Oregon Trails many thousands of later travelers used Salt Lake City and other Utah cities as an intermediate stop for selling or trading excess goods or tired livestock for fresh livestock, repairs, supplies or fresh vegetables. The Mormons looked on these travelers as a welcome bonanza as setting up new communities from scratch required nearly everything the travelers could afford to part with. The overall distance to California or Oregon was very close to the same whether one \"detoured\" to Salt Lake City or not. For their own use and to encourage California and Oregon bound travelers the Mormons improved the Mormon Trail from Fort Bridger and the Salt Lake Cutoff trail. To raise much needed money and facilitate travel on the Salt Lake Cutoff they set up several ferries across the [[Weber River|Weber]], [[Bear River (Great Salt Lake)|Bear]] and [[Malad River (Idaho-Utah)|Malad]] rivers which were used mostly by Oregon or California bound travelers.\n\n==Idaho==\nThe main Oregon and California Trail went almost due north from Fort Bridger to the Little Muddy Creek where it passed over the Bear River Mountains to the [[Bear River (Great Salt Lake)|Bear River]] valley which it followed northwest into the Thomas Fork area, where the trail crossed over the present day Wyoming line into Idaho. In the Eastern Sheep Creek Hills in the Thomas Fork valley the emigrants encountered Big Hill. Big Hill was a detour caused by an impassable (then) cut the Bear River made through the mountains and had a tough ascent often requiring doubling up of teams and a very steep and dangerous descent.<ref>Big Hill Idaho (OCTA Idaho) [http://www.idahohistory.net/OTbighill.html] accessed 5 February 2009</ref> (Much later, [[U.S. Highway 30]], using modern explosives and equipment, was built through this cut). In 1852 Eliza Ann McAuley found and with help developed the McAuley Cutoff which bypassed much of the difficult climb and descent of Big Hill. About {{convert|5|mi|km}} on they passed present day [[Montpelier, Idaho|Montpelier]], Idaho which is now the site of The National Oregon-California Trail Center.<ref>The National Oregon-California Trail Center [http://www.oregontrailcenter.org/] Accessed 25 February 2009</ref> The trail follows the Bear River northwest to present day [[Soda Springs, Idaho]]. The soda springs here were a favorite attraction of the pioneers who marveled at the hot carbonated water and chugging \"steamboat\" springs. Many stopped and did their laundry in the hot water as there was usually plenty of good grass and fresh water available.<ref>Soda Springs quotes Idaho State Historical Society [http://www.idahohistory.net/Reference%20Series/0182.pdf] Accessed 25 February 2009</ref> Just west of Soda Springs the Bear River turns southwest as it heads for [[The Great Salt Lake]] and the main trail turns northwest to follow the [[Portneuf River (Idaho)|Portneuf River]] valley to [[Fort Hall]] Idaho. Fort Hall was an old fur trading post located on the [[Snake River]]. It was established in 1832 by [[Nathaniel Jarvis Wyeth]] and company and later sold in 1837 to the British [[Hudson's Bay Company]]. At Fort Hall nearly all travelers were given some aid and supplies if they were available and needed. Mosquitoes were constant pests and travelers often mention that their animals were covered with blood from the bites. The route from Fort Bridger to Fort Hall is about {{convert|210|mi|km}}, taking nine to twelve days.\n\nAt Soda Springs was one branch of [[Emigrant Trail in Wyoming#Lander Road|Lander Road]] (established and built with government contractors in 1858) which had gone west from near South Pass, over the Salt River Mountains and down Star Valley before turning west near present-day [[Auburn, Wyoming|Auburn]], Wyoming and entering Idaho. From there it proceeded northwest into Idaho up Stump Creek canyon for about {{convert|10|mi|km|spell=in}}. One branch turned almost 90 degrees and proceeded southwest to Soda Springs. Another branch headed almost due west past Gray\u2019s Lake to rejoin the main trail about {{convert|10|mi|km}} west of Fort Hall.\n\nOn the main trail about {{convert|5|mi|km}} west of Soda Springs '''Hudspeth's Cutoff''' (established 1849 and used mostly by California trail users) took off from the main trail heading almost due west, bypassing Fort Hall. It rejoined the [[California Trail]] at Cassia Creek near the [[City of Rocks National Reserve|City of Rocks]].<ref>Hudspeth cutoff map (OCTA-Idaho) [http://www.idahoocta.org/Idaho_Trail_Sites.html] Accessed 5 February 2009</ref> Hudspeth's Cutoff had five mountain ranges to cross and took about the same amount of time as the main route to Fort Hall but many took it thinking it was shorter. Its main advantage was that it helped spread out the traffic during peak periods, making more grass available.<ref>For an Oregon-California trail map up to the junction in Idaho see ''Oregon National Historic Trail Map NPS [http://www.nps.gov/PWR/customcf/apps/maps/showmap.cfm?alphacode=oreg&parkname=Oregon%20National%20Historic%20Trail]. Accessed 28 January 2009.</ref>\n\nWest of Fort Hall the main trail traveled about {{convert|40|mi|km}} on the south side of the Snake River southwest past American Falls, [[Massacre Rocks]], Register Rock and Coldwater Hill near present-day [[Pocatello, Idaho|Pocatello]], Idaho. Near the junction of the [[Raft River]] and the Snake River, the California Trail diverged from the Oregon Trail at another Parting of the Ways junction. Travellers left the Snake River and followed Raft River about {{convert|65|mi|km}} southwest past present day [[Almo, Idaho|Almo]], Idaho. This trail then passed through the [[City of Rocks National Reserve|City of Rocks]] and over Granite Pass where it went southwest along Goose Creek, Little Goose Creek, and Rock Spring Creek. It went about {{convert|95|mi|km}} through [[Thousand Springs Scenic Byway|Thousand Springs Valley]], West Brush Creek, and Willow Creek, before arriving at the [[Humboldt River]] in northeastern Nevada near present-day [[Wells, Nevada|Wells]].<ref>[http://www.elkorose.com/osino/catrailsmap_smaller.jpg Northern Nevada and Utah, Southern Idaho Trail Map] Accessed 9 February 2009</ref> The California Trail proceeded west down the Humboldt before reaching and crossing the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevadas]].\n\nThere are only a few places where the Snake River has not buried itself deep in a canyon. There are few spots where the river slowed down enough to make a crossing possible. Two of these fords were near Fort Hall, where travelers on the Oregon Trail North Side Alternate (established about 1852) and Goodale\u2019s Cutoff (established 1862) crossed the Snake to travel on the north side. Nathaniel Wyeth, the original founder of Fort Hall in 1834, writes in his diary that they found a ford across the Snake River {{convert|4|mi|km}} southwest of where he founded Fort Hall. Another possible crossing was a few miles upstream of Salmon Falls where some intrepid travelers floated their wagons and swam their stock across to join the north side trail. Some lost their wagons and teams over the falls.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://history.idaho.gov/Reference%20Series/0752.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721042929/http://history.idaho.gov/Reference%20Series/0752.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-21 }}</ref> The trails on the north side joined the trail from Three Island Crossing about {{convert|17|mi|km}} west of Glenns Ferry on the north side of the Snake River.<ref>Oregon Trail North Side Alternate {{cite web |url=http://www.blm.gov/pgdata/etc/medialib/blm/id/publications.Par.50091.File.dat/OCTAbooklet.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-03-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325011951/http://www.blm.gov/pgdata/etc/medialib/blm/id/publications.Par.50091.File.dat/OCTAbooklet.pdf |archivedate=2009-03-25 }} Accessed 25 February 2009</ref> (For map of North Side Alternate see:<ref>[http://www.nps.gov/archive/ciro/hrs/images/fig7.jpg] Accessed 25 February 2009</ref>)\n\n[[Goodale's Cutoff]], established in 1862 on the north side of the Snake River, formed a spur of the Oregon Trail. This cutoff had been used as a pack trail by Indians and fur traders, and emigrant wagons traversed parts of the eastern section as early as 1852. After crossing the Snake River the {{convert|230|mi|km}} cutoff headed north from Fort Hall toward Big Southern Butte following the [[Lost River (Idaho)|Lost River]] part of the way. It passed near the present-day town of [[Arco, Idaho|Arco]], Idaho and wound through the northern part of [[Craters of the Moon National Monument]]. From there it went southwest to [[Camas Prairie]] and ended at [[Fort Boise#Old Fort Boise (1834&ndash;54)|Old Fort Boise]] on the [[Boise River]]. This journey typically took two to three weeks and was noted for its very rough, lava restricted roads and extremely dry climate, which tended to dry the wooden wheels on the wagons, which caused the iron rims to fall off the wheels. Loss of wheels caused many wagons to be abandoned along the route. It rejoined the main trail east of Boise. Goodale's Cutoff is visible at many points along [[U.S. Highway 20]], [[U.S. Highway 26]] and  [[U.S. Highway 93]] between Craters of the Moon National Monument and [[Carey, Idaho|Carey]], Idaho.<ref>Goodale\u2019s Cutoff NPS [http://www.nps.gov/archive/crmo/goodale.htm] Accessed 22 February 2009</ref>\n\n[[Image:Shoshone Falls, Snake River, Idaho ppmsca.10072u.jpg|thumb|right|300px|View across top of Shoshone Falls, Snake River, Idaho ([[Timothy H. O'Sullivan]], 1874)]]\nFrom the present site of [[Pocatello, Idaho|Pocatello]] the trail proceeded almost due west on the south side of the Snake River for about {{convert|180|mi|km}}. On this route they passed [[Cauldron Linn (Idaho)|Cauldron Linn]] rapids, [[Shoshone Falls]], two falls near the present city of [[Twin Falls, Idaho|Twin Falls]], Idaho, and Upper Salmon Falls on the Snake River. At Salmon Falls there were often a hundred or more Indians fishing who would trade for their salmon\u2014a welcome treat. The trail continued west to [[Three Island Crossing State Park|Three Island Crossing]] (near present-day [[Glenns Ferry, Idaho|Glenns Ferry]], Idaho).<ref>Three Island Crossing photos [http://www.nativeamerican.co.uk/oregonroute15.html] Accessed 22 February 2009</ref><ref>Three Island Crossing quotes {{cite web |url=http://www.wvi.com/users/TIC/tic.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-02-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206235002/http://www.wvi.com/users/TIC/tic.htm |archivedate=2009-02-06 }} Accessed 22 February 2009</ref> Here most emigrants used the divisions of the river caused by three islands to cross the difficult and swift Snake River by ferry or by driving or sometimes floating their wagons and swimming their teams across. The crossings were doubly treacherous because there were often hidden holes in the river bottom which could overturn the wagon or ensnarl the team, sometimes with fatal consequences. Before ferries were established there were several drownings here nearly every year.<ref>Three Mile Island Crossing Park [http://www.stateparks.com/three_island_crossing.html] Accessed 22 February 2009</ref>\n\nThe north side of the Snake had better water and grass than the south. The trail from Three Island Crossing to [[Fort Boise#Old Fort Boise (1834&ndash;54)|Old Fort Boise]] was about 130 miles long. The usually lush Boise River valley was a welcome relief. The next crossing of the Snake River was near Old Fort Boise. This last crossing of the Snake could be done on bull boats while swimming the stock across. Others would chain a large string of wagons and teams together. The theory was that the front teams, usually oxen, would get out of water first and with good footing help pull the whole string of wagons and teams across. How well this worked in practice is not stated. Often young Indian boys were hired to drive and ride the stock across the river\u2014they knew how to swim, unlike many pioneers. Today's Idaho [[Interstate 84 (west)|Interstate 84]] roughly follows the Oregon Trail till it leaves the Snake River near [[Burley, Idaho|Burley]], Idaho. From there [[Interstate 86 (west)|Interstate 86]] to Pocatello roughly approximates the trail. [[Highway 30]] roughly follows the path of the Oregon Trail from there to [[Montpelier, Idaho|Montpelier]], Idaho.\n\nStarting in about 1848 the South Alternate of Oregon Trail (also called the Snake River Cutoff) was developed as a spur off the main trail. It bypassed the Three Island Crossing and continued traveling down the south side of the Snake River. It rejoined the trail near present-day [[Ontario, Oregon|Ontario]], Oregon. It hugged the southern edge of the Snake River canyon and was a much rougher trail with poorer water and grass, requiring occasional steep descents and ascents with the animals down into the Snake River canyon to get water. Travellers on this route avoided two dangerous crossings of the Snake River.<ref>National Trail Map [http://www.fs.fed.us/recreation/programs/trails/natltrails.pdf] accessed 22 February 2009</ref> Today's Idaho State Route 78 roughly follows the path of the South Alternate route of the Oregon Trail.\n\nIn 1869 the Central Pacific established [[Kelton, Utah|Kelton]], Utah as a railhead and the terminus of the western mail was moved from Salt Lake City. The Kelton Road became important as a communication and transportation road to the Boise Basin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idahohistory.net/Reference%20Series/0074.pdf |title=IdahoHistory.net |publisher=IdahoHistory.net |date=2010-07-07 |accessdate=2011-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==Oregon==\nOnce across the [[Snake River]] ford near [[Fort Boise#Old Fort Boise (1834&ndash;54)|Old Fort Boise]] the weary travelers traveled across what would become the state of [[Oregon]]. The trail then went to the [[Malheur River]] and then past [[Farewell Bend State Recreation Area|Farewell Bend]] on the Snake River, up the [[Burnt River (Oregon)|Burnt River]] canyon and northwest to the [[La Grande, Oregon|La Grande]] [[Grande Ronde Valley|valley]] before coming to the [[Blue Mountains (Oregon)|Blue Mountains]]. In 1843 settlers cut a wagon road over these mountains making them passable for the first time to wagons. The trail went to the [[Whitman Mission]] near [[Fort Nez Perce]] in [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]] until 1847 when the Whitmans were killed by Native Americans. At Fort Nez Perce some built rafts or hired boats and started down the Columbia; others continued west in their wagons until they reached [[The Dalles, Oregon|The Dalles]]. After 1847 the trail bypassed the closed mission and headed almost due west to present day [[Pendleton, Oregon|Pendleton]], Oregon, crossing the [[Umatilla River]], [[John Day River]], and [[Deschutes River (Oregon)|Deschutes River]] before arriving at The Dalles. [[Interstate 84 (west)|Interstate 84]] in Oregon roughly follows the original Oregon Trail from Idaho to The Dalles.\n\nArriving at the Columbia at The Dalles and stopped by the [[Cascade Mountains]] and [[Mount Hood]], some gave up their wagons or disassembled them and put them on boats or rafts for a trip down the [[Columbia River]]. Once they transited the Cascade's [[Columbia River Gorge]] with its multiple rapids and treacherous winds they would have to make the {{convert|1.6|mi|km}} portage around the [[Cascade Rapids]] before coming out near the [[Willamette River]] where [[Oregon City, Oregon|Oregon City]], Oregon was located. The pioneer's livestock could be driven around Mount Hood on the narrow, crooked and rough [[Lolo Pass (Oregon)|Lolo Pass]].\n\nSeveral Oregon Trail branches and route variations led to the [[Willamette Valley]]. The most popular was the [[Barlow Road]], which was carved through the forest around Mount Hood from The Dalles in 1846 as a toll road at $5.00 per wagon and 10 cents per head of livestock. It was rough and steep with poor grass but still cheaper and safer than floating goods, wagons and family down the dangerous Columbia River.\n\nIn Central Oregon there was the [[Santiam Wagon Road]] (established 1861), which roughly parallels Oregon Highway 20 to the Willamette Valley. The [[Applegate Trail]] (established 1846) cutting off the [[California Trail]] from the [[Humboldt River]] in Nevada crossed part of California before cutting north to the south end of the Willamette Valley. Originally [[U.S. Route 99]] (later renamed to [[Oregon Route 99]]) and [[Interstate 5]] through Oregon roughly follow the original Applegate Trail.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|22em}}\n\n[[Category:Oregon Trail]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Oregontrail 1907.jpg|thumb|right|400px|Map from ''The Vikings team, or the Old Oregon Trail 1852\u20131906'', by [[Ezra Meeker]]]]\n[[Image:South pass marker2.jpg|thumb|right|Oregon Trail pioneer [[Ezra Meeker]] erected this boulder near [[Pacific Creek (Sweetwater County, Wyoming)|Pacific Springs]] on Wyoming's [[South Pass (Wyoming)|South Pass]] in 1906.<ref>''Ventures and Adventures of Ezra Meeker: Or, Sixty Years of Frontier Life'' by Ezra Meeker. Rainer Printing Company 1908. ASIN: B000861WA8</ref>]]\n\nThe historic {{convert|2170|mi|adj=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blm.gov/or/oregontrail/history-basics.php|title=Basic Facts About the Oregon Trail|work=U.S. DEPARTMENT OF THE INTERIOR - BUREAU OF LAND MANAGEMENT|date=n.d.|accessdate=May 12, 2016}}</ref> '''[[Oregon Trail]]''' connected various towns along the [[Missouri River]] to Oregon's [[Willamette Valley]]. It was used during the 19th century by [[Great Plains]] pioneers who were seeking fertile land in the West and North.\n\nAs the trail developed it became marked by numerous cutoffs and shortcuts from Missouri to Oregon. The basic route follows river valleys as grass and water were absolutely necessary.\n\nWhile the first few parties organized and departed from Elm Grove, the Oregon Trail's primary starting point was [[Independence, Missouri]], or [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]] (Missouri), on the Missouri River. Later, several feeder trails led across [[Kansas]], and some towns became starting points, including [[Weston, Missouri]], [[Fort Leavenworth, Kansas]], [[Atchison, Kansas]], [[St. Joseph, Missouri]], and [[Omaha, Nebraska]].\n\nThe Oregon Trail's nominal termination point was [[Oregon City, Oregon|Oregon City]], at the time the proposed capital of the [[Oregon Territory]]. However, many settlers branched off or stopped short of this goal and settled at convenient or promising locations along the trail. Commerce with pioneers going further west helped establish these early settlements and launched local economies critical to their prosperity.\n\nAt dangerous or difficult river crossings, ferries or toll bridges were set up and bad places on the trail were either repaired or bypassed. Several toll roads were constructed. Gradually the trail became easier with the average trip (as recorded in numerous diaries) dropping from about 160 days in 1849 to 140 days 10 years later.\n\nNumerous other trails followed the Oregon Trail for much of its length, including the [[Mormon Trail]] from [[Illinois]] to [[Utah]]; the [[California Trail]] to the gold fields of [[California]]; and the [[Bozeman Trail]] to [[Montana]]. Because it was more a network of trails than a single trail there were numerous variations, with other trails eventually established on both sides of the [[Platte River|Platte]], [[North Platte River|North Platte]], [[Snake River|Snake]], and [[Columbia River|Columbia]] rivers. With literally thousands of people and thousands of livestock traveling in a fairly small time slot the travelers had to spread out to find clean water, wood, good campsites, and grass. The dust kicked up by the many travelers was a constant complaint, and where the terrain would allow it there may be between 20 and 50 wagons traveling abreast.\n\nRemnants of the trail in Kansas, Nebraska, Wyoming, Idaho, and Oregon have been listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]], and the entire trail is a designated [[National Historic Trail]] (listed as the Oregon National Historic Trail).\n\n==Missouri==\nInitially, the main \"jumping off point\" was the common head of the [[Santa Fe Trail]] and Oregon Trail\u2014[[Independence, Missouri]]/[[Kansas City, Kansas]]. Travelers starting in Independence had to ferry across the Missouri River. After following the Santa Fe trail to near present-day [[Topeka, Kansas]], they ferried across the [[Kansas River]] to start the trek across [[Kansas]] and points west. Another busy \"jumping off point\" was [[St. Joseph, Missouri]]\u2014established in 1843.<ref name=\"travel\">{{cite web|url=http://north-america.traveltoworld.com/north-america-travel-guide/5317/saint-peters-missouri/|title=Saint Peters: Missouri|accessdate=August 30, 2007|publisher=North America Travel Guide|author=North America Travel Guide|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071006123625/http://north-america.traveltoworld.com/north-america-travel-guide/5317/saint-peters-missouri/|archive-date=October 6, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In its early days, St. Joseph was a bustling outpost and rough frontier town, serving as one of the last supply points before heading over the Missouri River to the frontier. St. Joseph had good steamboat connections to [[St. Louis, Missouri]], and other ports on the combined [[Ohio River|Ohio]], [[Missouri River|Missouri]] and [[Mississippi River]] systems. During the busy season there were several ferry boats and steamboats available to transport travelers to the Kansas shore where they started their travels westward. Before the [[Union Pacific Railroad]] was started in 1865, St. Joseph was the westernmost point in the United States accessible by rail. Other towns used as supply points in Missouri included Old Franklin,<ref>Old Franklin Missouri [http://www.santafetrailresearch.com/spacepix/franklin-mo.html] accessed 13 January 2010</ref> [[Arrow Rock, Missouri|Arrow Rock]], and [[Fort Osage]].\n\n==Iowa==\nIn 1803 President [[Thomas Jefferson]] purchased from [[France]] the [[Louisiana Purchase]] for fifteen million dollars (equivalent to about $230 million today) which included all the land drained by the Missouri River and roughly doubled the size of U.S. territory. The future states of [[Iowa]] and [[Missouri]], located west of the [[Mississippi River]] and east of the Missouri River, were part of this purchase. The [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]] stopped several times in the future state of Iowa on their 1805-1806 expedition to the west coast. A disputed 1804 treaty between [[Quashquame]] and [[William Henry Harrison]] (future ninth President of the U.S.) that surrendered much of the future state of [[Illinois]] to the U.S. enraged many [[Sauk people|Sauk]] (Sac) Indians and led to the 1832 [[Black Hawk War]]. As punishment for the uprising, and as part of a larger settlement strategy, treaties were subsequently designed to remove all Indians from Iowa Territory. Some settlers started drifting into Iowa in 1833. President [[Martin Van Buren]] on July 4, 1838, signed laws establishing the Territory of Iowa. Iowa was located opposite the junction of the [[Platte River|Platte]] and Missouri rivers and was used by some of the [[Rocky Mountain Rendezvous|Fur trapper rendezvous]] traders as a starting point for their supply expeditions. In 1846 the [[Mormons]], expelled from [[Nauvoo, Illinois]], traversed Iowa (on part of the [[Mormon Trail]]) and settled temporarily in significant numbers on the Missouri River in Iowa and the future state of [[Nebraska]] at their [[Winter Quarters (North Omaha, Nebraska)|Winter Quarters]] near the future city of [[Omaha, Nebraska]]. (See: Missouri River settlements (1846\u20131854)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://winterquarters.byu.edu/pages/settlements.htm |title=Winter Quarters Project |publisher=Winterquarters.byu.edu |accessdate=2011-03-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719155702/http://winterquarters.byu.edu/pages/settlements.htm |archivedate=2011-07-19 }}</ref>) The Mormons established about 50 temporary towns, including the town of Kanesville (renamed [[Council Bluffs, Iowa]] in 1852) on the east bank of the Missouri River opposite the mouth of the Platte. For those travelers to Oregon, California, and Utah who were bringing their teams to the Platte River junction, Kanesville and other towns become major \"jumping off places\" and supply points. In 1847 the Mormons established three ferries across the Missouri River, and others established even more ferries for the spring start on the trail. In the 1850 census there were about 8,000 mostly Mormons tabulated in the large [[Pottawattamie County, Iowa]] District 21. (The original Pottawattamie County was subsequently made into five counties and parts of several more.)  By 1854 most of the Mormon towns, farms and villages were largely taken over by non-Mormons as they abandoned them or sold them for not much and continued their migration to Utah. After 1846 the towns of Council Bluffs, Iowa, [[Omaha, Nebraska]] (est. 1852) and other Missouri River towns became major supply points and \"jumping off places\" for travelers on the [[Mormon Trail|Mormon]], [[California Trail|California]], Oregon and other trails west.\n\n==Kansas==\n[[Image:Ks rivers.png|thumb|Map of principal rivers in Kansas]]\n\nStarting initially in [[Independence, Missouri|Independence]] or [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]] in Missouri, the initial trail followed the [[Santa Fe Trail]] into Kansas south of the [[Wakarusa River]]. After crossing [[Mount Oread]] at [[Lawrence, Kansas|Lawrence]], the trail crossed the [[Kansas River]] by ferry or boats near [[Topeka, Kansas|Topeka]], and crossed the Wakarusa and Vermillion rivers by ferries. After the Vermillion River the trail angles northwest to [[Nebraska]] paralleling the [[Little Blue River (Kansas/Nebraska)|Little Blue River]] until reaching the south side of the [[Platte River]]. Travel by wagon over the gently rolling Kansas countryside was usually unimpeded except where streams had cut steep banks. There a passage could be made with a lot of shovel work to cut down the banks or the travelers could find an already established crossing.\n\n==Nebraska==\n[[File:Chimney Rock NE.jpg|thumb|left|[[Chimney Rock National Historic Site|Chimney Rock, Nebraska]]]]\nThose emigrants on the eastern side of the Missouri River in [[Missouri]] or [[Iowa]] used ferries and steamboats (fitted out for ferry duty) to cross into towns in [[Nebraska]]. Several towns in Nebraska were used as \"jumping off places\" with [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]] eventually becoming a favorite after about 1855. [[Fort Kearny]] (est. 1848) is about {{convert|200|mi|km}} from the Missouri River, and the trail and its many offshoots nearly all converged close to Fort Kearny as they followed the [[Platte River]] west. The army-maintained fort was the first chance on the trail to buy emergency supplies, do repairs, get medical aid, or mail a letter. Those on the north side of the Platte could usually wade the shallow river if they needed to visit the fort.\n\n[[Image:Platterivermap.png|275px|right|thumbnail|Map showing the Platte River watershed, including the North Platte and South Platte tributaries]]\n\nThe Platte River and the [[North Platte River]] in the future states of Nebraska and Wyoming typically had many channels and islands and were too shallow, crooked, muddy and unpredictable for travel even by canoe. The Platte as it pursued its braided paths to the Missouri River was \"too thin to plow and too thick to drink\". While unusable for transport, the Platte River and North Platte River valleys provided an easily passable wagon corridor going almost due west with access to water, grass, buffalo, and [[cow dung|buffalo chip]]s for fuel.<ref>Mattes, Merrill J. ''The Great Platte River Road''. Bison Books, 1987. {{ISBN|978-0-8032-8153-0}}</ref> The trails gradually got rougher as it progressed up the North Platte. There were trails on both sides of the muddy rivers. The Platte was about {{convert|1|mi|km}} wide and {{convert|2|to|60|in|cm}} deep. The water was silty and bad tasting but it could be used if no other water was available. Letting it sit in a bucket for an hour or so or stirring in a 1/4 cup of cornmeal allowed most of the silt to settle out. Those traveling south of the Platte crossed the [[South Platte River]] with its muddy and treacherous crossings using one of about three ferries (in dry years it could sometimes be forded without a ferry) before continuing up the North Platte River valley to [[Fort Laramie]] in present-day [[Wyoming]]. After crossing over the South Platte the travelers encountered [[Ash Hollow State Historical Park|Ash Hollow]] with its steep descent down [[Windlass Hill]].\n\nIn the spring in Nebraska and Wyoming the travelers often encountered fierce wind, rain and lightning storms. Until about 1870 travelers encountered hundreds of thousands of [[bison]] migrating through Nebraska on both sides of the Platte River, and most travelers killed several for fresh meat and to build up their supplies of dried [[Jerky (food)|jerky]] for the rest of the journey. The prairie grass in many places was several feet high with only the hat of a traveler on horseback showing as they passed through the prairie grass. In many years the Indians fired much of the dry grass on the prairie every fall so the only trees or bushes available for firewood were on islands in the Platte river. Travelers gathered and ignited dried [[cow dung|buffalo chips]] to cook their meals. These burned fast in a breeze, and it could take two or more bushels of chips to get one meal prepared. Those traveling south of the Platte crossed the [[South Platte]] fork at one of about three ferries (in dry years it could be forded without a ferry) before continuing up the [[North Platte River]] valley into present-day [[Wyoming]] heading to [[Fort Laramie]]. Before 1852 those on the north side of the Platte crossed the North Platte to the south side at Fort Laramie. After 1852 they used Child's Cutoff to stay on the north side to about the present day town of [[Casper, Wyoming|Casper]], Wyoming, where they crossed over to the south side.<ref>Pictures of Oregon Trail in Nebraska [http://www.globalclassroom.org/nebraska.html] Accessed 22 February 2009</ref>\n\nNotable landmarks in Nebraska include [[Courthouse and Jail Rocks]], [[Chimney Rock National Historic Site|Chimney Rock]], [[Scotts Bluff National Monument|Scotts Bluff]], and [[Ash Hollow State Historical Park]].<ref>[http://incolor.inetnebr.com/gnelson/neocta.html Nebraska's branch of Oregon-California trail Association] Accessed 22 February 2009</ref>\n\nToday much of the Oregon Trail follows roughly along [[Interstate 80]] from Wyoming to [[Grand Island, Nebraska|Grand Island]], Nebraska. From there [[U.S. Highway 30]] which follows the Platte River is a better approximate path for those traveling the north side of the Platte. The National Park Service (NPS) gives traveling advice for those who want to follow other branches of the trail.<ref>NPS road guide Oregon Trail Nebraska eastern Wyoming [http://www.nps.gov/oreg/planyourvisit/upload/NE_ATRIG_Web.pdf] accessed 8 February 2010</ref>\n\n===Cholera on the Platte River===\nBecause of the Platte's brackish water, the preferred camping spots were along one of the many fresh water streams draining into the Platte or the occasional fresh water spring found along the way. These preferred camping spots became sources of [[cholera]] in the epidemic years (1849\u20131855) as many thousands of people used the same camping spots with essentially no sewage facilities or adequate sewage treatment. There are many cases cited where a person would be alive and apparently healthy in the morning and dead by nightfall.\n\nFort Laramie marked the end of most [[cholera]] outbreaks. Spread by cholera bacteria in fecal contaminated water, cholera caused massive diarrhea, leading to dehydration and death. In those days its cause and treatment were unknown, and it was often fatal\u2014up to 30% of infected people died. It is believed that the swifter flowing rivers in Wyoming helped prevent the germs from spreading.<ref>\"Treading the Elephant's Tail: Medical Problems on the Overland Trails\". Overland Journal, Volume 6, Number 1, 1988; Peter D. Olch; Pp. 25\u201331; {{ISBN|978-0-674-00881-6}}</ref>\n\nThe cause of cholera, ingesting the ''[[Vibrio cholerae]]'' bacterium from contaminated water,<ref>[http://www.mayoclinic.com/health/cholera/DS00579/DSECTION=causes Causes of Cholera]</ref> and the best treatment for cholera infections were unknown in this era. Literally hundreds of travelers on the combined [[California Trail|California]], Oregon, and [[Mormon Trail]]s succumbed to cholera in the 1849-1855 time period. Most were buried in unmarked graves in Kansas, Nebraska, and Wyoming.\n\n==Colorado==\nA branch of the Oregon Trail crossed the very northeast corner of [[Colorado]] if they followed the [[South Platte River]] to one of its last crossings. This branch of the trail passed through present-day [[Julesburg, Colorado]] before entering Wyoming. Later settlers to much of what became the state of Colorado followed the Platte and South Platte rivers into their settlements there.\n\n==Wyoming==\n{{Main|Emigrant Trail in Wyoming}}\n\nAfter crossing the [[South Platte River]] the Oregon Trail follows the [[North Platte River]] out of Nebraska into Wyoming. [[Fort Laramie National Historic Site|Fort Laramie]], at the junction of the [[Laramie River]] and the North Platte River, was a major stopping point. Fort Laramie was a former fur trading outpost originally named Fort John that was purchased in 1848 by the U.S. Army to protect travelers on the trails.<ref>[http://www.nps.gov/archive/fola/chrono.htm Chronological List of Fort Laramie History]</ref> It was the last army outposts till travelers reached the coast.\n\n[[File:IndependenceRock2.jpg|thumb|right|Independence Rock]]After crossing the South Platte the trail continues up the [[North Platte River]], crossing many small swift flowing creeks. As the North Platte veers to the south the trail crosses the North Platte to the [[Sweetwater River (Wyoming)|Sweetwater River]] valley which heads almost due west. [[Independence Rock (Wyoming)|Independence Rock]] is located on the Sweetwater River. The Sweetwater would have to be crossed up to nine times before the trail crosses over the [[Continental Divide]] at [[South Pass (Wyoming)|South Pass]], Wyoming. From South Pass the trail continues southwest crossing [[Big Sandy River (Wyoming)|Big Sandy Creek]] (about {{convert|10|ft|m}} wide and {{convert|1|ft}} deep) before hitting the [[Green River (Colorado River)|Green River]]. Three to five ferries were in use on the Green during peak travel periods. The swift and treacherous Green River, which eventually empties into the [[Colorado River]], was usually at high water in July and August, and it was a dangerous crossing. After crossing the Green the main trail continues on in an approximate southwest direction until it encounters the [[Blacks Fork]] of the Green River and [[Fort Bridger]], Wyoming. From Fort Bridger the [[Mormon Trail]] continued southwest following the upgraded [[Hastings Cutoff]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scienceviews.com/historical/hastingscutoff.html|title=Hastings Cutoff |publisher=Scienceviews.com |date= |accessdate=2011-03-19}}</ref> through the [[Wasatch Mountains]]. From Fort Bridger, the main trail, comprising several variants, veered northwest over the Bear River Divide and descended to the [[Bear River (Great Salt Lake)|Bear River]] Valley.<ref>http://www.blm.gov/heritage/adventures/research/StatePages/PDFs/Wyoming/wyoming_5.pdf{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The trail turned north following the Bear River past the terminus of the Sublette-Greenwood Cutoff at Smiths Fork<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wyomingtalesandtrails.com/cokeville.html |title=Lincoln County Photos II-Wyoming Tales and Trails |publisher=Wyomingtalesandtrails.com |date=1952-06-30 |accessdate=2011-03-19}}</ref> and on to the Thomas Fork Valley at the present Wyoming-Idaho border.\n\nOver time, two major heavily used cutoffs were established in Wyoming. The '''Sublette-Greenwood Cutoff''' was established in 1844 and cut about {{convert|70|mi|km}} off the main route. It leaves the main trail about {{convert|10|mi|km}} west of South Pass and heads almost due west crossing Big Sandy Creek and then about {{convert|45|mi|km}} of waterless, very dusty desert before reaching the Green River near the present town of [[La Barge, Wyoming|La Barge]]. Ferries here transferred them across the Green River. From there the Sublette-Greenwood Cutoff trail had to cross a mountain range to connect with the main trail near [[Cokeville, Wyoming]] in the Bear River valley.<ref>[http://wyoshpo.state.wy.us/trailsdemo/sublettegreenwood.htm Sublette-Greenwood Cutoff Map]</ref>\n\nThe '''Lander Road''', formally the Fort Kearney, South Pass, and Honey Lake Wagon Road, was established and built by U.S. government contractors in 1858-59.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/additionalestima00unitrich |title=Additional estimate for Fort Kearney, South Pass, and Honey Lake wagon road : letter from the acting Secretary of the Interior, transmitting a communication from Colonel Lander in regard to the Fort Kearney, South Pass and Honey Lake wagon road : United States. Dept. of the Interior : Free Download & Streaming : Internet Archive |publisher=Archive.org |date= |accessdate=2011-03-19}}</ref> It was about {{convert|80|mi|km}} shorter than the main trail through Fort Bridger with good grass, water, firewood and fishing but it was a much steeper and rougher route, crossing three mountain ranges. In 1859, 13,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://history.idaho.gov/Reference%20Series/0631.pdf|title=0631.doc|format=PDF|accessdate=2011-03-19|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204020129/http://www.history.idaho.gov/Reference%20Series/0631.pdf|archivedate=2011-02-04}}</ref> of the 19,000<ref>[[#Unruh|Unruh]]: page 119\u2013120</ref> emigrants traveling to California and Oregon utilized the Lander Road. The traffic in later years is undocumented.\n\nThe Lander Road departs the main trail at Burnt Ranch near South Pass, crosses the Continental Divide north of South Pass and reaches the Green River near the present town of [[Big Piney, Wyoming]]. From there the trail followed Big Piney Creek west before passing over the {{convert|8800|ft|m}} Thompson Pass in the [[Wyoming Range]]. It then crosses over the Smith Fork of the Bear River before ascending and crossing another {{convert|8200|ft|m}} pass on the [[Salt River Range]] of mountains and then descending into [[Star Valley]] Wyoming. It exited the mountains near the present Smith Fork road about {{convert|6|mi|km}} south of the town of [[Smoot, Wyoming]]. The road continued almost due north along the present day Wyoming-Idaho western border through Star Valley. To avoid crossing the [[Salt River (Wyoming)|Salt River]] (which drains into the [[Snake River]]) which runs down Star Valley the Lander Road crossed the river when it was small and stayed west of the Salt River. After traveling down the Salt River valley (Star Valley) about {{convert|20|mi|km}} north the road turned almost due west near the present town of [[Auburn, Wyoming]], and entered into the present state of Idaho along Stump Creek. In Idaho it followed the Stump Creek valley northwest till it crossed the [[Caribou Mountains (Idaho)|Caribou Mountains]] and proceeded past the south end of Grays Lake.<ref>Grays Lake [http://www.seidaho.org/grays_lake.html] accessed 8 February 2010</ref>  The trail then proceeded almost due west to meet the main trail at Fort Hall; alternately, a branch trail headed almost due south to meet the main trail near the present town of [[Soda Springs, Idaho|Soda Springs]], Idaho.<ref>[http://wyoshpo.state.wy.us/trailsdemo/landerroad.htm Lander Road Cutoff Map]</ref><ref>\"Emigrant Trails of Southern Idaho\"; Bureau of Land Management & Idaho State Historical Society;1993; pp 117\u2013125 ASIN: B000KE2KTU</ref>\n\nNumerous landmarks are located along the trail in Wyoming including [[Independence Rock (Wyoming)|Independence Rock]], [[Ayres Natural Bridge]] and [[Register Cliff]].\n\n==Utah==\nIn 1847, Brigham Young and the [[Mormon Trail|Mormon]] pioneers departed from the Oregon Trail at [[Fort Bridger]] in Wyoming and followed (and much improved) the rough trail originally recommended by [[Lansford Hastings]] to the [[Donner Party]] in 1846 through the [[Wasatch Mountains]] into [[Utah]].<ref>Salt Lake Cutoff [http://www.americanwest.com/trails/pages/mormtrl.htm] accessdate=17 September 2009</ref> After getting into Utah they immediately started setting up irrigated farms and cities\u2014including [[Salt Lake City, Utah]]. In 1848, the [[Salt Lake Cutoff]] was established by Sam Hensley,<ref name=\"hensley\">{{cite news|url=http://historytogo.utah.gov/salt_lake_tribune/in_another_time/060594.html|title=It's Sam Hensley-Not Hansel-Who Discovered Cutoff|last=Schindler|first=Hal|date=June 5, 1994|newspaper=The Salt Lake Tribune|pages=D1|accessdate=2009-09-17}}</ref>  and returning members of the [[Mormon Battalion]] providing a path north of the [[Great Salt Lake]] from Salt Lake City back to the [[California Trail|California]] and Oregon Trails. This cutoff rejoined the Oregon and California Trails near the [[City of Rocks National Reserve|City of Rocks]] near the Utah-Idaho border and could be used by both California and Oregon bound travelers. Located about half way on both the [[California Trail|California]] and Oregon Trails many thousands of later travelers used Salt Lake City and other Utah cities as an intermediate stop for selling or trading excess goods or tired livestock for fresh livestock, repairs, supplies or fresh vegetables. The Mormons looked on these travelers as a welcome bonanza as setting up new communities from scratch required nearly everything the travelers could afford to part with. The overall distance to California or Oregon was very close to the same whether one \"detoured\" to Salt Lake City or not. For their own use and to encourage California and Oregon bound travelers the Mormons improved the Mormon Trail from Fort Bridger and the Salt Lake Cutoff trail. To raise much needed money and facilitate travel on the Salt Lake Cutoff they set up several ferries across the [[Weber River|Weber]], [[Bear River (Great Salt Lake)|Bear]] and [[Malad River (Idaho-Utah)|Malad]] rivers which were used mostly by Oregon or California bound travelers.\n\n==Idaho==\nThe main Oregon and California Trail went almost due north from Fort Bridger to the Little Muddy Creek where it passed over the Bear River Mountains to the [[Bear River (Great Salt Lake)|Bear River]] valley which it followed northwest into the Thomas Fork area, where the trail crossed over the present day Wyoming line into Idaho. In the Eastern Sheep Creek Hills in the Thomas Fork valley the emigrants encountered Big Hill. Big Hill was a detour caused by an impassable (then) cut the Bear River made through the mountains and had a tough ascent often requiring doubling up of teams and a very steep and dangerous descent.<ref>Big Hill Idaho (OCTA Idaho) [http://www.idahohistory.net/OTbighill.html] accessed 5 February 2009</ref> (Much later, [[U.S. Highway 30]], using modern explosives and equipment, was built through this cut). In 1852 Eliza Ann McAuley found and with help developed the McAuley Cutoff which bypassed much of the difficult climb and descent of Big Hill. About {{convert|5|mi|km}} on they passed present day [[Montpelier, Idaho|Montpelier]], Idaho which is now the site of The National Oregon-California Trail Center.<ref>The National Oregon-California Trail Center [http://www.oregontrailcenter.org/] Accessed 25 February 2009</ref> The trail follows the Bear River northwest to present day [[Soda Springs, Idaho]]. The soda springs here were a favorite attraction of the pioneers who marveled at the hot carbonated water and chugging \"steamboat\" springs. Many stopped and did their laundry in the hot water as there was usually plenty of good grass and fresh water available.<ref>Soda Springs quotes Idaho State Historical Society [http://www.idahohistory.net/Reference%20Series/0182.pdf] Accessed 25 February 2009</ref> Just west of Soda Springs the Bear River turns southwest as it heads for [[The Great Salt Lake]] and the main trail turns northwest to follow the [[Portneuf River (Idaho)|Portneuf River]] valley to [[Fort Hall]] Idaho. Fort Hall was an old fur trading post located on the [[Snake River]]. It was established in 1832 by [[Nathaniel Jarvis Wyeth]] and company and later sold in 1837 to the British [[Hudson's Bay Company]]. At Fort Hall nearly all travelers were given some aid and supplies if they were available and needed. Mosquitoes were constant pests and travelers often mention that their animals were covered with blood from the bites. The route from Fort Bridger to Fort Hall is about {{convert|210|mi|km}}, taking nine to twelve days.\n\nAt Soda Springs was one branch of [[Emigrant Trail in Wyoming#Lander Road|Lander Road]] (established and built with government contractors in 1858) which had gone west from near South Pass, over the Salt River Mountains and down Star Valley before turning west near present-day [[Auburn, Wyoming|Auburn]], Wyoming and entering Idaho. From there it proceeded northwest into Idaho up Stump Creek canyon for about {{convert|10|mi|km|spell=in}}. One branch turned almost 90 degrees and proceeded southwest to Soda Springs. Another branch headed almost due west past Gray\u2019s Lake to rejoin the main trail about {{convert|10|mi|km}} west of Fort Hall.\n\nOn the main trail about {{convert|5|mi|km}} west of Soda Springs '''Hudspeth's Cutoff''' (established 1849 and used mostly by California trail users) took off from the main trail heading almost due west, bypassing Fort Hall. It rejoined the [[California Trail]] at Cassia Creek near the [[City of Rocks National Reserve|City of Rocks]].<ref>Hudspeth cutoff map (OCTA-Idaho) [http://www.idahoocta.org/Idaho_Trail_Sites.html] Accessed 5 February 2009</ref> Hudspeth's Cutoff had five mountain ranges to cross and took about the same amount of time as the main route to Fort Hall but many took it thinking it was shorter. Its main advantage was that it helped spread out the traffic during peak periods, making more grass available.<ref>For an Oregon-California trail map up to the junction in Idaho see ''Oregon National Historic Trail Map NPS [http://www.nps.gov/PWR/customcf/apps/maps/showmap.cfm?alphacode=oreg&parkname=Oregon%20National%20Historic%20Trail]. Accessed 28 January 2009.</ref>\n\nWest of Fort Hall the main trail traveled about {{convert|40|mi|km}} on the south side of the Snake River southwest past American Falls, [[Massacre Rocks]], Register Rock and Coldwater Hill near present-day [[Pocatello, Idaho|Pocatello]], Idaho. Near the junction of the [[Raft River]] and the Snake River, the California Trail diverged from the Oregon Trail at another Parting of the Ways junction. Travellers left the Snake River and followed Raft River about {{convert|65|mi|km}} southwest past present day [[Almo, Idaho|Almo]], Idaho. This trail then passed through the [[City of Rocks National Reserve|City of Rocks]] and over Granite Pass where it went southwest along Goose Creek, Little Goose Creek, and Rock Spring Creek. It went about {{convert|95|mi|km}} through [[Thousand Springs Scenic Byway|Thousand Springs Valley]], West Brush Creek, and Willow Creek, before arriving at the [[Humboldt River]] in northeastern Nevada near present-day [[Wells, Nevada|Wells]].<ref>[http://www.elkorose.com/osino/catrailsmap_smaller.jpg Northern Nevada and Utah, Southern Idaho Trail Map] Accessed 9 February 2009</ref> The California Trail proceeded west down the Humboldt before reaching and crossing the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevadas]].\n\nThere are only a few places where the Snake River has not buried itself deep in a canyon. There are few spots where the river slowed down enough to make a crossing possible. Two of these fords were near Fort Hall, where travelers on the Oregon Trail North Side Alternate (established about 1852) and Goodale\u2019s Cutoff (established 1862) crossed the Snake to travel on the north side. Nathaniel Wyeth, the original founder of Fort Hall in 1834, writes in his diary that they found a ford across the Snake River {{convert|4|mi|km}} southwest of where he founded Fort Hall. Another possible crossing was a few miles upstream of Salmon Falls where some intrepid travelers floated their wagons and swam their stock across to join the north side trail. Some lost their wagons and teams over the falls.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://history.idaho.gov/Reference%20Series/0752.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721042929/http://history.idaho.gov/Reference%20Series/0752.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-21 }}</ref> The trails on the north side joined the trail from Three Island Crossing about {{convert|17|mi|km}} west of Glenns Ferry on the north side of the Snake River.<ref>Oregon Trail North Side Alternate {{cite web |url=http://www.blm.gov/pgdata/etc/medialib/blm/id/publications.Par.50091.File.dat/OCTAbooklet.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-03-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325011951/http://www.blm.gov/pgdata/etc/medialib/blm/id/publications.Par.50091.File.dat/OCTAbooklet.pdf |archivedate=2009-03-25 }} Accessed 25 February 2009</ref> (For map of North Side Alternate see:<ref>[http://www.nps.gov/archive/ciro/hrs/images/fig7.jpg] Accessed 25 February 2009</ref>)\n\n[[Goodale's Cutoff]], established in 1862 on the north side of the Snake River, formed a spur of the Oregon Trail. This cutoff had been used as a pack trail by Indians and fur traders, and emigrant wagons traversed parts of the eastern section as early as 1852. After crossing the Snake River the {{convert|230|mi|km}} cutoff headed north from Fort Hall toward Big Southern Butte following the [[Lost River (Idaho)|Lost River]] part of the way. It passed near the present-day town of [[Arco, Idaho|Arco]], Idaho and wound through the northern part of [[Craters of the Moon National Monument]]. From there it went southwest to [[Camas Prairie]] and ended at [[Fort Boise#Old Fort Boise (1834&ndash;54)|Old Fort Boise]] on the [[Boise River]]. This journey typically took two to three weeks and was noted for its very rough, lava restricted roads and extremely dry climate, which tended to dry the wooden wheels on the wagons, which caused the iron rims to fall off the wheels. Loss of wheels caused many wagons to be abandoned along the route. It rejoined the main trail east of Boise. Goodale's Cutoff is visible at many points along [[U.S. Highway 20]], [[U.S. Highway 26]] and  [[U.S. Highway 93]] between Craters of the Moon National Monument and [[Carey, Idaho|Carey]], Idaho.<ref>Goodale\u2019s Cutoff NPS [http://www.nps.gov/archive/crmo/goodale.htm] Accessed 22 February 2009</ref>\n\n[[Image:Shoshone Falls, Snake River, Idaho ppmsca.10072u.jpg|thumb|right|300px|View across top of Shoshone Falls, Snake River, Idaho ([[Timothy H. O'Sullivan]], 1874)]]\nFrom the present site of [[Pocatello, Idaho|Pocatello]] the trail proceeded almost due west on the south side of the Snake River for about {{convert|180|mi|km}}. On this route they passed [[Cauldron Linn (Idaho)|Cauldron Linn]] rapids, [[Shoshone Falls]], two falls near the present city of [[Twin Falls, Idaho|Twin Falls]], Idaho, and Upper Salmon Falls on the Snake River. At Salmon Falls there were often a hundred or more Indians fishing who would trade for their salmon\u2014a welcome treat. The trail continued west to [[Three Island Crossing State Park|Three Island Crossing]] (near present-day [[Glenns Ferry, Idaho|Glenns Ferry]], Idaho).<ref>Three Island Crossing photos [http://www.nativeamerican.co.uk/oregonroute15.html] Accessed 22 February 2009</ref><ref>Three Island Crossing quotes {{cite web |url=http://www.wvi.com/users/TIC/tic.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-02-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206235002/http://www.wvi.com/users/TIC/tic.htm |archivedate=2009-02-06 }} Accessed 22 February 2009</ref> Here most emigrants used the divisions of the river caused by three islands to cross the difficult and swift Snake River by ferry or by driving or sometimes floating their wagons and swimming their teams across. The crossings were doubly treacherous because there were often hidden holes in the river bottom which could overturn the wagon or ensnarl the team, sometimes with fatal consequences. Before ferries were established there were several drownings here nearly every year.<ref>Three Mile Island Crossing Park [http://www.stateparks.com/three_island_crossing.html] Accessed 22 February 2009</ref>\n\nThe north side of the Snake had better water and grass than the south. The trail from Three Island Crossing to [[Fort Boise#Old Fort Boise (1834&ndash;54)|Old Fort Boise]] was about 130 miles long. The usually lush Boise River valley was a welcome relief. The next crossing of the Snake River was near Old Fort Boise. This last crossing of the Snake could be done on bull boats while swimming the stock across. Others would chain a large string of wagons and teams together. The theory was that the front teams, usually oxen, would get out of water first and with good footing help pull the whole string of wagons and teams across. How well this worked in practice is not stated. Often young Indian boys were hired to drive and ride the stock across the river\u2014they knew how to swim, unlike many pioneers. Today's Idaho [[Interstate 84 (west)|Interstate 84]] roughly follows the Oregon Trail till it leaves the Snake River near [[Burley, Idaho|Burley]], Idaho. From there [[Interstate 86 (west)|Interstate 86]] to Pocatello roughly approximates the trail. [[Highway 30]] roughly follows the path of the Oregon Trail from there to [[Montpelier, Idaho|Montpelier]], Idaho.\n\nStarting in about 1848 the South Alternate of Oregon Trail (also called the Snake River Cutoff) was developed as a spur off the main trail. It bypassed the Three Island Crossing and continued traveling down the south side of the Snake River. It rejoined the trail near present-day [[Ontario, Oregon|Ontario]], Oregon. It hugged the southern edge of the Snake River canyon and was a much rougher trail with poorer water and grass, requiring occasional steep descents and ascents with the animals down into the Snake River canyon to get water. Travellers on this route avoided two dangerous crossings of the Snake River.<ref>National Trail Map [http://www.fs.fed.us/recreation/programs/trails/natltrails.pdf] accessed 22 February 2009</ref> Today's Idaho State Route 78 roughly follows the path of the South Alternate route of the Oregon Trail.\n\nIn 1869 the Central Pacific established [[Kelton, Utah|Kelton]], Utah as a railhead and the terminus of the western mail was moved from Salt Lake City. The Kelton Road became important as a communication and transportation road to the Boise Basin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idahohistory.net/Reference%20Series/0074.pdf |title=IdahoHistory.net |publisher=IdahoHistory.net |date=2010-07-07 |accessdate=2011-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==Oregon==\nOnce across the [[Snake River]] ford near [[Fort Boise#Old Fort Boise (1834&ndash;54)|Old Fort Boise]] the weary travelers traveled across what would become the state of [[Oregon]]. The trail then went to the [[Malheur River]] and then past [[Farewell Bend State Recreation Area|Farewell Bend]] on the Snake River, up the [[Burnt River (Oregon)|Burnt River]] canyon and northwest to the [[La Grande, Oregon|La Grande]] [[Grande Ronde Valley|valley]] before coming to the [[Blue Mountains (Oregon)|Blue Mountains]]. In 1843 settlers cut a wagon road over these mountains making them passable for the first time to wagons. The trail went to the [[Whitman Mission]] near [[Fort Nez Perce]] in [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]] until 1847 when the Whitmans were killed by Native Americans. At Fort Nez Perce some built rafts or hired boats and started down the Columbia; others continued west in their wagons until they reached [[The Dalles, Oregon|The Dalles]]. After 1847 the trail bypassed the closed mission and headed almost due west to present day [[Pendleton, Oregon|Pendleton]], Oregon, crossing the [[Umatilla River]], [[John Day River]], and [[Deschutes River (Oregon)|Deschutes River]] before arriving at The Dalles. [[Interstate 84 (west)|Interstate 84]] in Oregon roughly follows the original Oregon Trail from Idaho to The Dalles.\n\nArriving at the Columbia at The Dalles and stopped by the [[Cascade Mountains]] and [[Mount Hood]], some gave up their wagons or disassembled them and put them on boats or rafts for a trip down the [[Columbia River]]. Once they transited the Cascade's [[Columbia River Gorge]] with its multiple rapids and treacherous winds they would have to make the {{convert|1.6|mi|km}} portage around the [[Cascade Rapids]] before coming out near the [[Willamette River]] where [[Oregon City, Oregon|Oregon City]], Oregon was located. The pioneer's livestock could be driven around Mount Hood on the narrow, crooked and rough [[Lolo Pass (Oregon)|Lolo Pass]].\n\nSeveral Oregon Trail branches and route variations led to the [[Willamette Valley]]. The most popular was the [[Barlow Road]], which was carved though the forest around Mount Hood from The Dalles in 1846 as a toll road at $5.00 per wagon and 10 cents per head of livestock. It was rough and steep with poor grass but still cheaper and safer than floating goods, wagons and family down the dangerous Columbia River.\n\nIn Central Oregon there was the [[Santiam Wagon Road]] (established 1861), which roughly parallels Oregon Highway 20 to the Willamette Valley. The [[Applegate Trail]] (established 1846) cutting off the [[California Trail]] from the [[Humboldt River]] in Nevada crossed part of California before cutting north to the south end of the Willamette Valley. Originally [[U.S. Route 99]] (later renamed to [[Oregon Route 99]]) and [[Interstate 5]] through Oregon roughly follow the original Applegate Trail.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|22em}}\n\n[[Category:Oregon Trail]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: though\u2192through", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Route_of_the_Oregon_Trail"}
{"title_page": "SABRE (rocket engine)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Sabre (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox rocket engine\n |image                      = Sabre-model.jpg\n |image_size                 = 250px\n |caption                    = A model of SABRE\n |name                       = Reaction Engines SABRE\n |country_of_origin          = [[United Kingdom]]\n |designer                   = [[Reaction Engines Limited]]\n |purpose                    = [[Single-stage-to-orbit]]\n |predecessor                = [[RB545]]\n |associated                 = [[Skylon (spacecraft)|Skylon]]\n |status                     = [[Research and development]]\n |type                       = liquid\n |fuel                       = [[liquid hydrogen]]<ref name=\"names\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/downloads/REL_Engine_Names.pdf |title=Reaction Engines Limited Engine Names\n|publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305234315/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/downloads/REL_Engine_Names.pdf |archive-date=5 March 2012 }}</ref>\n |oxidiser                   = [[Air]] or [[liquid oxygen]]\n |cycle                      = Combined cycle [[precooled jet engine]] and [[closed cycle rocket engine]]\n |thrust(SL)                 = Approx. {{convert|1960|kN|abbr=on}}{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n |thrust(Vac)                = Approx. {{convert|2940|kN|abbr=on}}{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n |specific_impulse_vacuum    = {{convert|460|isp}}<ref name=\"user\"/>\n |specific_impulse_sea_level = {{convert|3600|isp|tsfc+km/s}}<ref name=\"user\"/>\n |thrust_to_weight           = Up to 14 (atmospheric)<ref name=\"precooled\"/>\n}}\n'''SABRE''' ('''Synergetic Air Breathing Rocket Engine'''<ref name=\"SABRE_page\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/sabre |title=SABRE \u2013 Synergetic Air Breathing Rocket Engine|publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]] |access-date=18 December 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219091110/https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/sabre |archive-date=19 December 2018 }}</ref>) is a concept under development by [[Reaction Engines Limited]] for a [[hypersonic]] [[precooled jet engine|precooled]] hybrid [[Engine#Heat engine|air-breathing]] [[rocket engine]].<ref name=\"compare\">{{cite web | title=A Comparison of Propulsions Concepts for SSTO Reusable launchers | url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/JBIS_v56_108-117.pdf |  | publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]] | pages=114, 115 | access-date=2 August 2010 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615104428/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/JBIS_v56_108-117.pdf | archive-date=15 June 2011 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=lapcat>{{Cite web\n\n  |title=Flight Applications\n  |publisher=[[Reaction Engines]]\n  |url=https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/sabre/flight-applications\n}}</ref> The engine is being designed to achieve [[single-stage-to-orbit]] capability, propelling the proposed [[Skylon (spacecraft)|Skylon]] [[spaceplane]] to low Earth orbit. SABRE is an evolution of [[Alan Bond (engineer)|Alan Bond]]'s series of [[liquid air cycle engine]] (LACE) and LACE-like designs that started in the early/mid-1980s for the [[HOTOL]] project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/45136248|title=Alan Bond Interview|website=Vimeo|access-date=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe design comprises a single [[combined cycle]] rocket engine with two modes of operation.<ref name=\"user\">{{cite web | url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/SKYLON_User_Manual_rev1-1.pdf | title=Skylon Users' Manual | date=18 January 2010 | publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]] | pages=4, 3 | access-date=2 August 2010 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418035934/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/SKYLON_User_Manual_rev1-1.pdf | archive-date=18 April 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The air-breathing mode combines a turbo-[[Gas compressor|compressor]] with a lightweight air [[Precooled jet engine|precooler]] positioned just behind the [[inlet cone]]. At high speeds this precooler cools the hot, ram-compressed air, which would otherwise reach a temperature that the engine could not withstand,<ref name=precooling>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-47832920 |title=UK's Sabre space plane engine tech in new milestone|website=BBC News|date= 8 April 2019}}</ref> leading to a very high [[Overall pressure ratio|pressure ratio]] within the engine. The compressed air is subsequently fed into the rocket [[combustion chamber]] where it is ignited along with stored [[liquid hydrogen]]. The high pressure ratio allows the engine to provide high thrust at very high speeds and altitudes. The low temperature of the air permits light alloy construction to be employed and allow a very lightweight engine\u2014essential for reaching orbit. In addition, unlike the LACE concept, SABRE's precooler does not [[Liquid air|liquefy the air]], letting it run more efficiently.<ref name=\"precooled\">{{cite web | url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/JBIS_v60_188-196.pdf | title=The Sensitivity of Precooled Air-Breathing Engine Performance to Heat Exchanger Design Parameters | date=29 March 2007 | publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]] | page=189 | access-date=9 August 2010 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130623100631/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/JBIS_v60_188-196.pdf | archive-date=23 June 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAfter shutting the inlet cone off at [[Mach number|Mach]]&nbsp;5.14, and at an altitude of 28.5&nbsp;km,<ref name=\"user\" /> the system continues as a [[staged combustion cycle (rocket)|closed-cycle]] high-performance rocket engine burning [[liquid oxygen]] and [[liquid hydrogen]] from on-board fuel tanks, potentially allowing a hybrid [[spaceplane]] concept like [[Skylon (spacecraft)|Skylon]] to reach orbital velocity after leaving the atmosphere on a steep climb.\n\nAn engine derived from the SABRE concept called [[Reaction Engines Scimitar|Scimitar]] has been designed for the company's [[Reaction Engines A2|A2]] [[Supersonic transport|hypersonic passenger jet]] proposal for the [[European Union]]-funded [[LAPCAT]] study.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/about/story-so-far |title=Reaction Engines has reached a number of high profile milestones|website=Reaction Engines|date=2018|accessdate= 8 April 2019}}</ref>\n{{toclimit|3}}\n\n==History==\nThe precooler concept evolved from an idea originated by Robert P. Carmichael in 1955.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hq.nasa.gov/pao/History/SP-4404/ch7-13.htm |title=Liquid Hydrogen as a Propulsion Fuel, 1945\u20131959 |publisher=NASA History Division |accessdate=1 July 2009 }}</ref> This was followed by the [[liquid air cycle engine]] (LACE) idea which was originally explored by [[General Dynamics]] in the 1960s as part of the [[US Air Force]]'s [[aerospaceplane]] efforts.<ref name=\"precooled\" />\n\nThe LACE system was to be placed behind a supersonic air intake which would compress the air through ram compression, then a [[heat exchanger]] would rapidly cool it using some of the [[liquid hydrogen]] fuel stored on board. The resulting liquid air was then processed to separate the [[liquid oxygen]] for combustion. The amount of warmed hydrogen was too great to burn with the oxygen, so most was to be expelled, giving useful thrust, but greatly reducing the potential efficiency.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\nInstead, as part of the [[HOTOL]] project, the liquid air cycle engine (LACE) based [[RB545]] engine was developed with more efficient cycle. The engine was given the Rolls Royce name \"Swallow\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2009/02/23/322955/secret-files-reveal-us-interest-in-uk-hotol-spaceplane.html|title=News Channel - Homepage - flightglobal.com|website=FlightGlobal.com|access-date=19 December 2017}}</ref> In 1989, after funding for HOTOL ceased, Bond and several others formed [[Reaction Engines Limited]] to continue research. The RB545's precooler had issues with [[Hydrogen embrittlement|embrittlement]] and excess liquid hydrogen consumption, and was encumbered by both patents and the UK's [[Official Secrets Act]], so Bond developed SABRE instead.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.daviddarling.info/encyclopedia/B/Bond.html | title=A. Bond | work=daviddarling.info |accessdate=8 August 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 the project received \u00a360m in funds from the UK government and ESA for a demonstrator involving the full cycle.<ref name=\"bbc_12July2016\">{{cite news|title=Funding flows for UK\u2019s 'revolutionary' Sabre rocket engine|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-36773074|accessdate=12 July 2016|work=Science|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=12 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Concept==\n\n[[File:Sabre cycle m.jpg|thumb|right|Simplified flow diagram of SABRE engine]]\nLike the [[RB545]], the SABRE design is neither a conventional [[rocket engine]] nor a conventional [[turbojet|jet engine]], but a hybrid that uses air from the environment at low speeds/altitudes, and stored [[liquid oxygen]] at higher altitude. The SABRE engine \"relies on a heat exchanger capable of cooling incoming air to {{convert|-150|C}}, to provide oxygen for mixing with hydrogen and provide jet thrust during atmospheric flight before switching to tanked liquid oxygen when in space.\"\n\nIn air-breathing mode, air enters the engine through an inlet. A bypass system directs some of the air through a precooler into a compressor, which injects it into a combustion chamber where it is burnt with fuel, the exhaust products are accelerated through nozzles to provide thrust. The remainder of the intake air continues through the bypass system to a ring of flame holders which act as a ramjet for part of the air breathing flight regime. A helium loop is used to transfer the heat from the precooler to the fuel and drive the engine pumps and compressors.\n\n===Inlet===\n\nAt the front of the engine, the concept designs propose a simple translating axisymmetric [[Inlet cone|shock cone inlet]] which compresses and slows the air (relative to the engine) to subsonic speeds using two shock reflections. Accelerating the air to the speed of the engine incurs [[ram drag]]. As a result of the shocks, compression, and acceleration the intake air is heated, reaching around {{convert|1000|C|F}} at Mach{{nbsp}}5.5.\n\n[[Bayern-Chemie]], through ESA, have undertaken work to refine and test the intake and bypass systems<ref name=BayernChemieSabreDevelopment>{{Cite web|url=https://bayern-chemie.com/bayern-chemie-concludes-agreement-with-european-space-agency-on-the-further-development-of-sabre-engine/|title=BAYERN-CHEMIE concludes agreement with European Space Agency on the further development of SABRE engine}}</ref>\n\n===Precooler===\n\nAs the air enters the engine at [[supersonic]] or [[hypersonic]] speeds, it becomes hotter than the engine can withstand due to compression effects.<ref name=precooling/> [[Jet engines]], which have the same problem but to a lesser degree, solve it by using heavy [[copper]] or [[nickel]]-based materials, by reducing the engine's [[Overall pressure ratio|pressure ratio]], and by throttling back the engine at the higher airspeeds to avoid melting. However, for a [[single-stage-to-orbit]] (SSTO) spaceplane, such heavy materials are unusable, and maximum thrust is necessary for orbital insertion at the earliest time to minimise [[gravity drag|gravity losses]]. Instead, using a gaseous [[helium]] coolant loop, SABRE dramatically cools the air from {{cvt|1000|C}} down to {{cvt|\u2212150|C}} in a heat exchanger while avoiding [[liquid air|liquefaction]] of the air or blockage from freezing water vapour.\n\nPrevious versions of precoolers such as HOTOL put the hydrogen fuel directly through the precooler. SABRE inserts a helium cooling loop between the air and the cold fuel to avoid problems with [[hydrogen embrittlement]] in the precooler.\n\nThe dramatic cooling of the air created a potential problem: it is necessary to prevent blocking the precooler from frozen water vapour and other air fractions. In October 2012, the cooling solution was demonstrated for 6 minutes using freezing air.<ref>{{cite web| last=Marks| first=Paul| title=Die Erben der Concorde| url=http://www.new-scientist.de/inhalt/hyperschallflugzeuge-die-erben-der-concorde-a-860705.html| publisher=[[New Scientist]]| access-date=10 December 2012| language=German| date=October 2012| url-status=dead| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121124100307/http://www.new-scientist.de/inhalt/hyperschallflugzeuge-die-erben-der-concorde-a-860705.html| archive-date=24 November 2012| df=dmy-all}} [https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=de&u=http://www.new-scientist.de/inhalt/hyperschallflugzeuge-die-erben-der-concorde-a-860705.html&prev=/search%3Fq%3D%2522mark%2Bford%2522%2Bestec%2Bsabre%26start%3D10%26hl%3Den%26safe%3Doff%26sa%3DN%26tbo%3Dd%26rls%3Dcom.microsoft:en-US:%257Breferrer:source%257D%26biw%3D1200%26bih%3D1805&sa=X&ei=4GHGUJmcIvH44QSckoHoCQ&ved=0CDEQ7gEwADgK In English]</ref> The cooler consists of a fine pipework heat exchanger with 16,800 thin-walled tubes,<ref name=AvWeek7apr2019/> and cools the hot in-rushing atmospheric air down to the required {{cvt|\u2212150|C}} in 0.01{{nbsp}}s.<ref>{{cite news| last=Amos |first=Jonathan |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-20510112 |title=BBC News \u2013 Skylon spaceplane engine concept achieves key milestone |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=28 November 2012 |accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref> The ice prevention system had been a closely guarded secret, but REL disclosed a [[methanol]]-injecting 3D-printed de-icer in 2015 through patents, as they needed partner companies and could not keep the secret while working closely with outsiders.<ref>Norris, Guy. \"[https://awin.aviationweek.com/ArticlesStory.aspx?id=ae0e5600-45e8-4259-9000-9f9c2d14c448 Reaction Engines Reveals Secret Of Sabre Frost Control Technology]{{dead link|date=September 2017|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}\" ''[[Aviation Week & Space Technology|Aerospace Daily & Defense Report]]'', 8 July 2015, p. 3 [https://awin.aviationweek.com/ArticlesStory.aspx?id=ae0e5600-45e8-4259-9000-9f9c2d14c448 Similar article]{{dead link|date=September 2017|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}} <!--paywall: http://aviationweek.com/technology/reaction-engines-reveals-inner-secret-sabre-propulsion-technology --></ref><ref>\"[http://www.engineering.com/3DPrinting/3DPrintingArticles/ArticleID/10407/The-Skylon-Spaceplanes-3D-Printed-Injector.aspx The Skylon Spaceplane's 3D Printed Injector]\"</ref><ref>\"[http://3dprint.com/81151/skylon-spaceplane-3d-printing/ Helping the Skylon Spaceplane Reach Orbit with a 3D Printed Injector Mechanism]\"</ref>\n\nIn September 2017 it was announced United States Defense Advanced Research projects (DARPA) had contracted with Reaction Engines Inc to build a high-temperature airflow test facility at Front Range Airport near Watkins, Colorado. The DARPA contract is to test the Sabre engine's precooler heat exchanger (HTX).\n\nThe test work which started in 2018 focussed on running the heat exchanger at temperatures simulating Mach{{nbsp}}5 of over {{convert|1000|C}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviationweek.com/space/reaction-begins-building-us-hypersonic-engine-test-site |title=Reaction Begins Building U.S. Hypersonic Engine Test Site |work= Aviation Week |date= 18 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/reaction-engines-awarded-darpa-contract-to-perform-high-temperature-testing-of-the-sabre-precooler/|title=Reaction Engines Awarded DARPA Contract to Perform High-Temperature Testing of the SABRE Precooler \u2013 Reaction Engines|date=25 September 2017|website=ReactionEngines.co.uk|access-date=19 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928232712/https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/reaction-engines-awarded-darpa-contract-to-perform-high-temperature-testing-of-the-sabre-precooler/|archive-date=28 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe HTX test unit was completed in the UK and sent to Colorado in 2018, where on 25 March 2019 a [[F-4]] GE [[J79]] turbojet exhaust was mixed with ambient air to replicate Mach{{nbsp}}3.3 inlet conditions, successfully quenching a {{cvt|420|C}} stream of gases to {{cvt|100|C}} in less than 1/20th of a second. Further tests simulating Mach{{nbsp}}5 were planned, with temperature reduction expected from {{cvt|1000|C}}.<ref name=precooling/><ref name=AvWeek7apr2019>{{cite news |url= https://aviationweek.com/space/reaction-engines-pre-cooler-passes-mach-33-test |title= Reaction Engines Pre-Cooler Passes Mach 3.3 Test |date= 7 April 2019 |author= Guy Norris |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref> These further tests were successfully completed by October 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=REACTION ENGINES TEST PROGRAMME FULLY VALIDATES PRECOOLER AT HYPERSONIC HEAT CONDITIONS |url=https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/news/reaction-engines-test-programme-fully-validates-precooler-hypersonic-heat-conditions |website=Reaction Engines |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Reaction Engines' precooler tech demo chills 1,000\u00b0C air in less than 1/20th of a second |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2019/10/22/reaction_engines_precooler_demo_mach_5/ |website=The Register |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Skylon\u2019s SABRE Engine Passes a Big Test |url=https://www.universetoday.com/143810/skylons-sabre-engine-passes-a-big-test/ |website=Universe Today |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe successful HTX test could lead to spin-off precooler applications which could be developed before a scalable SABRE demonstrator is completed; suggested uses are to expand [[gas turbine]]s capabilities, in advanced [[turbofan]]s, hypersonic vehicles, and industrial applications.<ref name=AvWeek15May2018>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/defense/turbojet-runs-precursor-hypersonic-engine-heat-exchanger-tests |title= Turbojet Runs Precursor to Hypersonic Engine Heat Exchanger Tests |date= 15 May 2018 |author= Guy Norris |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref>\n\n===Compressor===\nBelow five times the [[speed of sound]] and 25 kilometres of altitude, which are 20% of the speed and 20% of the altitude needed to reach [[orbit]], the cooled air from the precooler passes into a modified turbo-[[Gas compressor|compressor]], similar in design to those used on conventional jet engines but running at an unusually high [[overall pressure ratio|pressure ratio]] made possible by the low temperature of the inlet air. The compressor feeds the compressed air at 140 [[Atmospheres (unit)|atmospheres]] into the combustion chambers of the main engines.<ref name=\"how\">{{cite web |url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/sabre_howworks.html |title=SABRE: how it works |publisher=Reaction Engines Limited |access-date=29 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130726014458/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/sabre_howworks.html |archive-date=26 July 2013  }}</ref>\n\nThe turbo-compressor is powered by a [[gas turbine]] running on a helium loop, rather than by combustion gases as in a conventional jet engine. The turbo-compressor is powered by waste heat collected by the helium loop.<ref name=\"how\" />\n\n====Helium loop====\n\nThe 'hot' helium from the air precooler is recycled by cooling it in a heat exchanger with the liquid hydrogen fuel. The loop forms a self-starting [[Brayton cycle]] engine, cooling critical parts of the engine and powering turbines.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}} The heat passes from the air into the helium. This heat energy is used to power various parts of the engine and to vaporise hydrogen, which is then burnt in [[ramjet]]s.<ref name=\"user\" /><ref name=\"Reactionengines.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/faq.html#q5 |title=Reaction Engines Ltd \u2013 Frequently Asked Questions |publisher=Reactionengines.co.uk |access-date=1 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150602004107/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/faq.html#q5 |archive-date=2 June 2015  }}</ref>\n\n===Combustion chambers===\n\nThe combustion chambers in the SABRE engine are cooled by the oxidant (air/liquid oxygen) rather than by liquid hydrogen<ref name=\"uksa\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2009/6200.html | title=The rocket that thinks it's a jet | date=19 February 2009| publisher=[[UK Space Agency]] | accessdate=5 November 2015 }}</ref> to further reduce the system's use of liquid hydrogen compared with [[Air-fuel ratio|stoichiometric]] systems.\n\n===Nozzles===\nThe most efficient atmospheric pressure at which a conventional [[propelling nozzle]] works is set by the [[geometry]] of the [[De Laval nozzle|nozzle bell]]. While the geometry of the conventional bell remains static the [[Atmospheric pressure#Altitude atmospheric pressure variation|atmospheric pressure changes with altitude]] and therefore nozzles designed for high performance in the lower atmosphere lose efficiency as they reach higher altitudes. In traditional rockets this is overcome by using multiple stages designed for the atmospheric pressures they encounter. \n\nThe SABRE engine must operate at both low and high altitude scenarios. To ensure efficiency at all altitudes a sort of moving, [[Expanding nozzle]] is used. First at low altitude, jet powered flight the bell is located rearwards, connected to a toroidal combustion chamber surrounding the central rocket combustion chamber. When SABRE then later transitions into rocket mode, the bell is moved forwards, extending the length of the bell of the inner rocket combustion chamber, creating a much larger, high altitude nozzle for more efficient flight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US20150101337A1/en|title=Nozzle arrangement for an engine}}</ref>\n[[File:SABRE_Air_breathing_nozzle_mode.png|thumb|168x168px|Nozzle in Air Breathing Mode]]\n[[File:SABRE_Rocket_nozzle_mode.png|thumb|186x186px|Nozzle in Rocket mode]]\n\n===Bypass burners===\n\nAvoiding [[Liquid air|liquefaction]] improves the efficiency of the engine since less [[entropy]] is generated and therefore less liquid hydrogen is boiled off. However, simply cooling the air needs more liquid hydrogen than can be burnt in the engine core. The excess is expelled through a series of burners called \"spill duct [[ramjet]] burners\",<ref name=\"user\" /><ref name=\"Reactionengines.co.uk\"/> that are arranged in a ring around the central core. These are fed air that bypasses the precooler. This bypass ramjet system is designed to reduce the negative effects of drag resulting from air that passes into the intakes but is not fed into the main rocket engine, rather than generating thrust. At low speeds the ratio of the volume of air entering the intake to the volume that the compressor can feed to the combustion chamber is at its highest, requiring the bypassed air to be accelerated to maintain efficiency at these low speeds. This distinguishes the system from a [[Air turborocket#Types|turboramjet]] where a turbine-cycle's exhaust is used to increase air-flow for the ramjet to become efficient enough to take over the role of primary propulsion.<ref>{{cite web | title=Travelling at the edge of space: Reaction Engines and Skylon in the next 20 years | url=http://ewds.strath.ac.uk/space/OnDemandSeminar/tabid/4560/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/288/Travelling-at-the-edge-of-space--10-March-2010.aspx | publisher=[[University of Strathclyde]] | access-date=9 August 2010 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310093203/http://ewds.strath.ac.uk/space/OnDemandSeminar/tabid/4560/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/288/Travelling-at-the-edge-of-space--10-March-2010.aspx | archive-date=10 March 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n[[File:SABRE ENGINE.jpg|thumb|The latest SABRE engine's design.]]\nTests were carried out in 2008 by Airbourne Engineering Ltd on an [[expansion deflection nozzle]] called STERN to provide the data needed to develop an accurate engineering model to overcome the problem of non-dynamic exhaust expansion. This research continued with the STRICT nozzle in 2011.\n\nSuccessful tests of an oxidiser (both air and oxygen) cooled combustion chamber were conducted by EADS-Astrium at [[Lampoldshausen|Institute of Space Propulsion]] in 2010\n\nIn 2011, hardware testing of the heat exchanger technology \"crucial to [the] hybrid air- and liquid oxygen-breathing [SABRE] rocket motor\" was completed, demonstrating that the technology is viable.<ref name=\"precooltest\" /><ref name=\"fg20110901\">{{cite news |last=Thisdell| first=Dan |title= Spaceplane engine tests under way |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/spaceplane-engine-tests-under-way-361501/ |accessdate=4 November 2015 |newspaper=Flightglobal News |date=1 September 2011}}</ref> The tests validated that the heat exchanger could perform as needed for the engine to obtain adequate oxygen from the atmosphere to support the low-altitude, high-performance operation.<ref name=\"precooltest\" /><ref name=\"fg20110901\" />\n\nIn November 2012, Reaction Engines announced it had successfully concluded a series of tests that prove the cooling technology of the engine, one of the main obstacles towards the completion of the project. The [[European Space Agency]] (ESA) evaluated the SABRE engine's precooler heat exchanger, and accepted claims that the technologies required to proceed with the engine's development had been fully demonstrated.<ref name=\"precooltest\">{{cite web |url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/press_release/PRESS%20RELEASE%20-%20THE%20BIGGESTBREAKTHROUGH%20IN%20PROPULSION%20-%2028%20November%202012.pdf |title=The biggest breakthrough in propulsion since the jet engine | |publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]] |date=28 November 2012 |author=Reaction Engines Limited |access-date=28 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121207125042/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/press_release/PRESS%20RELEASE%20-%20THE%20BIGGESTBREAKTHROUGH%20IN%20PROPULSION%20-%2028%20November%202012.pdf |archive-date=7 December 2012  }}</ref><ref name=\"avEsa\">{{cite web| last=Svitak| first=Amy| title=ESA Validates SABRE Engine Technology| url=http://www.aviationweek.com/Blogs.aspx?plckPostId=Blog:04ce340e-4b63-4d23-9695-d49ab661f385Post:64760201-0b8f-4e1c-bd24-6bea77962435| publisher=[[Aviation Week]]| accessdate=8 December 2012| date=29 November 2012}}</ref><ref name=esar>{{cite web | url=http://ukspaceagency.bis.gov.uk/assets/ukspaceagency/docs/skylon-assessment-report-pub.pdf | title=Skylon Assessment Report | date=April 2011 | publisher=[[UK Space Agency]] | accessdate=26 April 2015 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013 the United Kingdom government announced further support for the development of a full-scale prototype of the SABRE engine,<ref>[http://www.sen.com/news/uk-pledges-fresh-support-for-revolutionary-space-engine.html \"UK pledges fresh support for revolutionary space engine\"] SEN. 27 June 2013. Retrieved 16 July 2013.</ref> providing \u00a360M of funding between 2014\u20132016<ref name = \"UKgovinvestBBC\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-23332592 \"UK government excited by 'disruptive' Sabre engine\"] [[BBC]]. 16 July 2013. Retrieved 16 July 2013.</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2013/jul/16/60m-space-rocket-engine | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=UK earmarks \u00a360m for super-fast space rocket engine | date=16 July 2013}}</ref> with the ESA providing an additional \u00a37M.<ref>[http://www.space.com/22004-skylon-space-plane-rocket-engine.html \"Futuristic British Space Plane Engine to Get Flight Test in 2020\"] space.com 18 July 2013. Retrieved 18 July 2013.</ref> The total cost of developing a test rig is estimated at \u00a3200M.<ref name=\"UKgovinvestBBC\"/>\n\nBy June 2015, SABRE's development continued with The Advanced Nozzle Project at Westcott. The test engine, operated by Airborne Engineering Ltd., is being used to analyze the [[aerodynamics]] and performance of the advanced nozzles that the SABRE engine will use, in addition to new manufacturing technologies such as the 3D-printed propellant injection system.<ref name='newsupdates Nov 2015'>{{cite web | url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/news_updates.html | title=BAE Systems and Reaction Engines to develop a ground breaking new aerospace engine | date=2 November 2015 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018192749/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/news_updates.html | archive-date=18 October 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, the SABRE engine concept passed a theoretical feasibility review conducted by the U.S. [[Air Force Research Laboratory]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Black| first=Charles |title=Revolutionary rocket engine passes U.S. Air Force feasibility test| url=http://sen.com/news/revolutionary-rocket-engine-passes-u-s-air-force-feasibility-test |accessdate=7 May 2015 |work= sen.com |date=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref>\"[http://www.theengineer.co.uk/aerospace/news/arfl-confirms-feasibility-of-reaction-engines-sabre-engine-concept/1020216.article ARFL confirms feasibility of Reaction Engines\u2019 SABRE engine concept]\"</ref><ref>\"[http://spacenews.com/afrl-gives-seal-of-approval-to-british-air-breathing-engine-design/ AFRL Gives Seal of Approval to British Air-breathing Engine Design]\"</ref> The laboratory was to reveal two-stage-to-orbit SABRE concepts shortly afterwards, as they considered that a single-stage-to-orbit Skylon space plane is \"technically very risky as a first application of SABRE engine\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/32115-skylon-space-plane-engines-air-force-vehicle.html |title=US Military Set to Unveil Concepts Based on Skylon Space Plane Tech |website=space.com|accessdate= 8 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015 the [[European Commission]] competition authority approved UK government funding of \u00a350 million for further development of the SABRE project. This was approved on the grounds that money raised from [[private equity]] had been insufficient to bring the project to completion.<ref>{{cite web|title=State aid: Commission approves \u00a350 million UK support for the research and development of an innovative space launcher engine|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-15-5495_en.htm|website=Europe.eu|publisher=European commission|accessdate=8 September 2015}}</ref> In October 2015 British company [[BAE Systems]] agreed to buy a 20% stake in the company for [[Pound sign|\u00a3]]20.6 million as part of an agreement to help develop the SABRE hypersonic engine.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://aviationweek.com/technology/bae-takes-stake-reaction-engines-hypersonic-development |title=BAE Takes Stake in Reaction Engines Hypersonic Development |last1=Norris |first1=Guy |date=1 November 2015 |website=aviationweek.com |publisher=Aviation Week & Space Technology |accessdate=1 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hollinger |first=Peggy |last2=Cookson |first2=Clive |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/11/02/bae-systems-to-pay-206m-for-20-of-space-engine-group.html |title=BAE Systems to pay \u00a320.6m for 20% of space engine group |work=CNBC |date=2 November 2015 |accessdate=5 November 2015 }}</ref>\nIn 2016, Reaction CEO Mark Thomas announced plans to build a quarter-sized ground test engine, given limitations of funding.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://aviationweek.com/technology/reaction-engines-refines-hypersonic-engine-demonstrator-plan |title=Reaction Engines Refines Hypersonic Engine Demonstrator Plan |last1=Norris |first1=Guy |date=21 September 2016 |website=aviationweek.com |publisher=Aviation Week & Space Technology |accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016 agents acting on behalf of Reaction Engines applied for planning consent to build a rocket engine test facility at the site of the former [[Rocket Propulsion Establishment]] in Westcott, UK<ref>https://publicaccess.aylesburyvaledc.gov.uk/online-applications/files/DFB7DF52C99227B18D89F8A79B37D276/pdf/16_03478_APP-APPLICATIONFORMNOPERSONALDATA-1596950.pdf{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> which was granted in April 2017,<ref>https://publicaccess.aylesburyvaledc.gov.uk/online-applications/files/9BFFC6D62D889B4C57727C889A3513B2/16_03478_APP-DECISION_NOTICE-1702440.rtf{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and in May 2017 a [[groundbreaking]] ceremony was held to announce the beginning of construction of the SABRE TF1 engine test facility, expected to become active in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/reaction-engines-begins-construction-uk-rocket-engine-test-facility/|title=Reaction Engines begins construction of UK rocket engine test facility \u2013 Reaction Engines|date=4 May 2017|website=ReactionEngines.co.uk|access-date=19 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222051252/https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/reaction-engines-begins-construction-uk-rocket-engine-test-facility/|archive-date=22 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/15268287.Space_plane_test_facility___39_up_and_running_by_2020__39_/|title=Space plane test facility 'up and running by 2020'|website=Oxford Mail|access-date=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017 it was announced the United States [[DARPA|Defence Advanced Research Projects Agency]] (DARPA) had contracted with Reaction Engines Inc. to build a high-temperature airflow test facility at Front Range Airport near Watkins, Colorado. The DARPA contract is to test the Sabre engine's pre-cooler heat exchanger (HTX). Construction of the test facilities and test articles began in 2018 with testing focusing on running the HTX at temperatures simulating air coming through a subsonic intake travelling at Mach{{nbsp}}5 or around {{convert|1800|F|C|-2}} beginning in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aviationweek.com/defense-space/space/reaction-begins-building-us-hypersonic-engine-test-site|title=Reaction Begins Building U.S. Hypersonic Engine Test Site &#124; Aviation Week Network|website=aviationweek.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-47585433|title=Super-fast engine set for key tests|first=Jonathan|last=Amos|date=15 March 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, the [[UK Space Agency|UKSA]] and ESA preliminary design review of the demonstrator engine core confirmed the test version to be ready for implementation.<ref>http://www.esa.int/Our_Activities/Space_Engineering_Technology/ESA_greenlight_for_UK_s_air-breathing_rocket_engine ESA greenlight for UK's air-breathing rocket engine</ref>\n\n===Engine===\n\nDue to the static thrust capability of the hybrid rocket engine, the vehicle can [[takeoff|take off]] under air-breathing mode, much like a conventional [[turbojet]].<ref name=\"user\" /> As the craft ascends and the outside air pressure drops, more and more air is passed into the compressor as the effectiveness of the ram compression drops. In this fashion the jets are able to operate to a much higher altitude than would normally be possible.\n\nAt Mach{{nbsp}}5.5 the air-breathing system becomes inefficient and is powered down, replaced by the on-board stored oxygen which allows the engine to accelerate to orbital velocities (around Mach{{nbsp}}25).<ref name=\"how\" />\n\n==Performance==\n\nThe designed [[thrust-to-weight ratio]] of SABRE is fourteen compared to about five for conventional jet engines, and two for [[scramjet]]s.<ref name=\"compare\" /> This high performance is a combination of the denser, cooled air, requiring less compression, and, more importantly, the low air temperatures permitting lighter alloys to be used in much of the engine. Overall performance is much better than the [[RB545]] engine or scramjets.\n\nFuel efficiency (known as [[specific impulse]] in rocket engines) peaks at about 3500&nbsp;[[Specific impulse#Units|seconds]] within the atmosphere.<ref name=\"user\" /> Typical all-rocket systems peak around 450 seconds and even \"typical\" [[nuclear thermal rocket]]s at about 900&nbsp;seconds.\n\nThe combination of high fuel efficiency and low-mass engines permits a SSTO approach, with air-breathing to Mach{{nbsp}}5.14+ at {{convert|28.5|km|feet|abbr=on}} altitude, and with the vehicle reaching orbit with more payload mass per take-off mass than just about any non-[[Nuclear pulse propulsion|nuclear]] launch vehicle ever proposed.{{citation needed|date=July 2013}}\n\nThe precooler adds mass and complexity to the system and is the most aggressive and difficult part of the design, but the mass of this heat exchanger is an order of magnitude lower than has been achieved previously. The experimental device achieved heat exchange of almost 1&nbsp;GW/m<sup>3</sup>. The losses from carrying the added weight of systems shut down during the closed cycle mode (namely the precooler and turbo-compressor) as well as the added weight of Skylon's wings are offset by the gains in overall efficiency and the proposed flight plan. Conventional launch vehicles such as the [[Space Shuttle]] spend about one-minute climbing almost vertically at relatively low speeds; this is inefficient but optimal for pure-rocket vehicles. In contrast, the SABRE engine permits a much slower, shallower climb (thirteen minutes to reach the 28.5&nbsp;km transition altitude), while breathing air and using its wings to support the vehicle. This trades gravity drag and an increase in vehicle weight for a reduction in propellant mass and a gain from aerodynamic lift increasing [[payload fraction]] to the level at which SSTO becomes possible.\n\nA hybrid jet engine like SABRE needs only reach low [[hypersonic]] speeds inside the [[Stratosphere|lower atmosphere]] before engaging its closed cycle mode, whilst climbing, to build speed. Unlike [[ramjet]] or [[scramjet]] engines, the design is able to provide high thrust from zero speed up to Mach{{nbsp}}5.4,<ref name=\"SABRE_page\"/> with excellent thrust over the entire flight, from the ground to very high altitude, with high efficiency throughout. In addition, this static thrust capability means the engine can be realistically tested on the ground, which drastically cuts testing costs.<ref name=\"compare\" />\n\nIn 2012, REL expected test flights by 2020, and operational flights by 2030.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/in-focus-british-engineers-crack-secret-of-reusab-379609/|title=IN FOCUS \u2013 British engineers 'crack secret of reusable spaceplane'|date=29 November 2012|website=FlightGlobal.com|access-date=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Resources==\n* {{cite web\n | title=The Skylon Space plane\n | url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/JBIS_v57_22-32.pdf\n |  | publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]]\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615104534/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/JBIS_v57_22-32.pdf\n |archivedate=15 June 2011 }}\n* {{cite web\n | title=The Skylon Spaceplane: Progress To Realisation\n | url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/The%20SKYLON%20Spaceplane-Progress%20to%20Realisation,%20JBIS,%202008.pdf\n | \n | publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]]\n | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615133300/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/The%20SKYLON%20Spaceplane-Progress%20to%20Realisation%2C%20JBIS%2C%202008.pdf\n | archive-date=15 June 2011\n | url-status=dead\n | df=dmy-all\n }}\n* {{cite web\n | title=A Comparison of Propulsions Concepts for SSTO Reusable launchers\n | url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/JBIS_v56_108-117.pdf\n |  | publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]]\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615104428/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/JBIS_v56_108-117.pdf\n |archivedate=15 June 2011 }}\n\n==See also==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Altitude compensating nozzle]]\n* [[Avatar (spacecraft)]] \u2013 India's air-breathing spaceplane\n* [[Liquid-propellant rocket]]\n* [[Precooled jet engine]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|SABRE (rocket engine)}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/sabre}}\n* {{cite web | title=This rocket engine could soon put planes in outer space (12 October 2015) | url=https://www.wired.co.uk/magazine/archive/2015/11/start/rocket-engine-planes-space | publisher=[[Wired UK]]}}\n* {{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/technology/reaction-engines-begins-test-facility-construction |title= Reaction Engines Begins Test Facility Construction |date= 4 May 2017 |author= Tony Osborne |work= Aerospace Daily & Defense Report |publisher= Aviation Week}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=srZzRVNj6uI TF1 time lapse \u2013 August 2018]\n\n{{Reaction Engines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reaction Engines Sabre}}\n[[Category:Rocket engines using hydrogen propellant]]\n[[Category:Rocket engines of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Jet engines]]\n[[Category:Ramjet engines]]\n[[Category:Proposed engines]]\n[[Category:Rocket engines using the staged combustion cycle]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Sabre (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox rocket engine\n |image                      = Sabre-model.jpg\n |image_size                 = 250px\n |caption                    = A model of SABRE\n |name                       = Reaction Engines SABRE\n |country_of_origin          = [[United Kingdom]]\n |designer                   = [[Reaction Engines Limited]]\n |purpose                    = [[Single-stage-to-orbit]]\n |predecessor                = [[RB545]]\n |associated                 = [[Skylon (spacecraft)|Skylon]]\n |status                     = [[Research and development]]\n |type                       = liquid\n |fuel                       = [[liquid hydrogen]]<ref name=\"names\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/downloads/REL_Engine_Names.pdf |title=Reaction Engines Limited Engine Names\n|publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120305234315/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/downloads/REL_Engine_Names.pdf |archive-date=5 March 2012 }}</ref>\n |oxidiser                   = [[Air]] or [[liquid oxygen]]\n |cycle                      = Combined cycle [[precooled jet engine]] and [[closed cycle rocket engine]]\n |thrust(SL)                 = Approx. {{convert|1960|kN|abbr=on}}{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n |thrust(Vac)                = Approx. {{convert|2940|kN|abbr=on}}{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n |specific_impulse_vacuum    = {{convert|460|isp}}<ref name=\"user\"/>\n |specific_impulse_sea_level = {{convert|3600|isp|tsfc+km/s}}<ref name=\"user\"/>\n |thrust_to_weight           = Up to 14 (atmospheric)<ref name=\"precooled\"/>\n}}\n'''SABRE''' ('''Synergetic Air Breathing Rocket Engine'''<ref name=\"SABRE_page\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/sabre |title=SABRE \u2013 Synergetic Air Breathing Rocket Engine|publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]] |access-date=18 December 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219091110/https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/sabre |archive-date=19 December 2018 }}</ref>) is a concept under development by [[Reaction Engines Limited]] for a [[hypersonic]] [[precooled jet engine|precooled]] hybrid [[Engine#Heat engine|air-breathing]] [[rocket engine]].<ref name=\"compare\">{{cite web | title=A Comparison of Propulsions Concepts for SSTO Reusable launchers | url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/JBIS_v56_108-117.pdf |  | publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]] | pages=114, 115 | access-date=2 August 2010 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615104428/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/JBIS_v56_108-117.pdf | archive-date=15 June 2011 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=lapcat>{{Cite web\n\n  |title=Flight Applications\n  |publisher=[[Reaction Engines]]\n  |url=https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/sabre/flight-applications\n}}</ref> The engine is being designed to achieve [[single-stage-to-orbit]] capability, propelling the proposed [[Skylon (spacecraft)|Skylon]] [[spaceplane]] to low Earth orbit. SABRE is an evolution of [[Alan Bond (engineer)|Alan Bond]]'s series of [[liquid air cycle engine]] (LACE) and LACE-like designs that started in the early/mid-1980s for the [[HOTOL]] project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/45136248|title=Alan Bond Interview|website=Vimeo|access-date=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe design comprises a single [[combined cycle]] rocket engine with two modes of operation.<ref name=\"user\">{{cite web | url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/SKYLON_User_Manual_rev1-1.pdf | title=Skylon Users' Manual | date=18 January 2010 | publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]] | pages=4, 3 | access-date=2 August 2010 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418035934/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/SKYLON_User_Manual_rev1-1.pdf | archive-date=18 April 2016 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The air-breathing mode combines a turbo-[[Gas compressor|compressor]] with a lightweight air [[Precooled jet engine|precooler]] positioned just behind the [[inlet cone]]. At high speeds this precooler cools the hot, ram-compressed air, which would otherwise reach a temperature that the engine could not withstand,<ref name=precooling>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-47832920 |title=UK's Sabre space plane engine tech in new milestone|website=BBC News|date= 8 April 2019}}</ref> leading to a very high [[Overall pressure ratio|pressure ratio]] within the engine. The compressed air is subsequently fed into the rocket [[combustion chamber]] where it is ignited along with stored [[liquid hydrogen]]. The high pressure ratio allows the engine to provide high thrust at very high speeds and altitudes. The low temperature of the air permits light alloy construction to be employed and allow a very lightweight engine\u2014essential for reaching orbit. In addition, unlike the LACE concept, SABRE's precooler does not [[Liquid air|liquefy the air]], letting it run more efficiently.<ref name=\"precooled\">{{cite web | url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/JBIS_v60_188-196.pdf | title=The Sensitivity of Precooled Air-Breathing Engine Performance to Heat Exchanger Design Parameters | date=29 March 2007 | publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]] | page=189 | access-date=9 August 2010 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130623100631/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/JBIS_v60_188-196.pdf | archive-date=23 June 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAfter shutting the inlet cone off at [[Mach number|Mach]]&nbsp;5.14, and at an altitude of 28.5&nbsp;km,<ref name=\"user\" /> the system continues as a [[staged combustion cycle (rocket)|closed-cycle]] high-performance rocket engine burning [[liquid oxygen]] and [[liquid hydrogen]] from on-board fuel tanks, potentially allowing a hybrid [[spaceplane]] concept like [[Skylon (spacecraft)|Skylon]] to reach orbital velocity after leaving the atmosphere on a steep climb.\n\nAn engine derived from the SABRE concept called [[Reaction Engines Scimitar|Scimitar]] has been designed for the company's [[Reaction Engines A2|A2]] [[Supersonic transport|hypersonic passenger jet]] proposal for the [[European Union]]-funded [[LAPCAT]] study.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/about/story-so-far |title=Reaction Engines has reached a number of high profile milestones|website=Reaction Engines|date=2018|accessdate= 8 April 2019}}</ref>\n{{toclimit|3}}\n\n==History==\nThe precooler concept evolved from an idea originated by Robert P. Carmichael in 1955.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hq.nasa.gov/pao/History/SP-4404/ch7-13.htm |title=Liquid Hydrogen as a Propulsion Fuel, 1945\u20131959 |publisher=NASA History Division |accessdate=1 July 2009 }}</ref> This was followed by the [[liquid air cycle engine]] (LACE) idea which was originally explored by [[General Dynamics]] in the 1960s as part of the [[US Air Force]]'s [[aerospaceplane]] efforts.<ref name=\"precooled\" />\n\nThe LACE system was to be placed behind a supersonic air intake which would compress the air through ram compression, then a [[heat exchanger]] would rapidly cool it using some of the [[liquid hydrogen]] fuel stored on board. The resulting liquid air was then processed to separate the [[liquid oxygen]] for combustion. The amount of warmed hydrogen was too great to burn with the oxygen, so most was to be expelled, giving useful thrust, but greatly reducing the potential efficiency.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\nInstead, as part of the [[HOTOL]] project, the liquid air cycle engine (LACE) based [[RB545]] engine was developed with more efficient cycle. The engine was given the Rolls Royce name \"Swallow\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2009/02/23/322955/secret-files-reveal-us-interest-in-uk-hotol-spaceplane.html|title=News Channel - Homepage - flightglobal.com|website=FlightGlobal.com|access-date=19 December 2017}}</ref> In 1989, after funding for HOTOL ceased, Bond and several others formed [[Reaction Engines Limited]] to continue research. The RB545's precooler had issues with [[Hydrogen embrittlement|embrittlement]] and excess liquid hydrogen consumption, and was encumbered by both patents and the UK's [[Official Secrets Act]], so Bond developed SABRE instead.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.daviddarling.info/encyclopedia/B/Bond.html | title=A. Bond | work=daviddarling.info |accessdate=8 August 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 the project received \u00a360m in funds from the UK government and ESA for a demonstrator involving the full cycle.<ref name=\"bbc_12July2016\">{{cite news|title=Funding flows for UK\u2019s 'revolutionary' Sabre rocket engine|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-36773074|accessdate=12 July 2016|work=Science|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=12 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Concept==\n\n[[File:Sabre cycle m.jpg|thumb|right|Simplified flow diagram of SABRE engine]]\nLike the [[RB545]], the SABRE design is neither a conventional [[rocket engine]] nor a conventional [[turbojet|jet engine]], but a hybrid that uses air from the environment at low speeds/altitudes, and stored [[liquid oxygen]] at higher altitude. The SABRE engine \"relies on a heat exchanger capable of cooling incoming air to {{convert|-150|C}}, to provide oxygen for mixing with hydrogen and provide jet thrust during atmospheric flight before switching to tanked liquid oxygen when in space.\"\n\nIn air-breathing mode, air enters the engine through an inlet. A bypass system directs some of the air through a precooler into a compressor, which injects it into a combustion chamber where it is burnt with fuel, the exhaust products are accelerated through nozzles to provide thrust. The remainder of the intake air continues through the bypass system to a ring of flame holders which act as a ramjet for part of the air breathing flight regime. A helium loop is used to transfer the heat from the precooler to the fuel and drive the engine pumps and compressors.\n\n===Inlet===\n\nAt the front of the engine, the concept designs propose a simple translating axisymmetric [[Inlet cone|shock cone inlet]] which compresses and slows the air (relative to the engine) to subsonic speeds using two shock reflections. Accelerating the air to the speed of the engine incurs [[ram drag]]. As a result of the shocks, compression, and acceleration the intake air is heated, reaching around {{convert|1000|C|F}} at Mach{{nbsp}}5.5.\n\n[[Bayern-Chemie]], through ESA, have undertaken work to refine and test the intake and bypass systems<ref name=BayernChemieSabreDevelopment>{{Cite web|url=https://bayern-chemie.com/bayern-chemie-concludes-agreement-with-european-space-agency-on-the-further-development-of-sabre-engine/|title=BAYERN-CHEMIE concludes agreement with European Space Agency on the further development of SABRE engine}}</ref>\n\n===Precooler===\n\nAs the air enters the engine at [[supersonic]] or [[hypersonic]] speeds, it becomes hotter than the engine can withstand due to compression effects.<ref name=precooling/> [[Jet engines]], which have the same problem but to a lesser degree, solve it by using heavy [[copper]] or [[nickel]]-based materials, by reducing the engine's [[Overall pressure ratio|pressure ratio]], and by throttling back the engine at the higher airspeeds to avoid melting. However, for a [[single-stage-to-orbit]] (SSTO) spaceplane, such heavy materials are unusable, and maximum thrust is necessary for orbital insertion at the earliest time to minimise [[gravity drag|gravity losses]]. Instead, using a gaseous [[helium]] coolant loop, SABRE dramatically cools the air from {{cvt|1000|C}} down to {{cvt|\u2212150|C}} in a heat exchanger while avoiding [[liquid air|liquefaction]] of the air or blockage from freezing water vapour.\n\nPrevious versions of precoolers such as HOTOL put the hydrogen fuel directly through the precooler. SABRE inserts a helium cooling loop between the air and the cold fuel to avoid problems with [[hydrogen embrittlement]] in the precooler.\n\nThe dramatic cooling of the air created a potential problem: it is necessary to prevent blocking the precooler from frozen water vapour and other air fractions. In October 2012, the cooling solution was demonstrated for 6 minutes using freezing air.<ref>{{cite web| last=Marks| first=Paul| title=Die Erben der Concorde| url=http://www.new-scientist.de/inhalt/hyperschallflugzeuge-die-erben-der-concorde-a-860705.html| publisher=[[New Scientist]]| access-date=10 December 2012| language=German| date=October 2012| url-status=dead| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121124100307/http://www.new-scientist.de/inhalt/hyperschallflugzeuge-die-erben-der-concorde-a-860705.html| archive-date=24 November 2012| df=dmy-all}} [https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=de&u=http://www.new-scientist.de/inhalt/hyperschallflugzeuge-die-erben-der-concorde-a-860705.html&prev=/search%3Fq%3D%2522mark%2Bford%2522%2Bestec%2Bsabre%26start%3D10%26hl%3Den%26safe%3Doff%26sa%3DN%26tbo%3Dd%26rls%3Dcom.microsoft:en-US:%257Breferrer:source%257D%26biw%3D1200%26bih%3D1805&sa=X&ei=4GHGUJmcIvH44QSckoHoCQ&ved=0CDEQ7gEwADgK In English]</ref> The cooler consists of a fine pipework heat exchanger with 16,800 thin-walled tubes,<ref name=AvWeek7apr2019/> and cools the hot in-rushing atmospheric air down to the required {{cvt|\u2212150|C}} in 0.01{{nbsp}}s.<ref>{{cite news| last=Amos |first=Jonathan |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-20510112 |title=BBC News \u2013 Skylon spaceplane engine concept achieves key milestone |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=28 November 2012 |accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref> The ice prevention system had been a closely guarded secret, but REL disclosed a [[methanol]]-injecting 3D-printed de-icer in 2015 through patents, as they needed partner companies and could not keep the secret while working closely with outsiders.<ref>Norris, Guy. \"[https://awin.aviationweek.com/ArticlesStory.aspx?id=ae0e5600-45e8-4259-9000-9f9c2d14c448 Reaction Engines Reveals Secret Of Sabre Frost Control Technology]{{dead link|date=September 2017|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}\" ''[[Aviation Week & Space Technology|Aerospace Daily & Defense Report]]'', 8 July 2015, p. 3 [https://awin.aviationweek.com/ArticlesStory.aspx?id=ae0e5600-45e8-4259-9000-9f9c2d14c448 Similar article]{{dead link|date=September 2017|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}} <!--paywall: http://aviationweek.com/technology/reaction-engines-reveals-inner-secret-sabre-propulsion-technology --></ref><ref>\"[http://www.engineering.com/3DPrinting/3DPrintingArticles/ArticleID/10407/The-Skylon-Spaceplanes-3D-Printed-Injector.aspx The Skylon Spaceplane's 3D Printed Injector]\"</ref><ref>\"[http://3dprint.com/81151/skylon-spaceplane-3d-printing/ Helping the Skylon Spaceplane Reach Orbit with a 3D Printed Injector Mechanism]\"</ref>\n\nIn September 2017 it was announced United States Defense Advanced Research projects (DARPA) had contracted with Reaction Engines Inc to build a high-temperature airflow test facility at Front Range Airport near Watkins, Colorado. The DARPA contract is to test the Sabre engine's precooler heat exchanger (HTX).\n\nThe test work which started in 2018 focussed on running the heat exchanger at temperatures simulating Mach{{nbsp}}5 of over {{convert|1000|C}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviationweek.com/space/reaction-begins-building-us-hypersonic-engine-test-site |title=Reaction Begins Building U.S. Hypersonic Engine Test Site |work= Aviation Week |date= 18 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/reaction-engines-awarded-darpa-contract-to-perform-high-temperature-testing-of-the-sabre-precooler/|title=Reaction Engines Awarded DARPA Contract to Perform High-Temperature Testing of the SABRE Precooler \u2013 Reaction Engines|date=25 September 2017|website=ReactionEngines.co.uk|access-date=19 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928232712/https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/reaction-engines-awarded-darpa-contract-to-perform-high-temperature-testing-of-the-sabre-precooler/|archive-date=28 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe HTX test unit was completed in the UK and sent to Colorado in 2018, where on 25 March 2019 a [[F-4]] GE [[J79]] turbojet exhaust was mixed with ambient air to replicate Mach{{nbsp}}3.3 inlet conditions, successfully quenching a {{cvt|420|C}} stream of gases to {{cvt|100|C}} in less than 1/20th of a second. Further tests simulating Mach{{nbsp}}5 were planned, with temperature reduction expected from {{cvt|1000|C}}.<ref name=precooling/><ref name=AvWeek7apr2019>{{cite news |url= https://aviationweek.com/space/reaction-engines-pre-cooler-passes-mach-33-test |title= Reaction Engines Pre-Cooler Passes Mach 3.3 Test |date= 7 April 2019 |author= Guy Norris |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref> These further tests were successfuly completed by October 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=REACTION ENGINES TEST PROGRAMME FULLY VALIDATES PRECOOLER AT HYPERSONIC HEAT CONDITIONS |url=https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/news/reaction-engines-test-programme-fully-validates-precooler-hypersonic-heat-conditions |website=Reaction Engines |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Reaction Engines' precooler tech demo chills 1,000\u00b0C air in less than 1/20th of a second |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2019/10/22/reaction_engines_precooler_demo_mach_5/ |website=The Register |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Skylon\u2019s SABRE Engine Passes a Big Test |url=https://www.universetoday.com/143810/skylons-sabre-engine-passes-a-big-test/ |website=Universe Today |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe successful HTX test could lead to spin-off precooler applications which could be developed before a scalable SABRE demonstrator is completed; suggested uses are to expand [[gas turbine]]s capabilities, in advanced [[turbofan]]s, hypersonic vehicles, and industrial applications.<ref name=AvWeek15May2018>{{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/defense/turbojet-runs-precursor-hypersonic-engine-heat-exchanger-tests |title= Turbojet Runs Precursor to Hypersonic Engine Heat Exchanger Tests |date= 15 May 2018 |author= Guy Norris |work= Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref>\n\n===Compressor===\nBelow five times the [[speed of sound]] and 25 kilometres of altitude, which are 20% of the speed and 20% of the altitude needed to reach [[orbit]], the cooled air from the precooler passes into a modified turbo-[[Gas compressor|compressor]], similar in design to those used on conventional jet engines but running at an unusually high [[overall pressure ratio|pressure ratio]] made possible by the low temperature of the inlet air. The compressor feeds the compressed air at 140 [[Atmospheres (unit)|atmospheres]] into the combustion chambers of the main engines.<ref name=\"how\">{{cite web |url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/sabre_howworks.html |title=SABRE: how it works |publisher=Reaction Engines Limited |access-date=29 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130726014458/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/sabre_howworks.html |archive-date=26 July 2013  }}</ref>\n\nThe turbo-compressor is powered by a [[gas turbine]] running on a helium loop, rather than by combustion gases as in a conventional jet engine. The turbo-compressor is powered by waste heat collected by the helium loop.<ref name=\"how\" />\n\n====Helium loop====\n\nThe 'hot' helium from the air precooler is recycled by cooling it in a heat exchanger with the liquid hydrogen fuel. The loop forms a self-starting [[Brayton cycle]] engine, cooling critical parts of the engine and powering turbines.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}} The heat passes from the air into the helium. This heat energy is used to power various parts of the engine and to vaporise hydrogen, which is then burnt in [[ramjet]]s.<ref name=\"user\" /><ref name=\"Reactionengines.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/faq.html#q5 |title=Reaction Engines Ltd \u2013 Frequently Asked Questions |publisher=Reactionengines.co.uk |access-date=1 July 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150602004107/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/faq.html#q5 |archive-date=2 June 2015  }}</ref>\n\n===Combustion chambers===\n\nThe combustion chambers in the SABRE engine are cooled by the oxidant (air/liquid oxygen) rather than by liquid hydrogen<ref name=\"uksa\">{{cite web | url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2009/6200.html | title=The rocket that thinks it's a jet | date=19 February 2009| publisher=[[UK Space Agency]] | accessdate=5 November 2015 }}</ref> to further reduce the system's use of liquid hydrogen compared with [[Air-fuel ratio|stoichiometric]] systems.\n\n===Nozzles===\nThe most efficient atmospheric pressure at which a conventional [[propelling nozzle]] works is set by the [[geometry]] of the [[De Laval nozzle|nozzle bell]]. While the geometry of the conventional bell remains static the [[Atmospheric pressure#Altitude atmospheric pressure variation|atmospheric pressure changes with altitude]] and therefore nozzles designed for high performance in the lower atmosphere lose efficiency as they reach higher altitudes. In traditional rockets this is overcome by using multiple stages designed for the atmospheric pressures they encounter. \n\nThe SABRE engine must operate at both low and high altitude scenarios. To ensure efficiency at all altitudes a sort of moving, [[Expanding nozzle]] is used. First at low altitude, jet powered flight the bell is located rearwards, connected to a toroidal combustion chamber surrounding the central rocket combustion chamber. When SABRE then later transitions into rocket mode, the bell is moved forwards, extending the length of the bell of the inner rocket combustion chamber, creating a much larger, high altitude nozzle for more efficient flight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patents.google.com/patent/US20150101337A1/en|title=Nozzle arrangement for an engine}}</ref>\n[[File:SABRE_Air_breathing_nozzle_mode.png|thumb|168x168px|Nozzle in Air Breathing Mode]]\n[[File:SABRE_Rocket_nozzle_mode.png|thumb|186x186px|Nozzle in Rocket mode]]\n\n===Bypass burners===\n\nAvoiding [[Liquid air|liquefaction]] improves the efficiency of the engine since less [[entropy]] is generated and therefore less liquid hydrogen is boiled off. However, simply cooling the air needs more liquid hydrogen than can be burnt in the engine core. The excess is expelled through a series of burners called \"spill duct [[ramjet]] burners\",<ref name=\"user\" /><ref name=\"Reactionengines.co.uk\"/> that are arranged in a ring around the central core. These are fed air that bypasses the precooler. This bypass ramjet system is designed to reduce the negative effects of drag resulting from air that passes into the intakes but is not fed into the main rocket engine, rather than generating thrust. At low speeds the ratio of the volume of air entering the intake to the volume that the compressor can feed to the combustion chamber is at its highest, requiring the bypassed air to be accelerated to maintain efficiency at these low speeds. This distinguishes the system from a [[Air turborocket#Types|turboramjet]] where a turbine-cycle's exhaust is used to increase air-flow for the ramjet to become efficient enough to take over the role of primary propulsion.<ref>{{cite web | title=Travelling at the edge of space: Reaction Engines and Skylon in the next 20 years | url=http://ewds.strath.ac.uk/space/OnDemandSeminar/tabid/4560/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/288/Travelling-at-the-edge-of-space--10-March-2010.aspx | publisher=[[University of Strathclyde]] | access-date=9 August 2010 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310093203/http://ewds.strath.ac.uk/space/OnDemandSeminar/tabid/4560/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/288/Travelling-at-the-edge-of-space--10-March-2010.aspx | archive-date=10 March 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n[[File:SABRE ENGINE.jpg|thumb|The latest SABRE engine's design.]]\nTests were carried out in 2008 by Airbourne Engineering Ltd on an [[expansion deflection nozzle]] called STERN to provide the data needed to develop an accurate engineering model to overcome the problem of non-dynamic exhaust expansion. This research continued with the STRICT nozzle in 2011.\n\nSuccessful tests of an oxidiser (both air and oxygen) cooled combustion chamber were conducted by EADS-Astrium at [[Lampoldshausen|Institute of Space Propulsion]] in 2010\n\nIn 2011, hardware testing of the heat exchanger technology \"crucial to [the] hybrid air- and liquid oxygen-breathing [SABRE] rocket motor\" was completed, demonstrating that the technology is viable.<ref name=\"precooltest\" /><ref name=\"fg20110901\">{{cite news |last=Thisdell| first=Dan |title= Spaceplane engine tests under way |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/spaceplane-engine-tests-under-way-361501/ |accessdate=4 November 2015 |newspaper=Flightglobal News |date=1 September 2011}}</ref> The tests validated that the heat exchanger could perform as needed for the engine to obtain adequate oxygen from the atmosphere to support the low-altitude, high-performance operation.<ref name=\"precooltest\" /><ref name=\"fg20110901\" />\n\nIn November 2012, Reaction Engines announced it had successfully concluded a series of tests that prove the cooling technology of the engine, one of the main obstacles towards the completion of the project. The [[European Space Agency]] (ESA) evaluated the SABRE engine's precooler heat exchanger, and accepted claims that the technologies required to proceed with the engine's development had been fully demonstrated.<ref name=\"precooltest\">{{cite web |url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/press_release/PRESS%20RELEASE%20-%20THE%20BIGGESTBREAKTHROUGH%20IN%20PROPULSION%20-%2028%20November%202012.pdf |title=The biggest breakthrough in propulsion since the jet engine | |publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]] |date=28 November 2012 |author=Reaction Engines Limited |access-date=28 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121207125042/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/press_release/PRESS%20RELEASE%20-%20THE%20BIGGESTBREAKTHROUGH%20IN%20PROPULSION%20-%2028%20November%202012.pdf |archive-date=7 December 2012  }}</ref><ref name=\"avEsa\">{{cite web| last=Svitak| first=Amy| title=ESA Validates SABRE Engine Technology| url=http://www.aviationweek.com/Blogs.aspx?plckPostId=Blog:04ce340e-4b63-4d23-9695-d49ab661f385Post:64760201-0b8f-4e1c-bd24-6bea77962435| publisher=[[Aviation Week]]| accessdate=8 December 2012| date=29 November 2012}}</ref><ref name=esar>{{cite web | url=http://ukspaceagency.bis.gov.uk/assets/ukspaceagency/docs/skylon-assessment-report-pub.pdf | title=Skylon Assessment Report | date=April 2011 | publisher=[[UK Space Agency]] | accessdate=26 April 2015 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013 the United Kingdom government announced further support for the development of a full-scale prototype of the SABRE engine,<ref>[http://www.sen.com/news/uk-pledges-fresh-support-for-revolutionary-space-engine.html \"UK pledges fresh support for revolutionary space engine\"] SEN. 27 June 2013. Retrieved 16 July 2013.</ref> providing \u00a360M of funding between 2014\u20132016<ref name = \"UKgovinvestBBC\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-23332592 \"UK government excited by 'disruptive' Sabre engine\"] [[BBC]]. 16 July 2013. Retrieved 16 July 2013.</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2013/jul/16/60m-space-rocket-engine | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=UK earmarks \u00a360m for super-fast space rocket engine | date=16 July 2013}}</ref> with the ESA providing an additional \u00a37M.<ref>[http://www.space.com/22004-skylon-space-plane-rocket-engine.html \"Futuristic British Space Plane Engine to Get Flight Test in 2020\"] space.com 18 July 2013. Retrieved 18 July 2013.</ref> The total cost of developing a test rig is estimated at \u00a3200M.<ref name=\"UKgovinvestBBC\"/>\n\nBy June 2015, SABRE's development continued with The Advanced Nozzle Project at Westcott. The test engine, operated by Airborne Engineering Ltd., is being used to analyze the [[aerodynamics]] and performance of the advanced nozzles that the SABRE engine will use, in addition to new manufacturing technologies such as the 3D-printed propellant injection system.<ref name='newsupdates Nov 2015'>{{cite web | url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/news_updates.html | title=BAE Systems and Reaction Engines to develop a ground breaking new aerospace engine | date=2 November 2015 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018192749/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/news_updates.html | archive-date=18 October 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, the SABRE engine concept passed a theoretical feasibility review conducted by the U.S. [[Air Force Research Laboratory]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Black| first=Charles |title=Revolutionary rocket engine passes U.S. Air Force feasibility test| url=http://sen.com/news/revolutionary-rocket-engine-passes-u-s-air-force-feasibility-test |accessdate=7 May 2015 |work= sen.com |date=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref>\"[http://www.theengineer.co.uk/aerospace/news/arfl-confirms-feasibility-of-reaction-engines-sabre-engine-concept/1020216.article ARFL confirms feasibility of Reaction Engines\u2019 SABRE engine concept]\"</ref><ref>\"[http://spacenews.com/afrl-gives-seal-of-approval-to-british-air-breathing-engine-design/ AFRL Gives Seal of Approval to British Air-breathing Engine Design]\"</ref> The laboratory was to reveal two-stage-to-orbit SABRE concepts shortly afterwards, as they considered that a single-stage-to-orbit Skylon space plane is \"technically very risky as a first application of SABRE engine\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.space.com/32115-skylon-space-plane-engines-air-force-vehicle.html |title=US Military Set to Unveil Concepts Based on Skylon Space Plane Tech |website=space.com|accessdate= 8 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015 the [[European Commission]] competition authority approved UK government funding of \u00a350 million for further development of the SABRE project. This was approved on the grounds that money raised from [[private equity]] had been insufficient to bring the project to completion.<ref>{{cite web|title=State aid: Commission approves \u00a350 million UK support for the research and development of an innovative space launcher engine|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_IP-15-5495_en.htm|website=Europe.eu|publisher=European commission|accessdate=8 September 2015}}</ref> In October 2015 British company [[BAE Systems]] agreed to buy a 20% stake in the company for [[Pound sign|\u00a3]]20.6 million as part of an agreement to help develop the SABRE hypersonic engine.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://aviationweek.com/technology/bae-takes-stake-reaction-engines-hypersonic-development |title=BAE Takes Stake in Reaction Engines Hypersonic Development |last1=Norris |first1=Guy |date=1 November 2015 |website=aviationweek.com |publisher=Aviation Week & Space Technology |accessdate=1 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hollinger |first=Peggy |last2=Cookson |first2=Clive |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/11/02/bae-systems-to-pay-206m-for-20-of-space-engine-group.html |title=BAE Systems to pay \u00a320.6m for 20% of space engine group |work=CNBC |date=2 November 2015 |accessdate=5 November 2015 }}</ref>\nIn 2016, Reaction CEO Mark Thomas announced plans to build a quarter-sized ground test engine, given limitations of funding.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://aviationweek.com/technology/reaction-engines-refines-hypersonic-engine-demonstrator-plan |title=Reaction Engines Refines Hypersonic Engine Demonstrator Plan |last1=Norris |first1=Guy |date=21 September 2016 |website=aviationweek.com |publisher=Aviation Week & Space Technology |accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016 agents acting on behalf of Reaction Engines applied for planning consent to build a rocket engine test facility at the site of the former [[Rocket Propulsion Establishment]] in Westcott, UK<ref>https://publicaccess.aylesburyvaledc.gov.uk/online-applications/files/DFB7DF52C99227B18D89F8A79B37D276/pdf/16_03478_APP-APPLICATIONFORMNOPERSONALDATA-1596950.pdf{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> which was granted in April 2017,<ref>https://publicaccess.aylesburyvaledc.gov.uk/online-applications/files/9BFFC6D62D889B4C57727C889A3513B2/16_03478_APP-DECISION_NOTICE-1702440.rtf{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and in May 2017 a [[groundbreaking]] ceremony was held to announce the beginning of construction of the SABRE TF1 engine test facility, expected to become active in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/reaction-engines-begins-construction-uk-rocket-engine-test-facility/|title=Reaction Engines begins construction of UK rocket engine test facility \u2013 Reaction Engines|date=4 May 2017|website=ReactionEngines.co.uk|access-date=19 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222051252/https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/reaction-engines-begins-construction-uk-rocket-engine-test-facility/|archive-date=22 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/15268287.Space_plane_test_facility___39_up_and_running_by_2020__39_/|title=Space plane test facility 'up and running by 2020'|website=Oxford Mail|access-date=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017 it was announced the United States [[DARPA|Defence Advanced Research Projects Agency]] (DARPA) had contracted with Reaction Engines Inc. to build a high-temperature airflow test facility at Front Range Airport near Watkins, Colorado. The DARPA contract is to test the Sabre engine's pre-cooler heat exchanger (HTX). Construction of the test facilities and test articles began in 2018 with testing focusing on running the HTX at temperatures simulating air coming through a subsonic intake travelling at Mach{{nbsp}}5 or around {{convert|1800|F|C|-2}} beginning in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aviationweek.com/defense-space/space/reaction-begins-building-us-hypersonic-engine-test-site|title=Reaction Begins Building U.S. Hypersonic Engine Test Site &#124; Aviation Week Network|website=aviationweek.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-47585433|title=Super-fast engine set for key tests|first=Jonathan|last=Amos|date=15 March 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, the [[UK Space Agency|UKSA]] and ESA preliminary design review of the demonstrator engine core confirmed the test version to be ready for implementation.<ref>http://www.esa.int/Our_Activities/Space_Engineering_Technology/ESA_greenlight_for_UK_s_air-breathing_rocket_engine ESA greenlight for UK's air-breathing rocket engine</ref>\n\n===Engine===\n\nDue to the static thrust capability of the hybrid rocket engine, the vehicle can [[takeoff|take off]] under air-breathing mode, much like a conventional [[turbojet]].<ref name=\"user\" /> As the craft ascends and the outside air pressure drops, more and more air is passed into the compressor as the effectiveness of the ram compression drops. In this fashion the jets are able to operate to a much higher altitude than would normally be possible.\n\nAt Mach{{nbsp}}5.5 the air-breathing system becomes inefficient and is powered down, replaced by the on-board stored oxygen which allows the engine to accelerate to orbital velocities (around Mach{{nbsp}}25).<ref name=\"how\" />\n\n==Performance==\n\nThe designed [[thrust-to-weight ratio]] of SABRE is fourteen compared to about five for conventional jet engines, and two for [[scramjet]]s.<ref name=\"compare\" /> This high performance is a combination of the denser, cooled air, requiring less compression, and, more importantly, the low air temperatures permitting lighter alloys to be used in much of the engine. Overall performance is much better than the [[RB545]] engine or scramjets.\n\nFuel efficiency (known as [[specific impulse]] in rocket engines) peaks at about 3500&nbsp;[[Specific impulse#Units|seconds]] within the atmosphere.<ref name=\"user\" /> Typical all-rocket systems peak around 450 seconds and even \"typical\" [[nuclear thermal rocket]]s at about 900&nbsp;seconds.\n\nThe combination of high fuel efficiency and low-mass engines permits a SSTO approach, with air-breathing to Mach{{nbsp}}5.14+ at {{convert|28.5|km|feet|abbr=on}} altitude, and with the vehicle reaching orbit with more payload mass per take-off mass than just about any non-[[Nuclear pulse propulsion|nuclear]] launch vehicle ever proposed.{{citation needed|date=July 2013}}\n\nThe precooler adds mass and complexity to the system and is the most aggressive and difficult part of the design, but the mass of this heat exchanger is an order of magnitude lower than has been achieved previously. The experimental device achieved heat exchange of almost 1&nbsp;GW/m<sup>3</sup>. The losses from carrying the added weight of systems shut down during the closed cycle mode (namely the precooler and turbo-compressor) as well as the added weight of Skylon's wings are offset by the gains in overall efficiency and the proposed flight plan. Conventional launch vehicles such as the [[Space Shuttle]] spend about one-minute climbing almost vertically at relatively low speeds; this is inefficient but optimal for pure-rocket vehicles. In contrast, the SABRE engine permits a much slower, shallower climb (thirteen minutes to reach the 28.5&nbsp;km transition altitude), while breathing air and using its wings to support the vehicle. This trades gravity drag and an increase in vehicle weight for a reduction in propellant mass and a gain from aerodynamic lift increasing [[payload fraction]] to the level at which SSTO becomes possible.\n\nA hybrid jet engine like SABRE needs only reach low [[hypersonic]] speeds inside the [[Stratosphere|lower atmosphere]] before engaging its closed cycle mode, whilst climbing, to build speed. Unlike [[ramjet]] or [[scramjet]] engines, the design is able to provide high thrust from zero speed up to Mach{{nbsp}}5.4,<ref name=\"SABRE_page\"/> with excellent thrust over the entire flight, from the ground to very high altitude, with high efficiency throughout. In addition, this static thrust capability means the engine can be realistically tested on the ground, which drastically cuts testing costs.<ref name=\"compare\" />\n\nIn 2012, REL expected test flights by 2020, and operational flights by 2030.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/in-focus-british-engineers-crack-secret-of-reusab-379609/|title=IN FOCUS \u2013 British engineers 'crack secret of reusable spaceplane'|date=29 November 2012|website=FlightGlobal.com|access-date=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Resources==\n* {{cite web\n | title=The Skylon Space plane\n | url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/JBIS_v57_22-32.pdf\n |  | publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]]\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615104534/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/JBIS_v57_22-32.pdf\n |archivedate=15 June 2011 }}\n* {{cite web\n | title=The Skylon Spaceplane: Progress To Realisation\n | url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/The%20SKYLON%20Spaceplane-Progress%20to%20Realisation,%20JBIS,%202008.pdf\n | \n | publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]]\n | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615133300/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/The%20SKYLON%20Spaceplane-Progress%20to%20Realisation%2C%20JBIS%2C%202008.pdf\n | archive-date=15 June 2011\n | url-status=dead\n | df=dmy-all\n }}\n* {{cite web\n | title=A Comparison of Propulsions Concepts for SSTO Reusable launchers\n | url=http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/JBIS_v56_108-117.pdf\n |  | publisher=[[Reaction Engines Limited]]\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615104428/http://www.reactionengines.co.uk/tech_docs/JBIS_v56_108-117.pdf\n |archivedate=15 June 2011 }}\n\n==See also==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Altitude compensating nozzle]]\n* [[Avatar (spacecraft)]] \u2013 India's air-breathing spaceplane\n* [[Liquid-propellant rocket]]\n* [[Precooled jet engine]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|SABRE (rocket engine)}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.reactionengines.co.uk/sabre}}\n* {{cite web | title=This rocket engine could soon put planes in outer space (12 October 2015) | url=https://www.wired.co.uk/magazine/archive/2015/11/start/rocket-engine-planes-space | publisher=[[Wired UK]]}}\n* {{cite news |url= http://aviationweek.com/technology/reaction-engines-begins-test-facility-construction |title= Reaction Engines Begins Test Facility Construction |date= 4 May 2017 |author= Tony Osborne |work= Aerospace Daily & Defense Report |publisher= Aviation Week}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=srZzRVNj6uI TF1 time lapse \u2013 August 2018]\n\n{{Reaction Engines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reaction Engines Sabre}}\n[[Category:Rocket engines using hydrogen propellant]]\n[[Category:Rocket engines of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Jet engines]]\n[[Category:Ramjet engines]]\n[[Category:Proposed engines]]\n[[Category:Rocket engines using the staged combustion cycle]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePrecooler:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: fuly \u2192 fully", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SABRE_(rocket_engine)"}
